<head>
<title>1994 - 1995 - Annual Report</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../../bakgr.gif" link="#800019" vlink="#4B4D4C">
<div align=center><center>
<table COLSPEC="L20 L20">
<tr><td><img src="../images/OVCENTRU.GIF" align=bottom width=180 height=137></td><td><font size=6>B</font><font size=5>ALTIC </font><font size=6>C</font><font size=5>ENTRE FOR<br>
</font><font size=6>W</font><font size=5>RITERS AND </font><font size=6>T</font><font size=5>RANSLATORS</font></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>Annual Report<br>
01.07.1994 - 31.06.1995</h1>
<p><font size=4><em><strong>Baltic Centre for Writers and Translators</strong></em></font></p>
<p>- was created as a tangible result of the 1992 Writers' and Translators' Cruise, &quot;Baltic 
Waves&quot;, was inaugurated in May, 1993 and commenced its activities in July that year</p>
<p>- is a joint Centre for Writers and Translators from the Baltic region: Russia, Estonia, Latvia, 
Lithuania, Poland, Germany, Denmark, Iceland, Norway, Sweden, and Finland</p>
<p>- is operated as a non-profit organization, financed by the Swedish Government and, partly 
by the County of Gotland Administration and the Municipality of Gotland</p>
<p>-	has as its member the Swedish Writers' Union, the County of Gotland Administration and 
the Municipality of Gotland</p>
<p><font size=4><em><strong>Objectives</strong></em></font></p>
<p>The Baltic Centre for Writers and Translators is supposed to</p>
<p>-	stimulate the literary and lingiustic exchange between the countries around the Baltic Sea</p>
<p>- serve as a place of working and meeting for writers and translators from the member 
countries</p>
<p>- promote the Centre as a site for seminars, cooperative projects, educational programs, 
and conferences within a literary or linguistic context</p>
<p>- support the construction of a reference library on Baltic literature, complete with an 
information data base</p>
<p>- act as a promoter within the cultural politics of the Baltic region</p>
<p>- work to enhance the collaboration between writers and translators in the area, while 
prioritizing east-west aspects</p>
<p>One of last year's partial aims was to strengthen the activities at the Centre itself according 
to guidelines and desires expressed from the early days on, to develop routines and to find a 
balance between supply and demand. A deliberate attempt was also made to disseminate 
information about the Centre and its possibilities, with a concentration mainly on the former 
Eastern countries.</p>
<p>Another partial aim was to solicit funds for grants and to request donations of books within 
the member countries.<br>
Also, an integration between the various writers' and translators' associations and the Centre 
was actively sought.<br>
Furthermore, with a very limited budget and few resources, a large project was carried out - 
The International Poetry Festival - where the chief aim was to familiarize the citizens of 
Gotland with the Centre.</p>
<p>Hopefully this report will show that the Centre has met the above objectives as is testified to 
by the fact that most of the guests at the Centre were from the former Eastern countries and 
that funds for grants and book donations were obtained from those areas.</p>
<p>A considerable number of articles on the Centre and its activities have appeared in 
newspapers and magazines in all the countries. The Writers' Unions of St.Petersburg, 
Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland have described in very positive terms the importance 
of the Centre for both the unions and the individual writers and translators.</p>
<p>The Centre Office has two employees, a Director and an Administrative Assistant, acting as 
the executive body of the organization. Their tasks involve booking of guests, taking care of 
guests and visitors, contact and information activities, correspondence, guided tours of the 
Centre, handling of scholarship applications, planning and execution of various projects, 
managing monetary contributions, preparing statements of accounts, collaborating with 
various institutions and acting as the secretariat of the Baltic Writers' Council.</p>
<p><font size=4><em><strong>Guests</strong></em></font><br>
During the fiscal year 1994/1995 the Centre's 11 guest rooms were occupied by visitors 
during 2 091 days.</p>
<p><em><strong>Big Projects throughout the Year</strong></em></p>
<p><em><strong>Russian-Swedish Translators' Seminar</strong></em> August 25 - 31, with 20 participants from 
Sweden, St. Petersburg and Moscow in collaboration with the Swedish Embassy in 
Moscow and the Swedish Institute.</p>
<p><em><strong>Cultural Journals around the Baltic Conference</strong></em> November 22 - 6, with 30 
participants from the entire region. Financed with Ars Baltica money.</p>
<p><em><strong>Meetings of Images</strong></em> January 28 - 30, a seminar with 20 children's books' illustrators and 
animators from the Baltic region. A collaboration with the Film Program on Gotland, the Art 
Museum of Gotland and the County Library. Financed by the Swedish Institute.</p>
<p><em><strong>Nordic Writers' Council's Meeting</strong></em> April 27 - 30 with 35 representatives from the 
writers' and translators' unions of the Nordic countries.</p>
<p><em><strong>Cultural Links between Islands</strong></em><br>
We had Greek Days at the Centre May 11 - 14 with guests from Rhodes and Athens, 
headed by the Mayor of Rhodes Mr. George Giannopoulos and the Greek Ambassador to 
Sweden Mr. Emmanuel Kalpadakis. Professor Sture Linn&eacute;r and other members of the 
Swedish-Greek Cultural Association were also invited and so were 12 Greek and Swedish 
poets. Peter Curman was as usual the driving force in the meeting. Among other things we 
had arranged for a Greek evening at the Centre, a poetry reading at the Art Museum and 
many contacts between Gotlandic and Greek authorities and institutions. The intention was 
mainly to give the Greek delegation the inspiration for a Sister Centre on Rhodes, and to 
sound out a possible interest in future cultural exchange and cooperation.</p>
<p><em><strong>The Poetry Festival</strong></em><br>
The Second International Poetry Festival on Gotland called &quot;From Bellman to Bellman&quot; 
took place June 11 - 14 and had 35 participants: poets, troubadours, translators, and 
Bellman experts from the Baltic region. During the festival we had seven poetry shows 
around the island, for instance on the island of F&aring;r&ouml;, at Bl&auml;se Limestone Museum, 
Kapitelhusg&aring;rden and the Frimurarhuset in Visby. A documentary was made during the 
festival.</p>
<p><em><strong>Newsletter</strong></em><br>
With the help of Inguna Bekere, International Secretary from the Latvian Writers' Union , 
we produced four issues of our Newsletter, with many contributions from all the member 
countries.</p>
<p><em><strong>The Black Sea</strong></em><br>
The Black Sea Cruise took place during ten days, November 13 - 23, and went from 
Athens to Odessa and back to Athens again with 400 writers and translators from 30 
countries. The Centre played a central role and the Director participated. The Cruise 
resulted in the Delphi Declaration and a catalog, Word Renaissance, where Gotland is 
strongely represented.</p>
<p><em><strong>Open House at the Centre</strong></em><br>
On December 18 we had a poetry reading at the Centre with Li Li, Tobias Berggren, 
Estonian and also local poets.</p>
<p>January 29 we had Open House at the Centre in connection with the Meetings of Images 
and also February 14 after the lecture by Ulla Rhedin.</p>
<p><em><strong>Other Items of Interest</strong></em><br>
On May 18 Swedish Radio P1 Tendens was broadcast live fom the Centre, and in 
connection with the Poetry Festival Maarja Talgre recorded a one-hour Salongen program 
for Swedish Radio together with some of the visiting poets; Jesper Svenbro, Jaan Kaplinski, 
Ylva Eggehorn, and Karin Bellman.</p>
<p>September 12, Gunilla Fors&eacute;n gave a speech at the Solhem Rotary Club.</p>
<p>November 6 - 7, Gunilla Fors&eacute;n was invited to the Literaturhaus in Vienna, Austria to give a 
speech on the Centre and its activities to 50 translators from all of Europe.</p>
<p>At the beginning of October Gunilla Fors&eacute;n visited the Centre Culturel Suedois in Paris to 
discuss a Baltic Cultural manifestation in Paris.</p>
<p>October 27 - 30 Gunilla Fors&eacute;n and Annette Glover visited &quot;Bok &amp; Bibliotek&quot;, the annual 
book fair in Gothenburg, where the Centre was represented in the Gotlandic Culture display 
case.</p>
<p>February 17 - 22 Gunilla Fors&eacute;n visited Tallinn to solicit grants for writers and translators 
from Estonia.</p>
<p>March 8 - 12 Gunilla Fors&eacute;n visited St.Petersburg in connection with the Swedish Literature 
Festival and the presentation of the Russian Bellman edition.</p>
<p>March 18 - 22 Gunilla Fors&eacute;n visited Riga to disseminate information about the Centre.</p>
<p>May 18 Gunilla Fors&eacute;n participated in the Baltic Sea conference in Norrk&ouml;ping, Sweden.</p>
<p>June 9 - 12 Gunilla Fors&eacute;n visited Helsinki to disseminate information about the Centre.</p>
<p><em><strong>Summer Substitute at the Centre</strong></em><br>
Last year as the year before, Sasja Afinogenova, a translator from Moscow filled in at the 
office during the summer.</p>
<p><em><strong>Grants Received</strong></em><br>
The Silverh&auml;ttan Rotary Club of Visby donated 7 000 SEK for the Latvian poet Vizma 
Belsevica's stay at the Centre. Vizma spent the month of April at the Centre and wrote the 
second part of her autobiography there. During this time, old poems started to surface in her 
mind, things she wrote in the 1960s and never could publish because the originals were 
confiscated by the KGB.</p>
<p>The European Council in Strasbourg donated two grants for translators from the former 
east, which were given to Alexander Branski, St. Petersburg and Silvia Brice, Riga.</p>
<p><em><strong>Donations</strong></em><br>
The Centre has recieved a generous donation from Desi Viksten consisting of two oil 
paintings and 12 lithographs made by the late Hans Viksten.</p>
<p>Helena Andreeff has donated a painting, in memory of the Library of Sarajevo.</p>
<p>The library of the Centre has received several large and small book donations from 
institutions and private persons from different countries. In the spring of 1995 a donation of 
300 valuable reference books in Polish was presented during a cermony at the Polish 
Embassy in Stockholm.</p>
<p>The Nordic Information offices in both Vilnius and Riga have been most helpful in putting 
together a collection of reference books in each of the two languages and in sending them to 
the Centre.</p>
<p>Several Norwegian Publishers have sent large and nice book packages.</p>
<p>The Russian Ambassador to Sweden, Mr. Oleg Grinevsky, has arranged for the donation of 
Russian reference literature.</p>
<p><em><strong>Visits</strong></em><strong><br>
</strong>August 5	Berit Skogsberg, En Bok F&ouml;r Alla<br>
August 5	Nordplan, 50 planners from all of Scandinavia<br>
August 10	Carin Fischer, Stockholm Cult. Capital of Europe '98<br>
August 12	Margaretha af Ugglas, Minister for Foreign Affairs<br>
August 13	Pierre Schori<br>
August 16	The Vard&oslash;-Seminar, lunch 30 persons<br>
August 18	Christina Sollenberg-Britton, journalist<br>
August 20-23	Visit of M. Nowak, B. Jaworowska, K. Wroblewska, from Gdansk<br>
August 26	Ann Hommerberg, journalist<br>
August 29-30	Nordic Adult Education confrence<br>
September 1	Baltic Film Festival, 40 persons<br>
September 7	Ambassador and Mrs. Robert Cormack <br>
September 8	Poul Binding, Brittish journalist and writer<br>
September 8-10	Minerva, 5 persons<br>
September 9	Wieslaw Tarka, Embassy of Poland<br>
September 16	Gunnel W. Berstr&ouml;m, journalist <br>
September 17	Thomas &Ouml;hrn, SIV<br>
September 26	Lunchmeeting, Swedish National Council for Cultural Affairs, 12 persons<br>
November 2	Hemse Community College, teachers and students<br>
April 3	Tukums Artmuseum, 12 persons<br>
April 19	Eva J&auml;rup, journalist<br>
May 19	Swedish County Librarians, lunch for 12<br>
May 28	Former Visby Students, 30 persons<br>
June 16	Barbro Thomas, Swedish National Council for Cultural Affairs</p>
<p><em><strong>The Library</strong></em><br>
The Centre has recieved a sum of 425 000 SEK from the State Culture department for the 
foundation of a library. During a six-month period last year The Municipality of Gotland 
contributed a parttime librarian, Birgitta Rydberg, to work at the Centre, for structuring of 
the library. A custom made bookcase and some reference books were purchased, while the 
main part of the work still needs to be done. We are also with great expectation awaiting the 
report on the Gotland libraries that will be done in the fall of 1995 by Karin Olausson.</p>
<p><em><strong>BWC - Baltic Writers' Council</strong></em><br>
BWC was founded on Gotland the fall of 1993 and is a free forum for discussion for 
representatives from the Writers' and Translators' Unions around the Baltic Sea, with an 
annual meeting in Visby. In 1994 BWC extended the invitation to Iceland. That means that 
BWC now has eleven members. Every country sends two representatives to the annual 
meeting, that usually takes place in October.</p>
</body>

