<html>
<head>
<title>Internet and literature - session 1</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><font size="7">Internet and Literature</font><br>
<font size="5">News from the seminar 23 september 1996</font></p>
<hr>
<h1>Background and examples </h1>
<p><img src="images/seminar1-s.JPG" align="left" hspace="10"
width="250" height="189">In the Congress Hall of Paradise Hotel
at Rhodes writers and translators from 40 countries gathered to
discuss Internet and Literature. </p>
<p>Peter Curman, Swedish writer and member of the Organizing
Committee, welcomed the participants and stressed the importance
of intercultural relations. &#147;Soon&#148;, he said, &#147;the
publishers will gather at the Bookfair in Frankfurt. Here the
decisions are made of wich kind of literature the readers will be
served. There is an overwhelming dominance of Anglo-American
literature and a lack of trust in Quality literature. Because it
is said to be a too small market for it. In this perspective the
Internet offers an interesting possibility. It can be a tool in
the hands of writers, literary magazines and small publishing
houses who want to create a more independent &#147;market&#148;
of literature.&#148; &#147;But&quot;, Peter Curman
concluded&#148;, there are practical problems there still to be
solved. Not least concerning literary rights. But Internet is
also a challenge for freedom of speech.&quot;</p>
<p><img src="images/intro1-s.JPG" align="left" hspace="10"
width="200" height="164">The Chairman <strong>Costas Tsoulakidis</strong>,
from the Aegean University of Rhodes, welcomed the participants
to Rhodes and dedicated the conference to Apollon, whom, Costas
thought, would have been very fond of the Internet. After that he
gave us some facts of Rhodes. Mostly about the Aegean University,
which is quite special, being situated on four different islands.
Therefore communication is essential. To exchange mail, databases
and other kinds of information Internet has now become a
necessity. Costas Tsoulakidis then explained the technical
possibilities and the history of Internet. &#147;World Wide
Web&#148;, he said, &#147;can be seen as a huge worldwide <i>book&#148;.</i> </p>
<p>Mart Marend from Gotland presented the internet server Mare
Balticum. He demonstrated how it is possible to present
literature on the net. One of the aims of Waves of Three Seas is
that all of the participating countries create a literary
homepage. Mare Balticum served as an example. &#147;It's actually
like a database&#148;, he says. It's like a directory of the
servers in the Baltic region. He showed The Literary Scene, a
database of literature, facilitating contacts across borders. </p>
