<html>
<head>
<title>Internet and literature - session 3</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><font size="7">Internet and Literature</font><br>
<font size="5">News from the seminar 23 september 1996</font></p>
<hr>
<h3>After the lectures there was time for discussions and
remarks. </h3>
<p><img src="india.JPG" align="left" hspace="10" width="120"
height="133">Who shall give us the information, who is
responsible for what? Who is responsible for the quality of the
material? Who is, in other words, the Webmaster? asked <strong>Indra
Nath Choudhuri</strong> from New Delhi. He stressed the
importance of discussing these important questions. </p>
<p>Another topic was censorship on the Internet. Is it possible?
Novica Milic replied by telling us about the strategies to
exchange information that where used during the war in former
Yugoslavia. </p>
<p><strong><img src="ryssen.JPG" align="right" hspace="10"
width="200" height="224"></strong><strong>Alexander Zhitinsky</strong>,
editor of <a href="http://www.spb.su/art/">Art<b> </b>Petersburg</a>,<b> </b>the
online-magazine in Saint Petersburg, showed the magazine and
pointed out texts that are published exclusively on the Web. </p>
<p>After this discussion Dimitrios Kilias from FORTHnet, Greece,
showed us some strategies to search for information on the
Internet. He demonstrated different search-strategies and how to
use the search-tools available. He underlined the importance of
being specific when one tries to find information. </p>
<p><img src="mart.JPG" align="left" hspace="10" width="150"
height="115">Yet another topic raised was privacy. Can anyone
read what I send, for example, as e-mail over the Internet? More
important than questions on security and cryptation is how we
relate to the new technology, said <strong>Mart Marend</strong>.
Questions concerning authenticity and falsifications were also
discussed. Mart Marend had to conclude that, as with any other
form of media, there is no guarantee that the material published
on the Internet is authentic. Do we believe everything we read in
our daily newspaper? We must develop the same critical attitude
towards electronical publications as we have done towards
information printed on paper. </p>
<p><img src="portrait3.JPG" align="left" hspace="10" width="120"
height="177">&#147;Life is always life-dangerous&#148; concluded <strong>Theo
In der Smitten</strong>. The Internet is as important as the
invention of printing or the novel. We must embrace this new
technology with open arms. <br clear="all">
</p>
