<html>
<head>
<title>Internet and literature - session 5</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="center"><font size="7">Internet and Literature</font><br>
<font size="5">News from the seminar 23 september 1996</font></p>
<hr>
<p><img src="mette.JPG" align="left" hspace="10" width="200"
height="151">Today, said <strong>Mette Newth</strong> from
Norway, authors are often seen as someone who is preventing
access to information on Internet. They are blocking the
development of the net by claiming their literary rights. But,
she continued, this is far to simple. There exists a strong link
between copyright and freedom of expression. They are two sides
of the same coin. It is important, she said, not to mix free
access with free of charge. Without copyright, and the
possibility <i>to some extent</i> charge for information, there
will be no freedom of expression. </p>
<p>Mette Newth presented the project Norwegian Forum for Freedom
of Expression, an independent liaison between 15 norwegian
organisations. The aim with the Forum is to promote freedom of
expression and free debate all over the world. </p>
<p>Since the Internet knows no geographical borders a mighty
problem is confronting those governments who wants to control the
political, moral or religious views of there citizens. Mette
Newth referred the discussion about the Communication Decency Act
in the USA over the last year. There is a problem, she claimed,
when one tries to control the <i>decency</i> of for example
literature. Instead she proposed two principles: 1) Explicit
prohibition against prior censorship, and 2) Explicit prohibition
against censorship by indirect methods, that is prohibition
against necessary technical devices. </p>
<p>&#147;The Internet&#148; she concluded, &#147;has the
potential to be a tremendous force for development - by providing
quick and inexpensive information, by encouraging discussion
rather than violence, and by empowering citizens, to cite but a
few examples. But this potential can be realized only if it
becomes a truly global effort. Policy makers must make every
effort to ensure that internationally guaranteed rights to free
expression are extended to on-line communication and call for the
repeal of censorship legislation. Without such commitments,
individuals face the danger of seeing their rights eroded by the
very technologies they are embracing.&#148; </p>
<p>The final discussion left us with some unanswered questions,
some of them to be answered tomorrow, and a lot of questions with
a lot of answers: How to put a price on the information? Who
shall pay for it? Isn't the main purpose in the end publicity?
What about the others, the ones not on-line? </p>
<p>The last words to Theo In der Smitten:</p>
<p><img src="forpeter.JPG" align="left" hspace="25" width="150"
height="211"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
