<head>
<title>Writers' and Translators' Centre of Rhodes</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<div align=left>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td valign=top width=33%><img src="images/waveso3seas.gif" align=bottom width=155 height=78></td><td colspan=2 width=67%><font size=4><strong>Writers' and Translators' Centre of Rhodes</strong></font><br>
<b>Laskou Street 10 A, 851 00 RHODES, GREECE</b> <br>
<b>Phone: +30-241-32 510, 32 520, Fax: + 30-241-32 455</b> <br>
<b>e-mail: </b><a href="mailto:waves@rho.forthnet.gr"><b>waves@rho.forthnet.gr</b></a> </td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=3 width=100%><h3 align=center><i><br>
under the auspices of<br>
</i><a href="http://www.unesco.org/" target="_Blank"><img src="images/UNESCO.gif" align=bottom border=0 width=497 height=43></a></h3>
</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<h1 align=center>Writers' and Translators' Centre of Rhodes</h1>
<p align=left>A new International Writers' and Translators' Centre recently opened on Rhodes, Greece. Nearly three hundred 
writers, translators, cultural personalities, media representatives and supporters from over thirty countries attended 
the inauguration on September 23-28, 1996. The programme included a seminar on literature and internet, poetry 
readings, lectures, discussions and an official opening ceremony, all generously hosted by the Municipality of Rhodes 
in collaboration with the working committee of the &#147;WAVES OF THREE SEAS&#147; with support from various 
sponsors.</p>
<p><img src="images/rhodes.gif" align=left hspace=10 width=264 height=183>The Centre itself (the former British Admiralty Building), is 
beautifully located on the slope underneath the old acropolis, 
overlooking the sea and only five minutes walk from the town. The 
newer part of the building with 10 bedrooms is ready to receive the 
first guests from the beginning of January 1997. Lorraine Hunt, a 
British born interpreter and translator (English, Greek, French, 
German) has been appointed Director of the Centre. Until her office 
is fully equipped, Ms Hunt will be operating from the Municipality 
and she will be pleased to give further information on telephone 
+30-241-46 314 or fax +30-241-46 323.<br clear=left>
</p>
<h3 align=center>Background</h3>
<p>This new writers' and translators' centre of Rhodes is one of the main concrete results of a literary cruise which took 
place in November 1994. Over 400 writers, translators and journalists, mainly from the countries around the Baltic, 
the Black and the Aegean Seas, travelled together during a fortnight from Piraeus to Odessa, Varna, Constanta, 
Istanbul and Izmir. Through an intensive programme with seminars and readings onboard and ashore a dialogue 
across borders began.</p>
<h3 align=center>Baltic Centre for Writers and Translators</h3>
<p>A similar cruise was made in the Baltic Sea in 1992, right after the fall of the Soviet Union, which has led to many 
significant results, among them a writers' and translators' centre on the island of Gotland, Sweden, which has become 
an important cultural meeting place in the middle of the Baltic Sea. The Gotland centre now serves as a model for 
Rhodes, which is an ideal site in the cross roads between east and west in the Aegean. Parallel to the inauguration of 
the Rhodes' Centre the towns of Rhodes and Visby of Gotland celebrated their twinning with a joint cultural festival, 
also this a result of the two cruises.</p>
<h3 align=center>Aims</h3>
<p>Both centres are international independent institutions open to all writers and translators, according to the aims of 
free dialogue, mutual understanding and tolerance that has guided our project from the beginning. The belief in the 
strength of literature serving as bridge to cultural peace is the base of our co-operation. This is also why UNESCO 
has decided to authorise our two centres to operate under UNESCO auspices, which will safeguard the international 
quality of our activities.</p>
<h3 align=center><b>More Centres to come</b></h3>
<p>The ultimate goal is to build a network of literary centres in many countries. Two new centres are already approved 
and on their way. One on the B&uuml;y&uuml;kada Island outside Istanbul with the support from the Turkish Foreign Ministry. 
The second one by the Prespa Lake in northern Greece, upon initiative of Greek and Albanian writers with the help 
of the Thessaloniki Cultural Capital. Other proposals have been made from Odessa-Ukraine, Constanta-Romania, 
Pitsunda-Abkhazia and Georgia.</p>
<h3 align=center>Financing and Support</h3>
<p>The necessary restoration and reconstruction of the premises of the Rhodes centre, as well as the running costs, are 
being covered and carried out by the Municipality of Rhodes. Various official institutions and private sponsors - 
international and national - have generously contributed to the preparatory work and the inauguration of the Centre. 
Yet, further financing is needed for the continuation, such as seminars and literary meetings in the centre, grants to 
writers and translators from countries without financial possibilities. We are also hoping for support from international 
organisations i.e. UNESCO and EU. </p>
<p>A full report from the inauguration, with presentation on the centre, the goals of the organisation and the future 
perspectives is under preparation for distribution in December 1996. In January 1997 the first writers and translators 
will come to stay and work in the centre. In the end of March 1997 a general assembly with all the participating 
writers' organisations will be held in Rhodes to elect an international committee, which will be responsible for the 
cultural activities of the centre. A local, legal administrative board for the running of the centre is already appointed. 
Meanwhile, the working committee will continue its function until the general assembly. Among their tasks is to study 
the possibilities of &#147;WAVES OF THREE SEAS&#147; becoming an NGO (non governmental organisation) and to keep 
our network alive in close collaboration with the Municipality of Rhodes. </p>
<h3 align=center>Next on the Agenda</h3>
<p>A special working comittee has been elected to carry out the preparatory work with the main task of fundraising and 
to keep all the participating organisations informed on the progress. </p>
<hr>
<p align=center><font size=5>For Further Information:<br>
</font><em><b>Lorraine Hunt </b></em><em>at the Municipality of Rhodes<br>
Phone: 30-241-46 314 (-316) Fax: +30-241 46 323 OR 46 305 <br>
e-mail: </em><a href="mailto:waves@rho.forthnet.gr"><em>waves@rho.forthnet.gr</em></a></p>
<p align=center><em><strong>Ewa A Kumlin</strong></em><em>, Co-ordinator of the Working Committee<br>
phone and fax number: +30-1-681 01 56<br>
mobile phone: 094-55 11 07<br>
e-mail: </em><a href="mailto:ewax@hol.gr"><em>ewax@hol.gr</em></a><em> </em></p>
