<html>

<head>
<title>Newsletter 95:3 - b</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../../bakgr.gif" link="#800019" vlink="#4B4D4C">
<div align=center><center>
<table COLSPEC="L20 L20">
<tr><td><img src="../images/OVCENTRU.GIF" align=bottom width=180 height=137></td><td><font size=6>B</font><font size=5>ALTIC </font><font size=6>C</font><font size=5>ENTRE FOR<br>
</font><font size=6>W</font><font size=5>RITERS AND </font><font size=6>T</font><font size=5>RANSLATORS</font></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>News from the Centre<br>
and Baltic Writers Council</h1>
<p><a name="the book fair"><font size=4><strong>The Book Fair</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> in Gothenburg</strong></font></p>
<p>26-29 October collected altogether some 100.000 visitors and was a strong manifestation 
for the book in general and with a strong emphasis on the freedom of expression. Great 
international names like Salman Rushdie, Yassar Kemal, Bei Dao, Doris Lessing and the 
Nobel Prize laureate Sheamus Heaney were among the large number of participants.</p>
<p>Many representatives from the Baltic region also were at the fair, writers and translators 
who took part in many different ways. Emil Tode (pseudonym for Tonu Onnepalu) was 
there to talk about his book Piiririik, which has lately been published in Sweden. Jaan 
Kaplinski gave an interesting lesson to his audience, comparing the situation in his country 
with a harem. With the collapse of communism the doors to the harem were suddenly wide 
open and nobody was any longer interested in the destiny of its inhabitants. Today there is a 
complete freedom, which in many cases means that you are free to choose between being a 
beggar or a prostitute. He also talked about one of the great paradoxes of our time. During 
the communist era every piece of text which you succeeded to publish, even in a censured 
version, was read with great attention and had a certain impact. Today it is the opposite. 
Everyone is free to write whatever he likes but there is no interest for the truth.</p>
<p><strong>From the Baltic to the Black Sea</strong> was the title of a seminar arranged by the Swedish 
Writers Union. Peter Curman was, naturally, the moderator and among the participants you 
could see well-known faces like Ewa A. Kumlin, Yuri Pokalchuk, Sezer Duru, Alexander 
Branski and Gunilla Fors&eacute;n. The vice mayor of Rhodos and Jan Larsson from the 
municipality of Gotland completed the company by telling about the advantages of culture in 
a greater political context.</p>
<p><em>Gunilla Fors&eacute;n</em></p>
<p><a href="http://www.gotlandica.se/summit96/freedom/freedom.htm" name="freedom"><font size=4><strong>Freedom of speech</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong>, information and libraries</strong></font></p>
<p>is the topic for a conference in Visby 3-4 May, 1996. At the same time there will be a 
meeting of all the Prime Ministers from the Baltic region and as we have preliminary decided 
a meeting of the Baltic Writers Council as well. Right now we are working on the program, 
searching for sponsors and also working with the idea to hire a ship for the conference. We 
imagine it could sail with the participants from Stockholm and during the meetings and 
conferences serve as hotel and hall in Visby harbour.</p>
<p>The conference is intended for writers and translators, for librarians and politicians and any 
other persons with a burning interest in these topics.</p>
<p>One of the ideas behind the conference is of course to catch the attention of the PMs and 
some of the hundreds of journalists who we expect to come to cover the Prime Ministers 
meeting.</p>
<p>The conference is organised by the Centre together with the Municipality of Gotland and the 
UBC, Union of the Baltic Cities.</p>
<p><a name="scholarships"><font size=4><strong>Scholarships</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> for translators</strong></font></p>
<p>The European Commission has granted the Centre a financial contribution of 36.037 ECU 
for 40 bursaries for 1996. The Community bursaries may be given only to translators from 
the Member States or countries having signed association agreements with the Community, 
in this case five bursaries for the following countries: Finland, Denmark, Sweden, Germany, 
Poland, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania and can be applied for from the Centre from now on.</p>
<p><a name="ars baltica"><font size=4><strong>ARS BALTICA</strong></font></a><font size=4><strong> in Paris October 1996</strong></font></p>
<p>The Centre together with Centre Cultural Suedois in Paris are working on a cultural project 
for October 1996. We want to present literature, jazz, fashion, animated and documentary 
films in Paris in collaboration with UNESCO. The project will be paid by Ars Baltica and 
take place at CCS, La Maison de la Poesie etc. during a week.</p>
</body>

