<html>

<head>
<title>Art project- Presentation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font size=7>People in a Landscape</font> </p>
<p><img src="images/andreas.JPG" align=right hspace=10 width=150 height=147>Maybe it<b> </b>is because of these difficulties of communication that we enjoy 
playing Chinese Whispers. This is a game where the participants are sitting 
at the end of the row and a person in the end of the row whispers a 
sentence to his neighbour who in turn poses it on to his neighbour etc. The 
person at the end of the row says the sentence aloud and it is totally 
distorted. Everybody laughs. </p>
<p>Why are we laughing? Presumably because we so easily misunderstand 
each other. The paradox is that we are united in this situation: we both produce and bridge the 
shortcomings of linguistic communication. </p>
<p>Here you can see an example of a similar game, but one I have made up. It is a kind of &#148;translation 
relay&#148;. A section of the Swedish poet Tomas Transtr&ouml;mer&#146;s poem &#148;Baltic Seas&#148; has been entitled 
&#148;People in a Landscape&#148;. This section, which was already translated from Swedish into French, was 
presented as an original French poem (&#148;Des gens dans un paysage&#148;) to an English translator. Then the 
English translation was presented to a Russian translator and then it was translated as an original 
Russian poem into Swedish. In the same way it was translated into Turkish, and on into French, English 
and so forth. </p>
<p>The original text is on a white background, the rest are blushing. </p>
<p>The poem by Transtr&ouml;mer is based on a photograph (&#148;&Aring;ngslupen Vikingen...&#148; ) In this regard this fact 
the orignal poem is in itself a kind of translation or interpretation from image to text. </p>
<p><i>Andreas Gedin</i> </p>
<hr>
<h5><a href="gedin01.htm">Back to previous page</a><br>
Soon you will be able to follow the &quot;whispers&quot; on these pages. Please visit us again later.</h5>
</body>

</html>
