<br>
<H4>a prolife:
</H4>

<h2>john edgar wideman: from time to time in africa</h2>
<br>


<P>



<b>by nicholas a. basbanes</b><br>
<br><br>
 <hr>
<blockquote>

   Rarely has the intimate relationship between author and reader
been explored more challengingly than it is in <b>The Cattle
Killing,</b> John Edgar Wideman's 13th book, and his first novel in
six years.<p>


   As  Wideman's audaciously inventive new work opens, an unnamed novelist
is traveling through the rough and tumble African-American
neighborhood of his youth to visit his aging father and to read
aloud for him the manuscript from his work-in-progress. The time
is the present, and a sense of moment is implied:<p>

  <IMG SRC="wideman.jpg" WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=220 HSPACE=10 vspace=10 ALIGN=left>

 "He would read to his father. Or offer to read. His father
not an easy man. He'd read from the new manuscript if his father
in bedroom slippers, hunched on the couch, swaddled in blankets
against the chill, was willing to listen. And will that
listening, if it happens, be part of the story, the beginning of
what he reads."<p>
   From there, <B>The Cattle Killing</B> (Houghton Mifflin, $22.95), races back more than 200 years to Philadelphia
and the summer of 1793, when an epidemic of yellow fever erupted
in the city, causing fear and chaos among all residents. <p>
   The voice quickly becomes that of an 18th-century black
preacher who has the gift - or curse, depending on your point of
view - to see worlds within worlds, layers within layers. He
arrives in Philadelphia to help his people during these trying
days of confusion, dread and abandonment, and encounters a young
African woman carrying a dead baby who thereupon will consume his
attention.<p>
   A constantly mutating tale, seemingly told to an unidentified
listener, <B>The Cattle Killing</B> encompasses many places and time
periods, and draws sustenance from a multitude of sources, many
historic, many mythic, many legendary, many imaginary. There is
no conventional plot to summarize simply, a circumstance made
clear by the assertion early on that the book is "not exactly a
novel."<p>
   The title derives from an old story about an African tribe,
the Xhosa, which destroyed its livestock as a ritualistic way of
ridding itself of European domination, only to find that the
prophesy being followed was false, and what resulted instead was
continued suffering.<p>
   In an epilogue, Wideman shifts once again to the present, with
an appreciative letter, apparently written by his own son,
offering yet another take on the special alchemy that transpires
between readers and writers. The young man, on his way to visit
Africa, has just read <B>The Cattle Killing.</B><p>
   "Perhaps this was his father's gift to him," the adult son,
also a writer, muses. "Pops setting the table, providing the
ingredients, inviting people to the feast, but leaving the final
preparation of the meal for him."<p>
    From these disparate reference points, it is clear that
Wideman seeks out a variety of responses to his writing, and he
expects his readers to participate in the creative process. "I
don't want the reader to get away too easily," the  55-year-old
author agreed in a recent interview.<p>
  "Good writing centers itself right in the middle of that
special relationship between two minds. I like to push that edge,
and explore that edge, and the writing I like best centers itself
in this process. Good writing creates a space between the mind of
the reader and the mind of the writer. This thing that writing
produces enacts itself somewhere in the middle of that space."<p>
   Despite this conviction about not letting readers "get away
too easily," Wideman nevertheless includes in his books what he
calls a "warning label," a statement of literary intentions no
different than a fairy tale that begins with the phrase, "once
upon a time." <p>
   "I make it pretty clear at the outset that this is going to
bea different kind of novel," Wideman said. "I make it pretty
clear that there are certain stylistic things that I'm going to
do, certain things with grammar and punctuation, and there are
certain things the reader has to do too. Part of the fun for me
is to find for each book or each story a special way to tell
it."<p>
   Born in Washington, D.C., Wideman grew up in a black
neighborhood on the east side of Pittsburgh known as Homewood,
which he has used often as a setting for his writing. A Phi Betta
Kappa graduate of the University of Pennsylvania, where he was an
All Ivy League forward on the basketball team, Wideman won a
Rhodes Scholarship in 1963 -  the second African-American to be so
honored - and studied 18th-century literature at Oxford
University.<p>
   Wideman's first novel, <B>A Glance Away</B>, was published four
years later, when he was 26 years old. He has twice won the
PEN/Faulkner Award, the first in 1984 for <B>Sent for You
Yesterday,</B> and again in 1991 for <B>Philadelphia Fire</B>. His
1994 memoir, <B>Fatheralong</B>, was a finalist for the National
Book Award. <p>
  Wideman's earlier memoir, <B>Brothers and Keepers,</B>
compellingly explored the divergent circumstances that led his
younger brother, Robert, to be convicted of murder and imprisoned
for life, and helped him achieve success as an author and
teacher. It was a finalist in 1985 for the National Book Critics
Circle Award.<p>
   Although he has been a professional writer for three decades,
Wideman said he finds special pleasure in teaching. He has held
positions at a number of prominent institutions, and is now a
professor and associate dean of the faculty of the Humanities and
Fine Arts Department at the University of Massachusetts in
Amherst.<p>
    "Teaching writing is fun, because you see the process
working with younger people," he said. "It also happens that
I'm a guy who grew up with nothing, and I always want to know
I've got the security of a day job."
<br>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<A HREF="mailto:NabatLfs@aol.com">Nicholas A. Basbanes</A> is a Massachusetts journalist and author
of <I>A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the
Eternal Passion for Books</I>.


</blockquote>
</blockquote>


