<HTML><HEAD>
<title>george jr. / february 1997 / features / q & a / lance olsen </title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>

<BR>
<H4>q&a:</H4>
<P>


<H3>lance olsen: pop goes the zeitgeist
</H3>
<blockquote>
<IMG SRC="olsen2.jpg" WIDTH=168 HEIGHT=154 HSPACE=10 vspace=10 ALIGN=right>
<A HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/~lolsen/">Lance Olsen</A>, Idaho
Writer-in-Residence and Philip K. Dick Award finalist for best science
fiction of 1995, is author of four novels, including <A
HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/~lolsen/tonguing.html"><I>Tonguing the
Zeitgeist</I>, two short story collections, and six critical studies,
including the first book-length one about cyberpunk godfather <A
HREF="http://www.vkool.com/gibson/netindex.html">William Gibson</A>.  He
teaches contemporary fiction and creative writing at the <A
HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/">University of Idaho</A>, and lives on a farm
with his artist-wife <A
HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/~lolsen/andi.html">Andi</A>.

<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>



<font size=5>q. </font>Critics have often associated your work with the
so-called <A HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/~lolsen/AP.html">"Avant-Pop"</A>.
Is this a comfortable literary fit for you?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>So-called is right.  The term, first appropriated
several years ago by critic Larry McCaffery and surfictionist Ron Sukenick
from a Lester Bowie jazz album, suggests a mode of expression that splices
the avant-garde's obsession with innovation, experimentation, and

<IMG SRC="olsen.jpg" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=220 HSPACE=10 vspace=10  ALIGN=left>

radicalization with a deep pop sensibility.  The result: an extreme fusion
and confusion of the traditional distinctions between "high" culture and
"low."  But if we think about this definition for a second, we realize
we've just defined postmodernism...nothing, in other words, that hasn't
been around in one guise or another for the last three or four decades.
<P>
I wonder, then, whether the A-P doesn't have more to do with a marketing
strategy than a literary one...with a generation of writers, in other
words, lacking socio-historical context who need to feel what they're doing
is new and thus important.
<P>
At the same time, I'm intrigued with the notion, adore many of the writers
that have been associated with the term (William Burroughs, Thomas Pynchon,
Kathy Acker, Mark Leyner, and David Foster Wallace, for instance) and
certainly agree my work displays some of the A-Ps concerns and obsessions.
<P></P>
<font size=5>q. </font> Is the Avant-Pop just another literary Flavor of
the Week, then?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>Not exactly.  I'm as wary as the next guy about
Flavors of the (Literarily) Weak.  At the same time, I'm also aware that
labels are nothing but shorthands for organizing reality, narratological or
otherwise, and hence helpful.  The alternative would be a sort of paralytic
intellectual schizophrenia.
<P>
So if you'd like to attach one to me, I'm comfortable enough with
Avant-Pop, but I'd probably feel a bit more so with something like <A
HREF="http://www.armory.com/~jay/convulsive.html">"Convulsive Beauty,"</A>
a lovely phrase first coined by Andre Breton in his surrealist manifesto,
and which, for me, suggests a socio-historically aware alternative
aesthetic mode that thinks back through a hypothetical trajectory of
vanguard art, appropriating from the past while nibbling always forward,
from the fifties, sixties, seventies, eighties, and nineties: through
Avant-Pop, Surfiction, Metafiction, Punk, Cyberpunk, RiboFunk, the
Multimedia Moment, the Deconstructive Turn, the Novel of Excess & Regress &
Digress, Language Poetry, Beat fiction, Faction, Magical Realism, the
Nouveau Roman, the New Wave, and so on, back through Lettrism, Surrealism,
Dadaism, Expressionism, Decadence, Imagism, Vorticism, Futurism, and
Symbolism...and back again, finally, to the doorstep of that paradigmless
paradigm of Romanticism committed to the idea of Convulsive Beauty (think
of Blake's visions, or, better, of the presence of Frankenstein's
monster--the latter an appropriated, electrocuted, existentially and
socially and epistemologically alien icon of the extreme instant in the
arts) with its thematics and formalistics of trespass, revolution,
Dionysian border-breaking, psychotic breach, brilliant rage, paranoid rant,
with its exploration of the illogical, the unconscious, the inner-world,
the drastic aesthetico-spiritual brink experienced by the Aztec sacrifice
who wants his heart to be removed because of what he'll see and feel.
<P></P>
<font size=5>q. </font> In other words, a fairly accurate description of
your new novel, <A HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/~lolsen/famine.html"><I>Time
Famine</I></A>, a dark-edged satiric science fiction in the tradition of
William Gibson's <I>Neuromancer</I> and Anthony Burgess's <I>A Clockwork
Orange</I>.
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>Exactly.  Satire as a literary genre supposes a
fairly strong moral impetus (think of Jonathan Swift or Kurt Vonnegut), an
impetus to disturb the reader out of his or her complacency, and <I>Time
Famine</I> is no exception.  It may at first seem to launch sorties on lots
of attack-points, but really there are only three major ones: 1) the
ignorant manhandling of the environment for short-term economic gain at the
risk of long-term spiritual loss; 2) the televisualization of reality in
the late twentieth century and its concomitant disruption of selfhood's
stability; 3) the fact that the American west--and, by implication, the
rest of the country--has really progressed a lot less over the last
hundred-and-fifty years or so than it believes it has.
<P>
All of these concerns organize themselves around a thready plot:  this
Disney-like corporation has bought the rights to the great atrocities of
history and built theme parks around them.  Hence Belsenland, the Iron
Curtain, and so on.  The nuclear reactor in one of these parks suffers a
meltdown, releasing a cloud of radiation over the southwest. The fallout
affects the population's sense of time, causing an outbreak of "intense
memory" (which may or may not be real memory) in many people. One of these,
Uly Sysop-of-the-Plains Stray, begins to slip, or hallucinate he's
slipping, into the nineteenth-century pioneer world of the ill-fated Donner
Party.
<P></P>
<font size=5>q. </font>Why choose to work in science fiction, a genre many
think is literarily low-rent?<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>People who think SF is somehow "low-rent" haven't
read Mary Shelley's <I>Frankenstein</I>, one of the really great novels to
arise out of the early Industrial Revolution, and in many ways the mother
of all science fiction texts.  They haven't read some of the finest
practioners: J. G. Ballard, Richard Kadrey, Lewis Shiner.  There's lots of
terrible, terrible stuff being written under the banner of SF.  Absolutely.
But there's also lots of terrible, terrible stuff being written under the
banners of realism, fantasy, experimental fiction, you name it.
<P>
Science fiction's a genre that re-presents our world to us through a
narrative glass darkly so we can see it anew, treating our present as
someone else's past.  It's the most forward-thinking literary genre we
have, and one that thus lends itself to thinking about Big Questions, as
opposed, let's say, to domestic psychological realism, which lends itself
to thinking about Small Questions.  SF asks us to think about tomorrow,
about global and universal matters, and warns us what might happen if we're
not careful, what might happen if we are, and hence is usually the only
genre that addresses questions about such important issues as the
development of nanotechnology, bioengineering, artificial intelligence, or
virtual reality.
<P></P>
<font size=5>q. </font>You've called <I>Time Famine</I> an "anti-sequel" to
<I>Tonguing the Zeitgeist</I>.  How so?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> I think of the two novels as companion pieces.
They don't share characters, and they don't share plot components, but they
do share the same world, and they do share many of the same themes.  So if
someone picked up <I>Time Famine</I> expecting to find a continuation of
<I>Tonguing the Zeitgeist</I>, someone would be disappointed.  But if
someone picked up <I>Time Famine</I> expecting to find an elaboration and
continuation of <I>Tonguing the Zeitgeist</I>'s world and vision (<I>Time
Famine</I> is set fewer than ten years ahead of <I>Tonguing the
Zeitgeist</I>), then someone would be content.  Hence the idea of the
anti-sequel.
<P>
There's nothing to my mind more tedious than a writer who repeats him or
herself, and so I always promise myself not to do the same thing twice.
Ick.  You might as well just thin the herd if you plan on doing that,
narratologically and creatively speaking.
<P></P>
<font size=5>q. </font>You're a critic as well as a fiction writer.  How
does one enterprise converse with the other?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>My understanding of contemporary fiction and theory
continually informs my creative work.  <I>Time Famine</I>, or the novel I
wrote just before it, <A
HREF="http://www.uidaho.edu/~lolsen/burnt.html"><I> Burnt</I></a>, are rife,
for instance, with fictional manifestations of Baudrillard's idea of the
evaporation of reality in the late millennium and Guy Debord's of ours as a
society of the spectacle.
<P>
My understanding of the writing process continually informs the way I
approach texts when exploring them analytically as well.  Last year and the
year before I had a great time close reading Nabokov's <I>Lolita</I>,
composing an almost scene-by-scene explication, which I just don't think I
could have done justice to without knowing fiction from the inside out.
<P></P>
<font size=5>q. </font>Speaking of the late millennium and forward-thinking
modes, what do you see happening to American fiction during the next decade
or so?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>New York publishing will continue to exclude, given
its seedy economic motivations, and thus it'll be harder and harder for
young writers to break in and mid-list writers to stay in.
<P>
That's the bad news, and bad it is.  The good news is that smaller presses
will continue to multiply, if not be all that economically fruitful, as
will interesting and important literary sites like this on the web.
<P>
So there will be 250 channels and everything on.  That's what makes this
moment so capitvating.  We've moved at every level--televisual, literary,
theoretical, you name it--from a this-ism or that-ism toward an any-ism, an
all-ism, a kaleidoscopic hypertext hotel, a high-tech garden of forking
paths.  Down one you might find gay fiction, down another neohumanist or
regionalist or metafictionist or feminist or politically incorrect or Asian
American or, better yet, all of them at some network once.  Diversity,
whether subatomic or cultural, may well be old news from an old front from
an old war.  We're moving toward a Unified Field Theory of culture, a
gesture that open-armedly <I>includes</I>, gobbles up, termites along,
without ever homogenizing.  It's a multimedia moment, and one that's really
exciting to be a part of.
<P>
Unless, of course, you're writing for fame or money, in which case you
should hurry along and do something else, and never look back.


</blockquote>



<HR><BR>

<a href="features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>
