<head>

<title>george jr. / february 1997 / features / margaret atwood<IMG SRC="/feb97/wideman.jpg" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=156 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left> </title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>
<hr>
<H4>a profile:</H4>


<H2>margaret atwood: lizzie borden's tale</H2>

<BR>


<B>by nicholas a. basbanes<BR></B>
<BR><BR>


   Eleven years after she imagined a harsh authoritarian society
of the future in <B>The Handmaid's Tale</B>, the Canadian novelist
Margaret Atwood has turned her attention to an actual crime from
the past to create an absorbing novel that poses more provocative
questions and riddles than it answers.<P>
<HR>
<blockquote>
<IMG SRC="atwood.jpg" WIDTH=204 HEIGHT=264 HSPACE=10 vspace=10 ALIGN=right>

   There is no conventional way to classify <B>Alias Grace</B> (Talese/Doubleday, $24.95), Atwood's 41st book and
ninth novel, although it certainly borrows from several literary
genres, historical fiction, the murder mystery and the Victorian

thriller among them.<P>

  "It is not a murder mystery, it is a mystery about a
murder," the 56-year-old author made clear during a recent
interview."In a murder mystery you have to come up with the
solution, or the readers will rise up against you. You can't just
end it by saying, 'Well, I don't know.'"<P>

   The salient point to make in this context is that if Atwood
has any firm opinion about what actually happened in the matter
of Grace Marks more than a century and a half ago, she has no
intention of letting on now, either within the pages of her book
or in conversation.<P>

   Providing a premise for <B>Alias Grace</B> are the fragmentary
facts surrounding the double murder on July 23, 1843, of Thomas
Kinnear, a wealthy Ontario land owner, and Nancy Montgomery, his
housekeeper and pregnant mistress. <P>

   Convicted of the brutal crimes were James McDermott, Kinnear's
manservant, and Grace Marks, a 16-year-old serving girl rumored
to have been romantically involved with her employer. McDermott
was hanged on Nov. 23, 1843, protesting to the end that the
murders had been Grace's idea, although he had given numerous
other contradictory accounts of just what had happened.<P>

   Grace gave authorities several conflicting stories of her own,
one of which may have persuaded a jury to believe her insane and
to pronounce a sentence of life imprisonment, not death by
hanging. Also arguing in favor of sparing Grace's life were her
age and her sex.<P>


    But vexing doubts persisted: Was Grace, as she claimed, James
McDermott's hapless victim? Was she a scheming conspirator? Or
was she insane? These central questions have remained unanswered
for decades, and gave Atwood all the background she needed to
frame a multi-layered work of speculative fiction that goes well
beyond the boundaries of a "whodunit."<P>

   Atwood's interest in the case was sparked by the 19th-century
writings of a woman named Susanna Moodie, an English emigrant who
wrote a number of books about life in Canada, including one in
which she described two meetings with Grace Marks. One of these
took place in the Kingston Penitentiary, the other was conducted
in the Toronto Lunatic Asylum, where Grace stayed briefly.<P>

  "I wrote a television play for Canadian television in 1974
about Grace called <B>The Servant Girl</B>, but I used only one
source, the one provided by Susanna Moodie, which I thought at
that time to be completely accurate," Atwood said. <P>

  "As it turned out, her version was seriously flawed. When I
realized that people have been fictionalizing this story from the
word go, it became interesting to me as a novel. They all had
their biases, they all had their own slants, they took sides. It
was like the Lizzie Borden case here in the United States."<P>

   For her work on this novel, Atwood became a scholar,
researching not only every piece of information she could find
about the trial, but material that revealed how people lived and
thought in 19th-century Canada, and material that gave insight
into pre-Freudian concepts of mental illness.<P>

   One of the characters Atwood created for the novel is Dr.
Simon Jordan, an American physician whose studies in unconscious
mental processes lead people who believe in Grace's innocence to
retain his services. <P>

   Dr. Jordan's meetings with Grace take place in 1859, when the
novel is set. The novel is presented alternately from their
points of view, with Grace narrating her version of events in the
first person, and Dr. Jordan's in the third. The interaction
between the two characters is an essential element in the novel,
and contributes measurably to Atwood's clever resolution.<P>

 "As a fiction writer, it helps me a whole bunch that so much
remains unknown," Atwood said."One ironclad rule I imposed on
myself was that if there was a clear fact, I couldn't change it.
It's a bit of game theory I have about the process. It's not real
if you cheat. But where there are no facts in the record, I give
myself the freedom to invent."<P>

   Citing one example, Atwood said that it would have been
wonderful for her purposes if Grace had been present at
McDermott's execution. "The date he was hanged is known, and
Grace was already in the penitentiary. That would have been a
pretty dramatic scene, watching this person that you may or may
not have been having an affair with, that you may or may not have
helped to kill somebody, dying. Too bad for me."<P>

   In the end, however, it was the continuing uncertainty about
the case that Atwood found most appealing. "The things that
interest me were not necessarily the things that would have
interested somebody writing about the case then. I'm interested
in the ambiguities. They were interested in the certainties,
which they made up even if they were not available."<P>

   Readers who seek parallels between <B>The Handmaid's Tale</B> and
<B>Alias Grace</B> will find Atwood's continuing concerns with
women's identity and domestic relationships, giving each book a
contemporary resonance.
   "We cannot help but be contemporary," Atwood said, quoting
her distinguished countryman, the late Robertson Davies. "No
matter where we set our books, or when we set them, we can't help
it. All fiction is about when it is written. And it happens that
I'm a late 20th century person."
<HR>
<blockquote>
<A HREF="mailto:NabatLfs@aol.com">Nicholas A. Basbanes</A> is a Massachusetts journalist and author
of <I>A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the
Eternal Passion for Books</I>.
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<HR><BR>

<a href="features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>    


  


</BODY>
