<head>
<title>george jr. / february 1997 / arcadia / poem by david baker</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoab.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>

<H2>muddying the waters</H2>
<BR>

<B>by colin hamilton </B>
<BR>
<HR>

	<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=4 CELLPADDING=4>

<TR VALIGN=Top>
<td><FONT SIZE=4><B>Plainwater, </b></font size=4> by Anne Carson, bears the subtitle "Essays and Poems."  One can't blame her table of contents for not distinguishing the two.  In this five-part collection, prose passages are often lyrical descriptions of subjective experience, while the verse lines tend to shoulder the analytical weight. <P>
 What interests Carson, however, is not formal distinctions, but the possibility of breaking down genres; in her title, and is as essential as essays or poems.  She succeeds in that--at the books most riveting moments -form is truly an instrument, a language in itself and not merely a justification.  At times original and haunting, Plainwater is weakest when written to challenge our conventions for the sole sake of experiment.<P>

	What unifies<B> Plainwater</B> is hard to say.  "The Anthropology of Water," which fills the last 138 of the book's 260 pages, seems complete in itself.  This section is comprised of three parts, each a journey reported in the form of a journal.  The first is a pilgrimage taken by Carson and a man she refers to as "my Cid" to Compostela, Spain.  The second is a cross-country drive taken with "the Emperor of China."  The third concerns her brother, who will, we're told, eventually disappear into a series of postcards sent from ever more exotic places and finally silence.  <P>

	Throughout "The Anthropology of Water," one hears the hyper-conscious, critical mind of an author who is, nonetheless, dependent upon her subjects and unable to dismiss them with a clinical intelligence.  In Lawrence, Kansas she writes:<BR>
<blockquote>

Enlightenment is useless but some of its principles are not--for example, unconventionality.  This means if you see someone struggling, help him don't ask what the object is.   A million maggots in a silk hat, says classical Chinese wisdom.  The emperor likes the idea of making love to women fitted with false penises.  I try not to neglect anything that is part of him.  It is rather like watching somebody die. (page 203)
</blockquote>
Each journey has its inevitable disaster.  The role of intelligence is to deny the disaster, to qualify it, to disarm it, while still documenting its approach.  These are frightening, moving narratives whose author never flinches before their blows.<P>

	But this tone is not sustained throughout the book.  In fact, it is only achieved at the end.  <B>Plainwater</B> rushes from the cerebral poetics of "Mimnermos: The Brainsex Paintings" through the jargony academics of "Canicula di Anna" to end on the lyric and elegiac prose of "The Anthropology of Water," the book's high point.  Though her virtuosity is evident in each case, its necessity is not.  This is most true in "Canicula di Anna," which chronicles a convention held in Italy and allows itself such banal commentary as:<BR>

<blockquote>
Famous phenomenologists of tutta l'Italia
have foregathered here.
They take things back to the sophists
then climb the stone stairs
for a heavy lunch.
Their foreheads are not so tall
as the foreheads
of French phenomenologists
but they are much more good natured. 
(page 53)
</blockquote>
A reader hears Stevens' rationalists in their square hats, but "good natured" is far more sterile than "sombreros."  Though one may wonder what hats acrobats or grave diggers may wear, this poem does not lead a reader to ask about the foreheads of Dutch or Chinese phenomenologists.<P>

	The other two sections, "Short Talks" and "The Life of Towns," are the collection's most successfully experimental works, synthesizing form and content.  "Short Talks" is comprised of 31 short prose poems, usually less than one hundred words written in school-house blocks which attempt to frame the lunging logic she brings to such subjects as hedonism, waterproofing and walking backwards.  She has this to say on the  Mona Lisa:<BR>
</blockquote>

Every day he poured his question into her, as you pour water from one vessel into another, and it poured back.  Don't tell me he was painting his mother, lust, et cetera.  There is a moment when the water is not in one vessel nor in the other--what a thirst it was, and he supposed that when the canvas became completely empty he would stop.  But women are strong.  She knew vessels, she knew water, she knew mortal thirst. 
(page 37, line breaks inexact)
</blockquote>
	"The Life of Towns" maps 36 "towns" such as "Apostle Town" or "Town of Greta Garbo."  Each town is written in lines which begin with a capital and end on a period, no matter how the sentences fall, foregoing all other punctuation.  In sections such as "Town of the Sound of a Twig Breaking" this fragmenting effect intensifies the language around it:<BR>
<blockquote>

Their faces I thought were knives.
The way they pointed them at me.
And waited.
A hunter is someone who listens.
So hard to his prey it pulls the weapon.
Out of his hand and impales.
Itself.
(page 104)
</blockquote>
	Carson is a classicist by training, and one not only senses her admiration of broken jars and half tablets, but comes to share it when her fragments reveal glimpses into elliptical, revelatory truths which would be buried by the whole.  One is tempted to say that is exactly what happens to this book's best parts: They are smothered by the dull. <P>
 <B>Plainwater</B> is frustrating as only something which rises to daring heights can be. Fortunately, in this collection the good does out-weight the bad, though stricter editing would have kept the scales at bay.  Three of its sections, most of the book, are not only wonderful, but unlike anything you've read.  It's other two sections read like several things you never bothered to finish.<P>


<TD><font color=red><B>book review</B><br>
<SUB>
<HR>

<B>Plainwater: Essays and Poetry</B><BR>

by Anne Carson<BR>

Knopf, 1995<BR>

260 pages, $23<BR>
<HR>
</font></sub>
</CENTER>
</TABLE>


<HR>
<blockquote>
<B>Colin Hamilton</B> lives in Kent, Ohio. Next month, he'll be writing here about Jorie Graham.
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
	
	
