<blockquote>

<H4>court report:</H4>


<H2>great moments 
 in panty hose jurisprudence</H2>
<BR>


<B>by richard grayson</B>
    <BR><BR>

<HR WIDTH="75%">
<BR>




<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=4 CELLPADDING=4>

<TR VALIGN=Top>
<td><FONT SIZE=4><B>As a staff attorney</font></b> and Visiting Assistant in Law Research at the 
Center for Governmental Responsibility at the College of Law at the 
University of Florida here in Gainesville, I was the recipient in 
October 1995 of a $47,500 grant from The Namath Foundation to study 
changing legal attitudes toward undergarments.  Perhaps the most 
fascinating subject of my research centered on one of the most recent 
innovations, panty hose.<P>


    Many times since the invention of panty hose, American courts 
have been called upon to make momentous legal decisions involving 
this item of clothing.  These decisions should be of interest to the 
lay public as well as to legal scholars.  Herewith I would like to 
present the following rulings as the most crucial.<P>


    (Those wishing to acquire the full 270-page report I presented to 
the Foundation on January 15, 1997 -- only seven months late -- may 
write to<A HREF="mailto:GRAYSON@LAW.UFL.EDU">me</A> for ordering information.)<P>

<IMG SRC="hose1.jpg" WIDTH=123 HEIGHT=97 vspace=10 hspace=10 ALIGN=left>
    In a groundbreaking 1969 opinion that marked the first federal 
appellate court ruling on the subject, the U.S. Court of Appeals for 
the Second Circuit decided a trademark dispute between a manufacturer 
that planned to bring out a line of panty hose with the Kiki label 
and the holder of the Kiki trademark for a line of tights.  On the 
basis of the evidence presented, the court found that panty hose and 
tights were not equivalent because panty hose show the leg through 
the material while tights are opaque and can be worn as outerwear.  
The ruling in Kiki Undies Corp. v. Promenade Hosiery Mills, 411 F. 2d 
1097 (2nd Cir. 1969), set the tone for future federal court opinions.<P>

    
    For example, following the precedent of Kiki Undies, seven years 
later the Fourth Circuit held that a patent covering a "combination 
panty and stocking" was in fact describing what has come to be known 
as panty hose.   However, it was the court's judgment in Tights, Inc. 
v. Acme-McCrary Corp., 541 F. 2d 1047 (4th Cir. 1976), that this 
patent did not cover all such garments but was restricted by its 
terms to those panty hose constructed with a single U-shaped seam 
running from front to back through the crotch area and having no 
intervening crotch-piece.<P>


    More recently, in another civil action, Kocienski v. City of 
Bayonne, 757 F. Supp. 457 (D. N.J. 1991), a federal district court 
judge in New Jersey ruled against the plaintiff, the administratrix 
of the estate of her sister, who committed suicide in the Bayonne 
Municipal Jail by hanging herself with her panty hose.  The court 
found that decedent's death was not the result of negligence on the 
part of jail personnel, who had failed to remove her panty hose when 
they took her earrings, shoelaces, and a gold chain prior to her 
incarceration.  <P>


    In contrast, a federal judge was called upon to interpret a 
contract dispute between two parties in Doral Hosiery Corp. v. Sav-A-
Stop, Inc., 377 F. Supp. 387 (E.D. Pa. 1974).  The court held that a 
provision regarding amortization applied to all the defendant's panty 
hose, not merely those bearing the Sheer-to-the-Waist label.<P>


    Panty hose has also been the subject of prominent criminal cases. 
 Early on, in a 1975 prosecution for larceny, State v. Carter, 211 
S.E. 2d 813, 24 N.C. App. 688 (1969), the Court of Appeals of North 
Carolina upheld the defendant's conviction, ruling that the trial 
court was not in error when it permitted a witness to testify 
concerning the value of four cartons of panty hose which had been 
stolen.<P>


    In another appeal from a criminal conviction, Stoppleworth v. 
State, 501 N.W. 2d 325 (N.D. 1995), the Supreme Court of North Dakota 
found that defendant's counsel was not ineffective in the testing of 
a pair of panty hose to determine whether a foot had been cut off 
while wearing the garment.  The court noted that it was evident from 
the testimony that there were strategic and tactical considerations 
in the attorney's decisions regarding the panty hose and upheld the 
conviction.<P>


    However, based on testimony that witnesses could not ascertain 
whether the defendant was wearing both legs of panty hose or only a 
single leg during the robbery of a pizza restaurant, the Court of 
Appeals of Ohio overturned the conviction of the defendant in State 
v. Jackson, 621 N.E. 2d 710, 86 Ohio App. 3d 568 (Ohio App. 1993).  <P>


   Perhaps the most recent appellate ruling involving panty hose is 
a decision by a New Jersey state court, which found that the 
plaintiff in Liptak v. Rite Aid, Inc., 673 A. 2d 309, 289 N.J. Super. 
199 (N.J. App. Div. 1996), who was held by store personnel after 
being accused of stealing coupons from panty hose packages, had 
established a prima facie case of unlawful detention because a 35 
cents-off coupon did not meet the legal definition of merchandise.<P>


    Undoubtedly, this is not the American judiciary's last word on 
the subject of panty hose.  With several wearers of panty hose now 
sitting on the United States Supreme Court, a landmark opinion may be 
expected in the near future as judicial attitudes regarding the 
undergarment continue to evolve.<P>

<TD><CENTER><IMG SRC="hose2.jpg" WIDTH=76 HEIGHT=128 ></center>
<CENTER><BR>
<SUB>
<font color=red><A HREF="http://www.rainorshine.com/weather/index/sites/national?site=&city=Gainesville+FL"><font color=red>Gainesville Weather</font></A><BR><BR>
<A HREF="http://apparelex.com/bluebook/hos_171.htm"><font color=red>Hosiery Suppliers</font></A><BR>
<BR>

<A HREF="http://www.projectcool.com/focus/"><font color=red>Future Focus<font></A><BR><BR>
<SUB>

<A href="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Ct/fedcourt.html#usappeals"><font color=red>United States Courts of Appeals</A><BR>
<BR>


<A href="http://www.law.emory.edu/1circuit"><font color=red>First Circuit</A>
<BR>
<BR>

<A href="http://www.law.pace.edu/legal/us-legal/judiciary/second-circuit.html"><font color=red>Second Circuit</A><BR>
<BR>


<A href="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Ct/ca03.html"><font color=red>Third Circuit</A><BR>
<BR>


<A href="http://www.law.emory.edu/4circuit"><font color=red>Fourth Circuit</A><BR>
<BR>


<A href="http://www.law.utexas.edu/us5th/us5th.html"><font color=red>Fifth Circuit</A><BR>
<BR>


