<HTML><HEAD>
<title>george jr. / february 1997 / departments / ask kitty  </title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/feb97/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<BR>
<br clear=all><BR>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<br><br> 'Tis February, and dear <A HREF="mailto:AskKitty@georgejr.com">Ask Kitty</A> has been working overtime - solving troubles, bringing joy and fixing broken water pumps everywhere. She is just too dang shy to tell you much about herself - such as, for two weeks in January she performed at Kingston Mines and B.L.U.E.S. in Chicago's North Side. Well, perhaps <B>george jr.</B> should devote a biographical page to the wonder who is Kitty. In the meantime, don't forget to <A HREF="mailto:AskKitty@georgejr.com">Ask Kitty.</A>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR>
<blockquote>

<FONT SIZE=5>	q.</FONT>
 I am a sentimental person who loves to celebrate romantic holidays like
Valentine's Day.  My partner, however, is not.  What can I do about this?<P>

<FONT SIZE=5>	a.</FONT> If I am correct in assuming that you have more power than a
household pet, the solution is pretty easy.  Take matters into your own hands.  Make dinner
reservations (or weekend reservations at a bed-and-breakfast) for two, decorate
the house, rent a steamy movie, whatever makes YOU happy.  Hell, buy yourself a
nice outfit or piece of jewelry if you can afford it.  The point is not to be
spiteful, simply proactive (don't you love that word, left over from 1980's
psycho-babble?).<P>

  Let your partner know what you are doing and that it is important to
you.  Invite him or her to join you in your celebration of romantic love.  DON'T beg
or accuse; you shouldn't have to constantly audition for your partner's
affection.  And DON'T try (or expect) surprises.  If your partner doesn't think on the
same lines as you in this respect, you are only setting yourself up for a major
disappointment.  Respect yourself, and make the occasion fun.<BR>
<BR>



<FONT SIZE=5>	q</FONT>. I am at my wits end with someone whom I thought was a good
friend.  We've shared a lot, and this person occupies a special place in my heart.  But our
friendship has become trying for me.  He only contacts me when he wants
something from me, at which time he invokes our friendship, and makes everything seem ok. 
But he doesn't follow through on his pledge of friendship.  I feel used and
stupid, but am not sure how to approach this touchy subject.<P>


<FONT SIZE=5>	a.</FONT> The institution of friendship has taken a hard hit in the late
twentieth century.  Time was when friendship was a sacred trust, and ties between
friends ran as strong as those of family.  We all got out of our houses more; had
a sense of community and loyalty.  Now we waste our time driving from one barren
landscape to another, isolated from people to care about, things to care about, places
to care about.  Friends have become as disposable as yesterday's gadgets and the
prefab houses we live in.  
	If you have tried to communicate your sense of hurt and
disappointment with your friend, and you continue to see the same patterns that are hurting your
spirit, try putting your friendship on long-term hold.  Maybe a few years (or
decades) down the road your friend will rediscover his priorities and you two can
renew a healthy exchange of friendship.  <BR>
<BR>


<FONT SIZE=5>	q</FONT>. My boss gave me a few breaks at an important juncture in my
career, breaks for which I am very grateful.  But I've noticed that others in my
workplaceoepeople who work very hard and produce good workoedon't get the same breaks, and
in fact are treated downright unfairly.  I am conflicted as to where my loyalty
should lie, and what I should do.<P>

	<FONT SIZE=5>a.</FONT> Start making your plans for a graceful exit.  If you can't muster
up the courage to confront the situation, you don't need to commit career
suicide, or turn on the person who gave you your big break.  
But get real.  How long can you stomach such a work culture?  And
should you see the writing
on the wall?  Many a privileged denizen of upper management has sold his soul for
a great job, only to be dumped when his management style (or hairstyle) goes out
of fashion. It's not easy leaving a Faustian situation, but do it.  Your soul
will thank you. <BR>
<BR>


<FONT SIZE=5>	q.</FONT> I always get depressed at this time of year.  What can I do
about it?<P>

<FONT SIZE=5>	a.</FONT> If it's a yearly but tolerable situation (Seasonal Affective
Disorder[SAD]-get it?-I think they call it), try doing a few things to help
you get
through it until the sun comes back in the Spring.  Here are a few ideas:<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
1.<B> Make some little healthy changes</B> in your life, and stick to them.  Go
for a walk first thing in the morning, for example, or get lost in a silly novel
every night before you go to sleep.<P>

2.<B> Pay attention to your body</B>: eat healthy, fresh foods, avoid alcohol,
and get a little exercise.<P>

3. <B>Return to things that have inspired you</B> in the past.  Reading an old
book of poetry, looking at the work of a familiar artist, or visiting a
favorite place can be renewing exercises.<P>

4. <B>Plan for the future. </B> Read seed catalogues, start making plans for your
summer vacation, or plot out projects you can pursue in the warmer weather.
Keep in mind that these activities are simply ways to treat the symptoms of
"the winter blues." </BLOCKQUOTE> If you sense that your depression is more than the above
suggestions can remedy, SEE YOUR DOCTOR.  Don't wallow too deeply in Dostoyevskian
despair before you get help.<BR>
<BR>


<FONT SIZE=5>	q.</FONT> Do you follow a beauty regimen?  I like expensive
department-store beauty products, and things like that, but wonder if I'm just being duped by the
oppressive powers of Madison-Avenue media hype.<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>
	a.</FONT> There's no doubt that "Madison Avenue" has played a harshnumber on most individuals' self-image.  We're all too fat, we smell, our noses are too
big, our lips lack definition, and our skin is imperfect.  We seek to cure these
media-produced ills by buying more and more silly, not to mention expensive, products,
which are flaunted in front of us constantly whether we try to avoid them or not.
	But hey, I'm not above indulging in a little luxury.  I adore
getting facials and body massages, and there is little else that makes me feel better than
having a great haircut.  And even though every dermatologist I have ever spoken to
tells me it's pointless, I still cleanse, tone, and moisturize (plus smear a few
placebos over my face) twice daily. After all, everyone needs a little vice in
her life.<P>

</blockquote>



<HR><BR>

<a href="/feb97/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>
