<title>george jr. / february 1997 / departments / letter from austin </title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<BR clear=all>
<HR>
<blockquote>
<BR>

<H4>letter from austin:</H4>
<H2>doing the 'la boh&egraveme'</H2>
<BR>
<B>by jeanne claire van ryzin</B>

<br clear=all><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=4 CELLPADDING=4>
<TR VALIGN=Top>

<td>

<IMG SRC="austin.jpg" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=149 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10>
<FONT SIZE=4><B> In 1986</B></FONT>, a group of Austin mavericks flagrantly ignored the then-bottomed out

Texas economy and launched the <A HREF="http://www.austin360.com:80/community/opera/index.htm">Austin Lyric Opera</A>, the city's first professional
opera company.  As it enters its 10th season, ALO can boast 26 productions
staged, an annual budget of more than $2.7 million a year, and the auspicious role as
one of the largest fine arts employers in Central Texas.  <P>
The three-opera season
is the hottest ticket with Austin flaunting an attendance of 35 for every 1,000
residents - more than three times the opera-going rate of some similarly sized
cities
in America - as well as regularly sold-out performances.  The company has
relied on
a repertoire of well-known operas - <b>La Traviata, Madama Butterfly, The
Magic Flute,
and Don Giovanni</b> - but also had the chutzpah to stage
<b>Tannh&aumluser</b> with a set evoking
a destroyed freeway and to advertise <b>The Ballad of Baby Doe</b> - Douglas
Moore's opera
based on the true-life sturm-und-drang of Colorado silver baron Horace Tabor and
his wife Baby Doe - with the admonishment  "No line dancing, please."
<P>



ALO's success is hardly surprising as Austin had really no need of a
promptbook to discover
that opera would satisfy its every demand for divertissement.  A city
characterized by a surplus of attitude, an excess of education, an abundance of
curiosity, and a litany of justifications for everything it does, Austin bears
the perfect profile.  When ALO launched its first season, every homegrown
aficionado, displaced New Yorker, or misplaced European, weary of traveling
elsewhere for a performance fix, emerged in triumph. Every<i> parvenu</i> buff and
patron claimed to have loved opera all along.  The excess of sweeping
characters,
the artifice of the drama, the minutiae of the attendant trivia, the style and
the gossip, all appealed to an audience who, in a newsletter distributed
before a
recent performance, read with equal attention the <b>Psychic Table of Rich White
Trash in Love</b> comparing the Horace Tabor/Baby Doe scandal to the Donald
Trump/Marla Maples affair, along with the more staid background notes.
<P> Also of
enormous importance to Austin, the opera provides the city with one of its few
opportunities to dress up as evidenced by the habiliment seen in the lobby
during
intermission:
<br>
<ul>

<LI><b><i>Slacker</i>  beget <i>Rent</i></b>
<br>
Cheap tickets plus a large population of students and other
slightly disenfranchised youth equals a crop of opera-going
twenty-somethings for
whom "dressed up" means black tights without holes, a new lime green vinyl
purse,
polished jewelry for pierced body-parts, and freshly touched up purple coifs.
<br>
<LI><b>Putting on the Dog</b>
<br>
Damn the animal rights activists, fur speed ahead.  Dozens of
fur coats fill the dress circle seats on opening nights reminding us that
politically correct Austin - despite the fact that the only Neiman-Marcus in its
city limits is an outlet store - still shares the same state as Dallas.
<br>
<IMG SRC="austin2.jpg" WIDTH=82 HEIGHT=220 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
<LI><b>Rode hard and put away wet</b>
<br>
 One opening night, seated amongst the donors and
doyennes, were two long tall cowboys in boots, chaps, dusters, and hats.  "They
said that after years of owning a profitable ranch, they were now spending their
time traveling the world and seeing opera," shrugged one ALO official who talked
to the duo during an intermission.  "You should see the way the stare at us when
we go to the Met!" the cowboys guffawed.
<br>
<LI><b>Don't like the weather? Wait 10 minutes</b>
Seasons don't abide by any schedule in Austin where a sudden Blue Norther
can plummet the temperature 30
degrees in a matter of hours or six inches of rain will dump from the sky in an
hour and produce flash floods powerful enough to float a Chevy Suburban.
Hence a
spaghetti strap peach-colored summer formal dress makes an unabashed
display on a
frigid January night, while on a balmy March evening, the fur coats make an
encore appearance in the dress circle.  With climate-controlled environments,
every place can be summer, or winter, for 15 minutes.
<br>
<LI><b>Anti-attire</b>
<br>
The mezzanine and balcony sections fill with aging hippies,
distracted university types, New Agers too serene to care, along with other
members of the habitually under-dressed who just, well, wear something clean or
something sensible.
<br>
<LI><b>Leave your personality at the tone</b>
<br>
 Beepers, cellular phones, pocket computers,
and digital watches must be turned off during opera performances, leaving male
cyber-types togged out, wide-eyed, and twitching in ill-fitting suits and theme
ties.
<br>
<LI><b>Big Hair 'N Beads dates the Texas Tuxedo</b>
<br>
Women in Big Texas Hair and sparkling bead-encrusted jewel-toned dresses
are escorted by men donning the Texas Tuxedo:
a typical tuxedo coat and shirt with a cumber bum replaced by a plate-sized belt
buckle tops creased jeans tucked inside well-polished cowboy boots.
</ul>
<P>
Such eclectic garb reflects the flux of a city always in the process of deciding
what it wants to be:  a liberal university town; a counter-cultural eco-correct
mecca; an emerging metropolis of the Southwest; a slick hub of cyber-business;
or, all of the above.  Yet such flux, which would throw any ordinary citizenry
into confusion about knowing what to wear, hardly seems to present a sartorial
conundrum for a city where even donning a t-shirt, however absent-mindedly,
becomes one's very own public statement of personal identity.<BR>

<TD><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="cowboy2.gif" WIDTH=61 HEIGHT=70>
</center>
<CENTER><SUB><BR>

<font color=red><A HREF="http://www.rainorshine.com/weather/index/sites/national?site=&city=Austin+TX"><font color=red>Austin Weather</font></A><BR><BR>


<A HREF="http://www.austin360.com/attitude/attitop.htm"><font color=red>Attitude, Austin</font></A><BR>

 Information on java joints,
 cigars, tattoos & piercing, Austin
 neighborhods, and  the answer to why
 millions of Mexican free-tail bats spend their summers under Austin's Congress Avenue bridge.<BR><BR>


 <A HREF="http://www.austinlinks.com/"><font color=red>Austin City Links</font></A>:<BR>
Everything cool
 in Austin, from the folks at Quadralaly.<BR>
<BR>

 <A HREF="http://www.toyjoy.com/"><font color=red>Toy Joy</font></A><BR>
 Where Austin shops for 
Virgin of Guadalupe mousepads and other important relics.<BR><BR>

 <B>Pix:</B> <BR>
That photo you're wondering about is <A HREF="mailto:jcvanryzin@mods.com">Jeanne Claire</A>, oh, a little bit of time ago.</font></SUB></CENTER>
</TABLE>

<HR>
<blockquote>
<A HREF="mailto:jcvanryzin@mods.com">Jeanne Claire van Ryzin</A> knows the horizon goes every which way in Austin, which she studies all hours of the day and night - so that you might know what she knows. She is a fiction writer and director  of information at the University of Texas' Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center. 

</blockquote>


</blockquote>

<br>
<HR>

<a href="departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
