<HTML><HEAD>
<title>george jr. / february 1997 / departments / letter from key west </title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR>
<BR>
<BR>
<blockquote>
<H4>letter from key west:
</H4>


<H2>rockets red glare</H2>
<BR>

    <B>
by patrick a. lennon</B>

<BR>
<BR>


<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=4 CELLPADDING=4>

<TR VALIGN=Top>
<td>


<FONT SIZE=4><B>If you're planning </B></FONT>to visit the Florida Keys, you might spend
more time in your automobile than snorkeling the reefs.  The
Department of Defense is going to halt traffic on US 1 while they
fire rockets from north Florida and intercept them with rockets
launched from the Keys.  In addition to the beautiful sunsets we
have, now you will be able to actually watch a mini Star Wars.
I'll bet Disney will be jealous since their rockets are so puny.<P>



Not everyone, including me, is excited about this turn of events.
Having fired a few rockets when I was a pilot in the Air Force, I
know they can zig when they're supposed to zag.  Our island
communities have enough problems with power failures, lousy cable
TV, a fragile water supply and the National Atmospheric and
Oceanic Administration.<P>

<IMG SRC="keywestpatrick.jpg" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=220 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
Congress, in its wisdom, decided to save the Keys.  They
established the Florida Keys Marine Sanctuary to be Administered
by NAOA.  This past November in a straw poll, Keys residents
voted it down.  We're not anti-environmental.  Actually, some of
us are tree-huggers.  We just want the current layers of
bureaucracy (Federal, State and County) to enforce existing laws,
thank you very much.  NAOA took note of the negative vote and
ignored it.<P>


But, the Federal mill keeps grinding out more and more
regulations.  As of now the regulations for recreational and
commercial use of the waters surrounding the Keys is about a foot
thick.  Our Congressman, who is actually a pretty nice chap, is
not straddling the fence, he is on both sides of the fence at the
same time.  He's in a no-win situation.<P>


I've researched the new regulations and haven't found anything
permitting or denying rockets being shot into the Sanctuary.
Since the Sanctuary will be under Federal control, I suppose the
Federal Government would rather launch rockets where it's warm
and sunny than in some isolated part of the world.  My greatest
concern is that the rockets were built by the low bidder, so I'll
keep my head down.<BR>
<BR>

<TD><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="snorkel2.gif" WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=80></center>
<CENTER><SUB><BR>

