<h2><A HREF="gambit.html">opening gambit:</A></h2>
An introduction, sort of. Art. Books. Music. Politics. Georgefoolery. Software updates.  Rocket fuel, July flowers and mayhem for E Pluribus You-num. 
<P> 
<h2><A HREF="qaedna.html">q & a:</a></h2>
Hot-as-Miami novelist Edna Buchanan  talks about murder most foul.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="qaedvard.html">q & a:</a></h2>
Tsar Nicholas II biographer Edvard Radzinsky says Russia is in the throes of a Stalinist revival, and there will be hell to pay.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="npr3.html">national public rodeo:</A></h2>
A  weekly roundup on art, books, music and software culture - for the wired. 
Updated Sunday.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="sandkuhler.html">wrapping the reichstag:</A></h2>
Artist Iris Sandkuhler muses on her work with Christo, who would giftwrap the earth.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="bodett.html">class lecture:</A></h2>
We left a light on for novelist <A HREF="features.html#bodett">Tom Bodett</A>, who has been a National Public Radio commentator since 1984.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="visser.html">class lecture:</A></h2>
Candadian observer Margaret Visser talks about showering, and turns a tad red.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="eidus.html">fiction by janus eidus:</A></h2>
The two-time O. Henry Award winner and author of the highly acclaimed novels, <I>Urban Bliss</I> and <I>Faithful Rebecca</I>.  Her story, which previously appeared in <A HREF="features.html#dean"><I>Mondo James Dean</I></A> will be collected in a book of her stories that City Lights will publish next year.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="sanford.html">fiction by christy sheffield sanford:</A></h2>
Her work may be found at:
<blockquote>
<A HREF="http://www.purplefrog.com/~christy/red-mona/">Red Mona</A><BR>   
<A HREF="http://web.syr.edu/~drkeith/tap/tap.html">Hootenanny</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/ob/ob3/ob3.html">Oyster Boy</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://enterzone.berkeley.edu/ez/e6/articles/sanford/spring.html">Enterzone</A>
</blockquote>
<P>
<h2><A HREF="pelevin.html">fiction by victor pelevin:</A></h2>
The Moscow writer who won the 1993 Russian Booker Prize for his novel, <I>The Yellow Arrow</I>. The opening chapter is excerpted here.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="singer.html">fiction by  alan singer:</A></h2>
The author of <I>Memory Wax</I>, <I>The Charnel Imp</I> and director of the Graduate Creative Writing program at Temple University.
<P>
<h2><A HREF="coffee1.html">coffee break with georgette:</A> </h2>
A  little something to get you going, from our friend Sandy Andes.
<P><P><hr><P><P>
<a name=dean>Janus Eidus,  <I>Jimmy Dean: My Kind of Guy</I> previously appeared in the anthology, Mondo James Dean (St. Martin's, $13.95), compiled by Richard Peabody Jr. and Lucinda Ebersole. Her fiction is reprinted in  George Jr. Magazine with the kind permission of the author, who used to have a really cool leather jacket.
<P>
<a name=bodett>Tom Bodett hosts the radio program The End of the Road, lives in Alaska and serves as a contributing editor to Alaska magazine. 

