<html>
<head>
<title>george jr. / july 1996 / features / opening gambit</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<H2>opening gambit</H2>
<P>
Books. Music. Reviews. Art. Cyberville. <A HREF="npr1.html">Weekly news</A> about all of it. Outtakes. Pickups. Droplets. Found art. And Short-order cooks. Interviews.
<P>
<B><b>george jr. magazine</b></B> returns for Round 3 - and July - with hot interviews, stretch-the-envelope fiction, advice for the lovelorn and landlocked, cool art and graphics and up-to-the-week updates on culchah.
<P>
Which we like. Which we are.
<P>
Why, just the other day, certain members of the George Jr.  staff were singing, not quite in unison and not exactly harmoniously, the heartfelt but bloated and dreadful <A HREF="gambit.html#link">Lee Greenwood song, <i>I'm Proud to Be an American </i></A> - you know the old chestnut - until the cel of musical stooges split off into marketing  segments  and focus groups bent on discussing  the relationship of  bikinis to  beer and boats; and then the group downsized itself and went to lunch. Ah, so that's what an American is!
<P>
Well, well. We are nevetheless glad to have as a fellow American the ubiquitous  Martha Stewart, whose $200 million self-named empire of food, clothing,  gardening, mail-order and magazine business in a way gave rise, in a way, to George  Jr. Magazine.
<P>
Anybody can call their friends and <A HREF="sources.html">sources</A> and come up a magazine named after her or him, and enough news  to choke a hog, and we have done so again this month.  (Hogs, consider yourselves choked.) Consider the lillies of our field: fiction, art, reviews, whirligigs and jaw-snappers. James Dean. Christo. Ask Kitty. Tony Mendoza. Edna Buchanon. Hey, if you don't Bookmark us, well, we'd be surprised.
<P>
We're not  pumping irony here, just content. <b>george jr. magazine</b>   means to take over the world. Or at least your plate. May we please fill it repeatedly?
<P>
Click on.
<P>
<b>
FYI, george jr. has nothing whatsover to do with John F. Kennedy Jr.'s magazine, which he calls George.  We're pretty sure you could tell the there is a difference, but what the hey.
</b>
<P>
<HR>
<p>
<P>
<a name=link>
<B>Other things and people we're not  keen on:</B>
<ul>
<LI>Dolly Parton
<LI>The Grand Ol' Opry
<LI>Merle Haggard
<LI>Scrooge McDuck
<LI>Brutus
<LI>Sammy Davis recordings of<i> The Candyman</i>
</ul>
<P>
