<head>
<title>george jr. / july 1996 / features / q & a / edna buchanan</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/edna.jpg" WIDTH=186 HEIGHT=271 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 
<P>
EDNA BUCHANAN: <BR>
Up Close and Homicidal
<P>
Edna Buchanan's latest novel, <i>Act of Betrayal, </i> (Hyperion, $21.95) is her fourth whodunit starring Britt Montero, a police reporter with the fictional <i>Miami News. </i>Buchanon's other books are <i>Contents Under Pressure, Miam, It's Murder  </i> and <i>Suitable for Framing,  </i> She won the Pulitzer Prize in 1986 for general reporting at the<i>Miami Herald.</i>
<BR clear=all>
<hr width=75%>
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> What kind of writer do you think you would have become if you hadn't relocated to Miami?  Do you think you would have become a writer at all?
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font>I would have been a writer, but without my experience in Miami as a police reporter, the subject might have been less intense.  I feel certain that it would have been somewhat along the same lines, however.  Early on, I was fascinated by the dark princes of my childhood, The Mad Bomber, Willie (The Actor) Sutton, who was the Babe Ruth of bank robbers, and mobster Lucky Luciano.  When my grandfather died, I was still a small girl but my immediate response was: "Who killed him?"  It never occurred to me then that people do actually die of natural causes.  It's still a surprise to me.  Of course that may also say something about my grandfather and his personality.
<P>         
<font size=+3>q:</font> What have you found to be the most difficult aspect of making the transition from the police beat to fiction?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font>The only difficulty was when I began my first novel.  I had clamored to do it, it was my childhood dream, but when I got the chance, I panicked.  I kept glancing to the left, for my notebook.  It wasn't there of course. I was on my own.  I kept remembering what Hemingway once said: 'That anybody who writes novels should work first for a daily newspaper - but never for more than eighteen months.'
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> Hey, you went over the time limit.
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font>By nearly two decades.  But then  something  wonderful happened.  I had heard      other writers talk about  this, and it's true.  After four chapters or so, the characters suddenly sprang to life.  The villain became far more evil and treacherous than I had ever imagined.  I was shocked.  I would say, "Oh no!  Look what she's doing now!" to Flossie, my favorite cat     who sat on my lap while I wrote.  And a minor character, a middle-aged police  detective became really powerful and tried to take over the book.  I had to almost  physically grapple with him and force him back with the promise that he could  return later, as a lead character in a future book.  Which he did, as Dan Flood,  the dying detective, in Miami, It's Murder.   Oddly enough, both books were nominated for Edgars.
<P>
The best thing about the transition from the police beat to fiction is resolution. As a journalist, I covered murders that went unsolved forever, missing people  who stayed lost, corpses never identified no matter how hard I worked or how   many clues we unearthed.  Those cases haunt me.  But in fiction, I am in charge.  At last!  I can wrap up the  loose ends, solve all the perplexing mysteries and, best  of all,  write the endings.  I can make the good guys win and the bad guys get  what they deserve.  So unlike real life.
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font>  In your novels, you thrust Britt Montero into one life-threatening situation after   another.  How do her experiences  compare with your own?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font> Many of the threats I received as a reporter are actually carried out against Britt.  She is far more adept at surviving than I would be.  For example: I received  threatening letters from an elusive rapist.  Britt encounters one, up close and  homicidal.  I was threatened by the deranged mother of a man whose arrest I had    reported. Britt is attacked by the deranged, knife wielding mother of a killer. A  police official once predicted that I would be arrested some day for being too aggressive as a reporter.  So far, I have eluded capture.  But Britt was arrested --  on a murder charge.  I weathered a major hurricane, trapped in a house.  The   hurricane of the century traps Britt in a house -- with a serial killer -- in  Act of  Betrayal.  I am a reporter, a klutz, somebody who takes notes, not action.  Britt is strong, brave, agile, and athletic, all the things I would like to be.
<P>       
<font size=+3>q:</font>  Your novels are written with an amazing attention to detail.  What kind of research do you do in preparation for writing them?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font>  Old newsroom habits die hard.  I ride the midnight shift with the cops, go to the   morgue, to the lab.  When Britt was locked in the trunk of her car by the villain in  Miami, It's Murder,  I even climbed into the trunk of my own car and slammed the lid shut to see what it smelled like, how dark, cramped, and stuffy it was, and if I  could escape.  In my case, a friend stood by to rescue me, if necessary.  In Britt's case, the bad guys pushed the car, with her in the trunk, into a deep and murky Everglades canal and beat  feet out of there.  Poor Britt.
<P>          
<font size=+3>q:</font>  What's next in Britt's future?  Will she ever win journalism's big enchilada -the Pulitzer Prize?  
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font> I have big plans and adventures for Britt, in both her  personal and professional  lives.  She's already won a Green Eyeshade Award, which I won more than a decade ago.  I don't know about the Pulitzer.
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> Your style of writing has drawn raves and sold a few million books.  Pardon this rather standard question: Which  writers would you say have most influenced you?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font>It's hard to say.  I read everything, from cereal boxes to the flyers strangers shove   under my windshield wipers.  My favorite novel of all time is Raintree County  by Ross Lockridge, Jr. It's about American journalism, patriotism, and a star- crossed love affair a hundred years ago.  Like the Bible, you can pick it up, read  any page, and gain something.  It's poetry.  Forget the movie, if you saw it, the  book is something entirely different.
<P>         
<font size=+3>q:</font>  As a reporter, you've interviewed thousands of people throughout your career.  How does it feel to be on the other end?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font>Scary and intimidating.
<P>     
<font size=+3>q:</font> You are still officially on leave from the Miami Herald.  Do you plan to return?  Do you still want to cover the police beat?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font> I miss the good creative people in the newsroom and the interaction with cops and  crooks and people on the street.  Most of all, I miss the joy of constant    communication with the readers who would see my story in tomorrow's paper, or  Sunday's at the latest.  They wrote, they called, they showed up in the newsroom.       Everything is so different with books.  The process takes so long.  By the time  your work touches readers who respond, you are deep into the next book, or the one after that.  I miss the instant gratification.  I miss the Herald.   I want to be back out on my   beat.  But I have also wanted to write books since I was four years old, and this is my chance.  And it is impossible to cover so demanding a beat and  also write a novel.  Novels, unlike non-fiction, require an almost reclusive lifestyle.  You can't just put your notes aside and casually return later to where you left off.  At least I can't.  You must immerse yourself in the world of your  characters.  And when you succeed in doing that, you fear and resent anything  that interferes.  You want to see   everything through your characters' eyes.  When    you are on a roll,   working hard -- and the door bell rings, it's infuriating,  maddening.  You want to plunge a knife into the heart of whoever it might be.  The fuller brush man, your mother. . .
<P>          
<font size=+3>q:</font> The late Elizabeth Montgomery portrayed you in two made-for-television movies  based on The Corpse Had a Familiar Face.   Were you pleased with the results?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font> The scripts were abysmal, but I thought Montgomery was wonderful.  Even though I was told she was ill, I thought she would get well.  She was a  woman who made you believe in miracles and magic.  I'm so sad that we have  lost her.
<P>     
<font size=+3>q:</font>  Miami is so vivid in your novels that at times the city seems almost like a major  character.  Will your books always be set in Miami, and what is it that's so magic  about the city?
<P>     
<font size=+3>a:</font> It is mystical.  The first time I saw it was like coming home, as though this is  where I was meant to be.  It's the jumping off place.  Look at the map.  We are  down there at the very bottom.  People on the run, from the law, each other and   from their own personal demands, all wind up there eventually if they run long enough.  It's always been that way.  In recent years, people on the run from the  south, from wars and dictators and poverty and from their own personal demands  have also made Miami their destination.  And, of course, they all bring their  demons with them.  Then the temperature soars, the barometric pressure drops,  the full moon rises, and all hell breaks loose.  What a great place to be a writer.
<P>
<HR><BR>
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    
