<head>
<title>george jr. / july 1996 / features / q & a / edvard radzinsky</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/stalin.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=294 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2>
<P>
EDVARD RADZINSKY: <BR> 
Stalin's Return and the Great Amnesia
<P>
Edvard Radzinsky is the author of <i>Stalin  </i>(Doubleday, $30), the first 
in-depth biography of  the man who was known among his countrymen as  "the Boss."  Radzinsky  based  his book on newly released documents from Russia's  secret archives and in-depth interviews. His previous work was <i>The Last Star,  </i>a biography of Tsar  Nicholas II.
<P>
<br clear=all>
<hr width=75%>
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> More than 40 years have passed since Stalin's death, and yet his name 
and face seem to be appearing with remarkable frequency in news stories 
coming out of Russia. Is there a rebirth of interest in Stalin - or even perhaps a rebirth of the Stalin "cult"?
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font> The restoration of his cult is already underway in Russia. A demonstration held on May 9, 1995 confirmed it. The 50,000 demonstrators  sang songs from the Stalin era as they proceeded from the Belorussian  Station, through the main streets of Moscow, to Mayakovsky Square.
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> The first time since his death?
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font>   For the first time since his death, dozens of portraits of Stalin floated  by, held aloft over the heads of the demonstrators. Communists, monarchists and Russian fascists marched side by side, at one in their devotion to the Boss. And rightly so. Was he not a greater  national-socialist than Hitler? Had he not created the greatest of  monarchist cults and enlarged the empire of the Romanovs? And had he not  served the Great Dream - a world in which Bolshevism reigned supreme.  Stalin had bided his time underground for more than 40 years. While those  of his victims who had survived the horrors of his reign of terror died  off one by one, and while their children grew old . . . But now that the  "Great Amnesia" had come upon the land, the Boss had risen from the grave.
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> The Communists made an impressive comeback in the last Parliamentry 
election, last year. Do you believe they're capable of regaining the country?
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font> Yes, for the first time since the fall of the Soviet empire this 
fearful specter has reappeared.
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> How is this possible?
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font> Stalin's current popularity - the first sign that communism can make a 
comeback in Russia, as it had in February 1917 - is a result of the 
weakness and lack of vision of democratic powers there, the bungling of 
the Russian bourgeoisie, and the people's thousand-year-old 
predisposition toward autocracy and slavery.
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> How does the Chechen situation - the repression of the independence 
movement there - fit in to this so-called Stalinist revival?
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font> It's an attempt to continue the same Stalinist imperialist policy of 
resolving matters through force and bloodshed. 
<P>
<font size=+3>q:</font> Oh, great.
<P>
<font size=+3>a:</font> The whole story is one of  blatant disregard for such notions as the sanctity of human life and the  right of people to self-determination.
<P>
<HR><BR>
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
