<head>
<title>george jr. / july 1996 / features / national public rodeo</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br><h3>NICHOLAS A. BASBANES INTERVIEWS JAY McINERNEY</h3>

   When ``Bright Lights, Big City'' was published in 1984, there was a
strong belief that the 20-something generation Jay McInerney was writing
about didn't read novels, let alone buy
very many of them.
<P>
   As a result, the decision was made by Vintage Books, a division of
Random House, to forego bringing out a hardcover edition of the young
author's hip take on the fast life in New
York City, and go directly instead with an inexpensive paperback version.
<P>   
``You could call what happened a desperate stab to reach an
audience,'' McInerney, now 41, said last week during an interview to
discuss publication of his fifth book, ``The Last of the
Savages'' ( Knopf,  $24), a hardcover release that demonstrates quite
persuasively that his readership encompasses a much wider demographic
spectrum now than initially
envisioned 12 years ago.
<P>   
``I was pretty nervous about going that original paperback route, but
two months after it was published, it was selling 20, 25, 30,000 copies a
week, and I think maybe I reached that
critical mass because I was in paperback first. Word of mouth carried
that book along for quite a while, and a lot of people who might not have
bought it in hardcover were willing to pay
$6.95 for a paperback. It finally sold about a million copies, and I'd be
crazy to argue with those figures.''
<P>
   Now, McInerney's books are reviewed in all of the major publications,
and the notices reflect a variety of attitudes, which is a healthy vital
sign for any author. But there remains the matter of his 1980s image, an
image forged not only by a wealth of immediate success, but by the
widespread notoriety his carefree social life occasioned.
<P>   
``It is true that I became a wildly over-celebrated author, and that a
lot of people still identify me with the kind of behavior and excess that
is now associated with New York in the
1980s,'' McInerney acknowledged. ``It also is true that I was made into a
scapegoat for the perceived sins of that era.''
<P>   
The two books that followed ``Bright Lights, Big City,'' ``Ransom''
and ``Story of My Life,'' seemed to reinforce the view held by some that
McInerney was destined to be a one-book wonder,
although newspapers continued to hum with gossip of his nocturnal wanderings.
<P>   
Publication in 1992 of his fourth novel, ``Brightness Falls,'' marked
a striking reversal, ``sparking evidence,'' according to one reviewer,
``of the author's maturation as a writer and of his talents as a
storyteller with a pronounced gift for dialogue.''
<p>   
Set in the days leading up to the Wall Street collapse of 1987, that
novel also represented McInerney's farewell to a tumultuous decade, an
artistic separation now made virtually
complete in ``The Last of the Savages.''
<P>   
In this new work, McInerney touches on the '80s, but he begins in 1965
and sweeps through three decades to the final years of the 20th century,
using the friendship of two boarding school
roommates as his vehicle.
<P>   
Patrick Keane, an Irish Catholic scholarship student who becomes a
successful New York lawyer, is the narrator; Will Savage, the son of a
wealthy Southern family, is blue-blood and
privileged to the core, but is driven only by a mission to produce the
music of African-American rhythm and blues singers.
<P>   
``This is my least autobiographical book in every way,'' McInerney
said, although he added that he sees parts of himself in each of the
characters. He also bridled at suggestions made by
several prominent reviewers that ``The Last of the Savages'' is his take
on F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby.''    ``I didn't have a model
for this book,'' he insisted. ```Gatsby' takes place over the course of a
summer, and the narrator in that book, Nick Carraway, is a man who hardly knew
Jay Gatsby; my book is about friendship, and about two guys who have
known each other for 30 years. If anything, it is more of a `Brideshead
Revisited' than it is a `Great Gatsby.'''
<P>   
Contentedly married now and the father of 18-month-old twins,
McInerney lives half the year in Tennessee just outside Nashville, and
spends the other six months in Manhattan. He admits finding the slower
change of pace agreeable to his writing, and to his peace of mind.
<P>      
``I didn't directly experience the '60s, so maybe this book is my '60s
envy,'' he said. ``My other books take place over a week or two, which in
New York can be almost a generation. I got kind
of inspired being in the South, and I wanted to do something different,
something from a historical perspective, with a strong Southern influence.''
<P>
   Hard at work now on his next novel, McInerney said he will return to
New York for the setting, but will people it with older characters.
``This will be a relatively short, relatively comic
novel that is tentatively titled `Model Behavior.' Oddly enough, it is
written in short sections, some in brief paragraphs; some are in first
person, some are in third person, and a couple are
even in second person.''
<P>
   Whether or not the work-in-progress represents a linear development in
his writing career is not something McInerney feels he can judge at this
point.    ``What I do know is that I am 41 years old and I have five
novels out there, and that's kind of exciting, regardless of what the
critics think,'' he concluded.
<P>      
``I would like it a lot if I didn't have to deal with the inevitable
backlash to my earlier success. But that is inevitable, I suppose, and I
wouldn't trade it for a normal career. The truth of the matter is that
it's been a very interesting life for me so far.''
<HR>
Nicholas A. Basbanes is a Massachusetts journalist and author. His book,
``A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the Eternal Passion
for Books,'' was a finalist this year for the
National Book Critics Circle Award in nonfiction.
<P>
   Until tomorrow, courage in every endeavor.
<P>
<HR><BR>
