<head>
<title>george jr. / july 1996 / features / iris sandkuhler</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/iris.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 align=left hspace=15 vspace=15>
<H2>Christo and Jeanne-Claude's<BR> 
Wrapped Reichstag:  An Insider's View</H2>
<P>
<H3>By Iris Sandkuhler</H3>
<P>
Iris Sandkuhler is an Assistant Professor of Art at Georgia Southern University.  The "Wrapped Reichstag" was her fifth project with Christo.  She has known the Christos for nearly 20 years.  Sandkuhler worked with the Christos on "Wrapped Walk Ways" (Loose Park, Kansas City, Missouri, 1977-78), "Surrounded Islands" (Biscayne Bay, Greater Miami, Florida, 	1980-83), "The Pont-Neuf Wrapped" (Paris, 1975-85), "The Umbrellas" (Japan-U.S.A., 1984-91), and, of course, "Wrapped Reichstag, Project" (Berlin, 1972-1995).
<P>
<BR clear=all>
<hr width=75%> 
<p>
When Jeanne-Claude told me I'd be Assistant to the Head of The Reichstag Project, Berlin, 1971-95,  I panicked and immediately started taking German classes.  Talking to my relatives was one thing, but telling strangers what to do was something else.  I studied hard and in a little more than a year found myself sitting at a conference table my first day on the job taking furious notes, trying to catch up to speed.  The meeting lasted five hours and was 95 percent German.  I became a consultant.  They asked me a lot of questions about what it was like on other projects, and how things worked.  Also questions about Jeanne-Claude and Christo's personalities.
<P>
Nine months later, the flavor of working on The Reichstag Project is the flavor of seeing how "my people" (Germans) think and behave in the  workplace.  There is also the lingering taste of Berlin and Russia by way  of (former) East Germans.
 <P>
June 7, 1995:  Gave last final and turned in grades.  Drove to  Atlanta.June 8:  Left in the p.m. for Berlin (changed planes in Zurich). June 9:  Arrived in Berlin.  Cold, raining, gray.  Sonja (a former Georgia Southern art student) picked me up.  I  swung by the project site to check it out.  There was already a skeletal structure (aesthetic) in place at the top of the building.  Found Wolfgang and said "hi."  Drove to Sonja's to settle in.  
 <P>
<B>EXCERPTS FROM MY JOURNALS</B>
<P>
<B>9:00 p.m.  Friday</B>. My first day here.  The cold rain has finally stopped and the air (or me) has finally warmed.  I had a traumatic shower aftermy long flight.  The hot water lasted about four minutes then became ICE cold.  And I mean ice.  It was painful beyond belief.  I was covered in soap and shampoo in a frigid room.  Something is wrong with the hot-water unit.  Suffered through the rinse cycle one body part at a time.
<P>
The household (all women) is on the second floor of a six-story complex.  Our windows look toward the inside of a giant, squared "O" building, the middle of which contains a playground, some parking and a lot of renovation garbage.  It's interesting cause most of the block-length building looks quite middle class, while our end of it is marred by graffiti (lots of anarchy signs), rubble, boarded-up (with any and all materials) windows and door ways.  It was such a shock for me to see all the garbage and graffiti.  Chunks of facades missing from buildings.  The neglect.  These buildings - unattractive rectangles for people to live in . . . This is a part of Germany that I've never seen or suspected, having always visited Munich, which is immaculately clean and conservative, and under the wing of my relatives.  Here it looks like a war happened and restoration is slow or nonexistent.
 <P>
This squat seems to run well.  If one cooks, one cooks automatically for 15 people.  Anything you want, you go in and eat.  People take turns grocery shopping . . . the members of the co-op/squat/commune contribute money every week.  Most of these people are (former) East Germans.  I now live in East Berlin.
 <P>
<B>June 10.</B>  Day No. 2 in Berlin.  Up at 7:30 - 8:00.  German coffee (could melt a spoon).  Hard rolls, cheese and butter.  Milk chocolate.  
 <P>
A group of the squatters bought a boat together, which they're refinishing.  I asked about it and the explanation was simple: They pitched in together because, alone, no one had the money to own a boat.   I realized the oddness of it: This was my first "real world" exposure to communism.  This part of it, at least, seemed to work. 
 <P>
Sonja took me to the subway where I bought a week's worth of tickets. They use the honor system, but occasionally spot-check.  With my maps, I  found my way to a main terminal "Alexander Platz".  That's where the communists built a giant space needle T.V. tower and spy station (to spy on West Berlin).  I changed to the above- ground train, which deposited me within eyesight of the Reichstag along the river.
 <P>
My meeting began at 10 a.m. and lasted till 3 p.m. without a break.  I still maintain I understand 70 percent, especially when they discuss one point for a half hour!  I'm being trained to deal with the Monitors.  The project is broken up into many categories - some of which are the press, construction, and monitors.  There will be 1,200 in two waves.  Today we worked out scheduling (shifts, training, rotation, pay, taxes, forms, ID, no shows) tote bags, uniforms, and meal tickets.  Stages of wrapping the building.  June 14, 15 training.  The 16th to hoist up the fabric. The 17th to do the roof. The 18th for the inner courtyards.  The 19th and 20th wrap facades.  Close to 1 million swatches will be given out when the project officially "opens", or is completed.
 <P>
One of the heads of the project, Roland, took me and another "guest worker" for a white bratwurst, and gave us a tour of the surrounding buildings that we will occupy for the project.  An (East) German government building will serve as the canteen.  The old interior is in a state of disrepair.  Stuff haphazardly stapled, glued or patched together 
but nothing restored.  Once elegant tiles covered with something that looks like fake wood shelf paper that squashes when you walk on it.  Doors cushioned with vinyl (obviously and carelessly stapled on) so no one could eavesdrop when government officials had meetings.  All this contrasted with a majestic marble staircase and statues.  Everywhere buildings are falling apart.  Garbage bins filled with rubble.  Old, 
broken down electrical things mixed in with the new.  Children playing in the heaps of scrap metal, plastic cars, chunks of cement, dangerous metal scraps . . .  I was home by 6 p.m.
 <P>
Another traumatic shower.  Again I was all soaped up when the heater went out and immediately delivered nothing but ice-cold water.  They said they'd fixed it.  Obviously not.  The weather's gotten colder.  Should have brought winter clothes.
 <P>
<B>June 11.</B>  Day No. 3 in Berlin.  Another good sleep.  Dragged myself out of my snug (mattress) bed on the floor in an ice-cold room.  Gazed down into the rubble filled courtyard as I was getting ready for work.  Saw a man hanging around, acting paranoid.  I was curious as to what he was up  to.  A few minutes later someone joined him.  They went off to the side, continually glancing around (but never glancing up, where I'd stepped  back from the window).  I suspected drugs.  Turned out to be cartons of cigarettes.  Black market cigarettes.  
 <P>
Yesterday it took me an hour and a half to get home from work.  Today just 45 minutes and I forgot my map.  It was pouring rain just in time for me to walk the last 15 minutes along the river Spree to the Reichstag.  I was soaked and freezing.  The other guest worker had arrived an hour earlier but no one was there to tell us what to do.  Vladimir greeted me and told stories of the Bulgarian mafia.
 <P>
I was put to work translating the roof-panel schedule into a visual plan for the monitors that could be photocopied.  A bird's eye view.  They will begin opening it at 5:30.  That's military time.  5:30 a.m.
  <P>
During this time, I chatted to an (East) German, Siegward, who doesn't speak any English.  He told me horror stories about the wall.  I didn't know it bisected buildings.  I asked, "Why didn't people just blast through the walls?"  He said the government treated it like a mouse that keeps getting into your home.  You kill them, find the new hole and plug it up.  Plus, not everyone wanted to escape.  And anyone could turn you in.
 <P>
My next job around 1 p.m. was matching computer-label names with monitor applications in a huge three-ring binder, removing the photo they sent, clipping it out the correct size then handing it on to someone who glued it on an I.D. background - then handing it to someone else who laminated them.   This is their workers' I.D.  They are expecting 600 monitors.  Tomorrow we will continue processing these applications.  The work was tedious and infinite, but it was interesting to meet Ferdinand, the Swiss collector and Gert.  We had a rhythm that sometimes bordered on manic.  The secretaries plied us with lunch and snacks to keep up our morale.
 <P>
Man, am I beat.  Jeanne-Claude and Christo aren't here yet.  I was hoping to take it a little easy before they arrive, but, as I suspected, there won't be any days off for the month that I'll be here. Sonja (who's bedroom I'm sleeping in) is in another room.  The women are discussing the situation around sharing the kitchen with the men from the other floor.  The men are not sympathetic with how women in general - and lesbians in particular - are oppressed.  They claim they are instead being oppressed by the lesbians because of some of the fliers (lesbian humor) taped up in the communal kitchen.  Well, you get the picture.
 <P>
We are planning to eat out.  I need green.  When someone got us lunch today (the canteen is not yet functional) she asked what I wanted, and I said anything green.  I got salty cake with specks of broccoli.  Seems like I've eaten nothing but bread, cheese, bratwurst, and chocolate since I got here.  I miss fruit juice.
 <P>
<B>Monday.  14:00 (2:00 pm)</B>.  I'm sitting in a window sill waiting for a store to reopen after lunch to buy another four boxes of push pins.   They're almost $2  for a box of 50.  This is my second trip of the day.  Instead of finishing up IDs I've had to put up posters up and down the "dorm" hall for the monitors.  Jeanne-Claude will arrive at 15:00 and everyone is in a panic to make everything perfect.  Three people told me three different ways to hang them.  It was getting irritating and seemed  a waste of valuable time.  Also had to shop for fruit (these diversions may be the only way I get to see Berlin).  The lady at the store complemented me on my German.  She didn't speak any English, most (East) Germans don't, having learned Russian as their second language.  Its raining, gray and so cold again.  
 <P>
Last night we (Sonja and some women from the squat) ate at a small hole in the wall (only five tables in what looked like someone's living room) typical of (East) German places to hang out.  The neighborhood looked like it probably did right after the last war.  Facades with huge chunks missing.  Exposed rusted metal structures hanging out.  I wonder if anyone ever gets hit with a chunk falling off a building as they walk beneath.  The buildings are a block long (probably cement court yards in the middle). It's  interesting to see the dilapidation running vertically down one set of apartments (with a straight edge) next to apartments where someone has renovated with new windows and cement finish on the walls.  It's all one wall, the renovation being the only division.  Here 
the poor live next door to the rich.  I wonder if they have ghettos.  Flaming orange/red hair seems to be popular with the younger crowd.
 <P>
First Tuesday in Berlin.  It's cold.  There was so much sleet 100  miles south of here that traffic was in peril.  Isn't this June!?!  No one uses heat and everyone has the windows open despite the 40- to 50-degree temperatures.  Because it's spring, they say.  Nearly full daylight and its 10 p.m.  I got to work at  8:30 this morning.  Now I'm standing at the train station writing on top of a metal box.  No train.  There's been a delay.  I'm exhausted.  I'm exhausted and just want to go home.  I told  the people in my office that I need to get some sleep before I develop  bronchitis from the cold, rain and grueling hours (they are already averaging 12 to 15) and left.  It's funny how everyone sneaks out, just disappears until the next day.  No one ever just says, "I'm going home".  
 Instead, they say they are going to the other office or going to locate so-and-so, and then they get in their car outside and leave.  Tomorrow the monitors will arrive.  I was completely involved in organizing stuff.  I'm one of the old-timers, and all the new people (98 percent of the workforce) don't know what they're doing.  Plus, these Germans (my people) want to make every thing perfect and waste precious time figuring out every possible scenario instead of going out to buy the office supplies we need to process a mass of people tomorrow.  I said, "Hey, where are the pencils?  Staplers?  Shouldn't we make some signs to divide the files up so the monitors know which line to stand in?  Who's in charge of what?  What kind of forms do they need to fill out?"  The people in this office have been here for months and they haven't organized anything.  It was making me very nervous.  I finally grabbed a pad and pen and started writing down people's names and what their assignments were to call attention to some huge gaps.  The professor in me was showing.
 <P>
<B>June 15.  10:00 a.m.</B>  I am physically and mentally exhausted.  I slept the sleep of the dead last night and woke up with my alarm clock on my chest turned off.  It was 7 a.m. and I was supposed to be at the cultural arts museum at 7:00 for the mob registration at 8:00.  The public transportation would take an hour and a half to get there from East Berlin.  I was in such a panic.  Asked a house mate how to get a cab.  None drove that part of the city (I guess the people who live there are too poor).  They said calling and waiting takes at least an hour.  The closest taxi stand was 15 minutes away.  I started jogging to it (forgot my coat!).  As luck would have it, a taxi actually came by.  I flagged it down and the traffic was awful.  It still took a half hour.  He had to drop me near the center cause the streets were closed off and rerouted already for the Reichstag.  It cost me about $35.  Shit.  Can't afford cabs in this town.  I ran across finely manicured lawns cutting straight to the Museum.  A colleague (the Swedish art collector who starts drinking beer in the morning, then hides the bottles all over the place, visiting them through-out the day) bought me a coffee to soothe my nerves when I arrived at 7:55.  Stress from the moment I opened my eyes this morning.
 <P>
Registration was a zoo.  Primarily because every 20 minutes or so someone else came from somewhere, and added or changed something about our routine.  I had to start keeping notes on all the forms (and the tangential changes) we were having them fill out.  Had to be especially careful with all the legal things.  My German studies paid off today since there were many people who spoke no English at all.  There were plenty more trying to scam their way into the project illegally, without their proper papers, etc.
 <P>
Right now there is a lull in registration. I went up to the second floor to see the second wave of monitors going through training and orientation.  It looked like a United Nations Conference.  I've heard everything already, but it was nice to sit down for just a few minutes.
 <P>
<B>Thursday June 15? </B> 10:30 p.m. on the U-Bahn.  Now, I, too, snuck out after 14 hours of work.  What I just saw in the subway passages struck me in a poignant way.  At first, I just noticed two men on the floor.  One crumbled against the wall.  The other kneeling in front of him.  The one against the wall was in his 50s.  A bloated red face in his hands sobbing mournfully, "I know, I know." The other, kneeling down in front of him was carefully and thoughtfully looking through the older man's wallet, trying to find a phone number to call asking him over and over who he could call . . .
 <P>
I wanted to photograph this, coming from a country where people are more likely to get mugged or on a good day, ignored if they're drunk and collapsed in a big-city subway.  But I knew it would be wrong.  Instead, I'll try and photograph the empty spot tomorrow.  Maybe on my way to Suzanne's place, my next home in West Berlin. <P>
<B>June 16?</B>There is a woman of about 65 who keeps showing up everyday to the Reichstag wearing silver lame' fabric.  Her hands twitch with anticipation as she tries to find the film cameras.  I observed her fidgeting and sneaking up behind an anchor woman so she would be in the frame with her.  After several takes, the film crew started yelling at her to get lost.  She keeps posing in front of unwilling cameras.  
 <P>
Then there's the "artist" in a gold leafed jacket who stands around with a sign that says "Dies ist kein Kunstwerk," followed by his name.  He smiles a plastic smile that looks as if he's practiced and then gathers an audience to lecture about why this isn't art.  I've seen free self-promotion post cards around the city.  People were already starting to catch a ride on the Christos' coat tails.  
 <P>
When Sonja had talked about the Lesbian Avengers wanting to use the project as a demonstration area, because of the media being there, I became annoyed.  Especially because Christo and Jeanne-Claude have always been equal-opportunity employers.  I told her about the Kansas City Walkway project in the '70s and how having women construction workers was unheard of . . . then -  and there we were, and in great numbers.  I tried to explain to her that it would give the wrong message.  I appealed to her art studies, particularly "content."  Even if their "visibility" had nothing to do with Christos or the project itself.  I explained the saying "riding on someone's coat tails."  During our discussion, I learned that they had modeled themselves after the American Lesbian Avengers, but the word "avenge" doesn't translate into German.  Instead, everyone believes it means "revenge."  So during all this time they have founded themselves on an incorrect principle.  Another big discussion.  A female reporter came to our communal home to interview Sonja and a few other lesbians.  We posed for a photo of us eating fire.  It was my first time.  I was nervous, hesitated and drew a blister on my bottom lip.  It was harder (nerve-wise) than I thought.
 <P>
<B>June 17.</B>  The building is becoming visually more active.  You can see some progress now.  There's a yellow metal fence surrounding the 
 Reichstag to keep the immediate building clear for the repellers.  I 
 follow photos in the newspapers on the way to and from work to keep up 
 with the latest developments.  From where I'm situated, I know more about 
 the inner workings than how the project actually looks. The old lady in 
 silver was there again, trying to get in every picture possible.  She ran 
 in front of the reporters to get within the vicinity of Christo and 
 Jeanne-Claude when they walked around the building, so she would be in 
 the picture frame.  Gert says she has a reputation of crashing parties 
 around the city.
<P>
<B>June 18. </B> The cold, rainy weather has gotten worse.  They had to postpone the unfurling of silver fabric panels because of the gusty winds.  There was a sudden downpour which caused the public (including us) to rush and crouch under nearby trees.  I forgot Germans shit in the woods.  You had to watch where you stepped.  For a people obsessed with cleanliness, I don't get it.
 <P>
<B>June 19/20.  6:30 a.m</B>.  My monitor's shift is over.  Graveyard.  I'm so tired.  Why did I bother working so hard to get over my jet lag just to 
 get caught up in swing shifts?  Now I'm undoing everything I strived for. 
  I'm seeing ghosts and things that aren't there.  Ears ringing.  Eyes 
 like sand paper.  I'm back at Suzanne's apartment.  Pigeons cooing on the 
 roof tops and window sills that only open up to a courtyard.  I'm on the 
 fourth floor with enough sliver of sky to guess what the weather is going 
 to be like.  Sun or rain, I know it won't get above the 50s.  Gert 
 described to me how these buildings were built during the industrial 
 revolution.  If you had money you lived with windows facing outside, the 
 street, trees, etc.  Less money, you face inside so you only see a cement 
 court yard and into your neighbors windows.  Sometimes an additional 
 building was built in the courtyard so no windows really face "outside."  
 There's also the "walk-up" factor.  The poorer you are, the higher you 
 must go.  By the time sounds find me from the windows or ground below, 
 they are shrill and loud.  You can hear the most intimate conversations 
 from the first floor as if it was going on in the next room.  I think 
 this is going to be a problem.  If I wear ear plugs, I won't wake up to 
 the alarm . . .  Gert said this is why so many people have a garden in 
 the country.
 <P>
 The city isn't really awake yet.  Daylight starts at around 3:30 a.m.  
 This is a magical time.  Sunlight on empty streets.  It never gets really 
 dark here when the clouds are gone.  There's still daylight at 10 p.m.  I 
 find it unnerving.  So far north I guess.  I'm physically and mentally 
 exhausted.
 <P>
<B> ???  Date?</B>  My left knee feels twisted for a week now.  I have shin 
 splints from walking around the Reichstag so much checking in with all 
 the monitor's captains and their teams.  Running them raincoats.  Suntan 
 lotion.  Work schedules.  Making them stay in couples, spread apart, 
 evenly dispersed.  Making them stand up.  Making the Captains make their 
 monitors follow the job descriptions.  The site is mobbed with people 
 which makes the going slow.  As I travel to and from work on the train, I 
 find it interesting to watch people's reaction as we curve around the 
 tracks to view the building on the other side of what looks like a waste 
 land and river.  Some people deliberately ignore it while others rush to 
 the doors and windows to focus better.  I felt quite proud.  
 <P>
<B> 2:15 p.m.</B>  I woke up about 1:00 p.m.  Suzanne and I diving quickly into a 
 deep conversation, which is the dynamics between us.  Especially because 
 we only meet in passing.  Considering I e-mailed my way into her living 
 room, we are doing well and under other circumstances (like time) I think 
 we could be great friends.  At least I don't have to worry about wearing 
 out my welcome since I'm only here to sleep and shower. Her hot water 
 only lasts about 5 minutes, too, which is a real problem with my long 
 hair. I'm waiting for the hot water to finish heating right now.  
 Showers.  What a luxury in this world.  And dry laundry.  I have to wash 
 socks by hand every day after my shift to keep the sock cycle going.  I 
 forgot Germans don't have driers.  And it's raining so much nothing's 
 drying.  And it's so damp and cold.  Suzanne has lent me lots of her warm 
 clothes.  I'm getting a care package (Goretex) from the States.  It never 
 occurred to me that I should bring camping- and hiking-type clothes to 
 work on this project.  I knew it would be cold, but not this cold and not 
 this much rain.  I have three blisters on each foot.  My feet are so 
 swollen I can't even put my boots on.  My men's style shoes are ripping 
 apart.  I may have to buy new shoes and more socks.
<P> 
 Eating nutella on luscious German bread  (when people used to survive in 
 jails on bread and water . . . it wasn't American bread!) indulging in 
 letter reading.
 <P>
 Dedication is remembering what you want.
 <P>
 Gert and I have become good friends.  He's a former East German, and I'm 
 getting an interesting perspective on what it was like before the wall 
 came down.  He's lived in Berlin for more than 10 years. When we can 
 squeak out a little time, he shows me places.  If it wasn't for him, I 
 wouldn't have seen anything except my trek back and forth to work.  
 Sometimes when we have that grueling shift that starts at 5:00 a.m., 
 he'll be waiting outside of the train station and give me a ride to save 
 me from the last 20-minute walk.  He's my partner and we've worked out a 
 good system to keep the troops in line.  We play good cop/bad cop.  The 
 workers think that I'm a real hardass.  I'm so sick of them not doing 
 their job right.  "No you can't open up your sleeping bag and sleep 
 during your shift. In fact you've been paid to stand up. No you can't 
 drink that bottle of champagne.  This isn't a party. You're supposed to 
 guard the building and be available to the public. You represent the 
 Christos."  In (what I'm learning is) typical German fashion, the 
 monitors each tell me the most optimum way they should be handling their 
 job; and me, mine.  I don't have time for these repetitive discussions.  
 I keep telling them we do what Jeanne-Claude says and anything else is 
 not an option.
 <P>
<B>22 June.</B>  More and more people coming to see the project.  We are 
 constantly having to drive off the vendors since they don't have permits. 
  We do our jobs.  They leave.  We turn the corner.  They return.  The 
 silver lady is always around.  We play "Where's Waldo."  She's actually 
 getting attention.  Apparently some people think she's related to the 
 project.  I've gotten her mannerisms down.  
 <P>
<B> 23 June.</B>  Friday  At work.  Oh god.  I have no concept of what day it is 
 anymore.  I have to ask people all the time but it doesn't stick.  Its 
 7:20 a.m.  I started work at 4:45 a.m.  Got up at 3:15 to catch the 
 bus/train/walk.  Went to bed at 10:00 last night after slamming down two 
 very tall beers and diving into deep conversations with Gert.  Gert, I 
 decided yesterday, is my best friend here.  In fact, all my closest 
 friends are men right now.  There's Ferdinand who speaks about two words 
 of English.  He was so proud of himself when he could say, "See you later 
 alligator."  Then one day I shocked him by replying, "After a while 
 crocodile." He grabbed a piece of paper and jotted it down.  And Ernst 
 (curator for a museum in Bonn) who reminds me of my father.  And of 
 course the Swiss guy who is very formal and deals with the stress and 
 sleeplessness with beer.  After a few, he's human and I like him more.  
 We are all bonding quickly because of the intensity of this job.  The 
 paperwork, the personalities.  Everyone is exhausted and getting on each 
 others nerves.
 <P>
 Gert is an excellent tour guide.  He's lived here most of his life as an 
 E-German,  but was very often in W-Berlin.  One night "check point 
 Charlie" was closed (he showed me the site) for the night and he had to 
 knock to get back into East Germany!  After hearing all the stories of 
 the lengths people went to escape, it was ironic to hear about someone 
 knocking on the door wanting to get back in to the East.  He has great 
 stories.  Their noncapitalistic perspectives are refreshing.  I see now 
 why some (former) east Germans feel jaded.  He's really sweet.  We're a 
 good team.  Helping each other out.  Covering for each other.  Dealing 
 with stress by making jokes and sometimes just giving that knowing look 
 across the room when someone is about to make a mess of things.  He tells 
 me that the mismanagement I'm witnessing is typical and the curse of 
 "perfectionist" thinking.  He thinks the Germans could learn a lot from 
 how Americans run businesses.  He seems to be familiar with some of the 
 current theories of management in the U.S.  The meetings are ridiculous, 
 starting after people have already worked 13 hours (and can't see 
 straight) often going around in circles until everyone gets fed up.  No 
 agendas.  Lots of talk.  Strategies change so often nothing ever gets 
 done.  Often Gert drives me home because I've missed the last train 
 trying to tackle some new three ring binder of paperwork that just got 
 thrown our way after a full shift and meeting.
 <P>
 I find myself drinking beer almost every day now to take the edge off the 
 stress, or to get a good six hours of sleep in broad daylight - with 
 those damn pigeons cooing only a few feet away.  At least the beer here 
 is worth drinking.
 <P>
 It's getting tougher to sit down and write.  Mostly I do it on the train 
 now.  The honeymoon, if ever there was one, is definitely over.  I've 
 only had one day of warmth and sunshine since I got here.  Any spare time 
 I have I either sleep or try and get in a little sightseeing, thanks to 
 Gert.  It rains all the time.  The cold is in my bones and I can't shake 
 it.  I'm stiff and sore from sleeping on the floor and walking around the 
 Reichstag so much.  My shoes finally disintegrated.
 <P>
 On our day off, which I spent half of sleeping, Gert took me throughout 
 Berlin, especially East Berlin, pointing out the sections of "The Wall"  
 that remain.  The images were powerful and sad not only because of the 
 subject matter, but also because they are quickly fading and flaking 
 away.  Saw some interesting architecture in East Berlin.  A lesbian bar 
 called the Whistle Stop Cafe named after Fried Green Tomatoes.  We  
went to an island in the middle of the Spree - a river.  Then a beer 
garden. More interesting conversation between East vs. West.  Capitalism vs. 
 communism/socialism.  His wife.  His child.  His parents - how they died. 
  How his father just couldn't cope with the collapse of communism and 
 wasted away first spiritually then physically.  After two to three hours,  
 I was pretty tipsy.  He took us to an authentic Russian restaurant in 
 East Berlin (phonetically) called Pasternak.  We were sitting at tables 
 on the sidewalk.  The food was fantastic.  Orange caviar on eggs, 
 stroganoff with some kind of wheat thing . . . rich beer . . . called 
 Budweiser, no less (but as different from ours as water is to,well . . . 
 beer).  Enjoying my time away from the project, I was suddenly roused 
 from my feeding frenzy when I hear my name, "Iris?," in German and looked 
 up to see my cousin from Munich!  I said, "Henrika?!!"  she said yes.  
 She's around 20 now -  shy, intellectual and nearly 6' tall.  I said "No, 
 it can't be!"  Three-and-a half-million citizens and she stumbled upon me 
 at the same restaurant while looking for a table for dinner.  Turns out 
 she's been in Berlin for a while studying at the university.  Henrika and 
 her friend joined us for dinner.
 <P>
 The next day they came to visit me at The Reichstag.  I introduced them 
 to Jeanne-Claude and was reprimanded for bringing strangers to their 
 office when everything was so busy and hectic.  Henrika and her friend 
 were thrilled never-the-less.  I gave them a couple of my signed Christo 
 postcards.  We walked around the Reichstag in extreme cold and wind.  
 Black thick clouds.  Driving rain.  I teased them about how glamorous my 
 job is.  They left right away because of the freezing weather. We 
 promised to try and meet for breakfast or lunch on Sunday.
 <P>
 Ferdinand (who reminds me of younger version of my handsome German 
 grandfather, with whom I studied as a teen-ager to learn how to smoke) 
 Ernst, Gert and I will try and have a dinner out on Tuesday 
 (Czechoslovakian or Brazilian).  They are partners - always during the 
 shift before us.  So it was difficult to come up with a time that 
 wouldn't interfere with our sleep.  I'm really looking forward to it.  I 
 need to recharge my batteries.
 <P>
<B> Another day . . . four ?</B> days ago the film crew interviewed me (after I 
 only had three and a half hours of sleep!) regarding the other projects 
 I'd worked on.  The first go around they ran out of film.  The second go 
 around they ran out of recording tape.  I probably came off like a dork.  
 We'll see later if they use any of it.  They seem to be interested in me 
 since I've worked previous projects and have dealt with sidewalks, an 
 ocean, Paris, desert climate, and now gray cold weather in my native land.
 <P>
 Gotta get to work.  Gert and I decided today I'm the mean guy and he will 
 be nice to the monitors (who are behaving worse as the days progress).  
 Tomorrow will be the opposite.  8:10 a.m.   
 <P>
<B>24 June.</B>  During our shift, around 4:00 a.m. someone shot a burning 
 arrow into the fabric from the neighboring trees/park.  Gert was out on 
 patrol and I was doing paperwork, keeping my ear to the radio.  I grabbed 
 my camera and went out for a look.  It was so unimpressive (the fabric is 
 fire retardant) that I didn't bother.  They didn't catch him.  I was 
 irked since it was our crew on duty and no one saw anything.  At that 
 time in the morning, we would constantly have to check up on them, some 
 of the monitors blatantly sleeping in sleeping bags or mats.  It's 
 becoming a constant battle.  I wish I had the power to fire people.  
 There's no leverage to make them do their job.
 <P>
 Later in the day the fence was removed since all the panels have been 
 opened.  Everyone is bracing themselves for dealing directly with the 
 public, which is increasing by thousands daily.
 <P>
 Gert and I admired the way the Reichstag transformed into Christo's 
 preliminary drawings/montage/vision.  Its a giant jewel.
<P> 	
<B>I think its the 26th.</B>  I'm having a half-liter of Becks beer and an 
 onion sandwich on stiff German bread with cheese and black peppercorns.  
 Listening to a terrific Russian Reggae (!) tape that Gert made for me.  
 Trying to unwind.  Its a serious time of reflection for me.  As with all 
 the projects, I am rejoicing in the impact of it all.  And grateful to be 
 an integral component in this art history in the making.  But, man oh 
 man, am I ready to go home.  I guess I am so high up in this hierarchy 
 that I see all the problems, but not high enough to do anything about it. 
  Telling the Christos would only stress them out more.  I've mentioned 
 things to Simon but he seems to be fed up with what ever it is he is 
 witnessing.  I keep readapting the motto "Just one day at a time."
 <P>
<B>28 June '95</B>.  Last night was particularly grueling.  It was the most 
 difficult shift as a shift leader.
 <P>
 I'm writing from a garden north of the city.  A datscha.  The Russian 
 word for a little garden with a little overnight house.  A place to get 
 away from it all.  The little house is classic late '50s.  Former East 
 Germany. I've done nothing today but relax.  After our two most disliked 
 shifts (5:00-11:00 a.m. then immediately after: 11:00 p.m. till 5:OO 
 a.m.) Gert and I left.  During this 11:00 p.m. shift we planned to catch 
 up on our paperwork, which continues to grow in responsibility daily.  
 Our plan was foiled because we weren't the only ones behind.  Other shift 
 leader partners were sitting there till 2 a.m. trying to catch up too.  
 Until they were done, we couldn't do ours.  
 <P>
 Meanwhile the happy people around the Reichstag had turned aggressive.  
 Ever-demanding crowds waiting for silver fabric swatches (1,150,000) 
 prepared for the monitors to hand out free (at an additional $48,000) for 
 souvenirs.  I was appalled at how nasty some people were.  A few days ago 
 Gert and I turned the corner to discover two of the British monitors had 
 people lined up (two by two) in a civilized queue.  They stood on the 
 steps and doled out swatches two at a time.  It was so prim and proper 
 and struck us as funny because the Brits are known for behaving 
 themselves in line.  Later we heard that a monitor found himself being 
 mobbed for swatches and in a panic threw his whole satchel as far over 
 the heads of the crowd as he could to escape their viciousness.  Today a 
 monitor showed me the bloody fingernail scratches covering her arms and 
 hands where she was mobbed by greedy people.  We decided to hold off - 
 thinking the monitors might be overwhelmed or rushed by the crowd.  It 
 was a difficult decision.  Which way would the public be more aggressive?
 <P>
 Shortly after the shift change at 11 p.m., the problems started.  I made 
 my first round.  A group of skin heads - walking in a pack - began 
 harassing the monitors.  I spotted an arrogant man faking drunkenness 
 with his lover,  while cupping a knife in his hand.  Caressing and 
 pressing his body against the fabric he kept trying to cut it - testing 
 the stiff fabric with his small knife.  Gert and I tailed him - monitors 
 were warned by us through our talkie-walkies (that's what they keep 
 calling them!).  The police were dealing with the skin heads in a polite 
 and restrained fashion.  One in particular was a real asshole.  I tailed 
 him from a distance.  Drunk and belligerent he began picking a fight with 
 a 40-year-old female monitor.  I called for backup, but the radio was 
 jammed with urgent requests overlapping each other, creating 
 incomprehensible snippets.  Finally I got through describing which facade 
 he was on (a nightmare for any one since their names challenged even the 
 non-dyslexic: Ost (east) facade Nord (north), Ostfassade Sud (south), 
 Sudfassade Ost, Sudfassade West, Westfacade Sud, and so on) while tailing 
 him.  The woman handled it well.  He moved on to the next monitor and 
 tried to pick a fight with him.  The police finally arrived (I'd followed 
 him half way around the building, squeezing through the crowd) and he 
 fought them immediately.  Holding on to the back of his neck, they lead 
 him away. He frequently pulled up his feet like a belligerent child.  I 
 was impressed with how the police were practicing enormous restraint.
 <P>
 Some of the monitors were really shook up.  The skinheads looked pretty 
 intimidating.  
 <P>
 Made another half-round patrol and heard over the radio that someone had 
 projected something onto the front of the Reichstag.  I didn't know what 
 to expect when I rounded the corner.  To my surprise and pleasure (though 
 we knew it had to be turned off) someone had managed to set up a million 
 watts (or so) of light behind two slides and projected a drawing of the 
 front facades of the Reichstag onto the Reichstag. The really impressive 
 thing was, it was totally to scale on the first attempt.  The drawing of 
 all the windows and portals were in the exact location of the originals 
 under the silver/gray fabric.  It lasted about 15 minutes.
 <P>
 Christo and Jeanne-Claude share the same birthday, June 13, 1935.  She 
 recently turned 60.  My office wanted to throw a party for her (Christo 
 was in the states).  I advised them against it since Christo wasn't there 
 and she probably wouldn't appreciate us not focusing on the project.  The 
 parties could come afterwards. Better to keep the ball rolling and not 
 pause.  Then she came down with a fever and bronchitis and didn't look 
 well at all.  We heard Jeanne-Claude was ordered to stay in her hotel for 
 three days.  All these events made me reflect.  I'd always assumed I'd 
 work on their projects forever.  I'd never thought about the fact that 
 there will come a time when there won't be any more projects.  It 
 reminded me of a trip home once, after I hadn't been home in a few years 
 and I realized with a jolt in my heart and stomach that my mother looked 
 older and things would not remain the same for the rest of my life.  I 
 forgot they are vulnerable like everyone else.  And with so much at 
 stake.  I worried about her.    
 <P>
 We had expected Jeanne-Claude to be out and about last night.  The 
 garbage that people left around the building and lawn was incredible.  I 
 was shocked.  This place is beginning to remind me of a cross between 
 Disney World and Woodstock.  Disney because of the holiday type of 
 feeling and all the children, families, etc.  Woodstock because of all 
 the camp fires, drinking and how about that strip tease in front of the 
 Reichstag's lights.  It was projected two or so stories!  (Did the 
 Christos hear about all this?)  The captains and especially the monitors 
 are getting more and more difficult to handle.  Too many of them are 
 developing the attitude that it is all a big party.  The captains are, in 
 general, the same age as their monitors and as a result the captains are 
 more concerned with being liked;  several just don't have any authority 
 in their personalities.  The most successful groups appear to be the ones 
 where the captains are older.  
 <P>
 The Christos were scheduled to do autographs at dawn; people were already 
 camping out in line by 1:00 a.m.  There were several camps in the round - 
 strewn all over the grounds.  Guitars and bad off-key versions of 
 Stairway to Heaven.  Other camps consisted of drunken belligerent men 
 with their women supporting them.
 <P>
 Gert got stuck in some problem involving the que that had grown one and a 
 half times around the Reichstag.  Instead of being done and heading off 
 to breakfast at 5:30 a.m.  it was 6:30.  Odd . . . these breakfasts.  
 Sometimes they are left over dinners during this time of the day.
 <P>
 Afterwards we hopped in the car and escaped north into the country side 
 and his datscha, where I'm writing now.  I could hardly keep my eyes 
 open.  Arrived at 7:30 a.m.  He opened the doors and windows to the 
 little house.  It was cold.  We were wasted, having used our last 
 strength to complete the paperwork at the end of our shift.  I parked a 
 lawn chair in the sun, wound a blanket around me and fell into an 
 exhausted sleep for three and a half hours. I woke up to the sound of 
 bumblebees, not pigeons.
 <P>
 Around noon, he got some breakfast and dinner fixings.  I took a shower 
 (and can't wait for one of my 20 -minute showers at home) and changed 
 into shorts while he was gone.  Gert wouldn't let me do a thing all day.  
 The breakfast was a typical German spread.  Spent the day sunning, 
 touring the yard/garden, talking, looking at books and basically trying 
 to relax and forget about the project for a while.  Finally, I was warm.
 <P>
 In the evening, we had a specially grilled pork chop kind of a thing.  
 Our discussion about his marriage and its unhappiness.  I just don't 
 understand why so many people stay in bad marriages.
 <P>
 Its 8 p.m. and he's packing up the house.  We're touring the country side 
 before we drive back into the city.   
 <P>
<B>Date?</B>  Tonight truly had to be the night from hell.  After working all 
 night, with other shift leaders backed up in the office with paperwork, 
 we heard that the president of Germany (not the Chancellor) was to visit 
 the project site around 7:00 am.  The site would obviously have to be in 
 tip top shape.  At around the end of our shift, it was obvious that the 
 trash collectors (big trucks with vacuum hoses and brushes) had missed a 
 large amount of garbage.  We'd been ordered to have the monitors pick up 
 trash in their section.  Gert distributed the bags.  Instead of 
 cooperation, we heard from most of the monitors that to pick up trash was 
 beneath them and also not included in the job description.  At the same 
 time, the trash trucks were stalled at the flagpole site (directly in the 
 front of the building) because some belligerent drunk had collected trash 
 (99 percent beer, wine and champagne bottles), which he'd placed on the 
 flag pole cement island as "art."  He refused to allow the trash 
 collectors to sweep up the bottles.  They tried convincing him and he 
 discovered suddenly he had an audience.  Getting more and more rowdy, he 
 wrote something on a poster board and tied it to the flag pole.  Then 
 started in his drunken drawl to lecture to everyone who'd gathered to 
 photograph him and listen.  The police was called to intervene on the 
 trash collectors behalf.  Meanwhile, all the monitors from that side of 
 the building heard about the commotion and started drifting to that 
 location, abandoning their positions and still not picking up any trash. 
 <P>
 Gert and I were trying to rustle them up and back into their positions 
 when, on the opposite side of the Reichstag, someone was hit on their 
 bicycle and was apparently bleeding.  The ambulance was called.  On the 
 radio, several urgent messages were going out when, somehow, one of the 
 monitors got on with a speech about "how dare we worry about garbage when 
 some one was lying there bleeding to death" (an exaggeration). We cringed 
 knowing the media was listening and probably the Christos, too.  This 
 person had jammed up all the radios and wouldn't get off the air.  
 Horrified, Gert and I were frantically trying to find the source.  In the 
 middle of all this chaos, guess who drove up in a limo . . .
<P> 
<B>Date?</B>  I was making my rounds squeezing through the crowd, when I 
 noticed everyone's attention was to my right.  I turned to see a man had 
 planted an A-frame ladder right next to me, climbed to the top (with his 
 back to the project) and dropped his coat.  His pale white hairy body was 
 clothed only in black nylon socks and shoes.  His friend on the ground 
 took a picture of him with the building in the background.  The Berlin 
 police stood politely by waiting for him to finish and get down.  Putting 
 on his coat, he was gently escorted to the trees on the edge of the park, 
 where they obviously wrote him a ticket.  It was all so civilized and 
 polite.  Somewhere in the distance there was the sound of a Bolivian pan 
 pipe group performing.
 <P>
A couple of days before leaving.  I've started saying my goodbyes, 
 taking my last pictures, briefly chatting to people that I hadn't had a 
 chance to say hi to, and hoping to hook up with the Christos.  All 
 together, during the course of this month, I've maybe said three 
 sentences to them as the projects are the worst time to try and 
 socialize.  Ironically they were briskly walking past the project.  I 
 caught up with them and asked what they thought now after all those years 
 of hard work (more than 20).  They were beaming with pride.  She spoke 
 briefly about the birthing pains involved with these projects.  Telling 
 them I was leaving soon, they hooked me up with one of Christo's private 
 tours of the interior of the building.  I donned a construction hat and 
 took two trips.  The first to hear the details, the second to spiritually 
 experience it.
 <P>
 The inside of the building was stripped bare to the stone.  Enormous 
 cables penetrated the ceilings, and came in the windows to hold the ropes 
 and silver fabric tight to the building. There were also concrete and 
 steel weights.  Apparently, many of the ropes had to be continuously 
 adjusted as they stretched out from the weight and wind.The inner court 
 yards were as magical as I'd imagined. I took several photos of the 
 architecture and the American ambassador and his family, who were the 
 focus of the tour. Taking the elevator to the top floor, we ascended the 
 stairs and climbed up onto the roof.  It was a shimmering, surreal 
 landscape.  Minimalistic and elegant.  If I'd had wings, I would have 
 flown in circles down the fabric lined inner courtyards.  It felt so safe 
 up there.  Below, in another world, you could hear the hundreds of 
 thousands of people milling around the building. 
 <P>
<B>July 6.</B> The unwrapping of the Reichstag has begun and I'm going home to 
 Georgia.
  <P>
 Final thoughts:  While I found working on the project grueling in terms 
 of hours and pressures, I can't adequately describe the honor and 
 satisfaction that I've experienced in being able to participate in such 
 incredibly important historical event.  During some of my most annoyed 
 and exhausted moments I've reflected on what it must (by comparison) be 
 like for Christo and Jeanne-Claude, striving to make their visions 
 tangible.  The enormous responsibility of it must, at times, be overwhelming.   
<P> 
<hr>
 <P>
 This article has been approved by Christo and Jeanne-Claude, in April 1996.
 <P>
