<IMG SRC="/graphics/bodett.jpg" WIDTH=193 HEIGHT=297 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15>
<H2>class lecture</H2>
<H3>Tom Bodett on: <BR>
Tom Bodett and <BR>
The Free Fall of Webster Cummings</H3>
<P>

Bodett's fourth book, <i>The Free Fall of Webster Cummings  </i> (Hyperion, $22.95), is a novel about a man  who survives an impossible fall from a commuter plane and the strange people his accident brings together. 
<P>
Bodett hosts the radio program <i>The End of the Road, </i >lives in Homer, Alaska; and he serves as a contributing editor to Alaska magazine. Apparently he also frequently visits  Motel 6.
<P>
<br clear=all>
<hr width=75%>
<P>
With half my life spent living in Alaska, there is no mystery to why I've devoted most of my writing and radio attention to the peculiarities of my Alaskan existence.  But I've never forgotten where I came from and, like most Alaska immigrants, my roots continue to petition for equal time.
<P>
Raised in Michigan and funneled to Alaska through a series of misguided adventures across America and through the Northwest, I arrived in Alaska in 1976 and never looked back.  Or that's what I like to say, anyway.  But I did look back.  Do look back.  And I see my old friends change and my parents grow old and the America I left behind becoming something else and even from my rarefied Alaskan perch I have to admit that it's the most interesting situation I've ever come across.  So I had to send a couple emissaries down to test the waters.
<P>
Ed Flannigan went first.  One arm, no job, no clue.  I wondered what would happen if the last of the real Alaskan men wound up in Quartz Creek, Oregon, a crystal-twirling new age power colony.  He is tested to the breaking point by the foreign challenges of organic farming, a born again and again channeler who thinks she knew him in another life, and a cranky little guardian angel who lives in his peach trees.
<P>
The next one out was Norman Tuttle, sixteen now and pretty much reduced to a raging hormone.  Norman gets lost in the jungles of adolescence in his little Alaska world and only finds his way by getting himself exiled from Alaska to a summer in the Lower 48.  What do sex, rock-n-roll and family secrets have to do with growing up in America?  Well, just about everything as it turns out.
<P>
Once Ed and Norman got my attention turned South, there was no going back.  Everywhere I looked there were fascinating characters buried behind the faces of ordinary people.
<P>
Lloyd and Evelyn Decker, retired and bored out of their seventy-year-old wits in Avalon, Ohio.  With a daughter playing logger in Oregon and a son who stalled and pumps gas in Booder, Indiana, they've run out of reasons to stay home.  Prepared for anything but the truth, they strike out in a powder blue Road Ranger motor home to see the America they never knew and remind themselves what their children look like.
<P>
Separated by more than the hyphens in their names, Richard and Katherine Bedinger-Hoople struggle to maintain two high-powered careers on both coasts while nurturing a pregnancy, a promotion, and a modern America relationship with cellular phones and flier miles.
<P>
I've always wondered who those people in the big coats shuffling by with their shopping carts are talking to.  It might be to Oliver the Dreamer, the soft spoken amnesiac who lives under a bridge in Seattle with his homeless family of friends.  Oliver's soiled associates--the original John Doe, voluntary vagrant Arthur P. Tender III, and poor mad Ramona--give the ragged edges of America a new and unexpected dimension.
<P>
Even a social climbing student of ambition like Buddy Bedinger stands to learn from the forgotten poor.  Lessons Buddy fails to learn as he works his way through law school and a parade of wealthy clientele as a room service waiter at the grand Merrimont Hotel in Seattle.
<P>
I suppose the thing that amazes me the most about the America I see from here is how much all these incredibly distinct characters have in common with each other and--even after twenty years in Alaskan exile--with me.  Is there a common American heart?  Or is this just the illusion created by the small world syndrome?  If it's true that we're only six people away from knowing anybody in the country, then Webster Cummings is the one everybody must know.
<P>
After surviving a mile-high fall from a commuter flight over New Hampshire, Webster is shaken from his plodding existence as a statistical research analyst and moved to seek out once and for all the identities of his biological parents.  His discoveries prove the Sherlock Holmes' theory:  once you've eliminated all possibilities, the answer must be the impossible.
<P>
In the America I see from here, anything is possible.  Especially the impossible.  As Webster's search becomes our odyssey he draws my scattered American brood to one inevitable conclusion in a most unlikely place a long way from home.
<P>
But for me, that's what this story is really about:  leaving home.  Leaving home and coming home and trying to understand the difference.  I think E. W. Howe said it best:  The worst thing in the world is the homesickness that comes over a man occasionally when he is at home. 
<P>
<hr>
