<title>george jr. / july 1996 / features / fiction / christy sheffield sanford</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>

<H2>fiction:</H2> 
<P>
<H2>Eleven Missing Days in Istanbul<BR>
(Memoirs of an Amnesiac: 11 Questions) </H2>
<H3><I>by Christy Sheffield Sanford</I></H3>
<P>
Having just mailed the completed <i>Murder on the Orient Express  </i>to her publisher, Agatha Christie was relaxing in a mauve peignoir in her suite at the Pera Palas hotel.  That afternoon Ali Firath, a rail engineer she'd quizzed in her mystery research, had paid a visit and offered her an extraordinary....
<P>

<b>THE FACTS</b>
<P>
<font size=+3>1)</font> Who Dropped the Handkerchief Initialed A.?  Opium on the Bosphorus, eleven days  of dreaming.  The most liquid time of my life. We would climb into his barque and float for hours.  But I must start at the beginning.  From the first, Ali Firath, educated at Oxford and fluent in French, reminded me of my detective Poirot.  Uncanny.  Ali was exactly as I'd imagined Hercule: slight physique, egg shaped bald head and a luxuriant shiny black mustache, that one instinctively wanted to stroke. 
<P>
<font size=+3>2)</font> The Pipe-Cleaner?  Was It Dropped by Colonel Christie ?  Or By a Rogue?  I had interviewed Ali at length on the Orient Express.  He'd come to my compartment and we had sipped Chartreuse, just as I'd imagined doing with Hercule.  Ah, what 
a weakness he had for sweets, he would bring me Turkish delight.  Boxes of it.  What decadence.  But I'm skipping ahead.  If Sir Maxwell had only known but  he was on a dig along the Straits of the Dardanelles.  
<P>
<font size=+3>3)</font> Who Wore the Electric Purple Kimono?  Istanbul was not my first episode of amnesia.  In 1926, I was still married to Colonel Christie.  I had visited my cousin in the country and returned unexpectedly to find the Colonel in bed with my red-headed secretary, half his age.  He was snoring with a smile on his face.  My green brocade spread was in a heap on the carpet.  I jumped in the sedan and drove to the edge of a Yorkshire cliff.  I remember pounding my head against the steering wheel.  I wanted to gun the accelerator but couldn't, and realizing my cowardice, again banged my head.  Exhausted, I climbed into the back seat and promptly fell asleep.  I awoke to stars and a radiant half moon.  I alighted, stretched and as if in a trance, began a trek down a cliffside path.  I walked most of the night.  Then gazing at the stars, I fell asleep on a grassy knoll. 
<P>
<font size=+3>4)</font> Who Was Masquerading as Engineer/Opium Dealer?  At dawn the next morning my foot was nudged by a man with a rifle.  A feather floated onto my face.  The partridge hunter--Trevor was his name--was holding a bird by the neck.  Helping me to my feet, he insisted on befriending me.  He seemed a bit crazed and talked incessantly whether I answered or not.  At first, this was comforting as I knew nothing to say.  But I began to chafe when he insisted I stay up all hours while he read me his memoirs.  
<P>
<font size=+3>5)</font> Why Are the Hands of My Diamond Wristwatch Frozen at 2:40 A.M.?  One night Trevor read, "My Life As an Infantryman."   He'd shot a soldier in the back and felt ashamed, though this act had won him a medal for bravery.  Suddenly I recalled the endless war stories of the Colonel, my husband who had killed me with his infidelity.  I dashed out the front door, Trevor in hot pursuit.  "Why are you escaping?" he yelled.  Then I realized, he'd planned to keep me there.  I began 
to run in earnest.  He went into the house and as I glanced over my shoulder, 
I saw him standing on his stoop with a rifle.  I ducked behind a tree as shot exploded against the bark.  He began to chase me and I began to sprint.  I thought, "He's just trying to scare me."  A rain of pings whizzed by my ear.  A pellet lodged in my hair.  I screamed.  Shocked, Trevor stood still and began 
to cry.  I kept running.  I reached a Yorkshire hotel at midnight--my body covered with bramble scratches.  Recognizing me, the innkeeper said, "You've been missing a fortnight, Miss Christie.  We suspected foul play." 
 <P>
<b>THE EVIDENCE</b>
<P>
<font size=+3>6)</font> Was a Murder Committed at 2:40 A.M.?  This amnesic episode hardly compared to the fugue I suffered in '32.  As I said, Ali had come to Pera Palas.  With him, I  felt a sense of eerie equality, never experienced with another man.  "Agatha,"  he said, "I know you have an affection, a deep involvement with The East.  I want you to share an experience with me.  I hold you in great esteem; you will  be perfectly safe.  You must try the essence of the poppy, the potion that has elevated the language of poets and been the utter downfall of the weak.  I have   taken the drug three times without lingering cravings.  I can protect you from yourself, if necessary."  "No addiction, whatsoever?" I asked.  "Pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment.  I will be your incorruptible guide."  
<P>
<font size=+3>7)</font> Could the Death Have Occurred Earlier?  Could the Victim Have Been Already Dead?  As one might imagine, with me to whom he was wildly attracted, the fourth time was his downfall.  I have a fleeting image of myself slipping into my hotel in the middle of the night like a hooligan.  Room 411 of Pera Palas became our den.  Endless hot baths and the hookah.  My apples, tea and writing implements beside the tub, undisturbed for eleven days.  And Ali rubbing my feet until I fell asleep or had another spontaneous orgasm.  The slightest descent into the crevice between my toes was intoxicating.  Everything seemed part of a skein and I would wake drifting toward one of the Princes' Islands in the Sea of Marmara-- the sun burning away the night mist from yet another castle.  
<P>
<font size=+3>8)</font> Could the Victim Have Revived at a Later Time, Minutes or Years Later?   Hercule, I mean Ali, began a recurrent theme: "Marry me."  "That would be bigamy," I said laughing.  "No, marry me here under different laws, we will disappear into a northern city."  He whispered in my hair, "No one will find you."  I remember our rail trip through the country where the terrain looked like giant phallic out-croppings.  Were my distorted visions due to euphoria?  A man, who'd sneaked out a compartment window was apprehended atop the train.  "An opium smuggler?" I asked, giggling.  My engineer said, "Shhhh," and then giggled back.  He, in his own dream world, was taking me home to meet his mother. 
<P>
<font size=+3>9)</font> Are We Certain the Victim Was Stabbed by Only One Perpetrator?  I had decided to marry him.  Insane, of course.  At the time, I thought it logical.  My deductive powers were at a standstill.  When we entered his house, he tried to introduce me to his mother; she began shouting at him in Turkish--a shrill kind of yam-mering.  Dressed all in black, she was wearing a veil.  I stood detached, watching her tantrum, then she began to pound on my back with a broomsedge as if to sweep me from her sight.  Roused from my delicious stupor, I felt an instant fury.  I began to beat her with my fists as though I'd studied boxing.  Suddenly I was Dempsey unleashed.  Then she fell and began to groan and curse.  I slumped to the floor, spent.  Ali picked me up and I woke at the Pera Palas.  I did not regain this memory until four days before my death.  
<P>
<b>HERCULE POIROT LIES DOWN AND THINKS</b>
<P>
<font size=+3>10)</font> How Else Could One Explain the Variety of Wounds?  After my last book was written, I heard from Ali.  He said, "You were the love of my life."  "Why did you disappear?" I asked.  "You mentioned Sir Max in a dream, I thought it meant you loved him."  "And your mother?" I asked, "how is she?"  "Dead, of course," he said, rather startled.
<P>
<font size=+3>11)</font> Was the Distorted Vision Due to Euphoria?  Several years elapsed and then four days before I died, it dawned on me.  "Did I kill her?  Did I kill her?"  I kept asking my niece and she kept telling everyone that I was demented and delirious.  Because, you see, I was giggling like a child.    
<P>
<hr>
<P>
Christy Sheffield Sanford is the creator of RED MONA, a World Wide Web Project, located at <A HREF="http://www.purplefrog.com/~christy/red-mona/">Red Mona</a>.  She is the author of seven books: <i>Sur les Pointes, The Ballerina and the Sea Anemone, The Kiss,; Italian Smoking Piece, Bride Thrashing through History</i> and <i>The H's: the Spasms of a Requiem, Only the Nude Can Redeem the Landscape </i> and <I>The Cowrie Shell Piece</I>.
<P>
