<br>
<H2>coffee break with georgette</H2>
On a July afternoon nothing goes better than Mom's hot apple pie and coffee. 
But since Georgette was out spanning the web, we thought  we'd feature a recipe from George Jr. correspondent Sandy Andes. Her name not only sounds as sweet as the honeysuckle,  this hip Baby Boomer  from Ashtabula, Ohio, has a great recipe for a killer apple pie with streusel topping that would melt any guest. 
<P>
<B>Crust:</B>
<MENU>
<UL>
<LI>3 cups flour
<LI>1.5 cup Crisco (preferrably butter flavor)
<LI>1 tablespoon vinegar
<LI>5 tablespoons water
<LI>1 egg
</UL>
</MENU>
<P>
Mix flour and Crisco until well blended. Add water, vinegar, and egg. Blend until dough  has a nice dough-like consistency. (You have a problem with that definition? Please don't tell me you were expecting Betty Crocker here?)
For those seeking to save time, the above steps may be substituted for Ready Made crust. But if it doesn't taste like homemade, don't come crying to me.
<P>
<B>Filling:</B>
<MENU>
<UL>	
<LI>1 tablesppon of lemon juice
<LI>1/3 cup honey
<LI>1 teaspoon cinnamon
<LI>3 to 4 cups thinly sliced Granny Smith apples
<LI>1 tablespoon butter
</UL>
</MENU>
<P>
Heat lemon juice, cinnamin and honey in a saucepan. Place sliced apples in an unbaked crust. Pour honey mixture over and dab with butter.  Cover with aluminum foil and bake at 425 degrees for 50 minutes. Uncover after 30 minutes.
<P>
<B>Streusel topping:</B>
<MENU>
<UL>
<LI>1/2 cup firmly packed light brown suger
<LI>1/2 cup flour
<LI>1/4 cup cold butter cut into small pieces
<LI>1/4 cup nuts (pecans or walnuts will do)
</UL>
</MENU>
<P>
Mix by hand. (Wooden spoons just don't cut it here. You need the right consistency that only your digits can do.) Cover pie and bake at 350 for 10 minutes.
<P>
If you are really trying to impress, prepare the pie the night before your dinner.  Add your streusel topping and refrigerate overnight. The pie can finish cooking while you are eating dinner or brewing coffee.  Makes the kitchen smell great and you look damn good too.
<P>
I'd like to be able to suggest a corresponding coffee here, but I think Sandy's speciality of the day could work best. That's going to your local java house and experienting by blending three of your favorite coffees together. The results can be quite pleasing to the palate. But remember, common sense applies.  A chocolate and hazelnut go, but a bitter Euthopian blend would probably not fit in this mix.
<P>
Bon appetite!
<P>
