<H2>we the peephole</H2>
Who would you like to see as President of the United States, and why? That's what we were wondering about for June's copy-and-paste column. This is how you answered:
<P><HR><P>
<B>From:  lruland@freenet.columbus.oh.us</B><P> 
<menu>
I'd have to vote for Bill Clinton because in my opinion nobody else is running.  I'd think seriously about Colin Powell because of his strong military background since we willalways be involved in somebody's war.  I'm curious to see if the country is ready to accept a black man.  Doyle is not only too old he has not learned anything from life.  Pat Buchanan is a dangerous man and should be locked up.  Steve Forbes is too rich and I can't see any way he has helped the poor (who are always with us).  Clinton is not too religious, too rich, too old or may I add too smart, but he's learning from his mistakes. </menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

<B>From:  DWCQ13A@prodigy.com</B><P>
<menu>
If I could choose anyone to be U.S. president, it would be either Adrienne Rich (she'd give proper attention to the arts and due respect to all things pragmatic), Ralph Waldo Emerson (big on finding 
common ground), or Bill Clinton. </menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

<B>From: Deep Blue Something, sapst23+@pitt.edu</B><P>
<menu>
OK then I am going to go into the showbiz category and pick Regis Philben. Now don't laugh, I have some pretty good reasos for this.  One, he shows every morning that he knows a lot about what's going on in this country.  Plus he is a real person, by that I mean what you see is what you get.  He lives like a regular person, and I can actually say that i have met him before so I can vouch for that.  Another good thing is that he isn't a politician, so even though he has money, he lives like a regular person.  He takes a cab to work, he is a sports fan, and he has morals! </menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

A   few of my friends have given their opinions as well:
<menu>
John Travolta, because he's cool
Cal Ripken - He would never take a sick day, and work ethic is great!
Mr Rogers - The sweater industry would thrive
Tracy Lords - Go down hard on Congress
Elvis - Just because he's Elvis
Clint Eastwood - You try and disagree with him!  Ask yourself this do you 
feel lucky, huh do ya?
Dennis Rodman - Looks better in short shorts than Bill Clinton - Never would need a haircut
George Foreman - Tell him no!
</menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

<B>From: Tomamann@aol.com</B><P>
Bob Dole.
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

<B>From:  WILHELMS@CC.DENISON.EDU</B><P>
<menu>
Clinton- I think some of the things he's doing, such as training for disadvantaged youth and education and youth/housing programs will turn out to be important. The Republicans are opposed to caring about others.</menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

<B>From: JefferyR2@aol.com</B><P>
<menu>
I would stick with Clinton because he's a known commodity whereas Dole is a known comedy.  There is some concern regarding Clinton's waffling on the issues but I'm not sure Dole is any better.  Clinton's waffling is due in part to the learning curve associated with dealing with the Washington insiders.  Dole has been an insider for 20 years.  He is a major reason we're in the shape we're in right now.  He offers us nothing but four more years like the past 20 and I'm not willing to regress right now.  Also, I'm not interested in candidates who are from Dole's generation.  The world has changed and change is picking up speed at a dizzying pace.  The information age is still in its infancy and I don't think we need another president who doesn't know his RAM from his Bytes. </menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>

<B>From:  MChevyC@aol.com</B><P>
<menu>
For president I would like Matthew Fox, whose views on how we should treat
the planet & each other closely match mine. (Well, on a good day.) Or Tea Leoni.</menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>
 
<B>From:  102504.503@compuserve.com</B><P>
<menu>
I have parked in front of the computer keyboard for much too long, sifting through a list of possible candidates. Bill Clinton has been a major disappointment, so I'd not want him for another four years. Bob Dole would be a disaster; he suffers from the same disease as Clinton, a severe shortage of
backbone. My ingrained Democratic leanings wouldn't permit me to vote for the GOP anyway.  Damn. Is there anyone capable of handling such a job? Probably not. All right, all right. I have to make a selection. Uhhhh, OK, I've got it. <BR>
GEORGE CLOONEY. He's accustomed to making quick decisions, so he'd be handy in a foreign policy crisis. He's good looking, intelligent, amusing, and I know his Aunt Rosemary, as well as his mom Nina and his dad Nick..  Go, George, Go! (Sounds better than Go, Pat, Go!, doesn't it?)</menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>
 
<B>From:  LSBSmith@aol.com</B><P>
<menu>
George Burns for President, Only thing, he is not around any longer, except his soul, which lingers strong and true on my shoulder. He was so wise. So happy. So feisty, smoking those stupid old cigars when everyone knows they kill you, early in life. He loved his wife, and said nice things about her. He seemed to really love our country. He was full of common sense, always able to make Gracey's gibberish
understandable. George would have been a good president. I would have voted
for him. As for the others running, I would like to have the opportunity to vote against them. Some countries let you do that, you know. They let you cast a NO vote for those running so that it can be heard loud and clear who the people DO NOT want in office. So, anyhow, that's all I have to say on
that matter. 
<P>
Oh, William Buckley....I wouldn't mind him for Pres, either. Not that more than a handful of folks in the country would ever know what he was saying.  But that man has a mind like a steal trap. I love the way his mind works.  Love his intelligence. Love his cool manner of dealing with people who don't
know a lick, but think they do. I would vote for William. But he's too wise to get into the down and dirty act of running for office. He knows that some dumb fool would try to make him straighten his tie and sit up straight and talk "straight" talk. Darn it. Wish he'd just jump in and run. I'd vote for
him. So, once again, I think that's all I have to say on the matter. But who knows, I may be back. </menu>
<P><HR WIDTH=50%><P>
 
