<head>
<title>george jr. / july 1996 / departments / ask kitty</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/departments.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
<H2>ask kitty</H2>
Everybody knows something about nothing, and nothing about something - but who can help out with the really important stuff? Kitty, of course. Just Ask Kitty (email address: <A HREF="mailto:askkitty@aol.com">askkitty@aol.com</A>).
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
<I><font size=+3>q:</font> What is desire?</I><BR>
<font size=+3>a:</font> Desire is the fierce little growl of your soul, that tiny feral beast, when it needs to be fed.  The object of one's desire is what the soul needs to fill the chasm between it and perfection, or bliss.
<P>
In the Sufic tradition, God is the beloved, the object of desire, of both humans and angels.  According to the tradition, Lucifer was God's archangel.  When he refused to acknowledge the preeminence of Man, God's new creation, because he knew that this new lover would compete for God's attention, Lucifer was cast out of heaven, longing for God forever, and never again able to hear God's voice.
Bummer.
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q:</font> How do you figure out a tip?  And why do you tip more in New York City restaurants than you do in Little Rock, AK?</I><BR>
<font size=+3>a:</font> Tipping is an implied bargaining tool by which a diner rewards or punishes a dining establishment for the quality of experience enjoyed (or endured) therein.
<P>
Or so it would seem.  
<P>
Actually, tipping is a way for employers to get away with underpaying a wait staff, and thereby keep prices down and profits high.  Why not simply add 15% to the price of a meal and pass the extra on to the staff?  Go figure that one out for yourself.
<P>
As for percentage tipping, get real.  Does it really take less effort to serve coffee than a single malt scotch?  Of course not.  So why "give" the server less of a tip for a meal at a diner than you would at a four-star restaurant?  And am I getting off to a bad start with the server if I order the grilled chicken and a soda rather than the filet and a martini?  
<P>
It's too much to bear.  
<P>
If you must tip by percent, tip AT LEAST 15% unless you actually saw the server spit in your tortellini.  And be sure to tip according to how much time and effort you are asking of a server.  Thirty free refills on your $1.25 bottomless cup o' joe don't translate to an $.1875 tip, hon'.
<P>
And if all these moralizing tips don't get to you,  remember:  Beware of tip karma.
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q:</font> Who or what or where is God?</I><BR>
<font size=+3>a:</font> I was watching Nick Parks's remarkable Wallace and Gromit claymation movies the other day, wondering, "How the H--- did he DO that?"  I mean it all looks so seamless and "real," and you KNOW he shot each frame separately, taking into account how different materials move, look under certain light, and a million other things I can't even imagine.  And all the while, he paid great attention to achieving superb comic timing and maintaining a story.  
<P>
I thought about this for a while, and it just blew my mind.  Then I decided just to sit back and enjoy the movie.
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q:</font> My co-workers are always taking smoking breaks at work.  I don't smoke.  Should I feel guilty about taking breaks just to drink a cup of coffee or talk to a colleague?</I><BR>
<font size=+3>a:</font> I know what you mean.  I work with people who are constantly hanging around outside getting a fix of nicotine while enjoying the relaxed company of their colleagues, not to mention the weather.
<P>
Why should they have all the fun?  
<P>
Why should we reward people for having an addiction to a deadly drug?  Why can't I simply go out and sit in a sunbeam, or take a little snooze, or chat idly with my friends for five minutes without people thinking I'm "goofing off?"
<P>
Here's my solution: vice breaks.  
<P>
Give everyone the same number of little breaks to use however they choose.  A free pass for five minutes here, five minutes there, what's the big deal?  Everyone would be happier and more productive, and the work world would be a better place. 
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q:</font> If someone schedules me for lunch two weeks hence, is that a sign that we really shouldn't be wasting each other's time?</I><BR>
<font size=+3>a:</font> Maybe your friends are avoiding you because you use pretentious words like "hence."  Do you invite them to meet you at "yonder bistro wherein one finds an exquisite kitchen, whence cometh all manner of divine comestibles such as nary a gourmand can resist?"  And afterwards do you suggest that you "retire to a contiguous purveyor of fine spirits and engage in a rowdy comus"?
<P>
You rogue.
<P>
Just between you and me, gentle reader, give your friend a couple of chances, allowing for busy spells, grumpy periods, and the like, then forget it.  Friends make time for friends.  As one of my personal favs, Marcus Aurelius put it:
"Never let the excuse of duty keep you from having lunch with your friends,"  or something to that effect.

<P>
