<title>george jr. / july 1996 / departments / coffee break, 3rd cup</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../july/departments.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<H2>coffee break, 3rd cup</H2>
Aye, it's time my fair-weather, web-spanning cooks to try your hand at a real dessert.  Yes, it's time to create a cheesecake. These delicacies may appear intimidating but are remarkably easy to make.
<P>
To tease you with a taste of summer,  I thought I'd feature a raspberry chessecake.
<P>
Raspberry Cheesecake:
<MENU>
<UL>	
<LI>1 cup of crushed graham crackers
<LI>1/4 cup chopped almonds
<LI>3/4 cup sugar
<LI>4 tablespoons flour
<LI>2 tablespoons butter - melted
<LI>3-8oz. bars of cream cheese
<LI>1/4 cup raspberry liqueur
<LI>1 tablesppon vanilla
<LI>2 eggs
<LI>2-8oz. containers of raspberry yogurt
 </UL>
</MENU>
<P>
Mix graham cracker crumbs, almonds, 1/4 cup sugar, 2 tablesppons flour and butter. Press into a 9-inch springform pan.
<P>
Blend 1/2 cup sugar, remaining flour, cream cheese, liqueur and vanilla. ( If you can't find any raspberry liqueur  substitute raspberry syrup, which can be found in any respectable grocery store) Beat until fluffy. Add eggs, yogurt until well combined. (But never overbeat eggs in any cheesecake. That can cause your cheesebake to crack.)
<P>
Pour into pan. Bake at 375 degrees for 50 to 55 minutes or until  center appears set. Cool for 15 minutes. Loosen sides of springform pan with a knife and remove. Cool for 30 minutes. Refrigerate uncovered overnight.  (Cheesecakes should always be chilled overnight to let the flavor soak in.)
<P>
Top with fresh raspberries and sprinkle with powdered sugar.

<P>
