<H3><b>Now you C/click it on the screen</b></H3>
San Francisco-based syndicator GGP and C\NET: The Computer Network have entered into a partnership to produce and distribute TV.COM, a syndicated weekly television series about the Internet to be launched this  fall.  C\NET, the nation's premier provider of on-air and online content about computing and the Internet, will produce the series while GGP will distribute and market the series to stations nationwide. <br clear=all>
<P>
TV.COM will be the first television series in syndication about the Internet and the online world.  Produced to capture the fun and excitement of the Internet and the World Wide Web, the show will  have extensive ties to its own web site (www.tv.com) which will offer  viewers a truly interactive experience. At the TV.COM site, viewers  will  be able to get more information about the topics and people covered on  each week's episode, chat with guests and participate in the interactive elements of the program, whether it be voting for the best Web site  of the week, or downloading and trying out the best of new technologies  for themselves.
<P>
TV.COM is the fourth television series from C\NET: The  Computer Network, the nation's leading provider of on-air and online  content about the Internet, computers and digital technologies. In  addition  to the series TV.COM and C\NET Central, C\NET recently announced that  it will launch two new weekly television series, The Web and The New  Edge, on the Sci-Fi Channel in July.
<BR>  
<hr>
<BR>
<H3><b>HBO on the web, too</b></H3>

Where can you meet the New Yorkers who come out at 3 a.m. or get the inside scoop on the upcoming  title fight? Experience the city from a cab driver's point of view or  get  the latest jokes from Dennis Miller? Through your own computer,  thanks  to HBO's new Web site (http://www.hbo.com). The network is bringing  its  own unique style of entertainment to the Internet.  Unlike most other television Web sites, HBO offers content that is truly original -- made exclusively for the Web and found nowhere  else.  In addition, the site promotes HBO programming with additional  content, games and prizes, that enhance the HBO viewing experience.
<P>
"HBO raised the stakes for good entertainment on television with  its unique approach to programming," said Kevin Dowdell, vice  president, interactive ventures at HBO. "Our plan is to do the same thing  on  the Internet. In fact, we see our Web site as a new  entertainment  network for HBO. We are devoting the same cutting-edge talent and  creativity  to the Web as we do to our television service."
<P>
HBO's Web site offers a variety of interactive areas enhanced  with Shockwave animation and RealAudio, including:
<P>
<menu>
<ul>
<li>"III:am" presents slices of New York City life at 3  a.m.  Updated weekly, the made-for-the-Web area features interviews, photos, and articles documenting real people at work and play in the city that  never sleeps.  Insomniacs can see that they are not alone, and the rest can find out what they are missing.
<li>"Dennis Miller Live" allows visitors to interact with comedian Dennis Miller's weekly show by answering polls, asking questions of upcoming guests, and offering caption ideas for the "Big Screen"  segment in addition to catching the latest jokes. The best contributors  will  be featured in a special area of the site and may win prizes.
<li>"Taxicab Confessions," based on the HBO documentaries in which real passengers reveal their innermost thoughts and secret  experiences to their drivers, features cabbie interviews and an area where net  users may post their own confessions and read those of others.
<li>"Norma Jean and Marilyn" focuses on the duality of screen  goddess Marilyn Monroe as explored in HBO's upcoming original film through photography, animated images, a timeline of her life and times, and  an interactive memory matching game.
<li>"HBO Entertainment News" provides sneak previews of upcoming programming, from comedy specials ("Russell Simmon's Def Comedy All  Star Jam") to original movies ("Norma Jean and Marilyn").
<li>"CyberSoul City," an Afrocentric site showcasing HBO programs  and other Time Warner products created for the African-American  community, features joke submission areas, contests, sweepstakes and links to  other Afrocentric sites.
<li>"Film Reviews" showcases the candid notebook jottings of HBO chief film critic Jim Byerley who travels the world looking for  films for the HBO and Cinemax networks. Search the database for  reviews  on everything from blockbusters to art films from the man who's seen it all.
</ul></menu><BR>
The Web site will be continually updated with new content and will grow over time. 
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
<H3><b>Little woman's 'Inheritance' found</b></H3>
Cosgrove/Meurer Productions and Alliance Communications, one of  world's  leading  motion picture and television distributors, have secured the  motion  picture  and television rights to Louisa May Alcott's long-lost manuscript, "The Inheritance," in open bidding with numerous major  motion  picture  studios and production entities.
<P>
The manuscript, believed to be Alcott's first novel  and  written  at the age of 17, was found eight years ago by researchers  Joel  Myerson  (of the University of South Carolina) and Daniel Shealy  (of  the  University of North Carolina) in Harvard University's  Houghton  Library.  Written  in long-hand by Alcott -- the renowned author who went on  to  write  classics such as "Little Women" -- the manuscript has been meticulously transcribed by the two academics and only recently  revealed  to  the public.
<P>
Described as a potential family classic, "The  Inheritance"  tells  the story of an impoverished 19-year-old orphan, Edith  Adelon,  who  was embraced by a wealthy, loving family.  Driven by jealousy, a cousin tries to sabotage her relationship with the family  and  her  new-found love, by accusing her of a crime she did not commit. 
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
<H3><b>Farm Dogs make 'Last Stand'</b></H3>

Bernie Taupin has  joined forces with musician friends Robin LeMesurier, Jim Cregan and  Dennis Tufano, to form Farm Dogs. The band's debut album, "Last Stand  In  Open Country," due out on July 9, hearkens back to the members'  musical roots, featuring songs written in-the-round in the countryside of California's Santa Ynez Valley.  It also marks their multi-album association with Discovery Records, a free-standing label of the  Warner Music Group.
<P>
Taupin, one of pop music's most prolific songwriters, developed  the urge to make an organic, stripped-down song album a year ago, and thought back to the vast backlog of musicians he'd always wanted to work with.  Guitarist LeMesurier immediately came to mind, as did vocalist/harpist Tufano and guitarist/vocalist Cregan. The  four  set upon a period of songwriting-in-the-round at Taupin's ranch in  Santa Ynez, all four co-producing with co-producer/engineer David Cole. 
<P>
Studio equipment was brought to the site of the band's  inspiration, and the album was recorded. The camaraderie formed by  the  members shines through in music that lends from styles as diverse as  rock, country, blues and traditional folk.  It is music strong on melody and lyric while maintaining a simplistic approach that is both intimate  and earthy.  "So much of the atmosphere of the album is inspired and drawn from this environment," says Taupin.  "It soaked into our veins.  It's organic, no-frills music that just invented itself."
<P>
Picture four guys sitting around in a circle playing music, swapping stories, writing songs, joking, smoking, drinking and haranguing each other mercifully, and you have Farm Dogs.
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
<H3><b>A 'Mother' of a co-op venture</b></H3>

"INSIDE EDITION" and  "AMERICAN JOURNAL," America's top syndicated newsmagazines, have joined forces with "Mother Jones," the nation's foremost investigative magazine,  to produce a series of hard-hitting and thought-provoking reports.
<P>
Marc Rosenweig, Vice President for East Coast Programming for King World, which distributes both shows, said the alliance's goal is  to craft eye-opening reports that will appear on air as well as in  the pages of "Mother Jones."
<P>
Early installments focused on questionable presidential campaign contributions and the growing danger tobacco chewing poses to the young.
<P>
Of the joint venture, Rosenweig said: "We're pleased  and  excited about teaming up with 'Mother Jones,' which produces some of the  most important investigations today.  We believe this association will further enhance the already strong, award-winning investigative units  of our shows to the benefit of our viewers."
<P>
"INSIDE EDITION" and "AMERICAN JOURNAL," which are seen by more  than 13 million viewers here and abroad every weekday, have consistently won honors for journalistic excellence.
<P>
This season alone reports on Medicare fraud and military recruiting fraud have either won or are in the running to win Sigma Delta Chi and Headliner Awards for Best Investigative stories.  An examination of the plight of Bosnian orphans last month garnered an American Women in  Radio and Television Commendation Award.
<P>
"Mother Jones," which reaches more than 300,000 readers,  recently was named "Best in the Business" for magazine investigative reporting  by the American Journalism Review. It recently made headlines  with  reports on the 400 richest fat cats in American politics, the tobacco  industry's efforts to curb government and social anti-smoking pressures, and  the environmental links to breast cancer.
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>
<H3><b>R&B fest to fry brains, ears in Rockport</b></H3>

Rockport Rhythm & Blues Festival-Newport  takes place on  Friday, July 26 at the Hotel Viking and Saturday, and Sunday, July 27 and 28  at Fort Adams State Park. Created in 1995, this  benefit  festival  will continue to raise funds for the Washington D.C. based Rhythm &  Blues Foundation, and thanks to The Rockport Company's new sponsorship,  this event has grown to a two-day celebration of fantastic rhythm and  blues.
<P>
On Friday, July 26 The Rockport Rhythm & Blues Festival-Newport  will kick off with an opening night party at 8 PM at the Hotel Viking  Grand Ballroom featuring Roomful of Blues. On Saturday, July 27  Chuck  Berry, Etta James & The Roots Band, Boz Scaggs, Dr. John, Hank Ballard &  The Midnighters, The Dixie Cups, The Spaniels, and Roomful of Blues  With Special Guest LaVern Baker will appear at the festival with the  soulful sounds of classic R & B and rock 'n roll from 11:30 AM to 6:30 PM  at Fort Adams State Park. Then on Sunday, July 28 the air will  be  filled with rockin' music of Little Richard, Solomon Burke, Percy  Sledge, Michael McDonald, Martha Reeves, The Moonglows, The Allen  Toussaint Orchestra, Narada Michael Walden, Steve Cropper, and Duke  Robillard again from 11:30 AM to 6:30 PM at Fort Adams. The  Rockport  Company, sponsor of the Rhythm & Blues Festival-Newport and headquartered  in Marlboro, MA, is a leading worldwide manufacturer of performance  comfort footwear, apparel and accessories for men and women.  Principal operating units include Rockport and Ralph Lauren Footwear.
<P>
Tickets for the Rockport Rhythm & Blues Festival-Newport  Friday July 26 dance party at the Hotel Viking are $35. Single  day  tickets for the Saturday and Sunday events at Fort Adams will be $33  in advance or $35 at the gate for general admission ($15 for  children under 12). There will also be a limited number of two-day  tickets  for the Saturday and Sunday events available until July 1 for $55. On site Fort Adams State Park parking will be available for $6.00 per  car. Tickets go on sale as of Wednesday, May 15, 1996. To  purchase  tickets by mail or to receive additional information, write to:  Rockport  Rhythm & Blues Festival-Newport, P.O. Box 128, Newport, RI  02840.  Please enclose a stamped, self addressed envelope and a $3 handling  charge
per order.
<P>
Tickets may also be purchased at all ticketmaster outlets or  by calling: 
<P>
401-331-2211 (RI)<BR>
617-931-2000 or 508-931-2000 (MA)<BR>
203-624-0033 (CT)<BR>
212-307-7171 (NY)<BR>
516-888-9000 (Long Island)<BR>
201-507-8900 or 609-520-8383 (NJ).  
<P>
In addition, tickets may be purchased directly at the festival office (cash or check only) at  670 Thames Street in Newport. For more information, (but not  to  charge tickets), call 401-847-3700.
<P>
