<html>
<head>
<title>george jr. / january 1997 / features / opening gambit</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/jan97/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<img src="/graphics/gambit.gif" hspace=10 width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=15 ALT="">
<br>
<B>Welcome to January!</B>
 <P></P> Don't let a little ol' new year get you down.<P></P> 

<b>george jr.</b>
 brings you  some bracing writing
                                                         talent, book 
talk, wishful thinking,  a bushel of music
                                                         and literary 
links and, we hope, another measure of digitized comfort.

<P></P> 
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>   
But why, o why o why o why?, you ask. Because, we answer. Because. There are conduits to be relined, harbors to be retrenched, wells to be drilled, bridges to be flung across their spans, and sawmills and gristmills built using the new knowledge of fluid mechanics that will put the old structures to shame. <p></p> And of that we're positive.<p></p>
  This month, and not quite for starters, we offer a <b><font  color=#336699> fiction contest</font></b> in which you supply the conclusion to a story already begun by the painter<b> Elizabeth Fergus-Jean </b>and <b>g. jr.</b>The No. 1 prize: a bunch o' software, but everybody gets their conclusions published. <p></p>Elsewhere, satirist <b>Neil Steinberg</b> carps about, Lordy, everything; and novelist <b>Paula Sharp</b> talks more seriously about her latest, <i>Crows Over a Wheatfield</i>.<p></p>

 <b>Don Webb</b> pitches a seasonal story of charm and impossibility.
<b>William Kotzwinkle</b>, the man who brought us E.T. and a number of
tales, tells about his life, his writing and an odd bear 
who may or may not have made off with someone's manuscript.
; and we offer, too, a portfolio of works by painter <b>Michael Bowers.</b>This month's cover painting is <b>Ken Marschall</b>'s from <b>Shelley Tanaka</b>'s book <i>On Board the Titanic</i>, which <b>Nicholas A. Basbanes</b> reviews herein.</b><p></p>

There's much to do, and ever so much ahead. Let's go. Because next month's <b>Monkey Buttons </b> feature will stop you from reading anything for exactly 17.4 minutes, and that worries us plenty.<p>
</blockquote>   

<P>

<HR><BR>

<a href="/jan97/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>





</body>

</html>

 
