<html>
<head>

<title>george jr. / january 1997 / features / q & a / neil baldwin </title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/jan97/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>
<hr>


<br>

<H2>q&a</H2> 

<h3>neil steinberg: irked up to here   </h3>



<P>

<IMG SRC="/jan97/neil.jpg" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=156 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>


  <b> Neil Steinberg</b> is the author of <i>Complete & Utter Failure, If at All Possible, Involve a Cow</i> and his latest, <i>The Alphabet of Modern Annoyances</i> (Doubleday), which puts him with Paul Theroux and Kingsley Amis in the classy-whiner category. <p>
   His new book of rants slams the expecteds -  advertising, bureaucracy, computers and Disney - but also some unexpected topics, as this interview proves out:


<br clear=all>

<hr width=80%>
 
<blockquote>


<font size=5>q. </font>
What don't you find annoying?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> 
 Leading with the tough question, eh? OK. Food, I suppose. If it's good food. And not too expensive. And not served cold. See, that's the problem with good things: It's so easy for them to slide into annoyances. Except, perhaps, for money. Money is never annoying. I've never opened the mail and thought, "Dammit, another check! When will the horror end?" But then, of course, you have to worry about getting more money. Or losing what money you have. See, behind every good thing are a dozen annoyances, biding their time.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>
Do you have any particular annoying attributes you wish to share with us?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> 
 This is the question everybody fudges on their job interviews - "Well, my biggest flaw is I'm a perfectionist. I drive too hard for excellence and it makes all my coworkers look bad." Right.
   Searching over my litany of grating qualities and presenting just one or two is nearly an impossible task, very much lke having a fresh two-pound Whitman Sampler set before you. So much choice. Do I pick the obnoxious pendantry? The tendency toward using overlong, blowzy language? The awkward candor? The blurting out of ill-advised opinions to superiors and cherished friends? There are so many choices, I just can't pick one. Reading the book, many of them will become crystal clear.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>
 How do you suggest we stop the insanity?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> 
 You mean besides institutionalizing Susan Powter? I think a good start would be to try to encourage curiosity. So many people not only don't know anything, but aren't interested in finding anything out. They flop around on the public stage, making idiots of themselves, because they don't know enough to feel shame. And they are so wrapped up with opening their big bazoos to trumpet their opinions and demand their rights, they never pause to find out, never mind consider, how other people feel. Much annoyance is do to this.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>
 How did you come up with the original poem for "G Is for Gimmick"?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> 
 I'm going to sound like the Ultimate Pinhead of All Time saying this,but it was the first idea that I had. I wanted the tone of the chapters to reflect their subjects, and after deciding that "Gimmick" should be written gimmicky, the first thought was: "Make it a terza rima poem, parodying Dante's <i>Inferno</i>." Terza rima is that strict rhyme scheme - ABA BCB CDC - where the first and third lines rhyme, and the second line rhymes with the first line of the next triplet. It took forever, balancing a rhyming dictionary on my knees, but I worked it out. I'm most proud of rhyming "eternal" with "urinal" and <i>Wall Street Journal.</i>
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>
Out of all your grievances - and, boy, Neil, are you an annoyed puppy - what peeves you most?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> 
 Postage stamps. They used to have heroes on them, Washington and Lincoln and Clara Barton and such. Now every time I look at a letter, the subject matter is steadily declining - from Elvis to Nancy and Sluggo to rag dolls. I'm expecting to go to the post office some day and be offered stamps honoring Cheetos, toilet brushes and Kato Kaelin - maybe as part of the "Famous Mopes in American History" series. It has to stop.
    


</blockquote>



<HR><BR>

<a href="/jan97/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>

</HTML>


  
