<html>
<head>
<title>george jr. / january 1997 / features / q & a / paula sharp </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/jan97/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>


<br>

<h2>q&a</h2>

<h4>paula sharp: inside, looking out  </h4>



<P>

<IMG SRC="/jan97/sharp1.jpg" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=220 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>


    <b>Paula Sharp</b> is the author of <i>The Woman Who Was
Not There</i> and 
<i>Lost in Jersey City</i>; and is a criminal
                                                          lawyer who has 
encountered domestic violence in
                                                          many cases. Her 
latest novel, Crows Over a Wheatfield,
 <i>Crows Over a Wheatfield,</i> is about such a case.<p>
   Her novel revolves around two very different women whose lives become intertwined: a stoic New York judge who has grown up in the shadow of her tyrannical father; and a self-styled radical who leads a John Brown-like insurrectionist movement for the rights of women trapped in abusive relationships.


<br clear=all>

<hr width=80%>

<blockquote>

<IMG SRC="/jan97/sharp2.jpg" WIDTH=120 HEIGHT=155 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=right>

<font size=5>q. </font> Readers of <i>Crows Over a Wheatfield </i>will be surprised, some of them to discover that you've infused your characters with eccentricities and found humor in some of the situations they face.
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> <i>Crows </i>isn't a comic novel, but it certainly has comic elements. Comedy is not incompatible with with difficulty or even tragedy. The best comedy has real knowledge of grief behind it.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> Mildred's battle to win custody of her son is a nightmare. The cutody proceedsings are used as a means of controlling and endangering her son. How have your experiences inside the legal system contributed to that aspect of your story?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> The criminal justice system does little to protect people against domestic violence, but it's very punitive when people defend themselves. There are countless women in prison for defending themselves against partners after years of abuse. Family Courts are the ones that are supposedly entrusted with the duties of keeping abusive parents away from their children, of issuing restraining orders against battering spouses, of fashioning custody and visitation orders to protect women and children from violence.<br> However, Family Courts are only as good as their judges. many judges are ignorant about domestic violence, or harbor prejudice against women whom they perceive as victimizing themselves, or have difficulty believing a woman's word against that of a man. For children, it's even worse: Children are rarely listened to.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> Do you think of yourself as a writer first, or a lawyer?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>I am a writer first. I wrote and translated fiction for years before I became a lawyer, and I continued to do so all through law school and afterwards. I also believed from the beginning that almost everything I was exposed to in the criminal-justice world would have to make me a better writer. You spend a lot more time as a criminal lawyer trying to puzzle people together, making sense of their motives and figuring out how the circumstances of their lives led them down the wrong roads.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> But court proceedsings help you write better, and plot a narrative?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> The professionals who form the criminal-justice system are fascinating - the judges, prosecutors and defenders. What kind of people like to judge others? Prosecute and punish them? Play with rules in order to protect people who have broken rules, however guilty they may be? As a public defender, you try to understand why some people need to punish, or to avenge wrongs in order to feel whole, and why others are able to temper justice with mercy. <br><br>You test the depths of your personal capacity for compassion. You have to ask yourself where your own sense of justice comes from, and what justice really is.




</blockquote>


<br>
