<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>george jr. / january 1997 / arcadia / memoir / william kotzwinkle</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/jan97/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>

<p><br>
<H4>memoir:</H4>


<H3>william kotzwinkle: the story of himself
and 'The Bear Went Over the Mountain'</H3>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/jan97/koltz1.jpg" WIDTH=155 HEIGHT=220 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>



Widely known as the author of <I>E.T., the Estraterrestrial</I>, <B>William Kotzwinkle</B> also wrote<I> The Fan Man, Doctor Rat</I> and other books that have been translated into a dozen languages. The French think of him as a political satirist, the Germans see him as a Tantric mystic and, in a recent article in the Croation magazine, <I>Kult</I>, he is called the "original master of magic realism."
   His latest satire is <I>The Bear Went Over the Mountain </I>(Doubleday), in which a bear finds a manuscript in rural Maine, decides it's pretty good, gets an agent, a publicist and becomes an overnight sensation. 
<br clear=all><P>
<blockquote>
<HR>
<p>
<br clear=all>I was born in Scranton, Pa. This fact cannot be altered, though everything else that follows can be manipulated, and will be, to my advantage. My grandfather was a fisherman, and I was frequently taken on visits to the firehouse where I was alowed to slide down the fire pole. It affected me deeply, and left me with a feeling that stairs are a nuissance.
<P>

As a teen-ager, I ate a Christmas tree ornament to impress a girl. She was not impressed. I attended Penn State where I am remembered for an underground apartment called the SpiderWeb. Here I learned to play the bongo drums all night long, to the delight of the engineering students who lived in the apartment above me. I recently met a woman who said she'd attended Penn State and that once she entered my apartment when I wasn't there in order to clean my stove, whose condition toubled her sleep. I have no memory of this.
<P>

In those days, co-eds were not allowed to enter young men's apartments even to clean their stoves. Hard to believe, isn't it? I couldn't believe it, and had co-eds in my apartment. One day a telephone call came to the SpiderWeb for a co-ed who was seated beside me at that very moment. The only one in the world who knew she was there was her roommate. I handed the phone to her. The voice that came through the line was that of the housemother of her dorm. We'd been set up by the roommate, who'd been pressured by the housemother. This was my first experience of the deviousness of housemothers and it altered my view of them, permanently. I was asked to leave Penn State, and did, under a cloud.
<P>

<IMG SRC="/jan97/koltz2.jpg" WIDTH=151 HEIGHT=220 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=right>
I went to New York where I got a job in the basement of Merit Farms painting barbeque chicken signs - a plucked chicken in red, with the price per pound. I was taught this art by a Cuban refugee, who once painted gigantic murals of Batista in downtown Havana. One day, out of despair, he painted his hair red. It was thought that I'd somehow encouraged him to do this. As he was a great painter of barbeque chickens and I was only a fumbling apprentice, I was asked to leave, which I did, under a cloud.
<P>

I then worked at Paramount Theatrical Supplies and mailed rubber noses to actors. I worked at the Douglas Massage Manufacturing Co., assembling vibrators for enthusiasts. I cooked nights at the Figaro and once served a cheeseburger with lettuce and tomato and neglected to insert the burger. The waitress brought it back with a bite out of it and said, "What the hell is this?" I was asked to leave, which I did, under a cloud.
<P>

I worked as a department store Santa at E.J. Korvette's department store. A child stuck her lollipop in my bead and was unable to extract it. She cried, "Santa Claus stole my lollipop!" and yanked. It came out covered with hair. I was asked to leave, which I did, et cetera.
<P>

And then I joined fellow Penn Stater Joe Servello, who'd once painted a mural of lovely young naked women on the wall of the SpiderWeb, much to the landlord's consternation. Now here was Servello in New York, paint brush in hand. In between serving burgers without the burgers, I'd written a children's book. Servello illustrated it and we got in published. The book was called <I>The Firemen</I> - influence of the old fire pole. After that I wrote my first collection of stories, <I>Elephant Bangs Train</I>, which enjoyed critical success, but made no money. On the strength of this critical success, I married the novelist Elizabeth Gundy, at the Breadloaf Writer's Conference in Vermont, and we moved to Canada, where a bear stole Elizabeth's manuscript.
<P>

And that is the story of my life.
<P>


</blockquote>



<HR><BR>

