<HTML><HEAD>


<title>george jr. / january 1997 / arcadia / fiction contest / elizabeth fergus-jean</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/jan97/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>
<br>
<H5>fiction contest:</H5>
<P>
<H2>father's tears, mother's bones</H2>
<P><P>
<B>by elizabeth fergus-jean and george jr.</B><P>
<blockquote>
<font color=red>Note: </font>Why, just the other day, the <B>george jr.</B> clubhouse was gathered around a fire wondering why it is that some people began their sentences with the word "why" - and then a story began to brew - right there, atop Hollywood's copper-domed Griffith Observatory, which, of course you've seen on the cover of the  Byrds' 1970 album <I>Untitled</I> and, more famously in <I>Rebel Without a Cause</I>. There we were, stars streaking by overhead and myths and archetypes bubbling from the very ground beneath.<P>
But - o, my! - how does it end? With what pinch of Perreault? With what gram of Grimm? With what touch of (Hunter S.) Thompson? How? How? That, dear reader, is up to you. Send in your Amazing Conclusions, and we'll publish 'em in <A HREF="mailto:jr@georgejr.com"><b>george jr.</b></A><P>
<HR>

<H5>and now, once upon a time:</H5>
<br>

<H2>father's tears, mother's bones</H2>
<br>

        Long missing from the woods, she turned abruptly from the
flowered path and strove into the thicket. She realized at once that she had
at last found her true home. She stepped into a trickling stream, and
got wet.<P>

      As she tried to step back onto the mossy shore, she found
her left foot was stuck. She reached down and freed herself and, while
peering into the water, saw a glistening blue egg, which she picked up.
The egg
began to move in her hand, ever so slightly. She cupped it, breathing
warmly on the shell. She heard a faint sound and saw a thin crack form and
slowly increased in size.<P>

     She brought the egg up very slowly to her face and peered in.<P>

      <I>  Oofffffft! </I>She was sucked inside.<P>

<img align=right hspace=10 width=128 height=123 src=fiction1.jpg>

       Inside the egg she seemed to be swirling and tumbling in the
yolk's gel slowly and more slowly - until she came to rest before a bearded
man whittling stars.<P>

        "Where am I?," she asked.<P>

         "You are here, with me," he said. Here, let me feed you
 something.

 You look hungry." He put a sliver of star between her lips.<P>

         "Mmm, tastes good," she said. "A wee bit salty, though."<P>

         "It should," he said. "And it should taste familiar, too, because
 it's made of your father's tears and your mother's bones."<P>

         A tear formed in her eye for she knew this to be true. She had
 known since she was a young girl that she was somehow related to all the
 elements of nature. She thought of how she loved to spend endless
 hours in
 the evening starring up at the stars, and feeling as if they were her all
 ancestors.<P>

<img align=left hspace=10 width=128 height=119 src=fiction2.jpg>

         "Now," he said, "Take this star back with you. Cut it in slivers
 and spread them on the ground of the people - your family and
 friends, your
 loved ones and former lovers, your children and neighbores - and tend to
 these slivers. Nurture them, so that they too may grow. Once you see how
 easy it is to cut them into splinters and spread them around, it'll be
 hard to stop.<P>

    "This is so strange," she said. "Is this a dream?"<P>

  "Not exactly. Not quite," he said, and he turned to his workbench of
 stars and diced up several more. Some of the shavings he put into his own
  pocket. He held two handfuls out to the young woman, who gently took
 them.<P>

   "What's your name?," he asked.<P>

<img align=right hspace=10 width=123 height=126 src=fiction3.jpg>
     She lifted her head and looked into his eyes. She heard him ask again,
 "What's your name?," and she realized that he hadn't moved his mouth. They
 had been communicating this entire time simply through their minds. This
 did not frighten her, however she did not know how it could be so.<P>

    "Alana," she said.<P>

     "Ah, Alana. You will need more tools than a pocketful of stars."<P>

     He reached behind his ebony chair and brought out a walking cane the
 color of tar pitch, a round ball, sembling nothing more unusual than the
 kind of rubber ball that can be found everywhere, and a white stone or
 scrimshaw the size of his open palm.<P>

    "Each of these will help you along your way," he said.<P>

    "My way?" she asked. "But what is my way."<P>

    "Out from here," he said, and he reached to her forehead, laying one
 hand on her left temple; and kissed her in a grandfatherly sort of way.<P>

    And she was gone.<P>


         Alana heard the rustle of leaves, and birds chattering away in the
 trees over her head. She reached out her hands and found that she had
 fallen asleep on the mossy shore next to the stream she had been wading in.
 Alana sat up, and as she did a rush of images flooded her mind.<P>

         What a strange dream, she thought.<P>

            But by her side she found a ball, a cane, a small white stone
 and, burning warmly in her pocket, a small white slice of melon. No, no.
 It was a piece of something. It looked like a sliver of star - o, how it
 glowed.<P>

         She turned the sliver over and over in her hands, and as she did
  this, she remembered the kind face of the white bearded man. She closed
her
  eyes and tried to recall exactly what this man had said to her.<P>

    Soon enough, a young man happened by and woke her from her reverie.<P>

    "Hey," he said, and repeated himself as she was slow to return to the
 present. "Hey, halloooo," he said.<P>

    "Hello," she said.<P>

    "You looked like you were, well, out of it," he said. "Listen, pardon
 me for barging in on you, but where did you get the cane? Check this out."
    He rolled up his left trouser cuff and revealed a small gash and deep
 bruise.<P>

    "A horse. It was a horse," he said. "It was just standing there, off
 to the side of the footpath. I thought maybe I could pet it, or get ahold
 of its bridle. Nope. It kicked me right here. I've got a long way to go.
 It's killing me."<P>

    He gestured toward her cane. "I'd like to get me one of those," he
 said.<P>

         She looked down at the cane. This is all so incredibly weird, she
 thought. Strange men kept popping into her life. Maybe she was meant to
 give the cane to this man standing before her. It wasn't really her own
 cane to begin with, it had been given to her, and maybe just for this very
 moment.<P>

         What was it he had said about a horse? A horse!?<P>

         "A horse, around here?" She asked.<P>

        Before he could answer, Alana stood up and began to scan the
horizon. She saw nothing that might resemble a horse. Was this guy for
real? She leaned down to closer inspect his injury, and gently touch it.
        "Ouch!!!" he said. "Hey, it's real already!"<P>

        "Oh, I'm sorry," she said. She put her hand just below the wound.


        She sat down and drew him towards her. Moving his injured leg into
her lap, she slowly began to massage his leg. He closed his eyes and melted
into the moment.<P>

  When he opened his eyes and looked at his leg, he found it healed.<P>

   "Yikes," he said. "How did THAT happen?" At that moment, he heard the
whinnying of the horse. he turned around and there it was, munching some
eel grass growing by the road. He and Alana stood and walked toward the
horse. Her hand might have brushed against his side, but maybe it didn't.
He climbed upon the horse, which allowed him to, and he rode off.<P>

        Alana watched as he rode over the hill. She had the urge to follow
him, so she went back to where she had been sitting to gather up her
things. When she reached the edge of the stream she located the spot where
she had been, and began to pick up the items on the ground. She picked up
the ball and rolled it around in her palm. It was so smooth and cool. She
looked into its polished surface and gasped at what she saw: an image of
the young man, riding off; and another, of an elderly woman meandering
toward her, along the very same path.<P>

   Alana turned just in time.<P>

   "Hello," said the woman. Her coarse-looking hair was the color of
steel. A red bandana she wore around it gave her the countenance of a warrior.
   "Hello," said Alana.<P>

   "I know, I know," said the woman. "You saw me in the polished stone,
just as I appeared behind you. I know all about it. I carried that same
stone with me for nearly 40 years."<P>

   Alana gasped. "You mean you know all about this? You mean, you can
tell me what this is all about?"<P>

       "Well, yes and no," she said as she sat down by the stream. She
leaned over, cupped her hands, then dipped them into the clear water and
drank. "My, that water tastes so good. Here, please come sit down next to
me,  and I will share with you what I can. I presume you have met my dear
friend and guild, the alchemist."<P>
<br>
	<CENTER> . . . to be continued, by you.</CENTER><br><P>
