<html><head>
<title>george jr. / january 1997 / arcadia / magical books / nicholas a. basbanes</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/jan97/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotofb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br><br>
<H4>kid stuff:</H4>


<H2>magical books, living forever</H2>

<B>by nicholas a. basbanes</B><br>
<SUB>Art from Colin Thompson's <I>How to Live Forever</I><P></SUB><P></P>


<blockquote><br>

 Anything is possible through the magic of books. Two new releases celebrate the libraries of the world in two very different ways, one through a fanciful leap of the
imagination, the other through a concise presentation of facts.<P>


<IMG SRC="magic.jpg" WIDTH=158 HEIGHT=220 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
In <I><B>How to Live Forever</B> </I>(Knopf, $17, all ages), the noted British author and illustrator Colin Thompson poses a question that has been pondered at some point by everyone, and gives it an unexpected twist in a story that will charm adults as
much as it will beguile young readers. The setting is an old library with a thousand rooms, a building that is quiet and sedate by day, but vibrant and alive at night. For two years, a character named Peter leaves his "home" within the pages of a book called "Quinces," and searches for a missing book he believes will give him the answer to eternal life. The wisdom he gains--and the decision he makes - can be summarized with a single adage: "To live forever is to not live at all."   <P>

<I>  <B> The Inside-Outside Book of Libraries</B></I> (Dutton, $15.99, Ages 5-10), the latest in a series of  "inside-outside" books by artist Roxie Munro and writer Julie Cummins, presents the wide diversity of American libraries, and the people they
serve. The 650 residents of Ocracoke Island off the coast of North Carolina, for instance, have a tiny one-room clapboard building to house a modest collection of books; the Library of Congress in Washington, D.C., adds to its vast holdings of more
than 20 million books at the rate of 10 items a minute. A nice touch here is the page of braille, a subtle reminder that books, indeed, are for everyone.<P>

    Two stories that have achieved folklore status, one over a period of centuries, the other in the space of a few brief decades, have been given fresh new tellings, with fresh new illustrations.<P>

    In <I><B>Robin of Sherwood</B></I> (Harcourt Brace, $22, all ages), Michael Morpurgo, the respected author of more than 40  books for children, teams up with the noted artist Michael Foreman to give a new vision to a traditional legend. In this version, a 12-year-old boy ventures outside his home after a fierce storm to discover an ancient tree uprooted, revealing a huge crater in the ground and a human skull. With echoes of
Dorothy and Toto going off to Oz, the boy is whisked back several hundred years and drawn into an adventure involving Robin, Marion (now his wife), Friar Tuck, the evil Sheriff of Nottingham, and a band of Sherwood Forest inhabitants known as the Outcasts. The result is a rollicking story that is both familiar and new at the same time. Hint: the site where the fallen tree once grew offers a clever solution to this richly-textured journey through time.<P>

    <I><B> On Board the Titanic</B></I> (Hyperion, $16.95 Ages 9- 11), by writer Shelley Tanaka and Ken Marschall, a special effects artist for the film industry whose real-life paintings have been featured in<I> National Geographic</I> and on the cover of <I>Time</I> magazine (and on the cover of <A HREF="http://www.georgejr.com">george jr.</A>). Here, they present an "I Was There" account of one of the 20th century's most haunting disasters from the viewpoint of Jack Thayer, a 17-year-old survivor of the sinking whose belief that the ill-fated liner broke in two on the surface before going down was validated 73 years later when the wreck was discovered by Dr. Robert Ballard in two large sections on the ocean floor.<P>
 Hundreds of details are included in the text, along with many photographs. But it is Marschall's extraordinary paintings that will linger long after the covers are closed.     
 

<HR>
<SUB>
<blockquote>
<B>Nicholas A. Basbanes</B> is a Massachusetts journalist and author of <I> A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the Eternal Passion for Books.</I>
</SUB></blockquote></blockquote><P>

