<head>
<title>george jr. /january 1997 / departments / ask kitty</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" 
ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/jan97/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" 
WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 
border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
<H2>ask kitty</H2>
<br>

    Ask Kitty is a straight arrow when it comes to life's imponderables, 
and we're ever so glad she's with <I>us </I> rather than
<I> them</I>. Have a question? Don't hesitate to <A 
HREF="mailto:askkitty@georgejr.com">ask kitty.</A> Our operator is 
standing by . . .
<br clear=all>

<hr width=80%>

  

<p>



<blockquote>
<P>
<font size=+3>q.</font>
 What's the correct way to behave with a house full of plumbers and
carpenters?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> 
 It depends on whether you are one of them, or they happen to be working 
in
your house.  If the former is the case, and the homeowner is nowhere to 
be seen,
just go ahead and do everything your mother taught you never to do in 
someone
else's home.  Property damage, not to mention general disgustingness, 
should
concern you not in the least.  The work you are doing is most likely so 
mysterious and
important to the homeowners that they will not only put up with your 
behavior,
but will pay you large sums of money to ruin their home.  If you are the 
homeowner
who is thinking about having these people carry on in your house, I 
suggest
you first rent the movie<I> The Plumber</I> (1980),  by Peter Weir, and 
realize
that it is a documentary.
<P>
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font>
 What was your New Year's Eve resolution?<BR>

<font size=+3>a.</font> Always to have tissues on my desk, clean 
underpants in my drawer, and a
respect for the passage of time.<BR>
<BR>
<font size=+3>q.</font> 
 How do I get my husband off the computer?<BR>

<font size=+3>a.</font> Do you love him?  Let him be who he is.  Too many 
a person reacts in
jealousy to his or her mate's interests.  Remember, you may be partners, 
but you are
also still individuals with individual wants and needs.  Not the least of 
which is
just to have the time to do silly (or enriching) things without guilt.  
And
besides, people have varying degrees of tolerance for the company of 
another.  So
unless this behavior is part of a bigger problem (i.e., he's shirking 
familial or
marital responsibilities), leave him alone.  And do some things for 
yourself to
boost your own self-esteem.<P>
</P>
<font size=+3>q.</font>
I'm stuck at my desk all day working, except for those hurried trips
to the company basement to buy processed food. What would you take to
work in a lunch bag if you were me?<BR>

<font size=+3>a.</font> 
 A brain.  Whether you pack your lunch or not, you do no favors to 
yourself
or your employer by habitually working through your lunch hour.  You  
NEED to
get away from your desk for an extended break in the middle of the day.  
Life is
too short for this nonsense.  And that's what it is.  Your work, not to 
mention
your soul, will benefit from a mid-day change of venue.<br>
<br>
<font size=+3>q.</font>


Do you dress in that skin-color system, i.e., according to whether you
are a fall, summer, spring or winter? And why do people do it?<br>

<font size=+3>a.</font> 

I've always been fascinated by color theory and how we perceive color. 
Did you know that cats see the world bichromatically?  This allows them 
to spot
small movement (like prey, or the fringe on your silk scarf) at a 
distance.  The
perception of too many colors apparently clutters the visual field.  
Humans filter
the visual world through two colors, red and green, which the brain then
interprets as being three distinct colors.  Wow.  And then there's the 
work of Chevreul,
Rood, Delaunay and Kandinsky.  Really cool stuff.  As far as dressing, I 
like to
wear things that I like.

</blockquote>



<p>

