<BODY>

<title>george jr. / january 1997 / departments / letter from austin 
</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" 
ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/jan97/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" 
WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br><br>
<H4>letter from austin</H4>
<P>
<P>
<H2>xmas-card index reveals key shifts in motifs</H2>
<P>
<P>
<B>by jeanne claire van ryzin</B><hr><P>

<blockquote>
        It reads as if it were a seasonal NASDAQ report:<P>


      <LI>  "Rustic snow scenes (especially doorways) held their own, 
remained
about 15% of total."

       <LI> "Ships and galleons dropped from 10% to 3%."

      <LI>  "Stage coaches dropped from 10% to 5%; Scotties from 9% to 
1/2%."

       <LI> "Santa Claus figures rose from 2% to 4%."

     <LI>   "Wise men and camels rose from 3% to 6%."

      <LI>  "Deer, of the Bambi type, almost displaced traditional 
reindeer at 10%."

       <LI> "Holly and poinsettia and mistletoe held their own, about 9%;
Victorian scenes (including Dickens) ditto, about 5%."

     <LI>   "Drinking scenes, clowns and mistletoe vanished."

    <LI>    "Stables and mangers rose from 1% to 4%."

       <LI> "Angels and cherubs rose from 2% to 7%."

      <LI>  "Yule logs held firm at 2%."

       <LI> "New motifs, e.g. skiing, 2%"

     <LI>   "Evergreens, pine cones, and trees, firm at 2%."<P>



        Writer Christopher Morley's <B>Analysis of Christmas Cards 1942 
(as
compared with previous analysis made in 1935)</B> is a reportage of 
inspired
absurdity and brilliance, surely compiled during the frightening bleak
January boredom of the post-holiday season.<P>

        Yet, not to let his findings languish without result, Morley
continued his Yule-time ratiocination of card themes in 1948 and penciled
in an update.  He records that snow scenes stayed high as did designs of
stars and candles, churches in deep snow, holly and poinsettia, angels and
cherubs, waits, carols, and churchbells.  Yule logs, monks and medieval
scenes disappear, as do ships and galleons, stables and mangers, drinking
scenes, clowns, and mistletoe.  Not surprisingly, the post-World War II
baby boom is reflected with "family photos, scenes, or persons (especially
babies)" as the new leader logging in at 16 cards.<P>

        Morley noted other new categories for 1948:<P>

       <LI> "Text only with illustration" (10 cards)
        <LI>"Madonna & child" (3 cards)
       <LI> "Cooking or drinking recipes" (1 card)
       <LI> "Modernist design" (1 card)
     <LI>   "Puppies or kittens" (1 card)
       <LI> "Sherlock Holmes" (1 card)
     <LI>   "Historic buildings or paintings" (5 cards)
       <LI> "Noel mentioned" (2 cards)<P>


        During his lifetime (1890-1957), Morley was one of America's most
popular novelists, essayists, and poets.  Yet while his first novel,
Parnassus on Wheels, was published in 1917 and remains in print today,
Morley's other contributions are seldom remembered.  The terrifically wide
span of his work easily earns him the title man of letters and one
contemporary of his said that Morley "indeed loves the English language 
for
its own sake."  His witty columns for the <I>New York Evening Post</I> in 
the
1920s and for the <I>Saturday Review of Literature</I> - for which he 
wrote from
1924-1941 and which he helped found-were widely read.  Twice he edited
editions of<I> Bartlett's Familiar Quotations</I>.  In a satirically 
self-written
obituary Morley submitted to the reference dictionary, <I>Twentieth 
Century</I><I>
Authors</I>, he wrote "Morley was probably as much puzzled or troubled by
himself as some of his readers were by him.  His best loved private
associations were with people devoid of conventional culture, such as
booksellers, shipmasters, traveling salesman, headwaiters, and occasional
professors of English literature."<P>

        In Texas our winters lack the insensate cold and attenuated
darkness as those of Morley's New York.  But we suffer no less from the
protracted and numbing boredom of the post-holiday period, enhanced by the
unromantic sight of leftover holiday yard displays in sunny, snowless
settings.  And so with Christmas tree recycling day upon us in
eco-conscious Austin, I add new rubrics for the continuation of Morley's
analysis from my own stack of cards received this year:<P>


        <LI> An unkindly amount of angels.
        <LI>Endangered species, especially the young of endangered 
species.
        <LI>  Endangered natural environments (printed, de rigeur, on 100%
post-consumer recycled paper).
        <LI> Cartoon characters (especially Dilbert and Far Side).
        <LI>  Disease-related causes:  various and assorted cancers, AIDS,
Alzheimer's, MS, dyslexia, etc.
        <LI> Winter Solstice, New Year's, Kwanzaa, Women's Empowerment, 
and
other events that are, foremost, Not Christmas.
        <LI> Admonitions to Peace on Earth, World Peace, One World, World
Unity, Children of the World, People of the World, Animals of the World,
etc.
        <LI> Anthropomorphized animals (especially cats) engaged in 
holiday
activities (tree-trimming, caroling, etc.) or dressed as holiday
characters.
        <LI>  Non-anthropomorphized animals (again, especially cats) 
decorated
with holiday trimmings or in holiday settings.
        <LI> Cards made by children in distress or under life-threatening
conditions (hungry children in large urban areas of the United States;
children in war-torn Bosnia; blind or hair-lipped children in missionary
schools in Central America, etc.).
        <LI> Cards made by anyone who suffers from compromised 
circumstances
or cards made and sold on their behalf (hungry adults in large urban areas
of the United States, people with physical or mental impairments, etc.).
        <LI> Designs created by dead artists-notably Andy Warhol and Keith
Haring-who nevertheless continually produce new holiday images each year.
        <LI> Images by famous artists and/or architects (in particular
Georgia O'Keefe, Frank Lloyd Wright, and any of the Impressionists) not
originally created to be holiday-like, but, through some tenuous visual
association (snow, use of red and green, images of stars, etc.), are now
considered in the spirit of the season.<P>


        I admit my own (snobbish) proclivity to sending cards from the
latter two categories.  However this year, after contemplating the pros 
and
cons of sending holiday email messages instead of actual cards or perhaps
even setting up a Christmas card web site to which I could then direct
everybody, I bucked my routine by sending old Mexican Christmas postcards
in clear envelopes which I then stuffed with glitter.  Most of the cards,
as I understand from my list of recipients, never made it through the U.S.
postal system.<P>

        Perhaps this proposes a new motif of sorts for the index:  cards
sent but never received.  And that leaves the possibilities for
message-writing enticingly endless.<P>
<HR>
<blockquote>
<font size=-1><B>Jeanne Claire van Ryzin</B> is a fiction writer and information 
director at the University of Texas' Harry Ransom Humanities Research 
Center.
</font>
</blockquote>
<P>
</blockquote>
