<BODY><P>

<title>george jr. / january 1997 / departments / key west / patrick lennon</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#336699" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/jan97/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotodb.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home2.gif" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=36 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br><br>
<H4> letter from key west:</H4>

<H2>the great train robbery</H2>
<blockquote>
<br>
<B>by patrick lennon</B><P>
<P>


     

     The rude buzz-saw shriek of a power mower roused J.C.

Terwilliger from sleep.  He struggled to his feet and glared at

the greens-keeper who waved a friendly hello and continued mowing

the sixth green at the Key West Golf Club.<P>


     Although J.C.'s address had an exclusive view, he was a bum.

He and Luke, a large black man, shared the protective canopy of a

gumbo-limbo tree in a thicket that separated the golf club from

U.S. 1.<P>


     J.C.'s head hammered with a hangover from cheap wine.  The

wine had helped him fall asleep without caring why he lived under

a tree.  He thought it ironic that his former home at Oak Hill

Country Club in Rochester, New York also had a golf course view.<P>


     He fingered his scraggly beard and struggled to recall the

conversation with Luke before he fell asleep.  It had been

something about outlaws.<P>


     "Jesse James,"  he said.<P>


     "Jesse James?"  Luke grunted.  He peeled the matted army

blanket off his ponderous body and rubbed sleep from his blood-

shot, brown eyes.<P>


     "I told you Jesse James was a thief and a racist," Luke

said.<P>


               "Perhaps, but  he believed in the free enterprise system.  A

          man ahead of his time.  A venture capitalist."<P>


               "Capitalist?"  Luke asked, stretching, "Henry Ford was a

          capitalist.  Jesse James was a fuckin train robber."<P>


               "True, but he didn't get any government hand-outs.  He

          depended on his own talents."<P>


               "In his day, robbin trains wasn't much of a talent.  All it

          took was a big gun, a fast horse, and a little nerve."<P>


               "That's what we should do,"  J.C. said.<P>


               "What you talkin 'bout?"<P>


               "Rob a train."<P>


               "How are we goin to rob a train in Key West?"  Luke snorted,

          scratching his belly.<P>


               "The Conch Train."<P>



               "Man, you are crazy."<P>


               "Tourists carry lots of cash.  They all have watches,

          jewelry, and cameras.  The Japanese usually have two or three

          cameras looped around their necks.  We could hock them at the

          pawn shop.  What we need is a plan."<P>


               "What we need is breakfast,"  Luke said.<P>


               "Food?"  J.C. asked.  "At a time like this, you think of

          food?"<P>


               "We can't rob a train on an empty stomach,"  Luke said.<P>


               "All right, how do you propose to pay for breakfast?"<P>


               Luke searched his pockets.  He removed his huge hands from

          his Levi's and produced three quarters.<P>




               "Remember, I bought the wine last night."  "Seventy-five

          cents.  How much you got?"<P>


               J.C. stuffed his hands into his pockets and produced five

          quarters, a dime, and twelve pennies.  "A dollar forty-seven."

               "O.K. I'll get us a croissant with egg and ham and two cups

          of coffee."<P>


               "Should I go with you?"<P>


               "Do you think I'd eat your share?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "Of course not, I trust you.  I'll work on the plan while

          you're gone."<P>


               "Whatever,"  Luke said, shaking his head, as he walked

          toward U.S. 1.<P>


               J.C. removed a water stained, yellow tablet and a Conch

          Train promotional brochure from his kit.  He chewed a point on a

          number two pencil stub and began writing.<P>


               When Luke returned with the coffee and croissant, J.C. had

          the plan nearly completed.  Luke split the croissant and passed

          half to J.C. along with a cup of coffee.  J.C., preoccupied with

          his plan, placed the food on the ground and continued writing.<P>


               "The get-a-way is critical,"  J.C. said.  "Jesse James

          always had a fast horse.  We'll need fast horses."<P>


               "Where the hell are you goin to find horses in Key West?

          I've lived here five years and never seen one horse.  We can't

          get no horses,"  Luke said.

               "You mean any horses."<P>



               "Any horses?  No horses?  We still can't find a fuckin horse

          in Key West!"  Luke bellowed, inhaling part of his ham and egg

          croissant.<P>


               "We need a substitute . . . any suggestions?"<P>


               Luke thought while he chewed his croissant.  He swallowed,

          sipped coffee, and said,  "Bikes!"<P>


               "Luke, you're a genius.  Bicycles are the answer.  Of

          course, they're not as dependable or as faithful as a spirited

          steed, but we must be flexible and adapt to local conditions."

               "O.K., so we get a couple of bikes.  Then what?"<P>


               "I've analyzed the Conch Train's route,"  J.C. said,

          pointing to a map inside the brochure.  "They turn south from

          Green Street onto Ann Street and stop a few moments so the

          engineer can describe the Curry Mansion.  It's a perfect place

          for an ambush.  That's where we strike."<P>


               "Strike?"<P>


               "Yes.  You'll block the way and wave a large gun at the

          engineer.  I'll start at the rear of the train and relieve the

          tourists of their wallets, purses, and cameras.  I'll put

          everything in a plastic garbage bag.  When I've finished

          collecting the loot, you'll order the engineer to continue toward

          Duval Street.  We'll get on our bicycles and make our get-a-way.

          It's simple and straight forward, like any good business plan."<P>


               "Except one thing,"  Luke said.<P>


               "What?"<P>


               "Where are we goin get bikes?"<P>



               "I'm responsible for planning.  You're in charge of

          logistics."<P>


               "Logistics?"  Luke thought a moment, and said, "Oh, you want

          me to steal the bikes?"<P>


               "That's logistics."<P>


               "What about the gun?"<P>


               Both men sampled their croissants.  J.C. wiped his mouth

          with a napkin, and said, "We'll need a gun.  A large gun.  A gun

          that will intimidate the tourists."<P>


               "Is that part of logistics?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "Yes, and the garbage bag."<P>


               "I got all the work,"  Luke said.<P>


               "I specialized in planning, before my unfortunate

          bankruptcy."<P>


               "If you're a planner, I'm a rocket scientist."  Luke

          countered.<P>


               "Can you get the bicycles, gun, and garbage bag?"<P>


               "I'm not sure about the gun, but I can latch onto a couple

          of bikes and a garbage bag."<P>


               "O.K., when you've assembled the resources, we'll put my

          plan into action.  Of course, you'll need a plan to appropriate

          the bicycles."<P>


               "I don't need no plan to get bikes in Key West,"  Luke said.<P>


               "You don't need any plan to get bicycles,"  J.C. corrected.<P>


               "That's what I said."<P>


               When they finished eating, Luke walked across Cow Key

          Channel bridge to the parking lot of a motel.  He located several


          bicycles haphazardly parked near the manager's office but out of

          view.  Only a few had locks on them.  He thought a pair of

          mountain bikes with knobby tires would be perfect.  He selected

          two that had baskets and casually walked up to them.  Trying not

          to look suspicious, he picked one up by the seat, balanced it

          across the handlebars of another, saddled onto the bike, and

          weaved out of the parking lot.<P>


               J.C. broke into a broad grin when he saw Luke.  "My father

          used to say the early bird gets the worm.  I see you've been

          successful."<P>


               "Do you know how to ride a bike?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "Of course."<P>


               "Let me see,"  Luke challenged.<P>


               J.C. tucked his right trouser cuff into his sock, hefted his

          leg over the seat, pedaled five feet, hit an exposed root on the

          Gumbo-Limbo tree, and tumbled to the ground.<P>


               Luke's belly jiggled as he laughed.  "Maybe your father

          should have got you a bike instead of a worm."  Luke sneered.<P>


               "I'm a little out of practice.  By the time you locate the

          gun and garbage bag, I'll be ready for the Tour de France."<P>


               "The gun is a problem,"  Luke said, his face growing solemn

          and his voice deepening to a whisper.  "I don't like guns."    He

          removed a knife from his back pocket and flipped open the switch

          blade.  "This was standard issue in my neighborhood."<P>


               "People run from knives.  They don't run from guns.  A gun

          has staying power."<P>


               "Those old white ladies with blue hair ain't goin to run.

          Besides, most of their husbands can't stand up without their

          walkers.  A knife will do just fine."<P>


               "No, we'll need a gun,"  J.C. said.<P>


               "Then you get the gun.  I've done all I'm goin to."<P>


               The two men sat silently for a minute.  Luke drew stick men

          in the sandy soil with a twig, nibbled on his sandwich, and

          avoided eye contact with J.C.<P>


               "O.K., I'll get the gun,"  J.C. said.  "I have a plan."<P>


               "When?"<P>


               Today,"  J.C. replied.  "Tomorrow, we rob the Conch Train."<P>


               "I'm goin to the Sunset diner,"  Luke said.  "They pay five

          dollars and lunch if I wash the breakfast dishes.  I'll see you

          later.  Oh, you want me to buy some wine?"<P>


               J.C. nodded yes and leaned his bike against the tree.  After

          Luke blended into morning traffic on U.S. 1, J.C. rummaged

          through his kit, removed a can of Vienna sausages and opened it.

          As he ate, he watched the sun slowly climb over Stock Island.

          "KMart doesn't open until nine o'clock."<P>


               At two in the afternoon, Luke returned with a gallon of Mad

          Dog 20-20 and a plastic bag filled with sandwiches.  "I must have

          done a good job.  The manager gave me these," he said, hefting

          the bag in front of J.C.<P>


               "Good . . . my day was equally successful."<P>


               "You got a gun?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "Yes."<P>


               "I don't believe it."<P>



               J.C. belched, as he leaned over and opened his kit.  He

          produced a revolver, and a box of plastic trash bags.<P>


               "Jesus Christ!"  Luke said.  "Where did you get it?"<P>


               "KMart."<P>


               "KMart?  A toy gun.  You got a toy gun?"<P>


               "It'll be just as effective as a real gun.  We have the

          element of surprise.  One look at you waving a gun will convince

          them we're desperate.  You'd be surprised what white people will

          do when a black man points a large gun at them."<P>


               "No different with a knife,"  Luke said.<P>


               Later that evening, they sat in quivering shafts of

          moonlight, filtering through the leaves of the Gumbo-Limbo tree.

          Luke sipped wine from a paper cup and asked,  "Do you think this

          is a good idea?  I'm not sure I want to go through with this."<P>


               "It won't fail,"  J.C. said.  "Have confidence in my plan."<P>


               "Man, you ever done hard time?"<P>


               "You mean prison?"  J.C. asked.<P>


               "Yeah."<P>


               "No."<P>


               "Sometimes things don't go like they's planned," Luke said.<P>


               "Only if it's a defective plan,"  J.C. said.  "Quit worrying

          and pass the wine."<P>


               At nine a.m., they biked across Cow Key Channel bridge, then

          followed the sidewalk along Roosevelt Boulevard until they came

          to Palm Avenue.  J.C., panting heavily, walked his bicycle to the

          top of the Garrison Bight Bridge on Palm Avenue, but coasted down

          the other side.<P>



               With Luke leading the way, they turned right on Grinnel

          Street and left on Caroline Street, continuing to Ann Street.

          They parked their bicycles on the sidewalk on the east side of

          the Curry Mansion.<P>


               "We'll wait until we see a full train before we execute the

          plan,"  J.C. said, catching his breath and mopping his forehead

          with a red calico bandana.<P>


               They stared north on Ann Street, and a few minutes later, a

          Conch Train rounded the Old City Hall, turning onto Ann Street.<P>


               "Looks full,"  Luke said.<P>


               J.C. studied the coaches.  "No, there's too many empty

          seats."<P>


               Sweat streamed from J.C.'s pink forehead.<P>


               "How you feel?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "I'm a little out of sorts,"  J.C. said.  "I'll be all

          right."<P>


               "Your face is redder than your bandana."<P>


               "I need a few minutes."<P>


               Another Conch Train turned on to Ann Street.  Only a few

          seats were empty.<P>


               "What about this one?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "No, let's wait,"  J.C. said.  "I'll move down the street.

          If I think the next train has enough passengers, I'll signal you

          with a "thumbs-up" sign.  Don't use our real names."<P>


               "What do you want me to call you?"  Luke asked.<P>


               "Jesse."<P>


               "Am I Frank?"<P>


               "Yes.  Did you know that was the name of Jesse's brother?"

          J.C. asked.<P>


               "Listen, Jesse, I didn't just fall off the back of a turnip

          truck."<P>


               J.C. walked north on Ann Street.  He sat on the concrete

          base of the fence surrounding the Curry Mansion, breathing

          heavily and mopping his forehead.<P>


               A Conch Train rounded Old City Hall with every seat filled.

          J.C. signaled Luke.  Luke gripped the handle of the toy gun

          stuffed in his waistband.<P>


               When the train's engine braked at Caroline Street, the

          engineer began his canned presentation of the historical

          significance of the Curry Mansion.  Luke approached the

          engineer's cab.  Suddenly there was a loud scream.  All the

          passengers on the train focused on J.C., facedown on the sidewalk

          near the last passenger car.<P>


               "Hey,"  a man with a New Jersey accent yelled from the last

          passenger car, "I think he's having a heart attack or something."<P>


               "I'm a retired nurse's aide,"  a woman with blue hair and an

          authoritative voice said, climbing down from her seat.  "I'll

          examine him."<P>


               Luke glanced at J.C., sprawled on the ground.<P>


               "Outta that seat twerp,"  Luke ordered the engineer.  The

          young man noticed the gun Luke gripped in his waistband, bounded

          out of the cab, and raced toward Duval Street.<P>


               "Load him on the train,"  yelled Luke.<P>


               As three men manhandled J.C. into the last car, Luke tossed

          the toy gun into the front yard of the Curry Mansion.  When

          everyone reboarded the train, Luke mounted the cab.  After

          scrutinizing the controls for a few seconds, he shifted the

          transmission into gear, pushed the accelerator to the floor, and

          turned left on Caroline Street.<P>


               The Conch Train was going thirty miles an hour when it ran

          the red light at Simonton Street.  As it whizzed through the

          intersection of Elizabeth and Caroline Streets, the speedometer

          registered fifty miles per hour.  At Grinnel Street, Luke braked,

          turned south, and nearly tipped over the cars.  Passengers

          screamed and pedestrians gawked at the fleeting train.  At Eaton

          Street, he turned left.<P>


               The passengers, clinging to their seats, shrieked and

          groaned as Luke threaded through traffic, turning into Trumbo

          Point and Peary Court.<P>


               When he reached Roosevelt Boulevard and turned left, Luke

          discovered the bell and rang it with urgency.  As he maneuvered

          down the center of Roosevelt Boulevard, cars veered left and

          right avoiding the speeding train.<P>


               A Key West Police car, with bubble gum lights flashing,

          pulled up next to Luke.  The officer riding in the passenger seat

          yelled at Luke, "What's going on?"<P>


               "A passenger's dying,"  Luke said.  "I'm takin him to the

          hospital."<P>


               "Follow us,"  the policeman said.<P>



               The siren screeched, tires squealed, and the police car sped

          ahead of the train.<P>


               The policeman radioed another patrolman who cleared traffic

          at the turn to Stock Island.  Following the police car, Luke

          swerved onto Junior College Road and braked at the emergency room

          entrance of Lower Keys Hospital.<P>


               Waiting under the portico, nurses and doctors, alerted by

          the police, sprang into action.  They clamped an oxygen mask on

          J.C. and loaded him onto a gurney.  The policemen followed J.C.'s

          gurney into the Emergency Room lobby.  The passengers disembarked

          the train and gathered around the engine.<P>


               "That was quite a job of driving," a passenger said to Luke.

          "If he lives, you saved his life, but you scared hell out of me."<P>


               "That's for sure,"  another passenger said.<P>


               "I've not had so much excitement in years,"  a matronly lady

          in plaid shorts and a bulging halter said.<P>


               "What happened to the engineer?"  A passenger asked.<P>


               "He panicked,"  Luke said.<P>


               "You deserve a reward,"  a man leaning on a walker said.

          "I've never seen such driving skill."<P>


               "Yeah,"  passengers echoed.  "You're a hero."<P>


               "Let's take up a collection,"  the matronly lady said.<P>


               A rotund man with a cherry red face passed his floppy straw

          hat among the passengers.  "O.K. I don't want to hear any coins

          tinkle in my hat."<P>


               The next afternoon, Luke stopped at the information counter

          of the hospital and asked a blue haired lady in a pink smock


          which room Jasper C. Terwilliger occupied.  She spun the rack and

          searched the admission cards.<P>


               "Sorry, we don't have a Mr. Terwilliger."<P>


               "What about James, Jesse James?"<P>


               "Yes, Mr. James has just been moved from the Coronary Care

          Unit to Room 423.  His diagnosis is an acute gallbladder."<P>


               "What's his condition?"<P>


               "It says good," she said, suspiciously looking over her

          half-eye glasses at Luke.<P>


               "I'd like to see him."<P>


               "Sorry, only relatives."<P>


               "I'm his brother, Frank."<P>


               "I've heard of you and your brother."  She handed him a

          pass.<P>


               "Luke!"  J.C. said, when Luke entered the room.  "What

          happened?"<P>


               "I'll explain it to you later.  How you feel?"<P>


               "Tip-top."<P>


               "Are you up to a dinner at the Pier House?"<P>


               "I take it our venture was successful?"<P>


               "Everythin worked out,"  Luke said.<P>


             J.C. beamed. "Just like I told you, we needed a plan."  <P>

          

<P>
<HR>
<P></blockquote>
