<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / features / opening gambit</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/gambit.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=15>
<br><br><br>
Welcome to the August issue of <b>george jr.</b>, which covers literature, the arts and web stuff in  rip-snortin', interactive, low-, medium- and highfalutin ways. 
<p>
This month we bring you our Summer Sex & God issue - well, what would you call it? -
comprising, after all, an interview with an ex-geisha as well as the man
who knows God best. Also, Joyce Carol Oates chats about macabre sexual obsessions and a
bad priest-to-be, Tony Mendoza offers a cat-house confession, and God knows
what else.

<p>
Raise a glass, if you please, to  Laura Patterson, Victoria N. Alexander, Karen Elizabeth Gordon, Joe Napora,  Richard Kostelanetz and  the rest of this month's gang.
<p>
And BTW:
<p>
Thank you for responding  for our impromptu questionnaire about the world's hottest creative couples, something we thought perfect for the Sex & God issue. We like your responses, which are:
<p>
Camille Claudel and Auguste Rodin<br>
Sonia and Robert Delaunay<br>
Clara and Andre Malraux<br>
Vanessa Bell and Duncan Grant<br>
Leonora Carrington and Max Ernst<br>
Frida Kahlo and Diego Rivera<br>
Kay Sage and Yves Tanguy<br>
Sea and Shore<br>
Anais Nin and Henry Miller<br>
Lillian Hellman and Dashiell Hammett<br>
Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg<br>
Simone and Andre Schwarz-Bart<br>
Lee Krasner and Jackson Pollock<br>
Edward VII and Wallis Simpson<br>
Frank Sinatra and Ava Gardner<br>
Margot Fonteyn and Roberto Arias<br>
John Lennon and Yoko Ono<br>
Heavens and Murgatroid<br>
Aces and Eights<br>
Clark Gable and Carole Lombard<br>
Gertrude Stein and Alice B. Toklas<br>
Katharine Hepburn and Spencer Tracy<br>
Boris Pasternak and Olga Ivinskaya<br>
Roy Rogers and Trigger<br>
John and Elizabeth Fergus-Jean<br>
Thunder and Lightening<br>
William Randolph Hearst and Marion Davies<br>
Grace Kelly and Prince Rainier<br>
Popeye and Olive Oyl<br>
Black and White<br>
Charlie Chaplin and Oona O'Neill<br>
Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton<br>
Rock 'n' Roll<br>
Jackie Robinson and Rachel Isum<br>
Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald<br>
Humphrey Bogart and Lauren Bacall<br>
Peanut Butter and Jelly<br>
<P>
Which brings us back to spreads. Spread out. Enjoy. Talk back. Ask Kitty. No charge.
<P>
<b>
FYI, george jr. has nothing whatsover to do with John F. Kennedy Jr.'s magazine, which he calls George.  We're pretty sure you could tell the there is a difference, but what the hey.
</b>
<P>
