<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / features / q & a / joyce carol oates</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/august/joyce.jpg" WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=254 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 
<P>
JOYCE CAROL OATES: <BR>
Sexual Obsession & Child Abuse
<P>
Joyce Carol Oates is the author of more than 20 novels, as well as many books of poetry, criticism and essays.  Her latest, First Love: A Gothic Tale ($18), interweaving harsha realism with the macabre, has just appeared from The Ecco Press. Her previous novels include Zombie, What I Live For, and George Bellows: An American Artist and The Assignation: Stories.
<P>
First Love is illustrated by an old favorite of <b>george jr.</b>, Barry Moser. Moser has illustrated and designed nearly 200 books, including the Arion Press edition of Moby-Dick, and the University of California's version of The Divine Comedy of Dante.
<P>
His edition of Lewis Carroll's Alice's Adventures in Wonderland won a National Book Award for design and illustration in 1983.<BR clear=all>
<hr width=75%>
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> What was your inspiration for First Love?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> It began as more of a straight realistic story about a young girl who, with her divorced  mother, comes to live with distant relatives in upstate New York. Among the family is  a young man accused, though never convicted, of child molestation.. The family doesn't tell the girl or mother about the young man's past - and the girl becomes his victim.
<P>
For two or three years, I had this idea for a novella. I wanted to present it from the girl's point of view. In retrospect, I began to meditate on the bond that often develops between victim  and  abuser,  and First Love evolved.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> You describe First Love as a Gothic romance. Can you explain?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> Because it deals with  taboo  subjects:  a  child's  romantic yearning for a relationship with a young man; a victim's  enchantment with  and  devotion  to  an abuser. Such emotions are complicated - and they make people very uncomfortable. And the setting comes from the Gothic tradition: an isolated, forbidding house with family secrets.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> First Love deals with many social  themes:  child  abuse,  sexual  obsession,  psychological manipulation, broken families. . .
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>It's hard to talk about a work of literature in that way. There's a danger of becoming reductionist. A work of literature is its language, mood atmosphere. It's not just about an issue.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Your protagonist, Josie S., is an 11-year-old wise beyond her years, who, at times, seems to seek out abuse at the hands of her 25-year-old cousin, Jared Jr. What motivates her?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> I believe there's a strong element of masochism in most women. Josie is a young woman involved in, and fascinated by, her own degradation. She Is fascinated by the mystery  of  Jared, Jr., this imposing male. She's also motherless and fatherless, desperate for attention, willing to be exploited.  Look at members of cults, at followers of David Koresh.  People will endure much  degradation for attention, for love.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Why do you say Josie is "motherless"?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> Josie's mother doesn't want to "play" mother, doesn't want to be a mother. She's a strong-willed woman of her own, and very narcissistic. She's not a villain, but she's not there for Josie. First Love is about that, too.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> First Love's real villain, Jared Jr., is studying to become a Presbyterian minister. Would you call him a religious fanatic?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> He is fighting the demons of his own internal disbelief. He's inherited a burden from his grandfather. Living in "the Reverend's" house, he's trying to live up to "the Reverend's" name, "the Reverend's' calling. Jared Jr. is disturbed, weak and pathetic. But there's no excuse for child abuse.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> First Love is set in rural, upstate New York,  which is a recurring locale in at least your  best fiction. Is the inspiration for Ransomville taken from your birthplace, Lockport, N.Y.?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> Ransomville is a real place, not far from where my parents live. But the real Ransomville is nothing like the fictionalized setting of First Love.

<P>
