<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / features / q & a / franco ferrucci </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/august/franco.jpg" WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=262 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 
<P>
FRANCO FERRUCCI:<BR>
The Man Who Would Be God
<P>
The Italian writer Franco Ferrucci  most recently is the author of a novel disguised as autobiography, <I>The Life of God  (as Told By Himself)</I>, from the University of Chicago Press. His other books include <I>Saturn's Moon, Far Away from Home, The Poem of Desire: Poetics and Passion in Dante</I> and a study of Homer, <I>The Siege and the Return.</I>
<BR clear=all>
<hr width=75%>
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> <I>The Life of God </I>is  the  most  widely  translated  of  your  seven  novels  and  has just appeared in English, too. How does it fit in - or does it? - with your other books?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> <I>The Life of God</I> has been the book of my life. Everything that I have  written rotates around this book, like planets around the sun. Maybe it is not  too  much  to  say  that  one of my best novels, <I>Saturn's  Moons</I> , has such an astronomical title because it rotates around <I>The Life of God. </I><I>Saturn's Moons</I> is only about two lovers, and they are lost  in  the  space  of  love;  such  a big space demands to be filled by some divine presence.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Estrangement  - as seen there in space, the absence of things and people  -seems a recurring theme in your work.
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> One of the premises of <I>The Life of God</I>  is that God's chief destiny seems  to  be  his original solitude. Somehow, he always feels as if  he  were  an  exile  in his  own  creation. This kind of estrangement is a constant theme in my novels, and affects all sorts of characters. My novels are typically about distance  from  home,  and  of  people  meeting  by  hazard, being lost in  the  world,  finding  themselves  stranded  and  uprooted.  This  is  the  most poetical situation I can think of, and perhaps in <I>The Life of God</I> I elevated it  to  something of a philosophic statement about the loneliness of life in the universe.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Umberto Eco called  the Italian edition  "religiously enlightened  and  orthodoxically  heretical."  Do  you  think   of   yourself   as   religious?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> Before this book I thought of myself  as  an  atheist.  It  came  naturally  to  me.  When  my mother took me to Mass for the first time (I was five years old), the  only  feeling  that  I remember  was  one  of  wondering  disbelief.  That  wonder  only  increased   when   I   read religious treatises, but, at the same time, I felt that religion was a great opening into people's  minds and imaginations.
<P>
I never thought  of  myself  as  a  believer  until  I  found  myself  writing about God.
<P>
Maybe this was a divine trick  to  pull  me  into this kind of discourse. But of course I  had  to  imagine  a  God  whom  I could  accept,  a  God who could satisfy my rational needs, since I did not  need  him  for  any  kind  of  spiritual protection. So I said to myself, "How about a defective God?' That  would  at least account  for some of the imperfections of  human nature.  Not  to  mention the missed  trains,  the  incredible delays  in  delivering the mail,  and the fall of  the  Roman  Empire  besides.
<P>
If  these  proved  anything  at  all,  it was the imperfection of  God.  This  is  how  I  discovered  my  religiousness,  such  as  it  is.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> How did  your  background  as  a lit professor shape  your  "life  of God"?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> In the novel there is  a  chapter  about  how  Dante  composed  <I>The Divine Comedy</I>  and  God's  vain  attempts  to  get  Dante  to  change  his  mind  about  God.  I  knew  what  God  was  up against,  since I have been a Dante scholar .  Obviously,   my God  failed  in  his  attempt  to  educate  Dante,  but  not  even  the  popes  could  convince him to change his mind about anything.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> I don't follow  . . .
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> I have always liked the  way  the  Greeks  used  mythology.  It  is  not  even  sure  that they believed in  it,  but  they  were  enamored  with  their  own  creations.  That  may  be why,  when I was young, I  wrote  a  study  of  Homer  and later a short book on myth in literature. Legends and fables fascinate me,  and  some  of  those  great  classics of children's literature, too, had a strong influence on <I>The Life  of  God. </I> I  also  have  a  great admiration for science, the greatest  fable  of  our  time.  In  my  novel,  God  becomes  a  good   friend of Einstein and plans his own departure with Einstein's help. I have often  thought  that  happiness  was  some  sort  of  fleeting  mathematical  state,  balanced   and  inexact, like harmony in music. Once I mentioned this  to  a  friend  of mine who was a  mathematician, and he did not contradict  me.

<P
<font size=5>q.</font> <I>The  Life of God </I>has already appeared in French, German, Dutch, Danish  and Spanish.  For  the  English  translation,  you   returned   to   the   book   and   made  revisions. Is the book now truly finished?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> Being the sun of my solar system as a writer, <I>The Life of God</I> is not  a  dead  star.  So  every time that I go back to it, as happened for the English version of the book, it is like touching a living thing: it reacts, it moves, it contracts. I can feel it breathing.  Yes,  I rewrote some sections of  it,  and  I  added  new  episodes--like  the  one  about  the  invention of language, or the one in which God enters Moby Dick.
<P>
I am sure that I will return to the book again,  This  book  will  not  be  finished  until I die. Don't forget that my God is an artist, guided by  inspiration rather than calculation. My attempt to write his autobiography is as close as I'll ever come to  writing my own.
<P>
