<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / features / q & a / victoria alexander </title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/august/victoria.jpg" WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=274 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 
<P>
VICTORIA ALEXANDER:<BR>
An American Geisha in Japan
<P>
 Former stripper Victoria N. Alexander's first novel, <br>
<i><i>Smoking Hopes</i> </i>(Permanent Press, 1996), is an <br>
almost-life story based on the author's experiences <br>
as a geisha girl in Japan. 
<P>
The New Yorker is writing her second book, also a <br>
novel, called <i>Trixie, Mad Pixie. </i>

<BR clear=all>
<hr width=75%>
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> What gave you the idea to write about Japanese hostess clubs?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>   I had a girlfriend who worked in one.  She used to move around
a lot, London, New York, Tokyo, L.A..  Hostessing was a way to make a good salary easily anywhere, without any kind of commitment.  I envied her freedom.  Her clients used to pay her rent, buy her groceries, pets and jewelry, and she said she didn't have to do anything but talk to them and light their cigarettes.  Of course, I didn't believe her.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> What is expected of the hostesses?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>   Conversation and matches.  Seriously.  Hostess clubs are private social clubs.  The men bring in their clients for entertainment.  They discuss business, and flirt a little.  They drink lots of scotch.  You dance with them, slow dance, like a waltz.  They leave their business cards.  That's it.  And they give mama san anywhere from one hundred to one thousand dollars. It seemed too incredible to be true - that's why I  decided to write about it.  I was intrigued.  It seemed to me that there
would be so much room for confusion and misunderstandings in a
situation like that, especially where two such opposite types meet - Japanese business men and young "artsy" New York women, you know.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Did you work in a hostess bar yourself?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>  Yes, in New York and in Tokyo.  I, too, was given outrageous
gifts.  I had always wondered whether my girlfriend's conscience bothered her, accepting all those gifts.  Didn't she feel guilty?  Couldn't she simply refuse them?  I discovered it wasn't so easy.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Why not?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>  The men were persistent and very sweet.  They always said, "No
string attached."
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Hmm. Were there?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font> Only heartstrings, maybe, but that was what made it tough.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> That's the "real life" inspiration for the novel.  Any
literary inspirations?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>  I started writing <i><i>Smoking Hopes</i></i> right after I read Martin Amis' <i>Money: A Suicide Note. </i> My heroine, Charlie Dean, is my
answer to Amis' John Self.  They both are representations of appetite, of licentiousness, of the overwhelming desire to be loved.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Anything else?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>  Everything I was reading at the time; it's all in there.  <i>Waiting for Godot</i> is very important to the theme.  In place of Vladimir and Estragon I have two beautiful "tramps," Lola and Charlie, who wait for their ex-lover, Gottlieb, to return.  I was also thinking of something Nabokov once said.  He said there were several themes that would be absolutely taboo as far as American publishers were concerned.  One of them would be "The atheist who lives a happy and useful life and dies in his sleep at the age of 106."  I had that in the back of my mind as I started writing.  My novel reflects that general idea, but subversively.  In other words, I had to make it a tragedy of sorts.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> You posed nude for the photograph on the back cover.  Why?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>   It's a lovely photograph.  My husband, Neil Grayson, took it. 
It reminds me of Horst's best work.  I like nudes, don't you?  I've always liked them.  This photograph really seems to have caught my personality, much better than any portraits that I've had taken.  Besides the novel is about feminine sexuality.  And readers like to think that what they're reading is real, is true.  The photograph, the biographical information that I was a stripper and a hostess, lets them imagine that <i>Smoking Hopes</i> is somewhat autobiographical. 
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Which parts, if you don't mind my prying?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>  Charlie Dean is a small part of myself, exaggerated, so are Hiro and Lola, etc.  I think anyone can find him/herself in my characters.
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> What's next?
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>   My second novel is called <i>Trixie, Mad Pixie.</i>  It's about a
sweet little stripper who winds up in the tabloids.  It's a tragicomedy. 
<P>
<font size=5>q.</font> Similar, thematically, to <i>Smoking Hopes</i>.
<P>
<font size=5>a.</font>  Yes, but a different tone, more optimistic, with some of the same character types.  You see, I love girls with meretricious charms.

<P>
<HR><BR>
