<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / features / fiction / tony mendoza</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>

<H2>fiction:</H2> 
<P>

<H3>TONY MENDOZA: THIS IS NORMAL </H3>
I was standing in line to the confessional at the pigeon-stained Polish Catholic church in downtown Wallingford. I was worried. The only thought that cheered me was that the line was long.
<P>      
It was September, 1955, the year I started as a ninth grader at the Choate School, an all-boys prep school in Connecticut. I had only been there for three weeks but I already knew that I was going to hate the school. I was fourteen and obsessed with girls, but now it was starting to become clear to me that for the next four school years I would be living the life of a monk. Choate had a clearly defined philosophy of education, and central to it was the idea that the presence (or the thought) of girls
would be detrimental to the proper pursuit of studies, sports, religion and citizenship.
<P>
        The only members of the female race Choate boys were allowed to become contaminated with were the dining room maids, who wouldn't be hired unless they were over sixty, and the master's wives, who were mostly old or unattractive. There was one exception: Mrs. Patterson. She had been a model in New York before she met and married Mr. Patterson, and she still looked great. She knew it and dressed provocatively, or as provocatively as she could, in a prep school, in those days. During dinners on Saturday nights, when they served roast beef and the Master's wives tended to dress up, there was always a lot of traffic, including me, around Mrs. Patterson's table.
<P>
 So here I was, in line to the confessional, because this line represented a rare loophole in the Choate keep-the-girls-out-of-sight philosophy. Catholics were the only students allowed out of the Choate grounds, so we could attend to our pagan rituals at the Catholic Church in downtown Wallingford; Confession on Saturdays and Mass on Sundays, and downtown Wallingford was crawling with girls. Suddenly, like a miracle, all the Cuban boys at Choate were  becoming devout Catholics again.
<P>
        I had come with Emilio Eloy, my best friend. Emilio was not confessing anything. He claimed he was an atheist. He would wait for me to finish in a rear pew. After my confession we were headed for the lunch counter at Woolworth-the hang-out, we had heard, of the local teen-age girls.
<P>
        I was a terrible Catholic, but I still went to church on Sundays, maybe out of habit, or lethargy. I attended a Jesuit school for seven years and during some of those years I probably believed in the Immaculate Conception, but whatever religious convictions I once held were rapidly fading. Still, I was worried. It had been a while since my last confession, and I would have to confess a large backlist of sins. In particular, the
recent summer vacation had been sensationally sinful. But now I had to confess those sins, and others.
<P>
        Only one very old Polish lady stood in front of me. I wondered: What sins could this eighty-year-old great grandmother have committed? Her turn came; she slowly shuffled forward and painfully knelt down on the padded stool. As soon as she fell to her knees she started whispering to the priest, rapidly, anxiously, and continued for quite a while. Whatever she had done, she felt awful about it. 
<P>
        The priest inside the confessional made me nervous. I had gone to Mass the previous Sunday and his sermon had made an impression.
<P>
        "Imagine a piece of red-hot coal pressed onto the palm of your hand," he had said. "It would be painful, wouldn't it? Now imagine hundreds of red-hot coals pressed onto every square inch of your body. Now, this would be extremely painful, wouldn't it? EXTREMELY PAINFUL! Now imagine this horrible pain lasting not one second, not ten seconds, but an eternity. AN ETERNITY!"
<P>
        This priest relished the thought of this torment. He hated sinners and wanted them burned. He had a 
booming, disagreeable, European-accented voice. He was bald. He looked evil. I knew he was going to hate me, and he would want the powers above to roast me like a marshmallow.
<P>
        The old lady ended her confession. She struggled up to her feet, then taking tiny steps, started walking back to her pew. I moved over and knelt down.
<P>
        "Yes, when was the last time you had confession?" He asked this question with some disinterest.
<P>
        "Six months ago, Father."
<P>
        My last confession, in Havana, had been normal-for a 13-year-old boy. I had lied, I had said bad words, I had bad thoughts, I had read smut literature, and I had masturbated. That priest had given me a standard penance, five Our Fathers and five Hail Marys. He had not been too concerned. Cuban priests were fairly tolerant about the ways of boys.
<P>
        "Yes, and what would you like to confess, my son?"
<P>
        "Father, I said bad words, I lied, I read smut literature, I had bad thoughts, ..."
<P>
        "Is that all my son?"
<P>
        "No, Father." Lying to a priest in confession was an extremely serious sin, probably punishable by eternal damnation. So I continued: "I got drunk, I gambled, I saw dirty movies, I masturbated, I French kissed, I slept with whores."
<P>
        "What was that!"
<P>
        "What was what, Father?"
<P>
        "The last item, young man."
<P>
        "I did it with whores."
<P>
        The priest's head suddenly darted out from the curtained confessional. He  stared disgustedly at me for a few seconds. I was shocked, convinced that they weren't supposed to do that. I knew the rules. He disappeared back into the confessional.
<P>
        "My son, how old are you?"
<P>
         "I'm fourteen, Father."
<P>
         "FOURTEEN!" He yelled.
<P>
        "Yes, Father."
<P>
        "THIS IS DISGRACEFUL!" He yelled again.
<P>
         "Yes Father."
<P>
        "DON'T YOU 'YES FATHER' ME! What do you mean whores? Was there more
than one?"
<P>
         "Yes Father. Sorry Father."
<P>
        "My son, how many times did you commit this terrible sin?"
<P>
        I had to pause a while to think about that one.
<P>
        "My son, I asked you a question."
<P>
        "I'm trying to count, Father.
<P>
        "YOU'RE TRYING TO COUNT!"
<P>
        "Father, I did it six times, at the end of summer vacation."
<P>
        "My son, is this your idea of how fourteen-year-old Catholic boys 
should celebrate summer recess?"
<P>
        "No Father."
<P>
        "My son, you have some explaining to do."
<P>
        "Father, you see, I'm from Cuba and in Cuba this is normal."
<P>
        "NORMAL! THIS IS NOT NORMAL!"
<P>
        I looked around. The priest's outbursts had not gone unnoticed. The parishioners sitting nearby were all staring at me, including the old Polish lady, who had poisoned her husband.
<P>
        "Father," I said, in a very low voice, hoping he'd get the hint, "what I mean is, all my friends were doing it too. My father did it at the same age. I went to a very reputable and elegant whorehouse and my family's chauffeur took me there. It's a tradition for the boys in our culture."
<P>
        "My son, this is a pitiful confession." He said this with some disgust. I knew I was in for it.
<P>
        "This is what I want to know," he said, "and I want you to speak from your heart. Are you aware of the enormity of your sins? Are you ashamed? Are you truly repentant?"
<P>
        This time I was prepared to risk eternal damnation. I just wanted to get out of there.
<P>
        "Yes, Father."
<P>
        For the next ten minutes he described to me the detailed landscape of hell, where I was obviously headed, and where I deserved to go. The penance was a long one. I had never heard of a such a long penance: two hundred Our Fathers and two hundred Hail Mary's.
<P>
        I went back to my pew and knelt down. The penance was going to ruin the afternoon.
<P>
        I thought about the priest questions. Was I ashamed? Was I truly repentant?     Truthfully, no. The French kissing orgy with an American tourist had been sensational. I had been proud of that accomplishment-my first necking sessions. Masturbation was, well, necessary, or I wouldn't be able to fall asleep at night. My brothel experiences had been, if anything, embarrassing, and had not harmed anyone.
<P>
        The more I thought about it, the more I became convinced that it would not be honest for me to spend the rest of the afternoon reciting Hail Marys. It would not mean anything. To be pious at fourteen did not make sense. My body screamed for sex. It was not my fault, it was how God made me.
<P>
        I noticed the old lady from the line to the confessional, kneeling a few pews in front of me. Whatever she had done, she was clearly repentant. She was hard at work, reciting her Hail Marys. I watched her for a while, and I couldn't help thinking how we had nothing in common. I got up and walked out. Emilio joined me and we headed for Woolworth.
<P>
<HR><BR>
<a href="../august/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>


