<html>
<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / citizenry / the uneasy chair</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/citizenry.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotoc.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<img src="../graphics/uneasy.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>
One of the Gods of American culture always - well, until recently - has been the National Endowment for the Arts. In this month's guest soapbox, countributor Robert Fox muses on a recent book about the NEA, and some of the missing gods and goddesses from the reviewed author's pantheon:
<P>
<h3>Guest soapbox by Robert Fox</h3>
<blockquote>
"Arts" has become an even dirtier word in federal politics this election year. Newt Gingrich has warned his minions in Congress to lay off the arts as they go out on the campaign trail, not wanting the Republican Party known for killing culture. The strategy at present is to delay reauthorizing the arts endowment so that next year, without the legislation needed to obtain funding from Congress, the agency will quietly expire.
<P>
The federal role in supporting the culture has been controversial since the founding of this country, as Robert Hughes documented in "Pulling the Fuse on Culture" (<I>TIME,</I> August 7, 1995).  The issue is not economic, for the NEA's budget  before the last reduction cost each taxpayer the equivalent of two first class postage stamps; it is part of a larger re-definition of the federal role.  Yet, many question the  intentions of those who use "humanistic," "liberal," and "arts" as dirty words.
<p>
What is at stake if we fail to support the national arts infrastructure is the primary focus of the title essay of Joe David Bellamy's collection, <I>Literary Luxuries: American Writing At the End of the Millennium </I> (Missouri, 1996). Bellamy provides the reader with his retrospective on American writing over the last 30 years, during which  time he was a college professor, founder of the literary magazine <I>Fiction International,  </I>board president of the Associated Writing Programs, a national service organization, and director of the NEA literature Program during John  Frohnmayer's ill-fated tenure.  Bellamy maintains that if we don't publicly support the fragile infrastructure that supports literature, literacy and the national memory will suffer.  It is not a question of supporting elite culture, he argues, but any culture at all.  "Do we want our legacy as a nation to be <I>Terminator II </I> and <I>Wayne's World?</I>"
<P>
Elsewhere in the collection he argues eloquently for arts education.  "The arts teach empathy, and empathy is a powerful basis for moral action as well as a viable mode for understanding the world . . .  The Arts open a window to help us understand others' misery, and in this way, our hostility is blunted and we have a  chance of finding peace ourselves."  Art transcends the egotism of politics.  Education however, generally neglects the imagination, an educable faculty,  "the great underrated domain of human perception, far more natural to us, and therefore far more practical, than analytical and other abstract modes of  perception" which have dominated the curriculum.
<P>	
The collection as a whole is spotty and does not live up to its subtitle's promise.  It is not a retrospective, but rather essays collected over a period of years. While some have their charms, especially the author's experience at Bread Loaf,  and his good fortune in having Reynolds Price for freshman English at Duke  University, other pieces are dated, especially the equivocal look at postmodernist  writing  in the mid-1970s, in which he attempts to find a middle ground between postmodernism and John Gardner's "moral fiction."  In attempting to assess the important American writers in the latter part of the 20th century (millennium  indeed!) Bellamy omits two of the most significant novelists to emerge in the 1970s:  Charles Johnson (a protege of Gardner's) and Toni Morrison!  The book is filled out with short reviews originally written for the <I>New York Times </I> and <I>Chicago Tribune,</I>  dated and out of context now.
<P>
In the essay "Five Sex Acts and Wild Thing:  John Frohnmayer's Last Days  at the NEA, and Mine," the author, in his role as bumbling literary Everyman at the end of the millennium, claims credit for Frohnmayer's demise as NEA chair, unwittingly joining the ranks of Pat Buchanon, Dick Armey, and Donald Wildmon,  who clamored for the political bounty.  Frohnmayer's own recounting of the episode,  concerning a poem from an NEA supported magazine (in his book<I> Leaving Town  Alive)</I> spares Bellamy the ignominy, in fact, neglects to mention his role at all.  Both versions are consistent though in illustrating the tactics of political extremists.  Congressman Armey had been after the literature program for years (<a href="uneasy.html#sidebar">see sidebar</a>).  However, it was Wildmon, executive director of the American Family Association,  who excerpted <I>Wild Thing</I>, a persona poem told from the point of view of a  teenage assailant in the Central Park jogger attack.  Frohnmayer vilified the  tactic, defended the poem as part of a venerable literary tradition despite its frightening message and at times offensive language, and was sent packing by the White House.
<P>
Bellamy quotes Frohnmayer's parting words, "I leave with the belief that this eclipse of the soul will soon pass and with it the lunacy that sees artists as  enemies and ideas as demons."  Several years later the lunacy has not yet passed. We don't know to what extremes the egos of political leaders will be driven next.  We need the empathic power and humility of the arts now more than ever, and  we need the federally supported infrastructure that has nurtured the arts well for the last 30 years.
<P>
Despite its flaws, the book has value for its impassioned yet well-reasoned defense of public support for the arts, from a writer who has served and observed  well over the last three decades.
<P></blockquote>
<hr>
Robert Fox, the literature program coordinator for the Ohio Arts Council, served on the National Endowment for the Arts literature panel from 1983 to 1986.

<hr>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name="sidebar">
<h3>How NEA Fellowships to Creative Writers Were Re-instated</h3>

During the summer of 1995, the 104th Congress slashed the NEA budget by more than one-third to a punitive $99.5 million but at the same time re-instated   fellowships to creative writers, the only remaining program through which   individuals can be funded competitively.  Ironically, many of the Congressional attacks on the NEA since its birth, in addition to the one that hastened  Frohnmayer's departure, have been directed at the literature program.  Some of them are as follows:
<blockquote>
- ca. 1970: literature program director Leonard Randolph defends and explains  Aram Saroyan's one-word poem<I> Light</I>, "lighght," on the floor of Congress
- ca. 1980: several members of Congress demand that Erica Jong return her NEA fellowship money since the supported manuscript became her best-selling novel,  <I>Fear of Flying</I>
- mid-1980s:  aides to Congressmen Dick Armey and Tom DeLay search the  poetry fellowship files for dirty poetry. According to then literature program director  Frank Conroy, aides were heard to complain, "Hey, this ain't poetry, it don't rhyme."
</blockquote>
LitNet, the lobbying arm of the Council of Literary Magazines and Presses,  claims credit for the re-instatement of the writers' fellowships, bringing well-known authors and other entertainment professionals to lobby Congress.  Allegedly,  Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich backed off his insistence against federal   bureaucrats making artistic decisions  when former NEA advisory  panelists E.L. Doctorow and Margaret Atwood told him bluntly that no federal bureaucrat could tell them what to think.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
Got a beef, a kvetch, a gripe? george jr says go, now, and be a citizen with these tools/addresses.
<blockquote><blockquote>
President Clinton<br>
202-456-2461<br>
email: president@whitehouse.gov
<P>
Vice President Gore<br>
202-456-2326<br>
email: vice-president@whitehouse.gov
<P>
The Congressional Switchboard<br>
202-224-3121<br>
<P>
House Speaker Gingrich<br>
202-225-0600<br>
email: georgia6@hr.house.gov
<P></blockquote></blockquote>
And while we're at it, save these numbers for issues that interest you:
<blockquote>
<ul>
        <li>      Human Rights Watch: 212-972-8400
             <li>Center for Democratic Renewal: 404-221-0225
             <li> Family Violence and Prevention Fund: 415-252-8900
             <li> People for the American Way: 202-467-4999
              <li>Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting: 212-633-6700
             <li> League of Women Voters: 202-429-0854
              <li>Congressional Switchboard: 202-224-3121
              <li>Council for Economic Priorities: 212-420-1133
              <li>Artists for a Hate-Free America: 503-335-5982
              <li>Equal Rights Advocates: 415-621-0672
              <li>Political Research Associates: 617-661-9313
              <li>Americans Friends Service Committee: 215-241-7000
              <li>Grassroots International: 617-628-1664
              <li>Center on Budget and Policy Priorities: 202-628-8787
              <li>Hand Gun Control Inc: 202-898-0792 
</ul></blockquote>
