<H2>history lesson</H2>
<h3>JOE NAPORA: <br>WITH CHURCHES BURNING, TIME IS RIGHT FOR  JOHN SANFORD</h3>

<P>
On the back cover of John Sanford's novel <i>The People From Heaven</i>(Illinois) appear these  bouquets: "His language is marvelous" from William Carlos Williams; "A sacred book" from Carl Sandburg; "your great talent" from Orson Welles. <i>The People From Heaven</i>was first published in 1942, and these comments failed to alert the public to the importance of the novelist or the novel. The book went soon out of print. But the author never stopped writing. He is writing still at age 91. And last year's re-publication might finally make it happen that readers of the American novel will come to share the opinions of Williams, Sandburg, and Welles, for this novel is as important now, or arguably even more important, than it was 50 years ago, if only because the theme is more timely and the technique more readily understandable.
<P>
Sanford is a radical, a technical improvisor who takes fiction writing to
its roots in story that is as varied in its form as in its content. Sanford
accepts no prior formal strictures, whether they be the disguised
reactionary aesthetic formal appeals to a Beauty outside of history or
whether they be the dictates of the Party: Sanford was a communist when he wrote this novel, and the Bosses were not happy. But the novel's theme can be understood and appreciated now, after the societal revolt of the 1960s and the formal revolution in writing that has moved fiction out of naive realism and into a continual self-questioning of the relationship of fiction to fact.
<P>
Alan Wald, who provides the introduction to this paperback reprint, summarizes the novel this way: "<i>The People From Heaven</i>is a 1943 novel by an unrepentant Jewish-American Marxist about anti-Black and anti-Native American racist culture in the North of the United States." It is this, but in this time of the Militias, the burnings of Black churches, the legacy of Wounded Knee, the persecution of the American Indian Movement, the assassinations of Black Panther leaders and the FBI's campaign to destroy Martin Luther King, it is also a 1990s novel. And yet the novel was ignored, but why? 
<P>
The critics are mainly to blame for their inability to understand and
explain what Wald describes as "a tour of sensory and intellectual
experience unlike those produced by any other text in U.S. literature." The
critics failed the public, and hence the public was denied the opportunity
to be aware that this novel deserved the praise of those artists, Williams,
Sandburg, Welles, who recognized genius when they saw it. Critics are a
timid bunch, no matter how strident their prose or their pose. I suspect
they were scared of Sanford's theme and style, and they deserved to be. But we should expect criticism to rise above self-imposed intimidation. The book has power, power that scared the critics as much as it scared the communist censors. As Wald relates, when a Party critic called the novel"anti-social," Sanford replied, "Art is a weapon," and "If that book isn't aweapon, I never saw one." In the forties, too many readers never saw this one. With this re-publication, there is now the chance for readers to judge for themselves. Take it, and discover a major talent with a body of work still forming that will soon redefine the history of American fiction.

<P>
