<br>
<H2>remembranza</H2>
<H3> Richard Kostelanetz's Brown University Memoir </H3>

<a href="/august/rememb.html#book">Click here</a> for an excerpt from Richard Kostelanetz's book <i>Autobiographies at Fifty</i>, which tells of some of his work and efforts on behalf of John Cage, Merce Cunningham and other musicians, artists and writers.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
It was nearly 35 years ago that I graduated from one of the lesser Ivy League colleges that, we should not forget, had a quota upon admitting people like me (Jews) when I entered. I went to Brown in 1958 because a fellow three years ahead of me in high school (and now a distinguished playwright) said, simply, that if my application were not accepted at Harvard, it was as good "a second choice" as any.  One favor he did for me, after I was accepted, was taking the catalog of offered courses  and underlining certain names twice and other names once.  Thanks to his considered advice, I soon established strong relationships with some of the better professors who at Brown, unlike some other places, were available to undergraduates.
<P>
   Although my upper-class suburban high school billed itself as "one of the best public schools in the country," it hardly equipped us for a rigorous regime of research papers and exams.  At the time I noticed that the few  eighteen-year-olds who were adequately prepared, who knew how to write 30-page papers and take written exams, had gone to one of only six institutions--Andover, Exeter, Bronx Science, Stuyvesant, Hunter, and Boston Latin--which were at the time the only high schools where students were really pushed.  The parents back in my suburbia wouldn't have allowed the teachers' giving us too much work, especially at a time, in the 1950s, when "conformity" and the organization-man mentality were commonly thought ideal.  (Curiously, my father had gone to a New York City high school comparable to the select six, in the 1920s, when, as he recalls, the teachers wouldn't have been intimidated by the parents because most of them "didn't speak well enough English.")  By the end of freshman year, some of us disadvantaged high school graduates caught up.
<P>
   Since Brown lacked financial resources commensurate with its ambitions, it was forever concocting "experimental programs" that would appeal to various funding agencies.  (I hear this is still true.)  In order to justify any successful funding, it had to persuade the better teachers and the best students to participate in the new program.  Around the time I matriculated it had received a grant to replace introductory survey lecture courses with "IC" seminars devoted to the intensive study of purportedly classic texts.  Not unlike other more ambitious (and perhaps brighter) students, I was conned into taking several of these seminars, some of them taught by professors with two lines under their names. While I largely enjoyed these courses and their teachers, I also realized, especially when I got to graduate school and compared experiences with those who had gone to Harvard or Columbia, that I had learned not about the great tradition of sociology, say, but about Emile Durkheim's <i>Suicide, </i>Robert Redfield's <i>The Primitive World and Its Transformations,</i> Harrison Brown's <i>The Challenge of Man's Future, </i>David Riesman's <i>The Lonely Crowd,</i> and C. Wright Mills's <i>White Collar. </i> Instead of surveys of modern poetry and fiction, I had a single semester devoted to the complete works of T. S. Eliot and then another semester devoted exclusively to William Faulkner.  Since Brown was as    comparatively expensive then as it is now, I wondered if my parents weren't gypped.  Needless to say, when the grant expired, after I graduated, these courses disappeared from Brown's curriculum, no doubt to be replaced by alternatives funded in other ways.
<P>
   Once I got to Brown, I discovered that most of the brighter students, beginning with those individuals who became my closest friends, had likewise been rejected by Harvard or, in a few cases, Yale or Princeton.  This created among us an aura of inferiority, if not self-hate, that while it seems ridiculous in any ultimate scheme of value certainly had an impact then.  (And perhaps later, as we shall see.)
<P>
   Whereas Harvard and Columbia and, to a lesser extent, Yale were in cities that offered corrective reality, Brown resided atop a steep hill that opened to a suburb so distant from the city, not only physically but psychologically, that undergraduates never went "downtown" except to take public transportation home. We began to realize that much that was peculiar about the university depended upon the isolation, not only from the city but from any larger cultural world.  It seems incredible to me now that the University Christian Association, as I think it was called, dominated extracurricular life. Whenever a particularly puzzling film arrived at the local moviehouse (such as the Ingmar Bergman films popular then), the UCA would be the first to sponsor a symposium to discuss its meanings.  When Fulton Lewis, Jr. (or maybe the Third) came to show the film Operation Abolition (about 1960 protests against the House Un-American Activities Committee), it was the campus Protestant minister who debated him.  Not that I objected then (or object now) to Christianity, even at a time of Jewish    quotas, but at no other Ivy League university at that time, to my knowledge (not even as comparably isolated and insular) Princeton), did avowedly Christian organizations have such presence.
<P>
   Some of the more disingenuous professors likewise depended upon the isolation.  I remember one who taught a course open to only selected upperclassmen that pretended to teach the truth, in contrast to those courses that had a disciplinary subject. What he was actually doing was preaching a cultural conservatism based upon the "humanistic need for unity" in a    purportedly nihilistic world.  In order to keep his illusion of truth-teaching alive, he had to choose students who lacked enough outside contacts or outside knowledge to contradict, let alone define, his ideology.  Although he spoke of wanting to take his program elsewhere, you knew it wouldn't survive in a university with a stronger reality-corrective.  Another professor billed himself as a major emerging poet, but you had only to learn enough about contemporary poetry in general, or speak to contemporaries studying poetry elsewhere, to discover how inconsequential he was (and still is).
<P>
   Not unlike other lesser Ivy League schools, Brown had a reputation for "play," which at that time meant drinking.  Especially on weekends, guys and sometimes women from our sister school drank to get drunk, especially in the fraternity houses. Just as disagreeable as the drunks who hung around the fraternities was the open truck full of stinky bottles and cans that was invariably parked just outside the campus lunchroom every Monday.  So revolting was this bacchanalia that not until I left college was I able to consume beer amicably.
<P>
   Campus life was so disagreeable that I knew by my sophomore year that I would go elsewhere unless I could live off-campus for the rest of my time there.  Fortunately, the dean acceded to my wish.  By my junior year I had entered the honors program, as it was called, whose seminars met in the afternoons.  That meant that for the remainder of my undergraduate career I scarcely saw students whose classes were in the mornings.  (When I recently saw a class reunion booklet, I noticed that few names were familiar to me, compared, say, to high school classmates, no doubt because most of the strangers were "morning people.")
<P>
   I entered Brown wanting to be a writer and so during my freshman year took a creative writing course in which an academic novelist, now better known than before, told me I had no talent for prose, which was probably true in the narrow sense of having no talent for the kind of prose he and his favored students wrote.  Although I contributed short pieces to both the undergraduate newspaper and literary magazine, I decided to avoid the college's writing program as well as its English department, which both I and my wife-to-be (presently a Professor of English at a state university) thought inferior. Whereas she majored in philosophy, I went into American Studies.  (When I receive class reunion catalogues, I notice that most of the classmates whom I remember as majoring in creative writing are now high school teachers which, if you think about it skeptically, is what that program best prepared them to be.)
<P>
   In my sophomore year I had a friend a year ahead of me, who had gone to Exeter, whose literacy and taste seemed superior to mine, who persisted in pursuing a writing major, even though he knew the limitations of those running the program.  Buried in the catalogue was a course in "verse writing" taught by an "emeritus" professor whose name, S. Foster Damon, was unfamiliar to me, even though there was a single line under his name in my hand-annotated course catalogue.  My friend took "verse writing" initially to get away from the other writing professors.  Coming to lunch after his first class, my friend told me of "an old guy [then in his middle 60s and so a decade older than I am now] who had gone to college with E. E. Cummings and Dos Passos" and was authentically literary.  I signed up for Damon's course, even though I had no intention at the time of writing poetry; and though I didn't do particularly well at the exercises of imitating verse forms from Beowulf to the present, I got to know a literary professional who, unlike the emerging stars, was generous and sympathetic toward a beginner. Damon regularly invited me to his house for dinner; before long, I brought friends both male and female.  In conversation and by his example, he taught me how to be a professional, how to do distinctive work, rather than how to write--the two are not the same.  In retrospect, I think it was through knowing Damon that I began to publish prose in national magazines immediately upon graduating from college.  Within a few years, my first book of poems appeared, fittingly dedicated to him.
<P>
   Comparing my university to others of its class and size, I would say remarkably few of my college contemporaries (graduating between 1958 and 1965) became professional artists: one writer of children's books, three playwrights (including my high school friend), two poets other than myself (neither of whom graduated), two sculptors who were more visible twenty years ago than now, two painters who continue to exhibit in spite of scant recognition, two composers one of whom was more visible twenty years ago (the other more visible now), one filmmaker and one video artist both of whom have become university professors who have not shown new work in years.  One thing we share, I've noticed, is majoring in fields other than art.  (My theory here is that Ivy League art departments are not as strong as those in the mainstream subjects upon whose superiority the university's reputation depends.  That is why many Ivy League art majors became high school teachers.)
<P>
   One reason for this comparative scarcity is that Brown alumni in the arts rarely support one another.  Of the hundreds of editors, publishers, lecture-sponsors, gallery directors, etc., who have underwritten my work over the past three decades (without whom I couldn't have survived professionally), only four are Brown alumni; and of those four, only two were connected to institutions that paid me money, each once (one as an editor at a slick magazine, the other as an executive of a summertime arts fair).  My hypothesis is that the inferiority complex described at the beginning of this memoir makes us think that since Brown was a university full of Harvard and Princeton rejects none of us can ever be any good.  (I'll admit that I've felt similarly toward other Brown artist-alumni before I saw their work.)  On the other hand, I can think of a dozen alumni, some of them older than I, others younger, who could have supported my activities.
<P>
   The trouble, in short, is that Brown doesn't have much respect for Brown. It doesn't recognize its most distinguished arts alumni.  If a literate Princeton boy can recall that F. Scott Fitzgerald and Edmund Wilson attended their school, few Brown boys can recall that Nathanael West and S. J. Perlman went to their school.  Few Brown boys can name the filmmakers.  (Try starting with Richard Fleischer.)  Whereas Harvard paid a handsome sum to acquire the literary papers of the poet Robert Lowell, who attended but did not graduate, the Brown University Library's Harris Collection lacks comparable archives of its more distinguished literary graduates.  And it can't recognize the best alumni, because it isn't in the same league as Harvard or Yale, disingenuous advertising to the contrary notwithstanding. Look in the back cross-index of the current Brown University Alumni Directory 1994 and you'll notice that "writer," "author," "composer," and "musician" are not categories for Brown alumni, though "visual arts," and "telecommunications," as well as, of course, "financial planning" and "homemaker," are. It is apparently impossible for Brown and its designated directory-publisher to conceive of an alumnus doing what I do.  Aren't these the marks of the self-consciously second-rate?
<P>
   If my father believed that sending me to a lesser Ivy League school would economically benefit my professional career, we would agree that he was ripped off.  It is scarcely surprising, given what I've said so far, that even though I'm one of only two Brown alumni with an individual entry in a standard encyclopedia of living poets and the only actively publishing alumnus with an individual entry in a standard encyclopedia of living fiction writers, Brown has invited me back only twice, more than 20 years apart, each time to give a single lecture to a class.
<P>
   While an unformed high school student became a professional writer after four years there, thanks no doubt to the courses he took and the teachers he    had, few others did.  Many aspired, and a few began, only to disappear professionally; and perhaps my recollections about the peculiar place account less for my survival than for the failure of others.
<P>
<a name="book">
<B>From Richard Kostelanetz's book <I>Autobiographies at Fifty</I></B>

<P>
    Successes in real estate often come as a surprise to  the buyer.
                   --John Train, The New Money Masters (1989)
<HR>


<I>AND SO FORTH</I> (1979).  A hundred-plus pages, each with a different 8" square geometric drawing, come loose in an envelope; my assumption was that any ordering of this modular piece would generate an abstract narrative in the tradition of my earlier Constructivist Fictions. Someday I'd like to do an exhibition in which the sheets would be laid in one continuous row along, say, seventy feet of walls, their order changing daily.
<P>

<I>METAMORPHOSIS IN THE ARTS</I> (1980).  A dozen years before, an art-book packager, who had a contact from a commercial publisher, commissioned me to write a text about avant-garde developments in all the arts in the sixties.  While he gathered illustrations for a sumptuous volume, I produced comprehensive essays about recent painting, sculpture, dance, music and film, as well as surveys of the new intermedial arts: environments, mixed-means events, machine art, artistic machines, word-imagery and inferential art. Though I delivered within a year a finished manuscript that was immediately typeset and corrected proofs in the early 1970s, reasonably expecting that the book would appear soon afterwards, the commercial publisher went through changes, while the packager went off to Europe for a while.  Since everyone involved claimed that the book was still in their production schedule, the typeset wasn't given to me until 1980, when Assembling Press fortunately had sufficient funds to issue it without illustrations.  Some years later, the packager asked to represent the text again, expecting to capitalize upon nostalgia for the 1960s, again without success.  As I introduced my edition as "a book that should never happen to any     writer," you can understand how merely remembering it, not to mention writing about it, even so many years later, makes me feel uncomfortable in the stomach.
<P>

<I>SCENARIOS</I> (1980).  This was meant to be the furthest-out collection of theatrical scripts ever gathered between covers.  It also turned out to have     704 pages, from over a hundred contributors; and since I had to design the book and paste it up as well, I vowed never again to do such a generous anthology     without sufficient support for a staff.  And there were no more.
<P>

<I>THE YALE GERTRUDE STEIN </I>(1980).  From the eight volumes of previously uncollected Stein texts that Yale University Press published posthumously between 1951 and 1958, I made a selection that emphasized her greatest departures and then backed my selections with an extended introduction. This began with a postcard proposal; and since the Press agreed without asking for any examples, I've always used that precedent to reply to any publisher soliciting more than a single-page proposal for a book.  ("If Yale can do it, why can't you.")  As my selections favored the more difficult Stein texts, including <I>Stanzas in Meditation </I>in its entirety, I defended the more experimental Stein against those who favor her Three Lives and Autobiography of Alice B. Toklas.  I wanted to call this book <I>Gertrude Stein at Yale,</I> alluding to the Frank Merriwell books popular with boys in the 1920s; but the     joke blew past my editor.  In the years since I've wanted to do a sequel, selecting from public-domain texts for an anthology to be called "The GreatAmerican Person of Avant-Garde Letters," but it hasn't had any takers.
<P>

<I>MORE SHORT FICTIONS</I> (1980).  This collection of my extremely radical fictions, both verbal and visual, remains, I would like to think, the most challenging     one-person story book ever published in America, for each work is not only drastically different from current conventions, but most of them beg to be  reclassified as "not fiction," which is to say something unknown.
<P>

<I>REINCARNATIONS</I> (1981).  This is the first of several books entirely of photographs, in this case of sixty-four recompositions of a favorite photograph of my face, cut apart into eighty squares, suggesting either that my character has been destroyed or that it has been reborn with other images.  Other books of my photographs, beginning with one systematically reworking the image of the Brooklyn Bridge, including another about the great Jewish cemetery of Berlin, remain unpublished, alas.
<P>

<I>AURAL LITERATURE CRITICISM</I> (1981).  A legitimate successor to the earlier anthology about visual literature, this contains extended critical essays about literature that coheres or is enhanced primarily in terms of sounds, rather than syntax or semantics.  No less pioneering than its predecessor, this remains the last book on the subject; for though criticism about visual poetry continues to appear, text-sound is rarely discussed.
<P>

<I>AMERICAN WRITING TODAY </I>(1981).  Voice of America made me an offer I should have refused--to organize fifty broadcasts about contemporary American literature and then edit two books drawn from them.  While I was slow to understand that     the USIA needed me to get the participation of literary colleagues who, if approached directly, would have turned down the USIA, the invitation seemed an     opportunity to do something comprehensive, and yet definitive; besides, if I did not accept the assignment, it would have gone to a bona fide idiot.  In the age of politicized panels, it was a pleasure to choose by myself the writers to be covered, along with the experts to talk and write about them; yet the project became more trouble than it was worth--financially, intellectually, morally.  What began as two volumes only for distribution abroad was reissued for domestic consumption as a single volume a decade later.
<P>

<I>THE AVANT-GARDE TRADITION IN LITERATURE </I>(1982).  This sequel to Esthetics Contemporary, likewise done for Prometheus, collects my favorite extended critical essays on the most extreme works and developments in modern literature. It was meant to compete with "modernism" anthologies discussing far more conservative work.  However, the book met a conspiracy of silence, because within three years the hardback copies were sold off to Archae (a.k.a. RK)  Editions, which still has plenty.
<P>

<I>ARENAS/FIELDS/PITCHES/TURFS </I>(1982).  This is the sequel to a chapbook published two years before, with the title's four words scrambled into a different order, with a great selection from the "geometric" poems, as I call them, in which four separate words, poetically related in some way, are distributed to the  four corners of the page. In two later sequences, four additional words appear in the center with their ends pointing in different directions, and then sixteen words become four squares, with me once again exploring possible poetic relationships within a severe constraint.
<P>

<I>THE LITERATURE OF SOHO </I>(1982).  Done before <I>Scenarios</I> depleted my anthological spirit, this was meant to show how the radical developments in  visual art associated with my neighborhood had their analogues in literature--visual poetry, sound poetry, structural experiments, minimalism, patterning,  intermedia, etc.; but the visual art community scarcely reads, while professional readers are too suspicious of visual art esthetics.
<P>

<I>AMERICAN IMAGINATIONS </I>(1983).  Merveverlag in West Berlin asked for a book of mine; we hit upon a collection of profiles and interviews as the best way of introducing my criticism to sophisticated readers in Berlin and Western Europe. What surprises me is how many European colleagues have actually read this book; American small publishers are rarely so effective at distribution.
<P>

<I>EPIPHANIES </I>(1983).  Walter Hollerer, then still directing Literarisches Colloquium Berlin, said he wanted to do a book of German translations of my  single-sentence stories outside his uniform series; and while this truly pocket-sized volume has only a few of the thousands of stories, the use of various typographies, with plenty of space between examples, gives a vivid idea of what can be done, not only in German but, eventually, in English and other languages.
<P>

<I>RECYCLINGS</I> (1984).  This is the entire manuscript, all 320 pages, of a book whose opening parts were published a decade before.  If anyone thought that this sustained experiment with nonsyntactic prose might have become any more acceptable in the interim, forget it.
<P>

<I>AUTOBIOGRAPHIES: NEW YORK-BERLIN </I>(1986).  Since Richard Kostelanetz himself was too lazy even to gather choice chapters from his <I>Autobiographies</I> (1981), let alone add new essays about living in Berlin in the early 1980s, Merve's Peter Gente personally spoke to Richard's twelve laboring elves, seducing them with promises of literary grandeur in Berlin and free flights to Europe on Merveverlag's outer-spatial express.  Once the translator Almut Carstens flashed her winning smile, they all went to work and, with characteristic dispatch, produced a German book.
<P>

<I>THE OLD FICTIONS AND THE NEW</I> (1987).  A companion to <I>The Old Poetries and the New </I>(1981), this reprints twenty-five years' worth of fiction criticism, collectively separating genuine avant-garde work and its traditions from pretenders that have received more attention. The book also collects a sequence of introductions to my own experimental fiction.
<P>

<I>PROSE PIECES/AFTERTEXTS</I> (1987).  Of these two books bound back to back, one collects various radical experiments with language done over the past decade, including single-sentence stories that are hundreds of words long; the other collects <I>Aftertexts</I>, which are single-page extractions of characteristic vocabularies from classic literature. Though this may well be the most unreadable book I've ever done, it is not, by any means, the least significant. Perhaps because no one has done a book like this before or since, it received only one review (from Noel Peattie, in his <I>Siappu</I>).
<P>

<I>THE GRANTS-FIX </I>(1987) is an unfortunate book.  A comprehensive expos of the failures of publicly funded literary granting, written well before the recent notoriety of the NEA and the NEH, this was commissioned by a publisher that went under.  The manuscript languished while I was working in Europe in the early 1980s.  Since most of the chapters had appeared in literary magazines, I self-published a photocopied edition, to be sold at a high price.  As my analyses go well beyond (or deeper than) current comprehension, the recent controversies always strike me as hopelessly ignorant.
<P>

<I>CONVERSING WITH CAGE </I>(1988).  Recognizing John Cage's effectiveness as an conversationalist, I composed initially for a German publisher and, once expanded, for publication here an ur-interview selecting choice passages from Cage's previous interviews. Though the book was produced with his cooperation, down to final proofreading, it is clearly my composition, acknowledging Cagean esthetics in making my own art entirely from someone else's material. Ignorant academics, including some quite prominent, often identify this book as "edited" by me.  There is no authority for that on either the book's cover or its title page; and if only these credential scholars had read as far as page xi (not "11"), they would understand why, as Cage speaks "of three ways of  composing nowadays. . . .  And a third way has developed in recording studios, which is similar to the way artists work in their studios to make paintings. Music can be build up layer by layer on recording tape, not to give a performance or to write music, but to appear on a record."  That is precisely what I did in the book (and have done in my audiotape compositions).  As the text reflects from my own tastes for challenging ideas and for humor, while minimizing chance esthetics, I'll even acknowledge that someone else could, and perhaps should, compose another ur-interview with Cage from the same sources.
<P>

O<I>N INNOVATIVE MUSIC(IAN)S </I>(1989).  This collects my most reprintable writings on music, including a broader range of subjects than is customarily found in such collections--serial music as well as aleatory, blues as well as pop--because its theme is avant-garde contemporary taste, broadly considered.
<P>

<I>UNFINISHED BUSINESS: AN INTELLECTUAL NONHISTORY</I> (1990).  This truly radical endeavor reflects the idea, so important to both conceptual art/architecture and psychoanalysis, that the wish may be as important as its realization. Between a single set of covers, I collected all my unfunded proposals, both to commercial publishers and to foundations, dating back to the beginning of my career, suggesting that they be considered intrinsic in my cultural achievement.  Though no one known to me has pursued this suggestion, I've not given up hope--not at all.
<P>

<I>ON INNOVATIVE ART(IST)S </I>(1991).  This collects my most reprintable writings on visual art, concentrating not upon painting and sculpture, as most other art     critics do, but upon such fringe activities as book-art, kinetic art, light art, and polyartistry, which is my coinage for individuals who excel at more than one non-adjacent art.  Indicatively, the individual mentioned most in the index is Moholy-Nagy.
<P>

<I>THE NEW POETRIES AND SOME OLD </I>(1991).  A sequel to The Old Poetries and the New (1981), this collects essays written mostly in the 1980s, demoting Joseph Brodsky for one while elevating radical alternatives.
<P>

<I>POLITICS IN THE AFRICAN-AMERICAN NOVEL </I>(1991) is my M.A. thesis, written twenty-five years before, whose parts appeared in scholarly journals at that time.  Though I tried hard to rewrite it, reading over fifty new books and reconsidering the original texts, I changed remarkably little, not because I was so bright then--I wasn't--but because I set up a scholarly machine that generated efficiently organized answers to the questions I was asking.
<P>

<I>GERTRUDE STEIN ADVANCED </I>(1991).  This anthology of criticism attempts to extend the position established in my earlier Stein editing--that the more     experimental, more difficult texts are the only ones worth considering; and this reprints some of the more insightful essays about them.  Needless to say, I planned a book of this kind many years before and, if only because I wanted to do it for so long, received no advance.
<P>

<I>CONSTRUCTS THREE</I> (1991), <I>INTERMIX </I>(1991), <I>CONSTRUCTS FOUR</I> (1991), <I>FLIPPING</I> (1991), <I>CONSTRUCTS FIVE </I>(1991), F<I>IFTY UNTITLED CONSTRUCTIVIST STORIES</I> (1991), <I>CONSTRUCTS SIX </I>(1991) are all limited photocopied editions of systemically developed abstract narratives done nearly two decades before.
<P>

<I>REFERENCES</I> (1991).  As another example of my commitment to revealing process in cultural decision-making, I published, with individual identities disguised, letters I've written on behalf of colleagues, mostly supporting their applications for major fellowships.  One sub-text here is strategies in confronting resistances to avant-garde culture in this persistently retrograde culture.
<P>

<I>PUBLISHED ENCOMIA,</I> 1967-91 (1991).  Not unlike other noncommercial writers I suffer from the angst of feeling that I'm dropping pennies into a well. Even though my work is commonly considered under-appreciated (certainly by publishers to whom I make vain appeals), I was surprised to find enough encomia to fill a forty-page, 8 1/2" x 11", single-spaced typescript that I published in a small photocopied, velobound edition.  Even though none of these books have been sold, it is a volume that I'm pleased, very pleased, to have on my shelf.
<P>

<I>SOLOS, DUETS, TRIOS, & CHORUSES</I> (1991) collects my efforts to write poems with only one word ("Partitions"), two words, and three words, relating within themselves and to each other in various ways.  The "Choruses" are nonsyntactic collections of words set in concentric circles.  No one else, to my knowledge, uses any of these forms.
<P>

<I>MERCE CUNNINGHAM </I>(1992) is an anthology collecting the best critical essays ever written about America's premiere choreographer.  This edition is considerably shorter than that initially prepared for another publisher; and should it do well, it would be good to get the excised essays, including one of mine, into a sequel anthology. The strongest essays come from David Vaughan.
<P>

<I>JOHN CAGE, WRITER</I> (1993) is a selection of his previously uncollected writings, including poems as well as essays.  The principal achievement of the book, in my opinion, is gathering into a single place Cage's prefaces to his own works, for no other composer ever wrote so well about his own art.
<P>

<I>WORDWORKS: POEMS SELECTED AND NEW </I>(1993) is a selection of poems composed over the previous quarter-century, reprinting them in over a dozen sections, each with its own preface, including visual poems, permutational poems, minimal poems, extended strings composed of overlapping words, scores for sound poems, photographs of video poems and holograms that contain only words, among other kinds of alternatives, all in an effort to be "the most inventive poet ever in America.  I'm not done yet."
<P>

<I>TWENTY-FIVE YEARS AFTER</I> (1993) is based upon notecards made at the time about rock concerts in the late 1960s, mostly at the Fillmore East.  My theme is     that, especially at the Fillmore, they were an excellent theater.
<P>

<I>A DICTIONARY OF THE AVANT-GARDES </I>(1993).  This is the first book done in decades upon a publisher's invitation, rather than my own initiative.  At first I refused, thinking it would be an impossible task for a modest advance; but then I discovered how to do it--essentially from memory. For four months early in 1992, I simply sat down at my wordprocessor and wrote entries in a disconnected order, one subject reminding me of another, occasionally checking arts encyclopedias and my own previous writings.  Before long, I had more than enough entries to make a book-length manuscript that then had to be cleaned up, beginning with the elimination of entries that were insufficient or incomplete. It was amazing to discover how many people, including friends of mine, I could  not write about satisfactorily from memory; but since there wasn't enough support to hire research assistants (or deal with people reluctant to release information), I had to plug on.  The principal difference between this and other professional dictionaries is that my book is opinionated (but how else could the avant-garde be written about?).  My principal stylistic problem was avoiding repetition; so that more than once an entry survived because of difference in style.  Should the book succeed, I might be invited to revise and  update it, much as the music lexicographer Nicolas Slonimsky (its dedicatee) was invited to revise his Baker's <I>Biographical Dictionary of Musicians</I> four  times over forty years.  (May I live so long.)
<P>

<I>WRITINGS ABOUT JOHN CAGE </I>(1993) is an anthology collecting the best critical essays ever written about America's premiere avant-garde composer. It differs from Merce Cunningham in using only essays that have never before appeared in books.  My sense is that its star is the French scholar Daniel Charles, who has written intelligently on many dimensions of Cage's music; my own contributions are probably the best on Cage's other cultural achievements.
<P>

<I>ON INNOVATIVE PERFORMANCES </I>(1994) draws upon notecards made at the time recording critical impressions of non-literary performances that, though they were seen by only a few people at the time, are still remembered by many. Between them are my extended essays on alternative performance, beginning with an abridgment of my appreciation of "The Theatre of Mixed Means" and including both my suggestions that the great tradition of American theater emphasizes performance over dramatic literature and my Smithsonian profile of the kinetic sculptor George Rhoads, who makes a kind of mechanical theater. It is unfortunate that few consider me a theater critic, because, by my count, this is at least my sixth book mostly about performance.
<P>

<I>NICOLAS SLONIMSKY: THE FIRST 100 YEARS </I>(1994) is a selection from the writings of America's best writers on classical music, done for his 100th birthday.  It is always a pleasure to read, organize, and represent first-rank prose.
<P>
<hr>
