<title>george jr. / august 1996 / departments / national public rodeo (week 1)</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="../august/departments.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<H3>Fun & Games To Frighten You</H3>
Universal  Pictures launched an innovative World Wide Web site for
 Robert Zemeckis-Peter Jackson film, "The Frighteners."  Combined 
with Universal's newly redesigned interface, the multi-level site
 -- which  at its apex becomes a 2-way communication venue with a 
voice-enabled 3D virtual environment -- will revolutionize the way 
millions of  consumers sample the latest movies on the Internet.
<p>
     Just as The Frighteners takes psychic con man Frank Bannister
 (Michael J. Fox) into the spirit world to stop a supernatural
 crime spree, so does the site transport computer users to the 
"other side"  of the Net -- a shadowy cyber-realm where ghosts 
appear and disappear, where haunted Web pages have a mind of their
 own and where graphics suddenly morph and melt away.
<p>
     "The Frighteners" site has three main components, each of which is designed
 to address different audience needs:
<ul>
    <li>A comprehensive preview section including  storyline, 
 behind-the- scenes facts, cast and crew profiles and extensive
 multimedia samples for the broad PC audience.
<li>A "2D" fully interactive Web adventure into the world of  the  film
 that delivers a rich, dynamic and seamless gaming experience for  players
 on the Internet.

<li>  A "3D" voice-enabled virtual reality environment from OnLive! Technologies that depicts settings based on the film, where  participants can explore familiar scenes from "The Frighteners" and talk with  groups of people by selecting their own animated icons, or avatars.
</ul>
      "The Frighteners" can be accessed at the new Universal Pictures
Home Page located at <a href="http://www.mca.com/universal_pictures">http://www.mca.com/universal_pictures</a>.  
 <p><center>


</center>
<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>ActiveX Controls for  Web Pages</h3>
 
   The popularity of the Internet is growing exponentially, and developers who want to make their Web pages stand out above the rest are incorporating interactivity and eye-popping graphics. They're hot to learn how to develop the ActiveX controls that will give them even more power. In answer to that demand, The Coriolis Group has just released Developing ActiveX Web Controls  by  Al Williams (Coriolis, $39.99).
<p>
    With the introduction of the new Microsoft Internet Explorer (MIE) 3.0 Web browser, programmers will be scrambling to develop for ActiveX. ActiveX technology allows Web developers to create a new generation of interactive pages and applications usable with MIE. Developing ActiveX Web Controls is the first book to give developers the inside knowledge they need to create their own ActiveX controls. ActiveX controls provide cross-platform reusable, self-contained, standard components.
<p>
    Like Java applets, ActiveX controls can be run on the Web without downloading player programs. In more than 450 information-packed pages, you'll discover a solid, technical introduction to Microsoft's sizzling new technology, plus you'll learn step by step how to create your own Web controls.  The companion CD-ROM includes source code from the book, OCX controls and ActiveX control tools.
<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>CNET Going After It</h3>
    CNET: The  Computer  Network (Nasdaq: CNWK) and Austin, TX-based Vignette Corporation, a  developer of innovative tools for managing content on Web sites, have signed a deal that has the potential to revolutionize  the way premier Web site publishers create and manage content.
<p>
     Under the terms of the agreement, CNET, publisher of three of  the Web's most popular Web sites, has sold PRISM (Presentation of  Real-time Interactive Service Material), its patented Web content management  and page generation system, to Vignette. Vignette will  integrate  PRISM
into Vignette's own content management product family, which  is currently in development and scheduled for beta release in October. Vignette will market and sell PRISM to the Web development community, maintaining all licensing relationships and  on-going development of the technology.
   <p>
  In addition, CNET has made an undisclosed investment in  Vignette and Halsey Minor, chairman and chief executive officer of CNET,  will become a member of Vignette's board of directors.  CNET will also provide technical consulting on an as-needed basis.
<p>
     CNET developed PRISM technology for use on its own Web sites, CNET.COM, SHAREWARE.COM and SEARCH.COM, three of the most  trafficked sites on the Web according to PC Meter  (<a href="http://www.npd.com">http://www.npd.com</a>).  Currently delivering over 1.3 million pages each day on CNET's services,  PRISM greatly facilitates the process of creating and maintaining  dynamically created Web content. Using PRISM Web publishers can  easily  customize Web content and presentation based on user interest and profile, browser capabilities, speed of connection and more.  Additionally,
PRISM is flexible enough to support virtually all authoring environments.
<p>
      Forrester Research recently reported that Web-based  content providers each spend an average of $1.3 million each year to run  their Web sites, with over 30% of their budgets targeted at content management activities. Forrester estimates that content  site  expenses will continue to outpace revenue growth until  2000.  Vignette's products are intended to reduce costs and accelerate increased Web  site revenues by increasing production capacity and content  sophistication while automating operations and reducing personnel costs.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>Ucky Stuff Now Online</h3>


  New Country magazine  launched its new World Wide Web site on August 1 at <a href="http://www.newcountrymag.com">http://www.newcountrymag.com</a>.  The site is designed to be the most comprehensive and timely source of information on country music available today, though personally  this kind of music drives  <b>george jr.</b> nuts.
 <p>
    The site includes a breaking story on one of the artists to be inducted into the Country Music  Hall of Fame in October, such as Lyle Lovett, BR5-49 and songwriting  legend Harlan Howard, plus interviews with Shania Twain and Mindy McCready.  The site will also contain an exhaustive alphabetical discography, with  its own browser, of all 2,300 albums that New Country has rated since  its first issue. The graphically appealing discography lists and rates  all styles of country music recordings as well as some that stretch  beyond country's boundaries.
<p>
     "Our company already produces one very successful site, I-way, a  Web guide for Internet users, located at <a href="http://www.cciweb.com">http://www.cciweb.com</a>, that receives up to 100,000 visitors a month," a flak said.<P>

