<head>
<title>george jr. / august 1996 / departments / ask kitty</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="../august/departments.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
<H2>ask kitty</H2>

Well, well, well. It's the dead of summer and you're no smarter than you were in the spring. What gives? Obviously, little. But we do have the most forthcoming "life advice" columnist this side of the magic Eight Ball. Got a question? Just <a href=mailto: missy@coil.com >Ask Kitty</a>; we'll protect your  identity.
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>


<I><font size=+3>q.</font>What's the proper way for a lady in a dress to sit on stage?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> If you want to do the Emily Post thing -- and if you're a lady, you will -- cross your legs at the ankles and tuck them under you, a little to one side.  This is the only way a lady should ever sit, on stage or off.  If you want to see people who ALWAYS sit correctly, check out the females in the world's highest paid welfare family (the British royals).  If they're good for nothing else, they'll never disappoint in the sitting correctly category.  And waving.  I love that royal wave.
 <P>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font> If I wear a shirt that shows cleavage, have I lost the gender war - or does thinking about it suggest that I lost another war - to the agit-props?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Oh, no.  You have to think about these things.  Clothes can help or hinder you in the little skirmishes you fight on a daily basis.  So it depends on what you want.  You can be sexy and powerful.  You can be androgynous and powerful.  Just be yourself and you'll be the most powerful person you can be.
<p>
But, gentle reader, tossing around words when you haven't a clue about them is like pretending to have cleavage when you don't.  I can spot a push-up bra a mile away.  "Agitprop" is a single word (no hyphen).  Like the word "propaganda," from which the "prop" comes, "agitprop" serves as both the singular and plural form of the word.  And another thing.  Agitprop is the propaganda, not the people who propagandize. 
<p> 
Don't worry about thinking about the wrong things.  Just make sure you pay attention to the right things too.  And quit fighting wars.  Life's too short.
<p>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font> Why doesn't Blockbuster Video carry the "Wallace and Gromit" movies?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Now I want you to know, I personally called Blockbuster to make sure that they don't.  They don't.  Why don't they?  Because they are a national chain, the handmaids of Satan, catering to the lowest common denominator.  I can't believe you go to Blockbuster.  You might as well give your soul to the devil right now and start reading USA Today, because soon, it's all you'll have left.  Don't tell me, I could tell.  You live in the suburbs, buy all your material goods at hideous mega-stores, drive everywhere, and think it's so sad that there's no countryside left, that you don't know your neighbors, and can't get a good cheeseburger.  I'll tell you why Blockbuster doesn't carry Wallace and Gromit.  It doesn't make them money.  These odd little videos are expensive to buy and don't rent that often.  If you go on shopping at the mega book store, the mega video store, the mega music store, the mega food store, you, along with zillions of others in search of "convenience" and a "better price," are narrowing the choices of what anyone gets access to and of where they can go to find it.  You can't just trust the little guys to carry the expensive, relatively unprofitable cool stuff, while you line the pockets of multinational executives every time you buy everything else.  So don't even look at Blockbuster.  For anything.
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font> How do I politely move away from someone who smells like cigarette smoke?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Carry a gun.  They'll move away from you.
<p>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font> If someone asks me to create a resume for him, how should I handle it when he criticizes how I created his resume?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Doing a friend's resume is a bit like cutting a friend's hair.  Don't do it.  You're asking for trouble.  From your friend's perspective, you'll never get it just right; from your perspective your idiot friend will never be grateful enough for your exquisite work, let alone all the friggin' time you spent on the twerp's stupid resume.  Not that any of MY friends have ever asked ME to work on their resumes.  Or cut their hair.
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font> I'm 15 pounds too fat. What's the best way to rid myself of this blubber?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> The mirror tells me some truth, but not Enough to merit constant thought.<br>
<blockquote> --Theodore Roethke, from  Lines Upon Leaving a Sanitarium</blockquote>
Are you uncomfy with your bod?  Ayhhh, get over it.  Nothing is quite as tedious as people who are overly concerned with body image.  Your body is there to use and enjoy.  If your "extra" fifteen pounds are keeping you from enjoying yourself, shed 'em.  How?  I'd say the best way to get your body where it needs to be is to start doing what you want it to do.  Take it slowly.  Your body will catch up and its capacity will grow.  <p>
Or go lift weights.  Whatever.
<p>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font> You sound like a philosophical being. What five books would you take  with you to a desert isle? And how about a dessert isle?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Hey, why should I limit myself to five books?  In this, the age of transmissibility, I've gotten used to easy access to great works and ways to do research on them.  Of course easy transmissibility also has it's negative side.  
<P>
So I don't contract an incurable virus, I'll settle for a few books.  Here they are (well, this week's version):
<ul>
<LI>The Collected Poems  of Theodore Roethke
<LI>Homer's Iliad  and Odyssey  (that counts as one)
<LI>The Oxford English Dictionary
<LI>Green Eggs and Ham, by Dr. Seuss
<LI>Liddell and Scott's Greek-English Lexicon  (the big one) 
</ul>
On a dessert island I wouldn't need any books.  But I would like someone to play with.  
<P>
<I><font size=+3>q.</font>My neighbor plays his radio or CD player waaaay too loud at night, and  we're not really friends. How do I tell him to shut the hell up?</I><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>Carry a shotgun.  Pee in his yard.  Let your cat walk on his Porsche.  Get the idea?
<P>
<HR><BR>
<a href="../august/departments.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
