<head>

<title>george jr. / august 1996 / departments / plato's cave</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="../august/departments.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<H2>plato's cave</H2>
 <p align=center>&#160; </p>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td valign=top width=50%><h1><strong>Personal Web
Sites</strong></h1>
<h3><strong>Harmless Dribble or a Bane to
Society</strong> </h3>
<p align=left><br>
by<br>
<br>
Mike Kelley<br>
<a href="mailto:mrk@well.com">mrk@well.com</a> </p>
</td><td width=50%><p align=center><img src="bull.gif" align=bottom
width=323 height=232> </p>
<p align=center><strong>High Tech Graphic<br>
circa 15,000 B.C. </strong></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p align=left><br>
So why do they do it? I suppose I should just as well ask why the
first cave type person drew the first shaggy buffalo on a cold damp
wall in the South of France, or why some bum Roman scratched
raunchy graffiti on the walls of ancient Pompeii. Self expression is
undoubtedly an indelible part of the human spirit. Instead of
charcoal and paints, today&#146;s Homo sapiens just happens to have
html and the World Wide Web at his or her disposal.<br>
<br>
Instead of wondering why these personal web pages exist, maybe it
would be more constructive to see if they can tell us something
about the authors of these on-line scrapbooks. Maybe we can even
get a clue as to what our culture is about; as in cave painting show
us chasing hairy buffaloes seemed to be in some 15,000 years ago.
Let&#146;s take a quick tour in our own online cave; the Well&#146;s (a
venerable, Internet suave, bulletin board) Community Pages.
(<a
href="http://www.well.com/community/">http://www.well.com/community/</a>)<br>
<br>
Uh. . . maybe we should take a psychiatrist and a strait-jacket along.
Could it be that the only thing we can learn from these pages is that
the authors are totally irreverent and self-possessed. How else can
one explain the:<br>
<br>
<em>Aikocat's Cynical Mind</em> (<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/aikocat/">http://www.well.com/user/aikocat/</a>) <br>
I never even got passed the A&#146;s before I saw this one!<br>
<br>
Oh okay, let&#146;s be fair, these pages are for the most part harmless
enough. Most even border on the serious and useful. There are the
usual &quot;Hi I&#146;m Bob and this is what I do with my life&quot; pages:<br>
<em>Eric Allen</em> (<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/eallen/">http://www.well.com/user/eallen/</a>
)<br>
<em>David Albert slept here, 1995 present</em>
(<a href="http://www.musenet.org/~aslan/">http://www.musenet.org/~aslan/</a>
<br>
(I&#146;m still not out of the A&#146;s yet.)<br>
<br>
And the relatively benign, &quot;This is my interest or hobby&quot;:<br>
<em>Big Lizard Video Home Page</em> (<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/bigliz/">http://www.well.com/user/bigliz/</a>
)<br>
<em>WELL co-founder Stewart Brand talks books</em>
(<a href="http://www.well.com/user/sbb/">http://www.well.com/user/sbb/</a>)<br>
<br>
And the standard, &quot;You're not doing anything today, why don&#146;t you
contribute heavily to my consulting business.&quot;<br>
<em>Axon Internet Consulting designs, builds and markets high quality
Web pages </em>(<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/andream/">http://www.well.com/user/andream/</a>)<br>
<em>Cap'n Crunch Home Page: as a Cyber Gypsy, I create WEB pages
on the fly, and put small businesses on the World Wide Web</em>.
(<a href="http://www.well.com/user/crunch/">http://www.well.com/user/crunch/</a>)<br>
<br>
<br>
So much for the almost normal. I, like most, are attracted to the
totally weird, and there are plenty of personal web sites on the Well
that fit this description:<br>
<em>Rau's Rodent Rehab Ranch</em> (<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/mirau/">http://www.well.com/user/mirau/)</a><br>
<em>Home Bob by the Bay, rawdirt</em>
(<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/rawdirt/">http://www.well.com/user/rawdirt/</
a>)<br>
<em>Burning Man photos by Barbara Traub</em>
(<a
href="http://www.zpub.com/mediaz/btraub.html/">http://www.zpub.com/mediaz/bt
raub.html</a>)<br>
<em>Brain Candy for Happy Mutants</em>
(<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/mark/">http://www.well.com/user/mark/</a>)<br>
<em>William A. Smith on Evolution and Why Are We Here?
</em>(<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/netsmith/">http://www.well.com/user/netsmith/
</a>)<br>
<em>David Ballinger's Universal Repository of Lozenges</em>
(<a href="http://www.well.com/user/dgb/">http://www.well.com/user/dgb/</a>)<br>
<em>black &amp; blue multiple mediums (a.k.a.the bruised duo) invite you
to indulge in other dimensions (weekly astrological forecast &amp;
kosmic art)... </em>(<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/blknblu/">http://www.well.com/user/blknblu/</
a>)<br>
<em>Say heyo to Cynsa Bonorris</em> (<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/cynsa/">http://www.well.com/user/cynsa/)</a><br>
<br>
So can we learn anything about on-line folks and current culture
from our little virtual spelunking. Well maybe that folks like to talk
about themselves, want to make money, and some are truly bizarre.
We can also conclude that many people have access to way too
much technology and have far too much time on their hand. Go
exploring yourself and see what you think. And by the way check out
this totally cool Web site: (<a
href="http://www.well.com/user/mrk/">http://www.well.com/user/mrk/</a>)</p>
<P>
<h5 align=center><i>The Grumpy Bachelor Website http://www.well.com/user/mrk<br>
Mike Kelley mrk@.well.com</i></h5>
<p align=left><br>
</p>
</blockquote>

<P>

