<html>

<head>

<title>george jr. / august 1996 / faq / What george jr. wants</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="../august/faq.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotofaq.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<H2>What george jr. wants</H2>
<blockquote>
<p align=left><br>


His name, mostly. He wants to keep his name. As 
<b>Newsweek, The Boston Globe, The Columbus Dispatch</b> and other news 
media reported the last week of July and the first week of August,  two 
dozen lawyers for John F. Kennedy Jr.'s  rather gigantic, 
celebrity-filled and monied George Magazine have ordered me to "cease and 
desist" publishing this home page because, they say, they own the first 
part of my name.  (This is going to come to a surprise to my dad and 
everybody else named George, not to mention the hundreds if not thousands 
of websters named George, and to those who have George as a part of their 
domain name or web site.)
<p>
    I'm ignoring the lawyers "cease and desist,"  and am fighting to keep 
my name - because my name  actually is George Jr. and my web site is 
actually called <b>george jr.</b> and not, after all, George. I suppose 
if there's a fight, both George Magazine and george jr. will be removed 
from the web until there is a peaceable kingdom. 
<p>


    In the meantime, and as a result of this snit, citizen webheads are 
posting rants against JFK Jr. all over the place and even on his own 
magazine. It may be that JFK Jr. has no idea that his lawyers have 
attacked me. He's a junior; I'm a junior. Certainly he would know that 
there is a real and genuine difference between "John" and "John Jr.," 
just as we know there is a real and  genuine difference between George and George 
Jr., not to mention <b>George Magazine</b> and <b>george jr.</b>
  <p>
   Now, here's what else <b>george jr.</b> wants:  editorial copy from 
you, for which we can pay neither a shilling nor a pence. <b>george 
jr.</b> is especially interested in Interesting Information smartly 
conveyed first, followed by  original essays, short-short fiction and 
even reprints (which we secure permission to reprint, always, and for 
which we neither pay nor charge a dime). 
<p>
   And, if you've had any interesting dreams, send them. <b>george 
jr.</b> is interested to learn if the web has a collective psyche, as 
well  as the usual psychoses.
<p>
   <b>george jr.</b> doesn't own a scanner and hates going to Kinko's (can I say 
"Kinko's"?) to have pieces of art scanned, so send your art digitized or 
as a print if you must. No slides, no heads of cabbage, please.
<p>
   Send letters as <a href="mailto:gmyers@coil.com">email</a>, 
and press releases as faxes.
<p>
   The next issue likely will have something to do with lawyers.
<p>
   A JFK Jr./George Magazine disclaimer already appears within the 
Opening Gambit; how many more does anyone think I really need?
</blockquote>

<P>

