<html>
<head>
<title>george jr. / september 1996 / features / opening gambit</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<img src="/graphics/gambit.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=15 ALT="">
<br>
<b>Welcome to the September issue!</b>
<br>   This month <b>george jr.</b>  again offers you interviews to curl your hair, whet your whistle, dry your nose, urge you to register to vote or visit a library, and make you do squat thrusts on command.
<br clear=all><blockquote>
 <p>  Novelists <B>Susan Power, Alan Furst</B> and young-punk wunderkind <B>Ashley Warlick</B> star in interviews, along with <B>Charles Bowen</B>, whose latest  book is a primer on online activism.
<p>  Idaho writer <B>Lance Olsen</B> contributes a story set in Seattle. Old friend <B>Margaret Visser</B> sashays about something offal. There's always more.
 <p>  Take, for example, our informal symposium on trademark law, scattered hither and yon this issue. We added it due to the heavy legal readership of late and the wish that we'd do something, something, in response to our being threatend by lawyers representing George Magazine, which <b>george jr.</b> has nothing whatsoever to do with.
<p>
The opinions
expressed in the <a href="citizenry.html#trademark">trademark symposium</a> are
strictly those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect the views of
<b>george jr.</b> or anyone else. 

<p>
<b>Bravura!</b><br>
   Welcome to the fun house --  what Mr. Media picked as a Pick, what Radio One and Yahoo! have picked as the site of the day and week, and what the McKinley Group picked as a Magellan Four-Star Site. <b>george jr.</b> is a monthly of actual content and nothing to sell but our souls.
<p>    Not content to sit on our collective keister, <b>george jr.</b>  this month brags up our favorite software of the month and special news for Trekkies, and  the always fabu National Public Rodeo where news  about the web, concerts, software and such appear Sunday.
<p>   If we lose your vote we'll just have to offer a 15-percent tax cut, nationwide, and see if you come back and <B>Bookmark our home page.</B>
<p>
<b>And thanks, chain gang</b>
<br>
    Thanks for checking in and thanks, again, to Alan Rapp and our friends at <A NAME="http://www.chronbooks.com">Chronicle Books</A>, which has allowed us to reprint the lovely man in chains on the home page. <B>Fred Johnson</B>'s 'Escape Artist' poster, now in the collection of Charles Boas, is one of many wonderful 1950-ish images from Carl Hammer and Gideon Bosker's <i>Freak Show Banner Art </i> ($14.95). 

<p>   Everybody else we thank and doff our hats to in the pages to follow.
<p>
<b>Still life with culture on a plate</b>
<br>
    Ah, you were wanting something from <b>george jr.</b>himself? Well, yours truly barely got through Phillip Lopate's excruciatingly self-absorbed new book,<i> Portrait of My Body, </i> and yours truly is more convinced than ever to not lard your plate with 'I think this' and 'I felt that' kind of stuff.
 <p>  <b>george jr.</i> will continue to be your dray horse, lugging culture behind us, but never will we be your huckleberry.
<p>   
   Funny how we say 'we' and 'our,' ain't it?
<p>
   Our pleasure. On with the promenade.
</blockquote>   
<P>
