<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / features / q & a / charles bowen</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/september/warlick.jpg" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=266 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 

<P>

Ashley Warlick:<BR>

The Distance From The Heart Of Things

<P>

 At 23 years old, Ashley Warlick was the youngest author ever to win the Houghton Mifflin Literary Fellowship, which resulted in the publication of her first novel, <i>The Distance from the Heart of Things </i>(HM, $21.95). The novel is narrated in the radiant first-person voice of the main character, Mavis Black, who returns home from college to be the accountant on her family's prosperous South Carolina vineyard.
<p>
<hr width=75%>
<br clear=all>
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> 

You began <i>The Distance From The Heart Of Things</i>, when you were  just  20  and  still  in  college,  an  ambitious project for someone so young. How did that come about?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

I had written a novella when I was a freshman and  liked  the  feel  of  it,  so  I    added  independent  study  in  the  fall  semester  of  my  sophomore   year   to write  some  more.  My  advisor  told  me  to  have  something  to  him   by  December. October  comes  around  and  I  have  a  couple  of  paragraphs. Thanksgiving,  and   I have a page and a half, and  then  it's  time  to  go  home  for  Christmas  and  I  ask my advisor if I can  get  a  manuscript  to  him  after  the  New  Year.  He  sighs  and tells me fine,  fine. So the holidays sweep  by,  and  then  I'm  pecking  away  at  this thing in my parents' living  room  and  all  I  have  basically  is  the  first  set  of  paragraphs  and  a  bunch  of  names.  But  I  get  something  in  the  mail,  and   one afternoon I  get  this  very  serious  message  on  my  machine  from  my  advisor  that says he needs to talk to  me  immediately,  and  I  know  I'm  in  trouble  because  the manuscript I sent him is  only  30  pages  and  page  30  leaves  off  mid -sentence.  I get him on the phone and he asks  me  to  come  see  him  --  no  details,  no  hint  of anything in his voice. So  I  set  out  to  his  house  with  all  the  speed  fear  and trepidation will allow and we are sitting at his kitchen  table  when  he  tells  me  he read the 30 pages and what  I've  got  is  a  novel,  and  he  sent  the  pages  to  his agent in New York and she says this  is  a  novel.  So  I  decided  I  must  be  writing a novel. I was told I had 'til graduation to complete it.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

Hey, nice advisor. You also  got  married  when  you  graduated  --  which  came  first,  the  wedding or completing your novel.

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

 By graduation in June, I was really close to  finishing  the  novel  and  I  wanted to be done with it before  my  wedding  on  August  1.  So  I  rented  a  room  in  this spooky old house for a month absolutely  convinced  I  could  pull  it  off.  My  mother was calling hourly from Charlotte  and  asking  if  I  was  done  yet,  and  my  fiancee was playing  pool  in  dark  bars  a  lot  asking  his  friends  if  what  I  was  doing seemed  sane. 

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 Forgive me, but: And then? And then? And then?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Around  July  4th  my  mother  
was  threatening  to  come  
up   and   get me, and my 
advisor  was  saying  that  
I  would  be  dashing  off  
the  final  sentences as I
 was walking down the aisle if I had to, that 
this was going to get done,  by God. I'd say I 
completed it under duress.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

You're  young to be coming to writing full  time.  Did  you  set  out  to  make

a profession of it?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

 Not really, but it's the only thing I can do, the only thing I love enough to  do. But I can't say that I think of myself as doing it -- it's  more  like  breathing,  or eating what tastes good. I  am  always  working,  whether  I  think  about  it  or  not, and a part of me  has  always  gone  to  laying  things  out  in  my  head,  has  always lived a little in the third person. It's a matter  of  paying  attention,  knowing  that when my brain turns  over  and  starts  running  with  something  I  need  to  write  it down.  My  father  is  a  natural  storyteller,  but   my   parents   never   especially encouraged  me  to  write  for  a  living.  Up  until  this  book   was   accepted   for publication, my mother was still calling me  and  saying,  You  know,  it's  not  too late to take up nursing.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> 

 Ha! Your novel is set on a  vineyard  in  South  Carolina. Did  you  know  a  place like it when you were growing up there?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Up until I was 11 or 12,  my  father  and  my  grandfather  ran  vineyards in York County, South Carolina, and sold  grapes  to  wineries  and  to  Welch's. It was quite a thing, when I was a  girl.  There  was  a  big  Grape  Festival  in  late summer,  a  parade  with  (Grape  Queens  in  convertibles  and   my   whole   family riding the picker, which was  always  sticky  sweet  out  of  the  fields.  And  then there were the blue million stories my  father  had  about  growing  up  amongst  all that. The heart of the book really rests in that place, that time. South Carolina  in so many ways is really nowhere at all, eerie and  vacant  and  dry,  But  my  father had come from there, and he is so  thick  with  himself,  so  wily  and  bigger  than life. His memories and  my own worked like  fodder.  As  for  true  facts  from  life, they're rarely in the book, but they're behind it.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 The narrator  of  your  novel,  Mavis  Black,  is  a  young  woman  who  seems  to have  already  figured  out  what  many  Generation  X  characters   struggle   with. What makes her different?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

  I think  there  is  something  elemental  about  Mavis,  something  enduring  that makes her age irrelevant. A lot of  her  strength  comes  from  people  thinking  she's strong and putting her out there in  the  world  without  excuses.  Mavis  says  in the beginning of the story that she likes weight placed  on  her,  that  it  feels  good), and to say this, she is also saying she can take  it.  She  could  take  about  anything given to her, horrible and perfect both,  and  I  suppose  that  is  a  rare  thing. She is thoughtful and self-aware,  but  she  does  all  her  thinking  on  her  feet. She sets the tone the book rises to, and I hope it's a timeless one.

<P>

<HR><BR>

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>

