<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / features / q & a / charles bowen</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/september/power.jpg" WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=179 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 

<P>

Susan Power: Naming Names 

<P>

 Susan Power's literary debut, <i>The Grass Dancer </i>(Putnam),  won the Ernest Hemingway Foundation Award in 1995. It is a much-heralded novel of interwoven tales that illuminated the hearts and minds of a handful of Sioux characters, especially Harley Wind Soldier and his mother, Lydia, who stopped talking when she was widowed. As the secrets of one tale is peeled away, another is revealed.
<p>    Next March, Power will release her newest novel, <i>Strong Heart Society </i>  (Putnam). The interview:
<p>
<hr width=75%>
<br clear=all>
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> 

 Who gave you the gift of storytelling?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Both my parents. My mother has a tremendous gift of imagination and was always telling me stories -- true tales and those she dreamed up on her own. She also told me about the professional storytellers she grew up listening to when she was a child on the Standing Rock Sioux Reservation. I visited the place where she lived as a child. She took me to powwows, and frequently gave rides there to Native American friends from the community. I remember sharing hotel rooms with older women who told chilling ghost stories.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

It has an especially 'oral' sense about it, as though it must be heard or spoken.

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

 My father read to me every night, even when I was old enough to read. This is why writing is such an oral experience for me. I have to read my work aloud over and over at both the writing and editing stages. I need to hear the language, hear the story, in order to make it live.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 How and when did The Grass Dancer evolve?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

I began writing it while attending the Iowa Writers' Workshop. Even though I was handing in the chapters as short stories, for the purpose of the Workshop, I knew I was working on a novel. It would have been difficult then for anyone else to see the connections among the chapter, but the overall structure was developing in my head, and I knew the ties would be made clearer the deeper I got into the book. One of its first images is that of an elderly Indian woman in full traditional regalia dancing on the moon. Naturally, I wanted to know what she was doing there, and in discovering her story I realized I had written the first chapter.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 What did you learn about yourself over the course of writing The Grass Dancer?


<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

I learned that I was raised even more "Dakota" than I thought. In doing research for the chapter called "Snakes," which is set in 1864, I came to understand that many of my mother' attitudes, values and expectations flowed directly from tribal customs and were not even her own eccentricities.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> 

 Names seem to have a special significance in the novel.

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Names have many kinds o»f meaning. They can carry historical weight and significance -- imagine being a Roosevelt or a Kennedy. Names can be descriptive and they can be gifts. My mother gave me her Sioux name, Wakca Wastewin (Prairie Flower) before she died, and even though I don't use it in daily life, it means a great deal to me.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 Well, why? How?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

It binds me to her and to the Standing Rock Sioux tribe in a  special way. A name can connect generations; it can be particularly powerful if the person who owns it endows it with his or her own strength and dignity.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

You have a bachelor's degree in psychology from Harvard/Radcliffe, and a law degree from Harvard Law School. Have these backgrounds helped your writing in some specific way?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Definitely. I have always been interested in complex characters, and psychology gave me an understanding of human behavior patterns. Law influenced my writing in terms of technical craft. I have written all my life, especially poetry, but I've thought of that as a release. Studying law helped me to pull back and choose words more carefully.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

Why not practice law?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Pure selfishness led me to leave the law before I'd even given it a fair shot. I was bored. The research was tedious, and I didn't feel that my creative instincts were given the right outlet. That's not to say that the practice of law doesn't require great creativity -- just not the breathless, dramatic use of imagination I was so enthralled with.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 Well, why? How?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

It binds me to her and to the Standing Rock Sioux tribe in a  special way. A name can connect generations; it can be particularly powerful if the person who owns it endows it with his or her own strength and dignity.

<P>

<HR><BR>

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>

</HTML>

