<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / features / q & a / alan furst</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/september/furst2.jpg" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=272 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 

<P>

Alan Furst:<BR>

Spies and Love in from the Cold

<P>

Novelist Alan Furst is the author of <i>The World at Night</i> (Random House) most  recently, but also <i>Polish Officer, Dark Star</i> and <i>Night Soldiers</i> - books that showcase his fidelity to Furst's abiding interest in idealism, heroism, sacrifice and, yep, espionage.
<p>
<hr width=75%>

<P>
<br clear=all>
<font size=5>q.</font>

I noticed the Boston Globe said your books "transcend the spy novel." Yet espionage in World War II remains a strong element in your work.

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Albert Einstein said, "This is not a gentleman's century. The principal business of this century is war." In such times, espionage is important, and people do it as an act of faith. It employs the worst and the best, and from its position you see inside and in back of events. It holds the balance in the great battle of this century -- Hitler/Stalin. It is also very much an equal opportunity employer -- Virginia Hall parachuted for the OSS into occupied territory during World War II. Under her arm she carried her artificial leg. One could go on -- eccentrics, beasts, saints and clerks, the gloriously right and the gloriously wrong -- Hieronymous Bosch visits the present century.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>
We never leave this stuff alone.

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Hard to explain why we never stop digging at this era -- on American television as in French hearts and minds, the war never ends- It defines heroism and honor and sacrifice and nationality -- it was really the worst of times but it brought out the best in some people. There was real evil, and breath-taking goodness, people torn between opportunism and self-sacrifice. None of the peoples in this war can forget it or leave it behind -- the Russians, the French, the Japanese, the British and the Americans -- we're still living out the destinies forged in that time. Maybe the turn of the century will change that, maybe it won't.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

Are Jean Casson and Citrine -- the film producer and movie star characters in THE
WORLD AT N]NIGHT -- real people?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

 Based on real people -- at least two film producers I know of were involved in spying for resistance movements. The tempting thing for me came from reading about French film. The occupation was certainly one of its greatest periods. That's very hard to believe at first, but <i>The World at Night</i>, in its history of the film "Hotel Dorado" suggests a possible answer: when you can't do reality, you do fantasy, and most of French life is based on fantasy. You can ask the French about that -- I did -- and they say, "So what do you want,  reality?"


<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

Having  written  about  two  such  dispirit   resistances   (The Polish Officer and <i>The World at Night</i>) do you think there was a right and a wrong choice?


<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>


Living in France, researching  the French and  Paris  in  1940/1941,  one  fact  becomes  clearer  and clearer: Don't lose a war. The  Poles  never  gave  in,  millions  died,  Warsaw  was  turned  to  ashes. France collaborated, the art and the cathedrals were saved, the national honor was  lost.  (In  Paris] sometimes -- especially during the Gulf  War  --  somebody  would  ask  me  if  I  was  American  and buy me a drink. Or somebody  would  whisper,  "I  remember.  I  saw  the Americans  march  in  here," But there's always  something  covert  in  such  moments.  The  French  don't forgive  the  Germans  for conquering them, they don't forgive the  Americans  for  saving  them,  and  they  don't  forgive  the British for sticking it out.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

After reading The Polish Officer and <i>The World at Night</i>, it Is clear that something about Paris and the French Resistance has a hold on you.

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

Living in Paris inspired me to write about the Polish resistance (The  Polish  Officer),  because  the Poles fought and the French really didn't. Even in the mid-Õ80s,  you'd  go  to  the  Pere  Lachaise cemetery on the Day of the Dead (November 1), and  there  would  be  the  Poles,  at  Chopin's  tomb, standing silent in the rain under umbrellas with Chopin's  "Polonaise" playing  on  a  tape  recorder and little vigil-light candles burning on the edge of the tomb. They were still at it, they were  never going to stop.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

What about the French?


<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

The French hadn't changed either, Early research for <i>The World at Night</i> led to the British historian Alan Clark, writing about "the apathy and  resignation  that  lay behind  the  French collapse in 1940, when a people sacrificed their country  and  institutions  for  their  own  personal safety. The pleasures of wine, adultery, and civilized conversation could,  it  seemed,  be  preserved simply by refusing to fight.
 The French believe in making love, in drinking wine,  in  staying  up  all night  and  talking  about  life. Certainly the hero of <i>The World at Night</i> believes in little else. But he -- like a few hundred French men and women -- tries to resist, to  fight  back  against  the  Germans.  He  does  it wrong, at least at the beginning, but at least he tries. Why does  he  fight?  For  the  right  to  remain French.

<P>

<HR><BR>

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    

</BODY>

</HTML>

</DOC>
