<html>

<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / features / fiction / lance olsen</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="../september/features.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>


<H2>fiction:</H2> 
<P>


<H3>Lance Olsen: Welcome to Seattle and Other Unnatural Practices</H3>

You are sitting with your wife in a turn-of-the-century cafe in Pioneer Square 
at rush hour on Friday.  You've just arrived from Moscow, Idaho, with plans to 
spend a weekend in Seattle.  See a couple of films, stroll along the icy January 
waterfront, attend a reading at Elliot Bay Bookstore.  Only when you raise your 
head from your coffee mug you see what's going to happen, clairvoyance, a 
nanosecond before it does.
<p>
I don't think he's going to make it, you tell your wife.
<p>
She continues to spread cream cheese on her bagel while reading the <i>LA 
Times </i> folded on the wooden table before her.
<p>
You have caught sight of this old guy, eighty, eighty-five, black beret, shiny 
cane, dark gray trench coat.  He teeters near an iron street lamp on a corner 
across the Square, clearly deciding whether or not to ford the intersection.  The 
traffic is dense, the light red.  Cars, trucks and busses rev their engines, 
releasing steam and particulate matter.  The old guy wobbles, peers left, right. 
Commuters insect around him over the crosswalk, collect on the other side, 
disperse.  The old guy tentatively steps off the curb, cane first.  He sets down 
one foot.  He sets down two.  The light changes to green.  The cars, trucks and 
busses come at him.
<p>
I don't think he's going to make it, you say again, for some reason feeling this is 
a fairly important point to make.
<p>
Your wife leisurely looks up and out the window, down at her paper, then does 
a double-take right out of a Three Stooges skit.  
<p>
Good lord, she says, as the first car, a white Celica, hits him.
<p>
From this distance the knock seems soft, sponge on sponge.  The cane spins 
briefly into the air like a baton. There are no horns, no brakes: it's just that 
kind of day.  The cane pauses at the apex of its arc, descends, lands in the 
middle of the intersection.  The old guy's legs buckle.  He retreats.  He pauses, 
takes stock of his situation, steps forward once more into traffic.
<p>
What is he doing? your wife asks.
<p>
Retrieving his cane, I think.
<p>
You lean forward to get a better view.  Your wife puts down her bagel and 
knife.  People on the sidewalk do not halt to watch.  The old guy gingerly takes 
two more steps.  He looks as if he is walking in bare feet on a field strewn with 
shards of glass, as if he is living in the dream you often have of navigating 
through a room whose floor is churning with rattlesnakes.  He raises his arm.  
It appears he is waving to someone, though it is impossible to tell who it might 
be.
<p>
He'll make it, my wife says, a little too confidently, a wink before the second 
car, a baby blue Escort, catches his hip and pivots him into the third, a crimson 
Jeep.
<p>
He takes short flight and lands poorly, on his knees, in the middle of the 
intersection, a yard away from his cane.  He surveys his surroundings, takes his 
coordinates, rises, brushes himself off, hobbles two steps, stoops to claim his 
prize, and continues into the path of a bus.  A couple walking toward the door 
of the cafe after a few beers notice what is happening and, interested, stroll up 
to your table.  You exchange a polite smile and point, although they are already 
looking in the right direction.
<p>
Get out the camera, the shaggy man in jeans and a calf-skin jacket tells the 
shaggy woman in jeans and a calf-skin jacket.  
<p>
She does, but discovers the camera is out of film.
<p>
What the hell are you carrying a camera for if you don't have any film in it? 
the man asks.
<p>
You're the one who wanted to photograph the ferry coming in from 
Bainbridge, the woman answers, not me.
<p>
My smile and these comments take fewer than four seconds.  
<p>
The whole event takes fewer than ten.  
<p>
This strikes you as an impressive fact.  You turn to your wife to share it and see 
her palms flat on the newspaper on the table in front of her.  You see her lips 
parted the width of a finger.  You see age webbing the soft skin below her wide 
blue eyes as she is held spellbound by the old guy's dance. When you check the 
intersection again, you discover he is airborne for the last time.  Yet this 
matters less than you might at first have imagined.  You are already thinking 
beyond his trajectory.  You already exist in your own future, remembering this.  
You remember how you will have remembered three things: the purple-gray 
color of the sky, the baton paused in sad half-light, your wife's parted lips.  
<p>
What you will have remembered most, however, is the fourth and fifth thing: 
the determination in that old guy's jaw, cocked as though ready to receive a fist; 
the homing signal in his walk.  He is the sort of guy, it occurs to you, who has 
places to go.  He is the sort of guy who has times to be there.
<p>
<HR><BR>

