<html>

<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / citizenry / the uneasy chair</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/citizenry.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoc.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<img src="/graphics/uneasy.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>
 Law and disorder? We've had enough and not enough, thanks. This month's rant,  by Gerald M. Sutliff,  is a commentary on the book <i>Smoke and Mirrors</i> by Dan Baum  (Little, Brown and Co.).
<P>
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
Who should read this book? Drug Czar Barry McCaffrey and everyone else who wants to know how we got into this mess. The failure of the War on Drugs (WoD) and its repercussions has been ably covered by other writers and commentators, recently in the February 12th, issue of <i>National  Review</i>. Former <i>Wall Street Journal </i>reporter, Dan Baum, sets a different goal: "<i><i>Smoke and Mirrors</i></i> is offered as a map of how we got here, in the hope of suggesting a way back." By showing where we were in 1967 and the steps taken to get where we now are makes  a better case against the WoD than do many contemporary snapshots.
<P>

      Baum's map consists of short and readable scenes reported by people who were there (he eschews "off the record" sources) and of individuals making their decisions on furthering the War on Drugs. The reader can turn to any page and find a fascinating
example of someone's raw avarice for power or another's defeat and retreat. If you ever thought that the Wod, at the political level,  had anything to do with the health and welfare of addicts or about  the physical and mental welfare of our youth, this book will 
dissuade you.
<P>
     What began as political expediency, for Presidents Johnson and Nixon -- both wanted to divert attention from the failing Vietnam War -- became, under  Reagon-Bush, a war against lack of virtue. In several examples the drug  warriors are shown to be eager enforcers who show little concern for innocent bystanders. No small time offender is too small for punishment. The small time offender and the ever lengthening mandatory sentencing becomes the "body count" for the WoD.
   <P>  
      Baum makes no pretense of being an objective reporter but  avoids preaching; Instead, he provides background to show the context  in which the decision makers operated (drawn from disinterested public sources). Having knowledge of the context in which the policy statement or the decision was made the reader makes her/his own evaluation.  This method of persuasive writing is highly effective. 
<P>
     <i>Smoke and Mirrors</i> is chronologically organized. At the end of each chapter (usually covering one year) the reported political haranguing about the drug crisis is counter pointed with the actual statistics of drug use, abuse and other relevant items.
<P>
     Here is one (not the most egregious) example of duplicitous practices by our government: In 1970 when asked how to improve the political effect of reporting drug interdictions, John E. Ingersoll, Director, Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs, wrote in a memo, " 'Alternatives, might be the illicit street value . . . By using
the illicit value concept, the hard drug figure would increase by at least a factor of 100 in relation to marihuana.' " Baum explains, "Born of the need to show triumph on the heroin front, street value  became the yardstick by which progress in the War on Drugs would be measured."
<P>
     This reviewer has yet to hear of a news reporter challenging a Drug Enforcement Administration or Attorney General's Office spokesman  after s/he announces drug bust gives the "estimated street value" by asking, "On what basis do you estimate the drugs' street value?"  Or  How can you be sure it's valid?" Or "What kind of research did did "What is the  exact amount of heroin, cocaine, marijuana, etc.  by value, weight, and/or purity seized?"
<P>
     Baum doesn't let his own profession off easily. He shows how the news media allowed Nixon to bury his own commission's recommendation that marijuana be decriminalized. he wasn't the first nor the last to get away with that.
<P>
As shown in <i>Smoke and Mirrors</i>, in 1970 when NIxon was  still developing the WoD:
<P>
<ul>
     <li>Number of Americans who died in 1970 from legal and  illegal drugs: 1,899
                       <li>Number who died of the flu: 3,707
     <li>Number of prescriptions for psychoactive drugs written in  1970: 214 
million
     <li>Amount spent by Americans on legal spirits, wine and  beer: $24 billion
     <li>Estimated size of illegal drug market: $2 billion
</ul>
     Had such facts been made part of the public debate in 1970, perhaps Nixon would have been denied his War on Drugs. Who else could have done it except the news media? Those politicians who privately had doubts about the WoD, then as now, with a few exceptions, were afraid to appear "soft on drugs."
<p>
     From the evidence shown in this book, it may fairly be argued that there was no _illegal_ drug crisis in 1970 (Nixon's era). During the Watergate crisis, mention of illegal drugs in the media was nil. Certainly there was no illegal drug crisis in 1980's when Reagan re-declared the War on Drugs.
<p>
     In 1990 almost one in five high school seniors (it's higher now) was smoking cigarettes every day as opposed to one in fifth smoking pot daily. We parents know the "drug crisis" is created by prohibition; when our children start smoking cigarettes we do what we can to educate and nag them out of the practice but we save our histrionics and dire threats for marijuana use. We fear that marijuana could enmesh them in the criminal justice system and ruin  their lives.
<p>
     Finally, Baum does us all a service by showing the gradual erosion of  out Bill of Rights protections over the last 30 years. It all happened under the  cover of the WoD.
The erosion hasn't decreased under Bill Clinton either. Consider the sharp increase in wiretapping by the federal government since the beginning of the Clinton administration (From 340 in 1992 to over 700 [estimated] this year). Almost all of it is for drug enforcement activities. It's enough to make this Democrat muse about voting Libertarian.
<p><hr width=75%><P>	 
<blockquote>
<font size =2><i>
Gerald Sutliff is a labor arbitrator who lives in Northern California and writes on social issues. He is a member of several drug reform organizations.
</i></font>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<hr>

<br>

<a href="/september/citizenry.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoc.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>


</BODY>

</HTML>

