<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / features / q & a / charles bowen</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/september/bowen.jpg" WIDTH=169 HEIGHT=226 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

<H2><font size=+3>q</font> & <font size=+3>a</font></H2> 

<P>

Charles Bowen:<BR>

Activism on the Line

<P>

 Charles Bowen is a political journalist active on the online press. He is senior news editor for CompuServe's 'Online Today' forum, contributing editor to <i>CompuServe </i>magazine, and a columnist for  <i>HOME PC </i>. He lives in Huntington, West Virginia. <i>Modem Nation</i> (Times/Business, $20), about political activism on the web, is his 16th  book.
<p>
<hr width=75%>
<br clear=all>
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> 

The word "computer" doesn't appear anywhere on the front or back cover of <i>Modem Nation</i>. So, is this a computer book about politics or a political book about computers?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

A little of both, I hope. Actually, this is the first of the 15 books I've done since 1984 that is NOT being pitched as strictly a "computer book." While obviously the topic embraces computers and online exploration, the subject is broader: politics, activism, Net citizenship, the future of the medium, its role, if any, in the current election campaign and where we go from here. I understand from the folks at Random House/Times Books that most stores are carrying it in their "politics/social studies" sections, which I'm very happy to hear. And just recently I got a flier in the mail called "Politics" from Borders book stores that included <i>Modem Nation</i>  in some pretty heady company, including Ted Sorensen, James Carville, Haynes Johnson, David Broder, Noam Chomsky and John Kenneth Galbraith. I had trouble getting a hat to fit for a few days after seeing that...

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

Where did the idea for the book come from?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

 Well, I've always been interested in government and politics. As a newspaper reporter in the late 1960s and throughout the 1970s, I covered city hall, county government, school boards, courts, planning and zoning boards, airport and transit authorities, urban renewal boards and all those other nuts and bolts of local and state government -- not to mention LOTs of elections. (I always figured that after writing about city budgets, covering computers was a cakewalk!) Then, for the past decade after leaving daily newspapering in the mid-1980s, I've been writing books about computer communications (CompuServe, America Online, Prodigy and the others). While the  technical aspects of those services have been interesting to me -- and the how-to manuals were so NECESSARY in the first decade of cyberspace, when all the various software and hardware configurations made it so darn complicated -- I've always been more interested in the social, psychological and philosophical sides of modemming.
     For that reason, I was looking forward to the time when I could write about the medium as a "given," the way we write about the other great appliances of our age, such as TV, radio, VCRs and automobiles. When the rise of the extremely simple
telecomputing afforded by the Web seemed like an invitation to do just that, it was fitting, I thought, to make the first of these NEW books about politics and activism -- the same topics that occupied so much of my attention in that earlier important crossroad in my life.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

 So, <i>Modem Nation</i>  deals exclusively with day-to-day politics of the partisan Democrat-Republican-Libertarian variety?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

No, not exclusively. Of course, the story of computers and politics STARTS with the current political situation. The past four years have been simply amazing, from a "cyber-political" point-of-view. When Bill Clinton took office four years ago, the White House was so non-wired that phone calls still were transferred by operators pushing plugs into holes in a board, just like something out of the 1940s movie. Now the entire
federal government is online, from the White House to the Senate and the House of Representatives to the judiciary. Did you ever wonder why these days, everyone from your grandparents to the your banker and the grocery store bag boy seems to know about the Internet and World Wide Web? Well, I think it's largely because Uncle Sam finally got interested in cyberspace. So the first few chapters of <i>Modem Nation</i>  concentrate on the current scene in online politicking, how the computer played its part in the GOP primaries earlier this year to how to log into the campaign headquarters in the Clinton-Dole showdown this fall.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

But then the book moves beyond the current election?


<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

 Oh yes. By chapter 4, we've moved on to covering the hundreds of Web sites devoted to all those hotly contested special interests that predate the campaign and will still be hot long after the election, from animal rights and free speech to abortion, the environment, feminism, gun control. You name it. The list goes on and on. These are some of the liveliest sites on the Net. It's one of my favorite parts of the book.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> 

 Then what?
     
<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

After that, the focus shifts again to what I call "cybercivics data tools" for getting information out of the newly wired federal government. It shows you how to use the Net to track federal legislation, get copies of Supreme Court decisions, texts of speeches and other documents. ... Did you know you can even find a job through the Net? The new Labor Department site has hundreds of thousands of job openings across the country listed in a searchable database. I think this gives a whole new meaning to "empowerment."
 
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

So, really the book isn't just about politics?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

  That's right. In fact, my editor at Random House, Tracy Smith, made an important last-minute change in the cover of the book. Our original subtitle for <i>Modem Nation</i>  was "The Handbook of Grassroots American Politics Online." However, the more she and I worked together polishing the manuscript, the more we realized that the topic was broader than politics. At the last minute, she ordered up a new cover with the new subtitle of, "The Handbook of Grassroots Activism Online."

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>

You think the switch from "American Politics" to "Activism" in the subtitle is significant?

<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>

  I do. I think many people who wouldn't label themselves as "political" are activists for issues and causes that move them. And I think activism is what the Web is to many people: intensely focused specific interests.

<P>

<font size=5>q.</font> Are we talking about a new kind of politics here, something outside the traditional "liberal" and "conservative" labels?
<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>Could be. It's awfully early in the game to try make a call like that, of course, but I think it's certain that the narrow-casting of the "Modemocracy," if you will, will have to be addressed in some way by the politicians who are used to talking to the nation on the big stage of broadcasting. The Net doesn't have a big stage, so if they want to talk to us, they going to have to come down into the special-interest Net neighborhoods
where we hang out.
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>But is the Net really all that interested in politics? A cynic might say the Web is really only interested in commerce, in buying and selling things?
<P>

<font size=5>a.</font> Again, I think we miss the big picture if we don't broaden our terms. I've got a whole chapter in the book devoted to what I call the "little-P politics" of consumerism. Self- interest, self-preservation is a driving force in all societies, online and off, and on the Web -- oh my! Self-interest just may the veritable energy source that powers the Web. But I don't think it's only the gimme-gimme-gimme of rampant commercialism. The same instincts also have fueled the Web's remarkable interests in consumer protection, product and service reviews and anti-fraud efforts.
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>Ah, but the Net also PRODUCES its own share of fraud, doesn't it?
<P>

<font size=5>a.</font> Oh, well, yes, and that's not the half of it! The <i>Modem Nation</i>  story is nowhere near finished because there are some truly mind-numbing challenges lying ahead for the Net. I wrap up the book with a section called "Web of Wonder, Web of Woe" that talks about some of the Net nightmares that keep waking me up, from fraud to child pornography to online bomb-making instructions. But, I tell you -- I also worry about over-zealous governments, in the name of protecting us from ourselves, trying to lower that big hammer of censorship. Repression is not the answer.
<P>

<font size=5>q.</font>So what is? What's your solution?
<P>

<font size=5>a.</font>Ah, well... I wish I could say I've come up with Bowen's Fool-Proof Plan and that I'm selling it between paper covers for $20 a copy. But I've not. However, I DO hope that we can at least persuade the would-be "regulators" of the Net to see the value in allowing cyberspace to evolve in its own way and at its own pace as much as possible. One of my heroes, the late historian Will Durant, spent most of his life thinking about what goes into the making of civilizations. He wrote, "Custom rises out of the people, whereas law is forced upon them from above. Law is usually a decree of the master, but custom is the natural selection of those modes of action that have been found most convenient in the experience of the group."
    I think we might  see new customs arise online that shape our society in the next century. It's fascinating, and frightening, and awe-inspiring -- and we all have great seats for the show.


<P>

<HR><BR>

