<html>

<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / citizenry / trademark symposium: ari goldberger</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/citizenry.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoc.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br><p>
<img src="rhino1.gif" align=left width=231 height=146 ALIGN=left ALT="">

<font size = 5><I>Esquire</I>, <br>
"the magazine for men" vs. 
ESQ.wire,<br>
 "the firm away from firm."</font>

<br clear=all>
<img src="rhino2.gif" align=left width=128 height=143 ALIGN=left ALT="">




   My Internet domain name, ESQwire and my pending trademark registration for ESQ.wire are the subject of a frivolous assault by a big-shot magazine publisher.  My nemesis is the Hearst Corporation, which claims to be the world's largest publisher of monthly magazines, including <I>Esquire Magazine.</I>   In a seven-count Complaint filed on May 15 with the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, Hearst alleges that the domain name for my cyberspace law "firm away from firm" infringes on the mark for its magazine for men and its trademark for the abbreviation ESQ., which it puts on watches, eyeglasses, and other items.  
<P>
<blockquote>
	ESQ.wire is an electronic law firm infrastructure  with a mission to provide attorneys with information, products and services via computer to enable them to practice law anywhere in the world with the click of a mouse.  Hearst first learned of  the word ESQ.WIRE when its attorneys spied my mark in the June 1995 edition of the Trademark Office's Official Gazette, where it was published as a pending service mark registration.   In the sixty years that <I>Esquire Magazine </I>had been in existence, neither Hearst, nor its predecessors, had ever thought of using the word "wire" in connection with <I>Esquire.</I>

 <P>	You might be thinking to yourself that Hearst has a pretty weak case for one or more of the following reasons: the marks are spelled differently; they are about different things; Esquire and Esq. are titles normally associated with lawyers; Esquire and Esq. are common words that exist in the dictionary.  Hearst does have a weak case for these and more reasons.   
 <P>	Almost forty years ago, a federal court said the following about the Esquire trademark in a case filed by a previous owner of  <I>Esquire Magazine:</I>
<P> <BLOCKQUOTE>'The word "Esquire" may not be capable of precise definition.  See Websters New Int'l Dictionary, 2d Ed.  But the fact remains that it is not a coined word but one firmly established in the English  vocabulary that has by no means become obsolete. . . We do not think a trader can pluck a word with favorable connotations for his goods or services out of the general vocabulary and appropriate it to his own use no matter how much effort and money he may expend in the attempt.'</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p> 
 Esquire, Inc. v. Esquire Slipper Mfg. Co., 243 F.2d 540, 543 (1st Cir. 1957). 
  <P>  This case has been cited as precedent by several courts throughout the nation for the basic proposition that common word trademarks are not entitled to protection outside their fields of operation.
   <P> So what gives Hearst the right to challenge ESQ.WIRE and ESQWIRE -- obvious different marks from Hearst's in an obvious different field?  Nothing.  But Hearst's case is not about rights, it is about corporate greed and power.  The power to hire lawyers to make frivolous and disingenuous claims in an attempt to satiate the greed of the Hearst Corporation.  
   <P> Hearst's case is not really about how ESQ.wire or ESQwire adversely impact on its marks, it is about Hearst's scheme to steal my intellectual property creation. The day before Hearst filed its Complaint, the corporate copycat filed applications to register ESQWIRE, ESQ.WIRE, ESQWIRED and ESQ.WIRED for computer-related fields for which it had never used ESQUIRE and ESQ.  Hearst wants my name and thinks that it can bully me with litigation to get it from me. 
<P>    Many people in my situation might simply give in because they cannot afford the legal fees.  But Hearst has met its match with me because I am an attorney, representing myself, and can afford to fight the pesky publisher every step of the way.  For starters, I have filed a motion to dismiss Hearst's case.  I also intend to file a motion against Hearst seeking sanctions for its frivolous behavior.  I hope that my victory in this litigation will help others similarly situated. 
<p>
<hr>
<blockquote>

<i> Ari Goldberger is an attorney with the Philadelphia law firm of Pepper, Hamilton & Scheetz.  More information on ESQ.wire and the lawsuit can be found at the Esq.wire site: <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="http://www.esqwire.com">http://www.esqwire.com</A>.  Mr. Goldberger's e-mail address is <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:ag@esqwire.com">ag@esqwire.com</A>.
</i> 	 
 <P>
 </blockquote>	
<hr>

