<html>

<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / citizenry / trademark symposium: paul overhauser</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/citizenry.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoc.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<P><H2>imposters on the internet!</H2>
<blockquote>
<img src="imp.gif" width=130 height=197 ALIGN=right ALT="">

<P>Has your company ever suffered from an identity crisis?  It's easy to have one on the Internet.  Whether your company has established a web site, or just thinking about doing so, one of the first things you need to do is register an Internet domain name.  The Internet has become an essential medium for soliciting customers and conducting business. 

<p>
 The Web is a &quot;great equalizer&quot; for small and medium size businesses, because everyone is given the same space within which to attract potential customers (this space being the size of the customers computer monitor).  However, this equality is bought at the price of product and service overload.  When so many are vying for attention, it is important to identify yourself so customers can find you and your products easily.  In the &quot;real world&quot; you do this with your trademark.  On the Internet, you do this with your domain name.</P>

<P> &quot;mcs.com&quot;, &quot;oreocookie.com&quot; and &quot;microsoft.com&quot; are all domain names.  

<p>
Each domain name actually consists of two parts separated by a period, an identifying prefix (&quot;mcs&quot;, &quot;oreocookie&quot; and &quot;microsoft&quot;) and the &#147;top-level domain&#148; (&quot;com&quot;).  Currently there are six top-level domains: &quot;com&quot; for commercial sites, &quot;edu&quot; for educational institutions, &quot;gov&quot; for U.S. Governmental institutions, &quot;mil&quot; for military agencies, &quot;org&quot; for non-profit organizations, and &quot;net&quot; for administration of other networks.  Domain names work much like descriptive street addresses.  Each computer linked to the Internet is given a unique address called an IP (Internet Protocol) address which consists of a long string of numbers (which looks something like <I>128.161.71.26</I>).  However, because humans don't think like computers, this string of numbers is usually identified with a more memorable string of characters called a domain name.  This one to one relationship is stored in a database called a domain name server.  When someone accesses your web page or emails you a message using your domain name, the domain name server is used to translate that domain name from the easy to remember series of characters into the numbers a computer can understand.</P>

<P> But why should you bother with a domain name?  Well, for one thing, it allows you to personalize your Internet presence.  Your email address becomes: <I>you@yourdomainname.com</I>.  Your web address becomes:  <I>http://www.yourdomainname.com</I>. You can use a domain name to describe your company (as Apple Computers does with &quot;apple.com&quot;), your product (as Paramount Pictures does with &quot;mission-impossible.com&quot; or as Nabisco does with &quot;oreocookie.com&quot;), or your favorite breakfast (&quot;hotcereal.com&quot;, also registered by Nabisco). 

<p>
 A domain name gives you the same name recognition you enjoy in the real world, which is very important in a medium in which everyone, from AT&amp;T to your uncle Ed, can set up shop quickly and easily.  The thing to keep in mind however, is that you aren't guaranteed registration of your company or product name as an Internet domain name, even if you have trademark rights to those names in the real world. 
To see
 why this is so, we must delve into the process of allocation of domain names a bit more deeply.</P>

<img src="internic.gif" width=141 height=72 ALIGN=left ALT="">
<P> In 1993, the InterNIC (the Internet Network Information Center) was created as the center for registration of domain names that fall under the &quot;edu&quot;, &quot;gov&quot;, &quot;net&quot;, &quot;org&quot; and &quot;com&quot; top-level domains.  

Before November 23, 1995, anyone wanting to register a domain name simply submitted their request to the InterNIC.  After the InterNIC ran a check of their database to make sure that no exact match of the name existed, registration of the domain name would be allowed.  That was it.  No precautions were taken to insure that the name registered in any way 'belonged' (as a trademark for instance) to the person, or entity, registering it.  Registration was done on a first-come/first-served basis.  

<p>
<img src="mci3.gif" width=241 height=84 ALIGN=right ALT="">
The InterNIC simply lacked the manpower and resources to do an extensive trademark search for each name submitted.  Unfortunately, this open registration policy lent
 itself readily to abuse. 

 Parties began to register the names of their competitors.  For example, Princeton Review (a standardized testing tutorial service),  registered the name of their principle rival, 'kaplan.com'. SPRINT registered 'mci.com'.  A few enterprising individuals also recognized the opportunity provided by the lax registration measures of the InterNIC and began registering as many famous names as possible with the intention of charging the rightful owners for their as
signment.
  Marks such as 'hertz.com', 'nasdaq.com', 'viacom.com', and 'coke.com' were all initially registered by people unaffiliated with the respective corporations. As an experiment, Joshua Quittner, a Time magazine journalist, successfully registered 'mcdonalds.com' (detailed in Wired Magazine's October, 1994 issue).  Mr. Quittner even gave himself the username &#147;ronald,&#148; so his e-mail address was &#147;ronald@mcdonalds.com.&#148;</P>

<P> InterNIC policy has since changed, mainly in response to the increased number of lawsuits about ownership of domain names.  Now, to register a name, you must a) state that you have the right to use the name and that this right does not infringe upon the right of any other party, b) state that you intend to use the name lawfully, and on a regular basis, c) agree to indemnify InterNIC and related organizations for any claims relating to use of the name and d) agree to a dispute resolution process.  While this policy change certainly makes it more difficult for unaffiliated 'name-pirates' to register well known company names, it does not eliminate all potential domain name disputes.</P>

<P> On the Internet, each domain name MUST be unique.  In trademark law, the same, or a similar name may be used by two separate registrants, as long as the name is not used for similarly confusing products or services.  So, for example, there can be an &quot;Apple Computer&quot; and &quot;Apple Dry Cleaners&quot; and an &quot;Apple Restaurant.&quot;  But on the Internet, since each domain name is identified with a unique computer address, there can be only ONE 'apple.com'.  Even though similar or identical names can be trademarked and co-exist peacefully in the real world, there can be only one successful registrant of a domain name.  So how do the courts resolve the question of who has the greatest right to a domain name?  Most likely, the domain name will be awarded to the first person to register it.  Several legitimate claims probably exist for each possible domain name.  If you want to make sure that Internet users think of your product when they see the words 'lugnut.com' (actually not registered) then it is in your best interest to register that domain is soon as possible.  </P>

<P> So if you are ever planning to solicit customers
 or do business on the Internet, register a domain name
 for your company or product as soon as you can. 
 It's probably a good idea at the very least to register
 your company name as a domain name even if you have no 
Internet expansion plans.  After all, you don't want a 
similar named company benefitting on the Web from your 
good name in the real world.  Registration is both cheap 
and easy.  The initial fee for registration is $50, and 
maintenance is $100 a year.  Although a domain name need 
not be a name that is already a registered trademark, it 
is often a good idea to use a name to which you already 
have an existing legal right.  Registering a name that
 you have already trademarked will give you a better chance 
of winning a domain name dispute if your right to the domain
 name is ever challenged.  Even though the InterNIC requires
 actual USE of the name, it doesn't take much effort or 
expense to set up a very bare-bones web site (consisting for example, simple of your company name and address and perhaps the ubiquitous web signature: &quot;Under Construction&quot;) as a kind of place holder.  Most Internet Service Providers will take care of the registration process for you as part of their Business Services.  Check with your local service provider for details.  For more information on domain name registration and the InterNIC, point your web browser to <B><a href="http://rs0.internic.net/rs-internic.html">http://rs0.internic.net/rs-internic.html</a></B> or send email to <a href="mailto:question@internic.net">question@internic.net</a>. </P>
</blockquote>
<p><hr>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><EM><P>Paul B. Overhauser is an attorney with Ice Miller Donadio &amp; Ryan, Indianapolis, IN, and chairs its Advanced Technology Service Group.  He can be reached at <a href="mailto:paul@imdr.com">paul@imdr.com</a> or (317) 236-2469.   Mr. Overhauser appreciates the assistance of Jamie R. Betley in preparing this article.</P>
<P></P></EM></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>

