<html>
<head>
<title>george jr. / september 1996 / departments / ask kitty</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/september/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
<H2>ask kitty</H2>

    Our life-advice columnist has just returned from Prague where she was helping someone battle through the maze of conscious identity, willed identity, unconscious identity, familial identity, identity as perceived by others, temporal  and geographic identity; and the generic identities of class, race, peer, professional, linguistic and national identities.
   You got a question, bub?
    It'll be a piece of cake. Send your questions to<A HREF="MAILTO:missy@coil.com"> ask kitty</A>.
<BR>
<hr>
<BR>


<font size=+3>q.</font>I'm getting married.  I want a bridal party but don't want my friends to have to buy stupid  dresses  they'll only wear once.  Is it bad form to ask them all to wear little black dresses?   That's my choice.<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Then go for it.  If you want to have some autonomy in your married life, now's the time to start.  If you let your worries about what everyone will think determine how you plan this public celebration of your love for each other -- not to mention what will probably be the biggest (if not only) party you will throw in your adult life -- then look out when your married relationship starts to define itself. 
<p>
It's hard enough to understand who you are with another person without having to look through all the veils of the expectations of outsiders.  And besides, if you are happy with the way your celebration of commitment goes, others will be glad to be a part of your joy.  And your friends will thank you for not making them pay gobs of money to look silly. 

 <P>
<font size=+3>q.</font> I'm right and the world's wrong; why should I be polite with fools?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>Be polite to everyone, lest you be found out the fool.
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font> How much fat is in a Big Mac?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>If you need to ask, you probably don't want to know.
<P>
<font size=+3>q.</font> How do I tell a co-worker that it would be good for morale if he'd only shower?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>Don't.
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font>I've been too busy all my life for books, and now know I've missed some things.  With what books would you start?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>It depends on what you want.  If you want to impress your friends and colleagues (or yourself, for that matter), you can pick up lists of what this person or that thinks is "important" to have read, then plow through the lists, book after book.  But if you want to experience the joy that reading books can give you, the main thing is to like reading.  Like sports?  Read sports books.  Mysteries?  Go for it. 
<P>

Let reading transport you to places and times and realms of being you never thought possible.  Every time you pick up a book, let it be like a little vacation.  When you get the hang of it, try reading some of the books you were supposed to read for school, but only got through <I>Cliffs Notes</I>.  You will be surprised at what a good read <I>The Scarlet Lette</I>r is.  And when you're feeling really good about it, try it with a friend.

<p>
