<title>george jr. / september 1996 / departments / national public rodeo (week 1)</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/september/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>
<H3>'Homeboys' Launched</H3>
  "Homeboys in Outer  Space," the new half-hour science fiction comedy focusing on the inter-galactic antics of spacemen Tyberious Walker (Flex) and Morris Clay (Darryl  M. Bell), two brothers from Earth, begins production today at The Walt Disney Studios. The series premiered, August 27, and runs weekly at 8:30 P.M. (ET/PT) on UPN.
    <p> Rhona Bennett, Paulette Braxton, Kevin Michael Richardson and  "Star Trek's" James Doohan ("Scotty") in the recurring role of Pippen,  also star in this out-of-this-world comedy series, produced by Sweet Lorraine Productions in association with Touchstone Television.
    <p> The series is set in the 23rd century, where our heroes, Ty and Morris, are combing the galaxies in their Space Hoopty (a cross  between a space shuttle and a 1964 Chevrolet Impala), looking for odd jobs  and loose change.  On board their vehicle is a computer with a back-in-your-
face personality named Loquatia (Bennett).  Loquatia has a crush on Morris causing her circuit boards to melt whenever he comes near,  but she has nothing but electrical shocks for Ty.
<p>  The guys' base of operation is the Jupiter Too, a bar run by Vashti, the Vognarian
(Richardson). In addition to assorted aliens in all shapes  and  sizes,
one of their companions is the ravishing Amma (Braxton), a space
mercenary for whom no mission is impossible -- for the right price.
  

<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>Republic Pictures Debuts Web Contest</h3>
Republic Pictures announces the launch of a 12-week Internet promotion following the studio's debut of its web site (www.republic-pictures.com).  Through the web site, movie fans will have access to Republic Pictures' extensive catalogue of films, complete with endless movie facts, actor profiles, information on directors, movie synopses, reviews and much more. The deal ends Nov. 19.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>'I Can Name That Tune in Three  Clicks!'</h3>

In a deal that shows that content on  the Internet is becoming increasingly competitive with television  broadcasting, Interactive Imaginations, the New York-based New Media company behind the popular Riddler multi-player game site on the Internet (www.riddler.com), has acquired the exclusive Internet rights to the internationally popular television game show "Name That Tune."
 <p>    Interactive Imaginations purchased the exclusive Internet rights to  "Name That Tune" from the widow and daughter of Harry Salter, the show's  creator.
 <p>     Interactive Imaginations expects to launch a multi-player version of  "Name That Tune" on its Riddler Web site by year end. The Riddler site,  which  is designed as a virtual game show network, currently features multi-player crossword puzzles and trivia games, in which players compete for advertiser-sponsored prizes typically found on television game  shows.  Recent
prizes have included new cars, cruises and exotic vacations.


<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>Sesame Street Wins Folio Award</h3>

  

The seventh annual Folio Awards, announced in the August issue of Folio magazine, has named Sesame Street Parents magazine the winner in the Parenting publications category for "Editorial Excellence."  Folio, which is published by Cowles Media, gives the awards to both consumer and trade publications.
<p>     Published by the magazine group of Children's Television Workshop,  which also produces the Sesame Street television series, Sesame Street Parents  won the Folio Award for the first time in its successful 11-year history.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>>Beastly Show</h3>

  Walt Disney's "Beauty  and  the Beast: A Concert on Ice," starring two-time Olympic Gold  Medalist  Ekaterina Gordeeva in the role of Belle and Olympic Gold Medalist Victor Petrenko  as  the Beast, begins production this week at CBS Television City in  Los  Angeles.  The hour-long special, marking Gordeeva's first duet performance since the untimely death of her husband and skating partner, Sergei Grinkov,  will  air this fall on CBS.
   <p>  Inspired by the Tony Award-winning Broadway musical and the  Academy  Award- winning full-length animated feature film, "Beauty and the Beast: A  Concert  on Ice" will be hosted by James Barbour, who currently stars as the Beast  in  the Los Angeles stage production. and Susan Egan, who was nominated for  a  Tony Award for her performance as the original Belle on Broadway.
   <p>  The magical score from the feature film, written by the  Oscar  Award- winning team of Alan Menken and the late Howard Ashman and the lyrics  from  the Broadway musical written by Tim Rice, will be performed by Egan and  members  of the Los Angeles cast including Barbour, Gary Beach ("Lumiere"),  Gibby  Brand ("Cogsworth"), Mari Jo Catlett ("Wardrobe"), John Dewar  ("Monsieur  D'Arque"), Heather Lee ("Babette"), Jeanne Lehman ("Mrs. Potts"), Aaron  Lipin  ("Chip"),
Michael Piontek ("Gaston") and Jamie Torcellini ("La Fou").
     

<HR><BR>

