<head>

<title>george jr. / september 1996 / departments / national public rodeo (week 1)</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/september/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<H3>Playboy Will See Red</H3>
Playboy Entertainment Group, Inc. and Zalman King Entertainment Inc. have concluded a  far-
reaching motion picture and television co-production agreement,  which includes co-financing, with Showtime Networks Inc., 18 additional episodes of the acclaimed series, "Red Shoe Diaries."
    <p>  Playboy and King have agreed on a motion picture co-production arrangement for up to ten films over the next three years.  The  first film, to be produced and directed by Zalman King, is currently in preproduction.
    <p> In addition, Playboy will assume international distribution  rights to 48 completed episodes of the "Red Shoe Diaries" series, which  airs domestically on Showtime.  This brings to 66 the total number of episodes that Showtime will air in the U.S. and distribute domestically and in Canada, and Playboy will distribute internationally.
   <p>

<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>Chris and Matt Hit the Road</h3>
Chris Farley and Matthew  Perry  will star in "Edwards and Hunt: The First American Road Trip," a comedy  about a mismatched pair of 19th c. frontiersmen who lead a bumbling  expedition on the ultimate race to explore the wild West.  Principal  photography began recently in northern California on this Turner Pictures Production directed by Christopher Guest and produced by Denise Di  Novi. Written by Mark Nutter, Tom Wolfe and Boyd Hale, the film also  stars
Eugene Levy, Bokeem Woodbine, Lisa B. and Parker Posey.
<p>
     Americans celebrate the intrepid explorers Lewis & Clark, but  how many remember their rivals Edwards and Hunt? Now for the  first  time, the unwritten history of these boldly incompetent patriots can be  told as Edwards and Hunt battle animals, Indians and the elements in a hilarious struggle to become the first American explorers to map a  route to the Pacific Ocean.
<p>
     Unprepared and ill equipped to embark on this voyage, they are  aided by a rag-tag entourage including:  Guy Fontenot (Eugene Levy), a Frenchman with a fluent mastery of indigenous languages he can  never seem to understand; Shaquinna (Lisa B.), his beautiful Native  American
traveling partner; as well as an unruly assortment of colorful  misfits. "Edwards and Hunt: The First American Road Trip" is produced by Denise Di Novi whose numerous credits include "Batman Returns" and "Little Women."
<p>
       A tall tale about forgotten lore, chivalry, and how the West was lost, "Edwards and Hunt: The First American Roadtrip" will be released nationwide by New Line Cinema in 1997. 

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>'Shut Up Bitch'</h3>

 First seen in 1993 in Vancouver, Canada, "Shut Up Bitch" proved to be a sellout hit, with C.B.C. remarking "at  the  end  of  the  show,  people are on their feet cheering." In  the  spring  of  1996,  it  was  nominated for three (and won two) Jessie Awards.  This  comedy by Michelle Porter explores the silencing of women throughout his-story and uses song and humor to provoke laughter and thought.  It gallivants through historical times while pointing  a  satirical  finger  at  our  own cultural biases. <b>george jr.</b>'s first field trip, in which we loaded a bus with 43 people and headed to West Hollywood, took it in and ate it up.


<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>Turner Gets Good-Guy Award</h3>

  The USA  Network's "Erase the Hate Campaign" that has helped kids and adults combat violence by non-violent means, and the Ted Turner organization's on- going $40 million project that communicates true stories and  histories of Native America through TNT movies, TBS documentaries, CNN news specials, Turner Publishing books, Turner Home Entertainment videos and Turner Education Services, have been voted the Academy of Television Arts & Sciences (ATAS) coveted 1996 Governors Award by the ATAS  Board.
 <p>
   Academy President Richard H. Frank will present the Governors Award Emmy statuettes to  executives of both cable networks  Sept. 7, during, the non- televised Creative Arts portion of the "48th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards" to take place at a black-tie ceremony in Sexson Auditorium on the campus of Pasadena City College, followed by a banquet in the  nearby
<p>
Pasadena Civic Exhibition Hall.
<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3> James Thurber Rides Again</h3>

New Line Cinema and the  Samuel Goldwyn Company have entered into a three-year co-development and production venture which includes the rights to remake the  perennial
<p>Goldwyn Company classic "The Secret Life of Walter Mitty," it was announced by Michael De Luca, President and Chief Operating Officer of New Line Productions, and Samuel Goldwyn, Jr., Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of the Samuel Goldwyn Company.
   <p>  As part of the pact, New Line and Goldwyn will immediately  begin developing "The Secret Life of Walter Mitty," the James Thurber  classic which originally starred Danny Kaye. Goldwyn Jr. will produce  with  John Bard Manulis, Goldwyn's President of Production serving as  executive
producer. New Line will handle worldwide distribution on  Mitty,  with future films from the partnership determined on a  picture-by-picture basis.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>MGM Has Rights to 'Julip'</h3>

 Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer has acquired the rights to the provocatively offbeat comedy "JULIP,' based  on  the novella by award-winning novelist Jim Harrison. The screenplay is  being written by <b>george jr.'</b>s old friend Kevin Falls.
  <p>   "JULIP" is the story of a beautiful and bohemian young woman who works as a dog trainer, but has an equally commanding effect on the  men in her life.
   <p> Its British-born directo,r Jon Amiel, most recently helmed the  suspense thriller "Copycat," starring Sigourney Weaver and Holly Hunter.  He  is currently in preparation on the screwball comedy "Watch That Man,"  to film in England. He previously directed the period  drama  "Sommersby," starring Richard Gere and Jodie Foster.  Amiel first came to international attention for his work on the acclaimed BBC series  "The Singing Detective." He made his feature film directorial  debut  on "Queen of Hearts," which opened at the Cannes Film Festival and was
named Best First Film at the Montreal Film Festival.
   <p>  Jim Harrison wrote several works that  have been adapted into successful films, including "Legends of the Fall"  and "Wolf." His other books include "The Theory and Practice of  Rivers  and
Other Poems" and "The Woman Lit by Fireflies."

<HR><BR>

