<br><br>
<H3>Microsoft Went Hollywood</H3>
    Hollywood Online Links With Microsoft  Hollywood Online(TM) Inc. has entered an agreement with Microsoft Corp. to develop exclusive entertainment multimedia content for users of the  Microsoft(R) Internet Explorer 3.0 Web browser. The "Explore Hollywood" area  of  Hollywood
Online's Web site (www.hollywood.com) will utilize Microsoft  ActiveX(TM) controls to provide some or the most dynamic multimedia content available  on the Web.
  <p>   The official launch of Internet Explorer 3.0 was August 13, 1996 at 6  a.m. Pacific Time. Hollywood Online is one of a select group  of  high-profile companies that provide free content offers for ActiveX.  Additionally,  there are more than 20 new "Activated" Web Sites which will feature ActiveX technologies.
  <p>    Game Zone and Explore Backstage will be accessible only to visitors  using the Internet Explorer 3.0 browser; while Premieres and Explorer Sites will  be available to all Web users.  Promotions will be available to users of Internet Explorer 3.0 via the Web and to users of other browsers through a mail-in program.  Hollywood Online will allow users to immediately download the Internet Explorer 3.0 Browser software.
     <p> Following its recent acquisition by Times Mirror, Hollywood Online  has launched a Hollywood News and Reviews section on www.hollywood.com with daily entertainment news, box office/ratings/sales charts as well as movie, television and music reviews.  As the most widely distributed online entertainment site, Hollywood Online has an audience of more than 20  million
consumers worldwide on the Internet via its popular Web site at www.hollywood.com and on leading online services such as America Online; CompuServe; MSN(TM), The Microsoft Network; Prodigy and Japan's  NIFTY-Serve.


<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>HarperEdge Logs On</h3>
    HarperEdge is a major new publishing imprint which will produce books on the impact that digital technology is having on society and culture.
 <p>   HarperCollins is the first major book publisher to devote an entire  imprint to books like this; i.e., books which fuse technology and life. The imprint  will be a real test case of the potential for this kind of book to win over a major audience. The imprint also is interesting in that it follows on the heels of Wired magazine's launch of its book imprint, Hardwired.
  <p> HarperEdge's inaugural list includes Timothy Leary's final book DESIGN FOR DYING, Michael   Dertouzos' WHAT WILL BE,  Jeffrey Zaleski's THE  SOUL  OF  CYBERSPACE  and DATA SMOG by David Shenk.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Ellen Considers Becoming Interesting</h3>

 Production has begun on the fourth season of the hit comedy, "Ellen," starring award-winning  Ellen DeGeneres in her namesake role. The series, which airs Wednesdays at  8:00  PM (ET/PT) an ABC, first premiered March 29, 1994 and, in its first three seasons, was a consistent winner of its timeslot.
   <p>   "It's time Ellen Morgan finds out who Ellen Morgan is," says DeGeneres  of the upcoming season.  "She's going to grow up and re-examine what is important to her."
   <p>  Ellen makes a move that surprises everyone when she seeks out a new Southern California dwelling and puts her bookstore up on the market, and <b>george jr.</b> is interested in buying it.  Feeling the direct effects of Ellen's personal temblor are her friends Paige  (Fisher) and Audrey (Lewis) but especially Joe (Higgins) and Spence (Piven), who  stand to lose their job and apartment, respectively. Gosh. We're really, really excited.
  

<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>F Musicfest To Be Held October 3-5 </h3>

  
Heralding the ninth  anniversary of its annual music convention, Concrete Marketing has announced  an expanded format for the upcoming 1996 confab.  Concrete's  Foundations
Forum (well known by its informal title, the "Concrete  Convention") will present, along with its usual events, a showcase of over  150  bands in 15 venues. The newly christened F Musicfest is scheduled  to  take place October 3, 4, and 5 in Hollywood.
  <p>   The  expanded 1996 format will make the F  Musicfest  the first music event of its scope ever held in Los Angeles.
  <p>   Featuring showcases by signed and unsigned artists from  across  the country (three times as many performances as in previous years),  the forum will encompass all genres of rock music, including  aggressive post-modern rock, cutting-edge trip hop, grass roots pop -- and,  of
course, plenty of hard-hitting music for which Concrete  is  justifiably famous.
    <p> Reflecting the F Musicfest's diversity, Concrete has  enlisted  L.A.'s renowned Goldenvoice to promote showcases in a variety of venues, including The Roxy, The Whiskey, The Palace, The Troubadour, Jack's Sugar Shack, The Coconut Teaszer, The Union, Post 43, Moguls,  Billboard  Live,
The Viper Room, The Dragonfly, Martini Lounge, Hell's Gate and  the American Legion Hall. Once again, Concrete has joined  forces  with  Kevin Lyman Productions (well known for his work with Lollapalooza and  the Warped tours) for his invaluable production expertise.
    <p> With its numerous artists and venues, the 1996 F Musicfest  will  be the first city-wide music event to be held in the  recording  industry's Los Angeles home turf. Other U.S. cities have  presented  well-known events -- e.g. New York City's New Music Seminar and the annual  South  By Southwest convention in Austin, TX -- but until now, Los Angeles  has never hosted a musical convention of this size and breadth.


<HR><BR>

