<head>
<title>george jr. / october 1996 / features / opening gambit</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/october/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<img src="/graphics/gambit.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=15 ALT="">
<br>

<B>Welcome!</B><br>
       . . .  to the October issue of <B>george jr.</B>, the internet monthly that is not Halley's Comet, not the color orange, not the idea blue. Neither are we a pumpkin pie, nor <I>George Magazine</I>, nor <B>George C. Scott</B>, nor a building with a beanie propeller on top. We are not<B> George Bush</B>, nor are we <B>Boy George.</B>
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
   We are the literary monthly named after me - that would be george jr.  - and are we ever so glad to bring you another digitized serving of fiction, interviews with authors (<B>Rafael Yglesias</B> and  <B>Carol Anshaw</B>) , Web and entertainment news (updated each Sunday in National Public Rodeo), advice in the call-and-response of Ask Kitty, all things weighted and measured in weights & measures, and several wordy things in the joy of lex.
<P>
   You're about to meet artist <B>Linda Leviton</B>, writers <B>Stanley Crawford </B>and <B>Lynne Sharon Schwartz</B>; and we tip our muskrat-lined derby  to <B>george jr</B>. correspondents<B> Nicholas</B>  'The Keyboard' <B>Basbanes</B> and this month's over-the-transom contributor <B>Joseph</B> 'Shotgun'  <B>Blankenship.</B>
<p>

<B>Catching up</B><br>
    Since  last we met here on this editor's page, the official Web site of the 32nd <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A href="http://www.planetchess.com/">World Chess Olympiad</A> opened  (sooner or later we had to refer to chess, don't you think?), Saga Furs of Scandinavia says People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (speaking of our embalmed muskrat) dropped its lawsuit against Saga, the world's largest fur marketeers; and A&M Records<B> Chairman Cafaro</B> responded to Wal-Mart's decision to not stock the Sheryl Crow's self-titled second album, <B>Sheryl Crow</B>. (How dare she use her name!)
<P>       "Sheryl has my complete and total support," said A&M's chairman.  "In their decision not to carry Sheryl Crow's latest release, Wal-Mart is choosing  guns over music.  Sheryl Crow's song, <I>Love Is A Good Thing</I>, is a cautionary tale. Everyday in America, children are dying by guns bought legally. This  is  a fact.  What is an appropriate response to this fact?  Where does our responsibility lie? Sheryl's responsibility as an artist is to  reveal  the truth, and it is our responsibility as a record company to defend her  ability to do so. Wal-Mart has no apparent interest in discussing  such  things.  They choose to preempt the dialogue by banning music which may provoke a discussion."
 <p>

<B>Urgent updates</B>
<br>        Also since we last met,  the Macarena died having been bumped  off byThe Miller Tongoneo,  matching hip-swinging moves to the song <I> El Tongoneo.</I> The song is from the Latino  group Mestizzo that  made<I> La Macarena</I> a hit.
<p>   Of course, Mestizzo has sold out. In September it teamed up with Miller Brewing Company to promote  national dance contest to beer  drinkers "of legal drinking age at dance clubs." The group's song is officially referred to as the Miller Tongoneo. Now, shall we get on with <b>the Miller george jr.?</b>
<p>   And, since we last met, no one yet has used in a sentence the word<B> pluvial </B>(plu.vi.al \'plu:-ve--*l\ aj [L pluvialis, fr. pluvia rain, fr. fem. of pluvius rainy, fr.] pluere to rain - more at FLOW 1a: of or relating to rain 1b: characterized by abundant rain of a geologic change  2: resulting from the action of rain), which we find a darn dry shame.
<p>    We've studied the planet for a month, looking high and low for rain,  and found that, yes, it's true,  New York would not have encountered modern art when it did had it not been for the caricatures of a Mexican artist and writer named<B> Marius de Zayas</B> (1880-1961).
<p>   We found, too,  that  the Broadcast Information Bureau  finally has its 1996-97 <I>Interactive Sourcebook </I> available. The new reference CD-ROM,  produced with the Interactive Services Association, lists 6,237 Internet and interactive media executives at 4,690 companies throughout North America. According to  <I>Sourcebook</I>  publisher <B>Ned Borowsky</B>, the ROM will save its users hours of research  and runaround time.
<p>    "Click and connect is how we describe it," says Borowsky, almost echoing <B>E.M.  Forster</B>. "With  just  a couple of clicks of a mouse, the Source book CD-ROM gives our customers  every name, address, phone and fax number they want in seconds." So much for this oddly placed, seemingly commercial plug.
<p>

<B>The  boulevardiers</B>
 <br>   Mythologies have continued to spring up around <B>Stephen King</B>,  who in the last half-minute published 623 novels, 68 books of other sorts and who just sold, only yesterday, 87 million copies of his books. Myths spring up around every wildly successful writer, just as they did around <B>Robert Johnson</B>.
   <p> Mythologies emerge around the unsuccessful ones, too. The only folks who get no mythologies are average folks like you, <B>Bob</B>; or you, <B>Roberta</B>, who will always have a home here with the rest of us <B>george jr.</B> boulevardiers.
<p>

<B>Hypered out</B>
<br>  On Nov. 1, Simon & Schuster will release <I>The Spot: The Book</I> based on the episodic <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A href="http://www.thespot.com">Web site</A>. What has this so-called culture come to? Well, <I>Clicking In: Hot Links to a Digital Culture</I> (Bay Press), with <B>John Perry Barlow, Sherry Turkle, Sandy Stone</B> and others, for another. And the superior <I>Tolstoy's Dictaphone: Technology and the Muse</I> (Graywolf), edited by <B>Sven Birkerts</B>; and<I> HotWired</I> editor<B> Martha Baer</B>'s novel about Web love, <I> As Francesca</I>, due in January. We like books about real, non-virtual writing better, but until all of<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A href="http://www.feedmag.com/95.09guyer/95.09guyer_sample1.html"> this</A> becomes an either/or deal, we'll fairly consider the latest medium.
 <p>  Hypertext  fiction  pioneer  <B>Bobby  Rabyd</B>, meanwhile,  has extended the scope of publishing a tad with the release of <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A href="http://www.sonicnet.com/sunshine69/">Sunshine '69</A>. The Internet-based novel incorporates  text, pictures and sound to create what the author  Calls,  "a  Web-based time  machine"  that  allows the reader to explore and contribute prose to the open-ended tale.
 <p>   "No one has grasped the nature  of  this  new  thing  called  the  'Net  with  more  supple- minded alacrity than the writer  Bobby  Rabyd,"  said  <B>Robert  Coover</B>,  the  noted  hypertext proponent and English professor at Brown University, who  served  as  editor  for  the  work.
 <p>  Ah, alacrity: That's so much who <B>george jr.</B> is that we've named this month's issue the cheerful readiness issue.
    <p>

   We're game for this and so much more. Are we in cahoots?
   Have fun.

</blockquote>   
<P>
