<head>
<title>george jr. / october 1996 / features / q & a / carol anshaw</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/october/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>


<H2>q&a</H2> 

<h3>carol anshaw:  making her move</h3>

<P>

<IMG SRC="/october/anshaw.jpg" WIDTH=110 HEIGHT=168 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<br>
  Carol Anshaw's career kicked into gear with the publication four years ago of <i>Aquamarine</i>, which won the Carl Sandburg Award and the Society of Midland Authors Book Award. Houghton Mifflin hopes to follow that success with its publication of Anshaw's  latest novel, <i>Seven Moves</i> ($21.95) , a psychological thriller in which a therapist wakens one morning and finds her paramour mysteriously gone.
   The interview:
<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>
<blockquote>
<font size=5>q. </font> Your last novel, <I>Aquamarine,</I> featured an unusual construction - giving a single character three parallel lives.  Does  <I>Seven Moves</I> also
bend the form in some way?
<br><font size=5>a.  </font>No, I wanted to work with a straightforward narrative this time.  I'd become interested in novels that were both serious fiction and at the same time compelling stories - a rare species, the literary page-turner, and I wanted to try my hand at creating one.
   Also, I'd seen a lot of books about people who go missing, but not much about
the people they leave behind.  If someone you love suddenly disappeared, this
would, I think, push you onto the hardest ground of your self, and I wanted to explore this constellation of event and emotion.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> So, who's your missing person?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>Her name is Taylor Heyes.  She's a travel photographer and a rather elusive character even when she is around.  But the book really focuses on her lover, Christine Snow.  The two women have been together four years.
 They share a house, a dog, a life.  Chris is a therapist with a busy private practice - mostly lesbians and gay guys, but also a small group of straight Hispanic women, who are devoted to Chris even though she's bewildered by them.
When Taylor suddenly disappears one morning, after a small domestic
disagreement, Chris is completely thrown.  She doesn't know what to feel - anger, fear, rejection?  Has her partner met with some terrible fate, or simply abandoned her?  If she has left on her own, in the middle of what Chris thought was a life together they were both engaged in, what does that say about her understanding of soul or psyche?  Her confidence is shaken on personally and professionally.  If she has been so deluded about her own life, how can she presume to counsel others?
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font> Does Taylor come back?
<br>
<font size=5>a.</font> I'll duck that question, but not because the book is a mystery.  When I wrote it, I thought of it as an anti-mystery.  Taylor turning up or not becomes less important than the discoveries about her and their relationship that Chris makes, along with discoveries about herself.
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font>  Why did you make the main characters gay women?
<br>
<font size=5>a.</font>  Well, it's the world I live in, and one I feel has been under chronicled.  I tried to create a sort of panoramic view of contemporary, urban lesbian life - show how we're very much like straight people, and also quite different.
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font>  Is the book autobiographical then?
<br><font size=5>a.</font>  Not really.  I think I'd try memoir if I wanted to write about my own life.  But all novelists bring into their work the world as they see it, people as they've overheard them, notions that intrigue them.  By setting the book in Chicago, in my own milieu, and addressing issues of intimacy, isolation and loss that have come up in my own life, I feel more vulnerable and exposed with this book than with Aquamarine, in which I created a protagonist quite unlike myself living lives very different from my own.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> How long did it take you to write <I>Seven Moves</I>?
<br><font size=5>a. </font> About three years, but I can't write all the time.  Sometimes I get questions like "Do you write in the mornings or the afternoons?"  Which seems to presume a much more orderly life than mine.  The truth is I write whenever I can between the thousand things I have to do to buy the time to write.
    I get the impression a lot of people think novelists live on huge advances easy-to-get grants and nutritious canapes they take home from literary cocktail parties, when if fact most of us have to teach and/or take on a lot of prosaic writing or editing jobs.  I've edited several deadly business books, and written everything from movie and restaurant reviews, to an articles on collectors of fascinating things like barbed wire, to mock trials with fairy tale characters in the witness box, to teen vampire novels.  It's really only when I get the last stake plunged into the heart of the last Undead teenager that I can turn to my own work.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> How did you become a novelist in the first place?<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> My mother tells me I tried to write my first book when I was six, but
didn't know enough words, kept bugging her until she told me to stop and wait
until I learned more.  I came to writing through reading.  My parents weren't
educated and so had no way of guiding me.  I'd just go to the library, look
for titles I liked, bring home these stacks of books.  And since they were
novels, that's what I wanted to write.
    That's basically where I jumped in, I didn't really bother with stories, just started writing novels.  I was really in a cave by myself during this time, through my 20s.  I had little in the way of formal education, didn't know anyone who wrote fiction.  I just kept reading and writing, teaching myself as I went along.  Now that I have a
belated MFA and teach in two graduate programs (at Vermont College and the
School of the Art Institute of Chicago), I can see how these can leapfrog a
writer over a lot of the technical problems I labored with for years.  But
the solitary nature of my own development did, I think, give me a way of
writing that isn't quite like anyone else's.  That's what I gained from my
time in the wilderness.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> What are you working on now?<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> I have the beginnings of a new novel in mind, also a short story titled "The Mystery of the Jungle Airstrip," which isn't a mystery and doesn't feature either a jungle or an airstrip.
</blockquote>
<HR><BR>
