<head>
<title>george jr. / october 1996 / features / q & a / rafael yglesias</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/october/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>



<H2>q&a</H2> 

<h3>rafael yglesias: on the evil that men do</h3>

<P>
<IMG SRC="/october/drneruda.jpg" WIDTH=120 HEIGHT=176 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

  Novelist Rafael Yglesias dropped out of high school and wrote his first novel, <I>Hide Fox, And All After</I> (1972) at age 16. Since then, he's published seven more novels, including Fearless (1993) and his latest, <I>Dr. Neruda's Cure for Evil,</I> which has been optioned by 20th Century Fox.
  He has lived in New York City all his life, and comes from a family of writers. His father, Jose, who died last year, published 11 books; his mother, Helen, six; his half brother, Lewis, four. His half sister, Tamar, is a playwright.
<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>

<blockquote>
<font size=5>q. </font>What  was  the  impetus  for  writing  about  a  psychiatrist  in  <I>Dr. Neruda's Cure for Evil?</I>
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>There were two. First, the  premise  of  traditional  psychotherapy,  the  "talking
cure," is  an  almost  mystical  belief  in  the  power  of  the  mind  and   imagination:
namely that  one   person,   doing   nothing   more   substantial   and   dramatic   than
listening and speaking, is able to cure  another  person  of  illness.  That's  an  excellent setting for a psychological novelist. Second, because I  wanted  to  write  about  the effect of the collapse of ideas in the 20th century  on  a  brilliant  man  for  whom the need for a philosophy is a matter of life and death.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>Ah, life and death. What kind of research did you do?
<br>
<font size=5>a.</font> I asked two therapists, one a psychologist, the other a  psychiatrist,  what  they
read in school to graduate. Eventually I  discovered  that  I  needed  to  read  more  than the basic texts, since  I  wanted  my  doctor  to  be  unusually  open-minded  about  the many schools of psychological theory. Also, since  my  novel  is  intended  to  be read as a "case history," I read case histories.  And,  of  course,  I've  also  been  in therapy.  Altogether,  three  years  of  reading  relatively impenetrable jargon was needed before I felt I could fake a psychiatrist's narration.
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font> You spend all of the book's Part One  on  Rafael's  childhood.  By doing  so,  what  are  you
saying about what a doctor brings to a patient's case?
<br>
 <font size=5>a.</font> There is no escape from the effect, of our early life on our ideas  and  actions
later on. As Neruda writes in the novel: "No one is  stronger  than or  independent
of the people and things that surround him. Ideas are objective, but  their truth is
not the glue that makes them stick to us." For better or worse, a  psychiatrist  brings  a
personality and  personal  history  into  the  room  with  a  patient.  Good  shrinks  know
it and try to compensate; bad ones think they are above it.
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font> I suppose you are sick of talking about your writing family.
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> Most novelists  are  volunteers;  I  was  drafted.  Most  writers  long  to  become
writers   and often must battle  discouraging  parents.  My  father  believed  writing was the only worthwhile endeavor.

<p>
<font size=5>q.</font> How did you learn how to write?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> By  listening  to  my  parents at dinner. I didn't truly decide - for myself - to  be  a writer,  until  well  after  I  had published my first three novels. I stopped writing novels for four years,  discovered I missed it, and resumed in my late twenties.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>You, your mother and your father were publishing books simulatneously.
<br>
<font size=5> a. </font>That  was  irritating.  Publishing  a  book is and should be an  individual  achievement.  Instead,  we  were  reviewed  and  discussed  as if we were the Flying Wallendas. The  oddity  of  our  family  achievement  distracted people from hearing our distinct voices.
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font> OK, let's go back to yours. In <I>Dr. Neruda's Cure for  Evil</I>,  you  posit  a  diagnosis  and even a  cure  for  evil. How did you come up with it?
<br>
<font size=5> a.</font> Slowly.  During  my  first  year  of  reading  psychological  theory,  it  became
obvious that good and evil create a problem for any systemized analysis of the
human  character.  Definitions  of   good   and   evil   change   dramatically   between
cultures and eras. I also  noticed  that  psychiatry  depends  on  patients  identifying
themselves as ill - either through violent or delusional  behavior - or  by  coming  into
a doctor's office to announce that they  feel  unhappy.  It  occurred  to  me  that  an
individual who wasn't violent or  unhappy - as  sociopaths,  serial  killers,  Nazis  and
so on, are - but who enjoyed hurting or manipulating others,  would  be  invisible  to  a
working psychiatrist. People  who  function  well  and  feel  "good  about  themselves"
only when they harm people, and yet the  harm  isn't  illegal  or  delusional - what  are
they? There's  no  psychological  definition  for  it.  I  decided  it  would  make  an
intriguing drama to put a  serious  psychological  theorist  face  to  face  with  this
unknown.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>How did you develop the idea of evil into the novel?
<br>
<font size=5> a.</font> By having Neruda's  treatment  of  Gene - a  technically  successful  example.  of
psychotherapy - end  in  a  catastrophe,   namely   Gene   murdering   his   wife   and
committing suicide. Such a result would be inexplicable to Neruda  and  force  him  to
investigate. Again, while researching therapy, I noticed one  of  its  oddities,  namely
that the psychiatrist (in theory) never meets the people who are so  important  to  the
patient. For a novelist this provides a fascinating narrative. First the reader  hears
about Hally and Stick solely from Gene. Then,  with  all  of  Gene's  "information,"  we
meet them again, this time through Neruda's eyes. It is  the  shock  of  his  discovery,
this journey into the "real world," that gives Neruda the clarity to come  up  with  his
diagnosis of evil.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>What else are you toiling on?<br>
 <font size=5>a.</font> I  am  adapting  <I>Dr.  Neruda's  Cure  for Evil</I>  for Amy Robinson   and   Joe
Ruben to  produce  for  20th  Century  Fox.  I  recently  adapted  Victor  Hugo's   <I>Les
Miserables</I>  (not  the  musical)  for  Mandalay  Entertainment.  Gillian Armstrong   is
signed to direct, but we're not cast yet. After that script, I plan to  write  my ninth
novel, which will be about a long and happy marriage.
</blockquote>

<HR><BR>
<a href="/october/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    
</BODY>
