<head>

<title>george jr. / october 1996 / arcadia / the uneasy chair</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/october/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoa.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<img src="/graphics/uneasy.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>
After recently watching the Eagles prevail against the favored Detroit Lions, the person of <B>george jr.</B> deployed to the front steps of his home and began repairing the broken front cement steps.
<P>
  Chip, chip. Caulk, caulk, scrape, scrape - and I was tapped on the shoulder. Surprised, because this shoulder tapper had made no sound, I wheeled and came face to face with the ghost of <B>George Washington Carver</B>, as he introduced himself to me.
<p>     'As you're likely to know,<B> Mr. george jr</B>.,'  there are  farragoes  occurring now worldwide with attorneys and bulks of paperwork and corporations and companies and subsidiaries of fame and fortune all trying to leverage their identities into every household in the world, including yours.'
<p>   'Yes,' I said. 'I know.'
<p>   'Well,' he said, 'I want you to know that you and I have something in common.'
<p>   'Is it that we both have a foot, yours more spectral than mine, in this wet cement?'
<p>   'No,' said the ghost. 'What we have in common is our names.'
<p>   'Ahh,' I said. 'The part that is George.'
<p>  'Yes, that's it,' he said. 'I'd like you to give up yours now, or I'll do something supernaturally painful to you that will rock your wallet and very home.'
<p>   Shocked into a daze, I excused myself from the ghost of the historical personage and went inside to check on the football scores.
<p>   I turned on <B>ABC</B> (or was it <B>NBC</B>?), or maybe it was <B>CBS</B>. And was shocked and alarmed to discover that each of these corporate giants had used a full third of each other's identities in their names: the letter <B>C</B>.
<p>   What was with this letter <B>C</B>?
<p>   Had no one owned it yet? Had all three owned it?
<p>   Why was the letter <B>C</B> so valuable to the United States of America's broadcasting giants that they'd risk confusion among people like me, who never until now had to wonder about who was who and who was not. That <B>C</B> must be some consonant.
<p>   I, too, began to lust for that letter of the alphabet.
<p>   I wondered what other vowels and consonants I might buy or own, in random or tandem with other words and letters, and then flipped to <I>Seinfeld</I> and came face to face with a fictional guy named 'George.'
<p>   Had the ghost of <B>George Washington Carver</B> pressured him, too? Or maybe I should, if there was something to gain by pressuring a guy to give up his name. 'Dear Producers of <I>Seinfeld</I>,' I began my letter, 'immediately quit using the name George in your show, because it's mine.' Well, not precisely mine; it's my father's. Mine, after all, is <B>george jr.</B> So I quit with the letter.
<p>   I turned off the TV and opened the magazines on my nightstand: <I>St. George Magazine</I>, followed by <I>George Realty</I>; and then ordered some funny pet dishes from a pet-novelty company  (very cool catalog) called George.
<p>   <B> George Steinbrenner Jr.</B> is a person, like me, with part of my name. I considered threatening him over his name because, like, well, you know, there was a chance that any money he's earned in his lifetime possibly might have been meant  for me. Somebody might accidentally have sent him a Christmas card, when they were thinking of me - and, come to think of it, I did get one fewer Christmas card last year.
<p>   And then, a tapping at my bedroom window.
<p>   It was the ghost of <B>George Washington Carver</B> again, staring in at me through my bedroom window.
<p>   'Give me your naaaaaaame!,' he moaned, and threatened me for the second time. I picked up my address book and began to throw it at the pane when, miraculously, the book opened to the <B>W</B> page and there, before me, was the Los Angeles address for actor <B>George Wendt</B>.
<p>    I paged rapidly through the book, and there, too, were the Houston address for <B>George Bush</B>; and still other addreses for artist <B>George Segal</B>, musician<B> George Allan Russell</B>, economist <B>George Stigler</B>, journalist <B>George Will</B>, comedian<B> George Carlin,</B> Gov. <B>George E. Pataki Jr.</B>
of the State of New York, Ohio Gov.<B> George E. Voinovich</B>, the mayor of <B>Georgetown</B>, the provost of <B>Georgetown University</B> and - lo and behold - a George for every letter of the alphabet.
   Even <B>C</B>.
<p>   There's that much-coveted letter of the alphabet again.
   And from it, I take <b>C</b>ourage.

<hr>

<br>

<a href="/october/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoa.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>


</BODY>

