<H2>gallery:   linda leviton</H2> 
<P>
 
      Mixed-media artist Linda Leviton graduated Summa Cum Laude from the  University of Cincinnati's School of Design, Art and Architecture in 1976. Now living in Columbus, Ohio, Leviton's works have been exhibited in solo and group shows at the Richmond Art Museum in Indiana, the Evansville Museum of Art in Illinois, the Artemisia and Artspace galleries in Chicago and the List visual Arts Center in Cambridge, Mass.
<p>     "Many of my pieces combine copper and brass wire, fabric and wood," she  said. "As medieval alchemists sought to transform base metal into gold, I  seek to do the same with my work."
 <p>   Using discarded materials to represent the 'alchemical process,' she
tries to transform subconscious beliefs and images into the gold of
"meaningful symbols of our experience that speak to us of what is
happening on a spiritual level.''
<p>     "By taking discarded manmade materials and combining them with objects  from nature - stone, bone, gourds - I make whole again things that have  been separated. I breathe new life into these combined materials and transform them into something of value: art."



The artworks:
<p>
