<H2>the ruination of lynne sharon schwartz</H2> 
<h3><i>by nicholas a. basbanes</i></h3>
<P>
  Of all uniquely human experiences, reading, more than any other, 
allows people to transcend time and space and commune one-on-one with 
artists and thinkers throughout the world.
<p>
  "Reading is such an intimate thing that people feel uncommonly 
passionate about it,'' the novelist Lynne Sharon Schwartz said during a 
recent interview occasioned by release of a charming new book she has 
written about the pertinence of books to her life; the title, <I>Ruined 
by Reading </I>(Beacon Press, 119 pages, $18), is so preposterously 
ironic that it cries out for an explanation. 
<p>
   The author previously of such acclaimed novels as <I>Disturbances in 
the Field, Leaving Brooklyn</I> and <I>The Fatigue Artist</I>, Schwartz 
explained that <I>Ruined by Reading</I> was selected after 20 other 
proposals, each one seeming to suggest a kind of personalized travelogue 
through favorite books and card catalogues, were weighed and discarded by 
her publisher.
<p>
   As an afterthought, Schwartz suggested taking a phrase from a wry 
remark about books attributed many years ago to Jimmy Walker, the dapper 
songwriter-turned-politician who served as mayor of New York City from 
1925 to 1932. Asked once to comment on a controversial censorship case 
then being argued, Walker is said
to have replied that as far as he knew, "no girl was ever ruined by 
reading a book."
<p>
   Schwartz said she proposed <I>Ruined by Reading</I> as a joke. "I 
threw it in for laughs, to let my editor have a good time looking at 
it," she said, but it turned out to be the overwhelming favorite of the 
publishing house, and it seems to be pleasing early readers of the book 
as well.
<p>
   "There is this small band of people - and I'm one of them - who feel 
that when everything else is over and done with, now is the time that you 
can finally sit down and read," Schwartz said. 
<p>
   "For me, that is each day's goal, to get everything else out of the 
way so I can have this private moment with my books. It's much more than 
an escape, it's like a little inner dialogue that  makes it so 
wonderful."
<p>
   What gives her tightly composed, elegantly phrased book such 
good-natured charm is that it is a personal reflection of one woman's 
passion for words on paper, not a didactic tract that gets mired in 
fashionable bombast or high-minded pedantry. 
<p>
   "I love to read," Schwartz explained simply. "It shaped my life. 
When I was a child, I would read under the covers late at night with a 
flashlight. Reading is such a private act, there's nothing else quite 
like it. It's a special way of being alone."
<p>
   Being absorbed by the private act of reading, however, and writing 
what is essentially a long, personal essay about it, are two different 
matters, and Schwartz is frank about what motivated her to embark upon it.
   "I started writing it right after I had finished <I>Leaving 
Brooklyn</I> in 1989, and the truth is that I wrote it in a state of 
desperation," she said. "That's not as bad as it sounds,
because I write a lot of books in desperation, but this time I feared 
that I was written out. I thought that I had nothing more to say. I felt 
I didn't have a topic."
<p>
   So, while "casting around" for something to write about, Schwartz 
hit on a subject that had enchanted her since early childhood. "I 
realized that what I know about is reading, it's something I had done all 
my life. I started writing just whatever thoughts came to me about the 
books in my childhood and what had touched my life."
<p>
   In the book, Schwartz notes that her "addiction" these days is to 
"works of the imagination," novels, poetry and various other creative 
pieces, but that as a girl she "longed to read everything, simply 
because it was written, like adventurers who
climb Mount Everest because it is there."
<p>
   More of a reflection on meaning than a long recitation of titles, 
<I>Ruined by Reading</I> is a window into the shaping of a soul. She does 
cite some books from her childhood with particular fondness, however, the 
fairy tales of the Brothers Grimm and Hans
Christian Andersen, the novels of Dickens, the stories of Kipling and 
Poe, the poems of Keats, the sonnets of Shakespeare. 
<p>
   "I remember my childhood books because they were engraved so deeply 
in my consciousness, whereas books I didn't love so much, or some of the 
books I picked up after the age of 30, I don't remember as well because 
they didn't form me or shape me in a way."
<p>
   And while <I>Ruined by Reading</I> is very much about her own "life 
in books," as the subtitle states, Schwartz stressed that she has not 
written a memoir. "I don't have this urge that a lot of other writers 
have to tell about my life, which is why I write fiction," she said.
<p>
   "I don't like the idea of people reading my books to find out about 
me. They should not be interested in me, they should be interested in the 
book. This book talks about reading as a lens through which you see 
everything. It is something that you love
to do, and that you will do until the day you die."
<hr>
<blockquote><font size=-1>
   Nicholas A. Basbanes is a Massachusetts journalist and author. His 
book,<I> A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the Eternal 
Passion for  Books </i> was a finalist this year for the National Book 
Critics Circle Award in nonfiction.
</font></blockquote>
<P>

