<title>george jr. / october 1996 / arcadia / gallery</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/october/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoa.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>

<H2>essay:   finding a way 'Home'</H2> 
<h3><i>by Beth Powning</i></h3>
<IMG SRC="/october/home.jpg" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=237 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
 
     Beth Powning is a naturalist whose work has been published in a  variety of books, journals and magazines.  She has two photography books,  <I>Roses for Canadian Gardens</I> (1991), and <I>Hardy Trees and Shrubs</I> (1996),  both with Key Porter Books (Toronto).
    In May, her  book of lyrical prose and color photographs was published simultaneously by Penguin Books Canada (Toronto) as <I>Seeds of Another Summer: Finding the Spirit of Home in Nature</I>, and, in the United States, as  <I>Home: Chronicles of a North Country Life</I>  by Stewart, Tabori & Chang ($22.50). She muses on how her life and book came to be:
<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>
<blockquote>
  This book was a coming together of my love of nature, which I had been expressing with my camera, and my increasingly strong feeling that my sense of estrangement was lessening the longer I lived in one place and grew to know the  natural world.
<p>
   Having left a home and landscape where my ancestors had been rooted for generations, I was particularly strong by a feeling of displacement when I left that home. I realized that memory is a strong component of belonging, and began to see how familiarity affects vision; my relationship with a new landscape had no dimension because I did not know it. Knowing is more than simply looking.
<p>
   As I began writing <I>Home</I>,  I was keenly aware of the environmental problems facing the planet, and had been involved in coming to grips with these problems in various political ways. I began to feel that by using my own voice, by quietly but passionately sharing my love for the natural world, I might help to restore some degree of respect, and perhaps wonder for rocks, trees, spiders and grasses.
<p>
   I was deeply moved by Bill McKibben's book, <I>The End of Nature</I>, which I read as I was writing <I>Home</I> in a tiny cabin at the Banff Center in Alberta. I was participating in the Leighton Artist's Colony. From my many-windowed cabin, I could see a rocky ledge where, every afternoon, five or six elk would curl up and bask in the thin winter sunshine. On the day I was writing the chapter called 'Trees' - as I was about to describe my feelings about the hidden animals in the woods - a very real coyote trotted past my window. And at another moment, a young elk pressed her nose to the glass of my window and gazed wonderingly at me, making me feel that I was the caged animal.
<p>
   I wrote much of this book in my own house in the quiet countryside, in my studio that is a large room over the kitchen. Even though I was describing the place where I live, I was sad to finish the book, in the way that authors miss their characters; for, of course, it is as much a myth as a real place, a landscape of the mind, and, as such, is an attempt to capture my intense love for the spiritual quality that I feel in the wind, the storms, and the clear light of this place.
<p>
   I have written ever since I was a small child and feel that my love of words was fed by growing up in the country surrounded by dairy farms, without a television; and my grandfather, Sharon Brown, who was a professor of literature and poetry at Brown University, and who read poetry to us at most family gatherings. I spent much time alone and reading, and I spoke to myself in the third person (outloud, sotto voce) for much of my early childhood, telling myself the story of myself.
<p>
   I was extremely fortunate to have my years at Sarah Lawrence College coincide with those of E.L. Doctorow, who had just finished <I>The Book of Daniel</I>  and with whom I worked closely for a year. During that year, I wrote a novel and listened to his quiet and contemplative musings about the perils and joys of writing. Another major influence was the Canadian photographer Freeman Patterson, who opened the world of photography for me.
<p>
   <I>Home</I>  was always conceived as a combination of words and photographs and, in fact, I could not conceive the words until I had pondered my photographs and moved in the direction they sent me.
</blockquote>
<P>

