<head>
<title>george jr. / october 1996 / departments / ask kitty</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/october/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
<H2>Ask Kitty</H2>
<br>
    Our smart, brilliant, sassy friend Ask Kitty not only is jargon-free, but she owns her own shadow and walks her own walk. We're just glad she checks her mail from time to time, or <b>george jr. </b> would be plum without her wisdom.
<br>
  Send your questions to<A HREF="MAILTO:missy@coil.com"> ask kitty</A>.

<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>
  
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font> I have a friend - well, ex-friend - who just stiffed me in the <BR>
business world. Do I respond, make a big deal about it, or chalk it up to
business.
<BR>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Sounds like you've already made up your mind.  I refer, of course, to the
fact that you call this friend an &quot;ex-friend.&quot;<BR>
Take a hint from all the mafia movies you've ever seen, and don't do
business with your friends or family.  It's too easy to make oversights in the name
of a special relationship that will haunt both your business dealings and
your relationships.  You could end up broke, friendless, dead, or with a
curse on the future generations of your family if you're not careful.<BR>
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font> Who are you, Miss Kitty?
<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Just a cat who likes to think about stuff.
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font> Do you think horoscopes are stupid?</B><BR>
<font size=+3>a.</font> I think microwave dryers, WalMart, the religious right, &quot;smart&quot;
cars, mall-walking, exercise videos, outer-outer belts, social climbing,
and concerns about one's waistline are stupid.  But horoscopes?  Naw.<BR>
 <p>
<font size=+3>q.</font>  Why is the really excellent stuff to eat rotten for you?</B><BR>
<font size=+3>a.</font> Oh, but it isn't!  I mean barring stuff with dangerous chemicals,
disease-producing
microorganisms, and the like, and considering that you don't have a
specific
medical condition that prevents you from eating certain foods, and that
you keep in mind how your eating habits affect the biosphere and your own
karma, you should eat what you want to eat.  I mean what's life without
a few french fries every once in a while?
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font> I've read your comments, over the months, on Greek literature or
myths
<BR>
or whatever. Do you approve of fraternal societies, too?</B><BR>
a. I never had any brothers, but have always enjoyed the company of men.
<p>
<font size=+3>q.</font> Who are you going to vote for, for president, and why?</B><BR>
<font size=+3>a.</font> I'll write in George Jr.  Anyone who can be so swept up in the pursuit of
Right over Might can't be all that bad.  In fact, I've heard that his
legal
fees are mounting to equal the amount of a presidential campaign, if not
the national debt.  And who better to lead our troops into battle than
someone
who's willing to run with his chest out for the tape -- even at the
beginning
of the race?  He's fought the big guys, always keeping the interest of his
people foremost in his mind, and kept his head held high, even as the
arrows
are flying through the air.  And besides, he lets me write this column,
for free!
<p>
But I would never vote for you, gentle reader, because you can't tell an
object from a subject.
<p>
<HR><BR>
