<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/october/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<H3>First Person: Marvin Minsky-The Society of Mind</H3>
   Minsky's theories come to life as the visionary thinker walks, talks, 
and jumps across the page, challenging conventional notions of what makes 
us tick, in this cool Voyager CD-ROM. <I>First Person: Marvin Minsky 
</I>includes the full text of <I>The Society of Mind</I>, as well as a 
selection of Minsky's best articles, a video timeline, over 100 minutes 
of original and archival video, over 200 color graphics, over 1,100 pages 
of text, and an interactive tour of Minsky's living room. <br>
   A pioneer in the field of artificial intelligence,  Minsky cofounded 
the MIT Media Lab and is currently Toshiba Professor of Media Arts and 
Sciences at MIT.<br>
   Visit the Voyager Web site at<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A href=" 
http://www.voyagerco.com "> http://www.voyagerco.com </A>or call 
800-446-2001 to order or find out about the nearest outlets carrying 
Voyager titles.
<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3> 'Homeboys' Launched</h3>

 <I>Homeboys in Outer  Space</I>, the new half-hour science fiction 
comedy focusing on the inter-galactic antics of spacemen Tyberious Walker 
(Flex) and Morris Clay (Darryl  M. Bell), two brothers from Earth, begins 
production today at The Walt Disney Studios. The series will run on UPN.
<br>     Rhona Bennett, Paulette Braxton, Kevin Michael Richardson and  
<I>Star Trek'</I>s James Doohan ("Scotty") in the recurring role of 
Pippen,  also star in this out-of-this-world comedy series, produced by 
Sweet Lorraine Productions in association with Touchstone Television.
<br>     The series is set in the 23rd century, where our heroes, Ty and 
Morris, are combing the galaxies in their Space Hoopty (a cross  between 
a space shuttle and a 1964 Chevrolet Impala), looking for odd jobs  and 
loose change.  On board their vehicle is a computer with a back-in-your- 
face personality named Loquatia (Bennett).  Loquatia has a crush on 
Morris causing her circuit boards to melt whenever he comes near,  but 
she has nothing but electrical shocks for Ty.
<br>  The guys' base of operation is the Jupiter Too, a bar run by Vashti, 
the Vognarian (Richardson). In addition to assorted aliens in all shapes  
and  sizes, one of their companions is the ravishing Amma (Braxton), a 
space mercenary for whom no mission is impossible -- for the right price. 
Promising.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Republic Pictures Debuts Web Contest</h3>

  Republic Pictures  launched  a 12-week Internet promotion following 
the studio's debut of its web site (<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A 
NAME="http://www.republic-pictures.com">www.republic-pictures.com</A>).  
Through the web site, movie fans will have access to Republic Pictures' 
extensive catalogue of films, complete with endless movie facts, actor 
profiles, information on directors, movie synopses, reviews and much 
more. The deal ends Nov. 19.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>'I Can Name That Tune in Three  Clicks!' </h3>

 In a deal that shows that content on  the Internet is becoming 
increasingly competitive with television  broadcasting, Interactive 
Imaginations, the New York-based New Media company behind the popular 
Riddler multi-player game site on the Internet (<!-- Anchor Point Tag 
--><A href="http://www.riddler.com">www.riddler.com</A>), has acquired 
the exclusive Internet rights to the internationally popular television 
game show <I>Name That Tune.</I>
     Interactive Imaginations purchased the exclusive Internet rights to  
<I>Name That Tune </I>from the widow and daughter of Harry Salter, the 
show's  creator.
<br>      Interactive Imaginations expects to launch a multi-player version 
of <I> Name That Tune</I> on its Riddler Web site by year end. The 
Riddler site,  which  is designed as a virtual game show network, 
currently features multi-player crossword puzzles and trivia games, in 
which players compete for advertiser-sponsored prizes typically found on 
television game  shows.  Recent prizes have included new cars, cruises 
and allegedly exotic vacations.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Sesame Street Wins Folio Award</h3>
      The seventh annual Folio Awards, announced in <I>Folio</I> 
magazine, has named <I>Sesame Street Parents </I>magazine the winner in 
the Parenting publications category for "Editorial Excellence."  Folio, 
which is published by Cowles Media, gives the awards to both consumer and 
trade publications.
<br>     Published by the magazine group of Children's Television Workshop,  
which also produces the <I>Sesame Street</I> television series, <I>Sesame 
Street Parents</I>  won the Folio Award for the first time in its 
successful 11-year history.<p>
       <hr><p>
   <b>Beastly Show</b><p>

      Walt Disney's <I>Beauty  and  the Beast: A Concert on Ice</I>, 
starring two-time Olympic Gold  Medalist  Ekaterina Gordeeva in the role 
of Belle and Olympic Gold Medalist Victor Petrenko  as  the Beast, begins 
production this week at CBS Television City in  Los  Angeles.  The 
hour-long special, marking Gordeeva's first duet performance since the 
untimely death of her husband and skating partner, Sergei Grinkov,  will  
air this fall on CBS.
<br>     Inspired by the Tony Award-winning Broadway musical and the  Academy 
 Award- winning full-length animated feature film, "Beauty and the Beast: 
A  Concert  on Ice" will be hosted by James Barbour, who currently stars 
as the Beast  in  the Los Angeles stage production. and Susan Egan, who 
was nominated for  a  Tony Award for her performance as the original 
Belle on Broadway.
<br>     The magical score from the feature film, written by the  Oscar  
Award- winning team of Alan Menken and the late Howard Ashman and the 
lyrics  from  the Broadway musical written by Tim Rice, will be performed 
by Egan and  members  of the Los Angeles cast including Barbour, Gary 
Beach ("Lumiere"),  Gibby  Brand ("Cogsworth"), Mari Jo Catlett 
("Wardrobe"), John Dewar  ("Monsieur  D'Arque"), Heather Lee ("Babette"), 
Jeanne Lehman ("Mrs. Potts"), Aaron  Lipin  ("Chip"),
Michael Piontek ("Gaston") and Jamie Torcellini ("La Fou").


<P><hr width=75%><P>

See you next Sunday.
