<title>george jr. / october 1996 / departments / national public rodeo (week 1)</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/october/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<H3>Mall Rat Paid for Loitering</H3>
  Teen-age videogame  phenom  Michael Tang crashed in on the Mall of 
America and claimed a $25,000 college scholarship in the FuncoLand 
National Video Game  Championships(SM),  featuring
the PlayStation(TM) game console .
<p>
      A resident of Sunnyvale, Calif., Tang beat a field of 12 other 
finalists from around the country. Tang, who blew away the  competition  
in  the early rounds, was pressured by Jimmy Nguyen (17) from Houston, 
but  managed  to hold on to take the grand  prize.

<p>
      The tournament began August 5 with individual FuncoLand  store  
tournaments, with the winners advancing to regional competitions. Each  
of  the  finalists received a PlayStation game console, a $100 FuncoLand 
gift certificate,  a  copy of thejust-released PlayStation exclusive 
title, Crash Bandicoot,  and  a trip for two to that real swingville, 
Minneapolis. Now that's what we call a prize.

<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>Print Still Has Stuff to Say About Pixels</h3>

    <I>Internet Voyager</I> magazine, billed as Your Monthly Guide to 
Navigating the Internet, is a handy (no freezes! no lost connections! no 
plug-ins required!) print journal loaded with helpful web-site reviews, 
features on access tools and productivity. The July ish offers its "Net 
Turkey" non-award to ChemSoft, which offers a quick-rich scheme on the 
web; and a dishonorable mention to Alan Gaynor, for his cosmetic-surgery 
site. "My fervent hope," says senior editor Dick Rubinstein, "is that the 
Net is an intelligent enough place that neither blatant fraud nor flashy 
self-promotion will get more than passing attention."
<p>
   <B>george jr.</B> has truly no time to surf, and quit it altogether 
back in June, so the <B>g. jr.</B> staff relies wholly on gee-williker 
genius Laura Logan's monthly Net Stars web-site reviews.
<p>
   <I>Internet Voyager</I> costs $59 for 12 issues from IV, 83 Boston 
Post Road, Sudbury, Mass. 01776-9900.


<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Deadly Accident on the Set Movie</h3>

   There has been an accidental death on the set of Nicolas Cage's 
latest film, <I>Con Air.</I>  Cage and his co-stars John Malkovich, John 
Cusack and Ving Rhames were not on the set at the time of the fatal 
accident. Special effects crew member Phil Swartz was killed on the 
Wendover, Nevada set when a rigged plane accidentally fell, crushing him 
underneath. 

<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>'A Simple Wish' Cast Comes Up Short</h3>

  Martin Short and Kathleen Turner star in Universal Pictures' A Simple 
Wish, a Bubble Factory presentation which has begun production in 
Toronto, Canada under the  direction of Michael Ritchie (<I>Fletch, The 
Bad News Bears, HBO'sThe Positively  True Adventures of the Alleged Texas 
Cheerleader-Murdering Mom</I>). 
<p>
     In this comedic fantasy adventure, when 7-year-old Anabel Greening 
(Mara Wilson) wishes for a fairy godmother to help her handsome cab 
driver  father (Robert Pastorelli) fulfill his dream of becoming a 
Broadway actor, what she gets is an inept spellcaster named Murray 
(Martin Short), the world's  first affirmative action-mandated male 
practitioner. 
<p>
      In addition to filming in Toronto, A Simple Wish will shoot on 
location in New York City, and will be released by Universal Pictures in 
1997. Universal Pictures is a part of MCA Inc., a unit of The Seagram 
Company Ltd., a global beverage and entertainment company, so drink up.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Buy Me and Live On Line</h3>

   <I>Dr. Livingstone's Online Shopping Safari Guidebook</I>, by Frank 
Fiore, is packaged with software and a companion web site to create an 
all-in-one online shopping kit.  Written in easy-to-understand  language, 
this new book highlights the vast array of products, services and 
information available on the Infobahn.  Using a light safari theme, 
author and futurist Frank Fiore provides step-by-step instructions for 
anyone who wants to learn how to shop on the  Web. 
<p>
    Every question about  online shopping is answered  from "What kind of 
Merchandise is Available?" to "How Do I Pay for Something Online?"  Also 
included are "Ten Laws of the Shopping Jungle" that help you enjoy safe 
and  satisfying online shopping safaris. "Dr. Livingstone's Online 
Shopping Yellow Pages" lists more than 2,000 online merchants.  <I>Dr. 
Livingstone's</I> "Secret Scouting Reports" review 200-plus online 
merchants and rate them on price, convenience, selection, service and 
security.   
<p>
    The book is packaged with the newest version of Netscape Navigator 
and a special offer from NETCOM for thirty days of unlimited Internet 
access for only $5.00 (USA only).  <I> Dr. Livingstone's Online Shopping 
Safari Guidebook</I> (Maximum Press)  is a 421-page paperback that costs, 
oh, about $24.95.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Blockbuster Adopts 'Green Lights'  Program</h3>

 Blockbuster  Entertainment Group is converting approximately 1,500 
video and music stores in the United States to the Environmental 
Protection Agency's "Green Lights" program, which is designed to reduce 
energy consumption through the use of energy-efficient lighting. The 
program will result in a savings of about 15 percent in a  store's total 
utility bill. No rental discounts mentioned, though.


<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>As the Crow Flies into CD-Rom</h3>

 The night is dark and its cold  air smothers you like an icy blanket. 
As you fly through the city, the  crow  leads you inside an abandoned 
cathedral where a panoramic QuickTime video  plays revealing 
stained-glass windows, mysterious shrines and secret  paintings. Graphix 
Zone, a leading interactive entertainment  publishing company, today 
shipped "The Crow The Complete Interactive Collection" CD-ROM based on 
the comic book series by James O'Barr and the films<I>The Crow</I> and 
<I>"The Crow: City Angels.</I> 
<p>
     The disc immerses the user into the mysterious, gothic world of  
death, love and revenge made famous by James O'Barr's comic books and 
revealed through behind the scenes footage of both films including  the  
unreleased "Skull Cowboy" from the first Crow film. It also features 120  
film  clips, interviews and biographies of the two casts, excerpts from 
O'Barr's  famous graphic novel, as well as many unpublished O'Barr 
drawings which are  also featured in an exclusive sketch book that is 
bundled with the CD-ROM.
<p>
       "The Crow The Complete Interactive Collection" CD-RDM is playable 
on  both the Macintosh and PC platforms and is available now at all major 
 software retail outlets and fine comic book stores with a suggested 
retail price of $39.95.


<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Not Fadeaway Issues Statement After Statement After Statement</B>
</h3>

  As the Summer Olympics were hosted in Atlanta, Not Fade Away  
Graphics presented the 1996 Lithuanian Basketball t-shirt inspired by  
the overnight success of the Lithuanian Basketball Team shirts of the 
1992 Olympics. Not Fade Away Graphics and the Grateful Dead joined forces 
 with  the Lithuanian Team and the Phoenix Suns to create a shirt 
featuring the  team colors with the trademark skull logo subtly worked 
into the graphic. 
 In  the Summer of 1992 the Lithuanian Basketball Team made their Olympic 
debut  as their country celebrated its new found independence from the 
Soviet  Union.  As the team lacked the financial backing that other 
Olympic athletes  enjoy, Sarunas Marciulionis, who was playing 
professional basketball for the  Golden State Warriors at the time, 
approached the Grateful Dead after seeing one  of their shows. In 
conjunction with the Grateful Dead and the  Golden  State
Warriors, Not Fade Away Graphics was asked to create and produce the  
team shirts used in practice sessions to prepare for the games. When the  
team  took the Bronze Medal, they wore the tie dyed t-shirts on the 
podium during the medals ceremony. The team's victory against the odds 
thrilled  the  sports world and the shirts became a runaway success. The 
media grabbed hold  of  the story and sales skyrocketed. Not Fade Away 
Graphics proudly donated  a  portion of the proceeds from the sale of 
each shirt to the Lithuanian Children's  Fund.
<p>
     While the Summer Games have come and gone, the controversy 
surrounding  the 1992 Lithuanian t-shirts is still alive. Greg Speirs, 
co-author of  the  1992 design, was employed as an artist by Not Fade 
Away when we were approached  by the Grateful Dead to do the project. As 
a long-time Dead licensee,  we  gladly accepted the challenge and Martin 
Leffer, President of Not Fade Away, set  to work with Greg Speirs to come 
up with the slam-dunking skeleton design  which became so popular. Mr. 
Speirs left the employ of Not Fade Away  shortly  after the 1992 Olympics 
to pursue a freelance career and proceeded to make a  claim against the 
company to stop the sale of the shirt. He maintained that  he  was not 
properly compensated or credited for the design and sought  damages.  Not 
Fade Away contended that Mr. Speirs was a staff artist at the time and 
operating under the "Work for Hire" provision of the Copyright Law (Title 
17, U.S. Code) and that the artwork was and is the sole property of  Not 
Fade Away who has the rights of copyrighting and merchandising. Not  Fade 
<p>
 Away Graphics does and has always held the registered copyright of this 
design.
<p>
      In an effort to settle the matter amicably, Not Fade Away entered 
into  an agreement with Mr. Speirs in November 1992 and paid him a lump 
sum for  his contribution to the design. In return, he agreed that he was 
not  entitled  to any of the copyrights or merchandising rights to the 
t-shirt. In  November  of 1995, Not Fade Away was served with a lawsuit 
filed by Greg Speirs asking  for monetary compensation of at least 
$500,000 for the 1992 design claiming  that Not Fade Away misrepresented 
the amount of shirts sold in the settlement agreement even though all 
accounting of the Lithuanian design had been reviewed and approved by all 
of the parties involved in its creation.
<p>
     In 1996 Lithuanian fever struck again as the Team was favored to win 
another medal. Not Fade Away Graphics, Liquid Blue (another  Dead  
licensee), the Grateful Dead and the Phoenix Suns joined forces creating 
a  merchandising team to help raise money for the Lithuanians and the REX 
Foundation, a  non- profit organization spearheaded by the Grateful Dead 
to help needy  charities,
by selling officially licensed products depicting the skull logo among  
other images such as skeletons playing basketball. Not Fade Away's  
"Steal  Your Face" net design created by staff artist Wayne Swarthout and 
the  "Backboard Rebounder" developed by our Art Director, Richard 
Gamache, were the  hottest selling items at the Olympics. Not Fade Away 
was again served  with  papers asking for injunctive relief against the 
sale of an "imposter t-shirt"  which Greg Speirs alleges is a direct 
rip-off of the 1992 design. The  shirt  in question was produced by 
Liquid Blue, in collaboration with the Grateful Dead, the Lithuanian Team 
and the Phoenix Suns with no intention of infringing  on another design.  
Not Fade Away did not sell the "imposter shirt" at the Olympics nor were 
we at any time contracted to participate in its  creation.
<p>
     The initial vision of the Lithuanian project was to help the  
orphaned children of the Baltic State by providing necessary food, 
clothing,  shelter and medical attention as well as setting up a 
basketball camp for other Lithuanian Olympic hopefuls. The idea of 
integrating skeletons  with  sports images is not new to the Grateful 
Dead as we introduced sports skeleton designs in 1985, pre-dating Greg 
Speirs' idea for the 1992 Lithuanian t-shirt.
Mr. Speirs has made no overtures to the Team or to the Grateful Dead 
indicating his interest in helping the cause through the proper  
licensing channels. Mr. Speirs has been notified by all parties to cease  
and  desist marketing the 1992 Lithuanian shirt through his company, Slow 
Leak Apparel, as it violates his settlement agreement with Not Fade Away. 
We  are  confident that this frivolous lawsuit will be dismissed as we 
continue to operate as  a legitimate licensee in the entertainment world. 
You got this far?

<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>MTV Europe WORMs onto the Web</h3>


   MTV Europe has appointed innovative US-based web designer House of 
Blues New Media  to create the first web site for the channel's 
prestigious WORM (Word of Relevant Mouth) youth marketing conference.  
The event-specific site will be MTV Europe's second venture onto the 
Internet, and will feature graphics by UK-based design company, Fuel.  
Find it at <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A 
NAME="http://worm.mtve.com">http://worm.mtve.com</A>.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Warner Site To Debut Real Audio Jukebox</h3>

 Warner Bros. Records  launched a new feature in its worldwide web 
site with the addition of a Real Audio jukebox. Operating in much the 
same way as  a  free-standing audio jukebox, visitors to the Warner Bros. 
Records web site (<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A 
NAME="http://www.wbr.com">http://www.wbr.com</A>) will be able to select 
the song of their choice and listen to it in its entirety in Real Audio 
2.0 format.  Each track will be accompanied by visual images of the 
artists and album artwork.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

See you next Sunday.
