<H3>Alliance Benefits  Burned  Churches</H3>
    The  Nashville  Division  and  the Black Music Division of Warner 
Bros. Records  have  joined  with  Warner  Alliance in a campaign to 
raise money for the Burned Churches Building Fund, established and 
administrated by the National Council Of Churches.<BR>
     Spearheaded by Demetrus Alexander, VP  Gospel  Music,  Warner  
Alliance released a commercial five-song cassette  on  September  10  
entitled  <I>No Weapon.</I> The title track,  featuring  Beverly  
Crawford,  has  been  recently released to radio.  Other artists included 
on the compilation are Carlton Pearson, Andrae Crouch, The Winans  and  
The  Brooklyn  Tabernacle  Choir.  A portion of the proceeds will go to 
the building fund.<BR>
     Reverend Joan Brown Campbell, General Secretary  of  the  National  
Council  of Churches, said, "The burning of African American  churches  
is  no  longer  hidden. It is on the national agenda and Americans of 
good will are responding in unprecedented ways. They are morally outraged 
 and  ready  to  go  to  work."<BR>
      There are more than 55 churches (five burned in  August)  that  the 
National Council of Churches  has  targeted  for  rebuilding.  The  
Council's General Secretary for Public Policy,  Albert  Pennybacker,  
reported  that  the organization is trying to raise $12 million towards 
the cost of restoration.<BR>

<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3>Everybody  Sued By Writer Bill  Waid</h3>

  Bill Waid, a widely- published San Francisco writer, claims that 
his original screenplay,  "Launch Sequence," was the basis for the Walt 
Disney Company's 1995 release  <I>Crimson Tide. </I>A complaint was filed 
by Hollywood attorney Bruce Traney, August  19  in the Superior Court for 
the State of California, County of Los Angeles, alleging six causes of 
action.<BR>
     The Walt Disney Company is named as a defendant; also Hollywood  
Pictures Company; Buena Vista Pictures Distribution, Inc.; 
Simpson-Bruckheimer  Films; The Don Simpson Estate; Jerry Bruckheimer; 
Tony Scott; Bill Unger; Lucas Foster; Michael Moder; Michael Schiffer; 
Richard Henrick; Michael Stenson;  and others as yet unidentified parties 
designated as Does 1 through 200.<BR>
     Breach of Implied Contract is alleged; also, Intentional 
Interference  With Prospective Economic Advantage; Conversion; 
Accounting; Fraud and Deceit; Negligent Supervision Of Employees And/Or 
Agents.<BR>
     "Damage in an amount which cannot be ascertained at the present 
time,  but which is in excess of $1,000,000," is asserted by Traney.<BR>
     Waid, who served two years aboard a U.S. Trident-class nuclear  
submarine, wrote the screenplay "Launch Sequence," dealing with a nuclear 
 missile-launch crisis by such a vessel, which is the subject of "Crimson 
Tide."  He registered his screenplay with the Writers Guild of America 
April 20, 1989. Through his literary agent, Waid then arranged to have 
"Launch Sequence" submitted to approximately 120 production companies and 
production  executives.<BR>
     Waid says that because of the high interest in "Launch Sequence" he 
personally met with executives at Universal Pictures, Island Pictures,  
Geffen Films, Paramount Pictures, Pathe Films and Frank Yablans 
Productions. Particularly interested in "Launch Sequence," Waid contends, 
was Lucas  Foster, then of Frank Yablans Productions.  Mr. Foster later 
was listed as an executive producer of <I>Crimson Tide</I>.<BR>
     Traney states: "The Walt Disney Company and, in fact, all named 
defendants, are fully aware of Waid's claims, and the lawsuit filing 
should not surprise any of them."<BR>
     Waid has another screenplay soon to be marketed, and Traney believes 
 the lack of acknowledgement for<I> Crimson Tide</I> also detracts from 
Waid's opportunity to profit from his new film stories.<P>


<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Too Busy and Don't Wanna Learn</h3>

    People, Osborne/McGraw-Hill addresses an important new trend in the 
PC-buying and -using public: busy users who are increasingly dependent on 
their PCs, but have neither the time - nor the interest - in becoming 
fluent in high-tech computer jargon.  Responding to this growing, 
time-strapped audience, <I>PC's for Busy People</I> focuses on the 
essentials to ensure that readers will make the smartest use of their 
time at the computer.    <BR>
    <I> PC's for Busy People</I> is a one-stop guide to purchasing, 
owning, and making the most of a PC, whether for business or home use.  
Written for both the beginner who needs to get up to speed quickly, as 
well as the more experienced user seeking to stay abreast of significant 
advancements,<I> PC's for Busy People</I> begins with the basic hardware 
and software options, with a focus on Windows 95 applications and the 
equipment that best supports them.  It also discusses the advantages of 
plug-and-play for integrating printers, modems, and other add-ons.  <BR>
     Full consideration is given to the important issues of connecting to 
the online community, both on the Internet and commercial services.  <BR>
    <I>PC's for Busy People</I> is a-304 page paperback, full-color, with 
illustrations throughout.  Suggested retail price:  $22.95<P>

<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>'The Day Df The Jackal' Begins Production</h3>

   Bruce Willis, Richard  Gere and Sidney Poitier star in Universal 
Pictures' <I>The Day of the Jackal</I>,  which has begun principal 
photography in Montreal, Canada under the direction  of
Michael Caton-Jones.<BR>
     In flick a ruthless assassin is on the move -- his identity, 
whereabouts and deadly timetable are unknown.  This mysterious mercenary 
is known only as the Jackal.<BR>
     The FBI's Deputy Director (Sidney Poitier) faces the biggest 
challenge  of his career. In order to track down this cold-blooded 
killer, he  and  Russian officer Major Valentina Koslova (Diane Venora) 
enlist the aid of an  imprisoned underground operative Declan Mulqueen 
(Richard Gere). Together  these  unlikely allies enter a global race 
against the clock to stop the Jackal (Bruce  Willis) before he can 
complete his deadly assignment.<BR>
     <I>The Day of the Jackal </I>is an Alphaville production directed by 
 Michael Caton-Jones (<I>Rob Roy, Scandal, This Boy's Life</I>) from a 
screenplay  by Chuck Pfarrer & Kevin Jarre. The screenplay is inspired by 
the 1973  film  of the same name, based on Frederick Forsyth's classic 
best-seller.  Jim  Jacks, Sean Daniel and Kevin Jarre are producing the 
film, which will be released  by Universal Pictures. Terence Clegg serves 
as executive-producer guy.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>There Isn't Any There There, Either</h3>

   Los Angeles was the site of the  U.S. theatrical premiere of the 
compelling satire,<I> "the four corners of nowhere,"</I> a Steve Chbosky 
film presented by MGI Distribution  & Production in assocation with Kit 
Parker Films. <BR>
     The story chronicles the philosophical Duncan's nomadic journey to 
discover if "America is nothing but an enormous McDonald's 
drive-through."  While hitching a ride to Ann Arbor, Michigan, Duncan 
encounters a host of diverse characters who will change his life, 
including Toad, a performance artist from the suburbs;  Jenny, a 
co-dependent moonbeam; Hank, a pretentious painter who can't paint;  and 
Julian, a sociopathic dee-jay

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>And if you're lucky you'll get mugged</h3>

 Producer Kenneth  Feld  will create a completely unique entertainment 
experience  for  the New York-New York Hotel & Casino, bringing the 
distinctive beat of  the streets of New York City to Las Vegas for the 
very first time in an  all new, talent-driven blend of dance, song and 
physical comedy. The  show  is scheduled to open in the hotel's 1,000 
seat theater in May  1997.  Kenneth Feld is the world's leading producer 
of live family entertainment, including Ringling Bros. and Barnum & 
Bailey(R), Walt Disney's World  On Ice(SM), Siegfried & Roy(R) and the 
smash-hit Broadway musical  Big(SM).<BR>
      New York-New York Hotel & Casino will re-create traditional  New  
York landmarks and attractions, including a classical  Manhattan  
skyline.  The $460 million property will have 2,035 rooms housed in 12 
skyscrapers,  a 150-foot replica of the Statue of Liberty and other 
attractions such  as Manhattan Express, a Coney Island-style roller 
coaster, a 300-foot  long<BR>
replica of the Brooklyn Bridge and a 510-foot, 47 story Empire  State 
Building. New York-New York Hotel & Casino is an equal  joint  venture 
between MGM Grand, Inc. (NYSE: MGG) and Primadonna Resorts, Inc. (Nasdaq: 
PRMA, and all dat stuff).

<P><hr width=75%><P>

See you next Sunday.
