<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<H3>Elvis, Ho-Hum </H3>
   Affinity Entertainment Group, Inc., a wholly owned movie subsidiary 
of Affinity Entertainment Inc. has  purchased the film rights to<I> Elvis 
& Leon</I> (working title, but hardly working if you ask us) from 
Paramount Pictures.<br>
    <I> Elvis & Leon</I> is billed as a contemporary comedy/adventure 
film geared toward family and youth entertainment with humor, heartfelt 
relationships in a Frank Capra-like story (yeah, and <B>george jr.</B> is 
the pontiff). <I>Elvis & Leon</I> was written by Dick Christie and  Joe  
Lerer for Paramount Pictures. Christie's other writing credits include 
<I> Shores  of Tripoli</I> starring Tom Berenger, and "Stormbird" 
directed by David Ward  (<I>The Sting, Major League</I>) which are 
scheduled for production in 1997.  <I>Elvis & Leon </I>is scheduled to 
begin production in the Spring of 1997.

<P><hr width=75%><P>


<h3> 'The Flood' Under Way</h3>

  <I>The Flood,</I> a high  action crime thriller starring Morgan 
Freeman, Christian Slater, Randy Quaid  and Minnie Driver, has begun 
principal photography in the Los Angeles  area.  The film is being 
directed by Mikael Salomon based on a screenplay by Graham  Yost about an 
armored car heist set against the backdrop of an impending  natural 
disaster facing a sleepy Midwestern river town. 

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Butt out, Collins</h3>


      The five members of the rock band Aerosmith confirmed that they 
were parting ways with Tim  Collins, their manager of 12 years. Aerosmith 
acknowledged the collective success that they have  shared with Collins 
and expressed the hope that he would continue to flourish
in his future endeavors.<br>
     In response to speculation over why the separation has occurred  and 
in order to reassure their fans, the band's only comment was: "Any 
inferences that members of the band have backslid into drug abuse is 
ludicrous. All we can say is that although we may be drinking  too  much 
coffee, our immediate plan is to complete our new Columbia album,  which 
we and the label are extremely proud and excited about, and get back out 
on the road."

<P><hr width=75%><P>

 <h3>Old guy still trying</h3>

   Struggling phoenix Burt Reynolds (Striptease),  Don Cheadle (Devil in 
a Blue Dress), William H. Macy (Fargo), Heather  Graham (Drugstore 
Cowboy), John C. Riley (What's Eating Gilbert Grape), magician Ricky Jay, 
and Joanna Gleason have joined the ensembled cast  of New Line Cinema's 
dark comedy <I>Boogie Nights.</I><br>
      As previously reported, the film also stars Mark Wahlberg (Fear)  
and Julianne Moore (Nine Months).  Boogie Nights follows an extended 
family of filmmakers who struggle to redefine and revolutionize the  
adult entertainment industry.  Led by an idealistic producer who dreams 
of elevating his craft into an art form, the film takes a  
behind-the-scenes journey into the turbulent lives of those who rise and 
fall in  the misunderstood underworld. Written and directed by Paul  
Thomas  Anderson, the film will be released next April.<br>
      The film will feature a Capitol Records soundtrack infused with 
classic music form the 70's and 80's, representing the era which 
<I>Boogie Nights</I> chronicles.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Film-Goers Wait For Scratch 'n' Sniff Celluloid</h3>
   Movie magic comes alive as  never before in <I>Special Effects</I>, a 
new IMAX format film featuring a  behind- the-scenes look at films 
including <I>Star Wars Trilogy Special  Edition, Independence Day, 
Jumanji</I> and <I>Kazaam</I>. Narrated by John  Lithgow  (NBC's <I>Third 
Rock From the Sun</I>) and directed by four time Academy  Award-winner 
Ben Burtt, Special Effects is produced by NOVA/WGBH Boston (creators  
of<I> NOVA,</I> the highly-acclaimed public television science series) 
with  major funding from the National Science Foundation, 18 science 
museums,  and corporate funding by Silicon Graphics Computer Systems. It 
opened  at IMAX and IMAX Dome Theaters in select US cities on July 4, 
1996.

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Way Nuttier Than the Professo</h3>

    Monty Python  returns,  and  this  time it's worldwide and web 
footed! It's all rolled  and  patted  into  a  new website called 
PythOnline (<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A 
href="http://www.pythonline.com">http://www.pythonline.com</A>),  thanks to  the  
technology  gurus  at 7th Level. <br>
     You'll enjoy a veritable brain enema with pages of totally new 
Python material when PythOnline lunches, oops, launches.  Would you care 
to donate your organs online?  Shop  for Python  memorabilia?  Or,  just 
take the PythOnline All-Nude Tour?  Just log on and click.
     Expect to see new drawings by Terry Gilliam, a report from Terry 
Jones on Bulgaria (written in his bathroom  before  leaving),  John  
Cleese in praise of cowardice, Michael Palin confessing he  may  be  the  
fattest Python and Eric Idle claiming to be the sixth-nicest.
<p>
     Now for a small introduction to PythOnline:
    <!-- List Tag --><UL>
<LI> De Tour
<LI>     New stuff
<LI>     Shopping
<LI>     Plugs
<LI>     Games
<LI>      Or, for the myopic and middle aged:
<LI>     De Tour - Delphine, an ex-Lap-Dancing Operative  will  reveal  
all  for you.
<LI>     New Stuff: Well it's all bloody new isn't it?
</UL>
     We promised you a short view, and there it was. Did we forget The 
Spam Club?  Pop the top, and get  many  benefits,  including  the
right to change your star sign for a  brand  new  Monty  Python  star  
sign, e.g. Herring or Frog and the right  to  be  called  "Rupert"  in  
Holland. And finally, you can witness random acts  of  Python  humor  
RIGHT  NOW at  <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A href=
"http://www.pythonline.com">http://www.pythonline.com</A>.  

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<h3>Cutting-Edge 3D Game Programming with C++</h3>

  3D games are the most popular on the market, and best-selling games 
like Doom and Quake have redefined the game industry. Creating 
super-charged 3D games that impress consumers is difficult, and it 
requires the technical knowledge that, until now, was buried in obscure 
programming texts.  In <I>Cutting-Edge 3D Game Programming with C++</I> 
(Coriolis, $39.99), you'll find the detailed, advanced information to 
create computer games with 3D animation. <br>
   Paired with a CD-ROM full of game programming tools, this book covers 
all the hottest techniques, including 3D morphing, digital sound effects, 
collision detection, and more. Between these covers you'll find more than 
700 pages packed with the advanced game programming techniques you need 
to create blockbuster-quality games. <br>
   Master game programmer John De Goes gives you all the information and 
tools you need to write vivid, eye-popping 3D games.  The companion 
CD-ROM includes source code, 3D game programming tools, demos and other 
stuff.


<P><hr width=75%><P>

See you next Sunday.
