<title>george jr. / october 1996 / departments / the joy of lex</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/october/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>


<H2>the joy of lex</H2> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>1</H2>
Log rolling (definition): A bargaining strategy in which members trade votes in order to ensure passage of a measure of special interest to them.
<H2> 2</H2>
 "As a Jew, Christ would have had less than affectionate regard for  pigs." -  Roger A. Caras, <I>A Perfect Harmony</I>
<H2>3</H2>
When the new moon holds the old moon in her lap the weather will be fair.
<H2> 4</H2>
<B>hard magnets</B>: Permanent magnets; high-coercivity materials.
<p><B>soft magnets</B>: Temporary magnets; low-coercivity materials.
<p><B>permeability</B>: Factor by which the magnetic field of the current field of the current-carrying coil of an electromagnet is amplified by a soft-magnetic core. A common quality index for soft magnets, permeability usually varies inversely with coercivity.
<p><B>magnetic domain</B>: Region with a ferromagnet in which all the atomic magnets point in the same direction.
<p><B>Curie temperature</B>: Temperature beyond which magnetic materials lose their magnetism.
<p><B>domain wall</B>: Boundary between two magnetic domains magnetized in different directions. The movement of domain walls is easy in soft magnets, hard in hard magnets.
<H2>5</H2>
L'eggs Products purchased a full-page newspaper advertisement in the sports section of the weekend edition of USA TODAY to respond to recent public requests made by flamboyant basketball star Dennis Rodman to appear in future L'eggs  advertising.  The black & white ads created by Saatchi & Saatchi Advertising, sum up  L'eggs' reaction in two words:  "Sheer audacity."
<H2>6  </H2>
A, E, eyes. Oh, you.
<H2>7</H2>
<I>Popular Mechanics</I>, the 94-year-old Hearst magazine, has relaunched its web site, the PM Zone.  Web users will find a new design with an easy to navigate interface, an  upgraded search engine and virtually double the amount of content compared to the original site. That's right; you can find it.
<H2>8</H2>
<B>Vesperi</B>: In the evening (Latin)
<H2>9</H2>
A superfluous list of links for which <B>george jr.</B> has added no context:
<!-- List Tag --><UL>
<LI>  <a href=http://wings.buffalo.edu/epc/authors/creeley/> Robert Creeley </A>
<LI>  <a href=http://www.lm.com/~kalin/leiris.html>Michel Leiris</A>
<LI><a href=http://www.roughguides.com/>Rough Guides</A>
<LI> <a href=http://cool.infi.net/> Cool Site of the Day</A>
<LI><a href=http://www.cbs.com/lateshow/>David Letterman's Top 10 Today</A>
</ul>
<H2>10</H2>
The <I>Webster's New World College Dictionary</I> Word of the Month for September: <B>Americanism</B>: Words, phrases or usage originating in or peculiar to  American English, i.e., Dorm, couch potato, Labor Day, grunge, oldie,  streetwise.
<H2>11</H2>
Actual names of several blues performers:
<br>Peetie Wheatstraw was really William Bunch
<br>Sonny Boy Williamson: Aleck Miller
<br>Sonny Boy Williamson: John Lee Williamson
<br>The Yas Yas Girl: Merline Johnson
<br>Koko Taylor: Cora Walton
<br>Tampa Red: Hudson Whittaker
<H2>12</H2>
 "...the 'cold fire' of ruby - its deep red luminescence - adds to the  mystique and aura ... It is crystalline Al2O3 (sapphire) with a dilute doping of Cr3+ions ..."
- G.F. Imbusch and W.M. Yen, Lasers, <I>Spectroscopy and New Ideas</I>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
