<head>
<title>george jr. / october 1996 / departments / shotgun movie review</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/october/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<!--IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15-->
<H2>shotgun movie review</H2>

<h4>by joseph r. blankenship</h4>

<blockquote>
    Hi folks.  Welcome.  I call this what it is because I'll discuss movies and moviemakers indiscriminately and randomly.  A complete layman's point of view.
<p>    It won't be unusual for me to praise Jackie Chan and Max von Sydow, or some other odd pairing in the same breath.  Anything goes.
<p>    Once in a while I may even devote a column to just one movie , director or actor.   I will review some films new to theaters but,  for the most part, I am interested in helping you discover and rediscover films that may not have grabbed your attention the first time around - new and older foreign releases as well as film classics from a fresh and not so high brow perspective.
   <p> In other words, if I don't like <I>Belle de Jour</I>, you'll know  it, despite what everyone else has been saying.
<p>      Granted, it's not the cleverest of segues, but the first film I'll review is  <I>Belle de Jour. </I> The 1967 French film by Luis Bunuel  was re-released in theaters and on video last year bearing the moniker of a modern classic.  Incidentally, I did like it.  Although it was not my favorite film of all time.  In it, Catherine Deneuve plays a bored housewife who turns to prostitution during the day (thus the title) to her and her husband's ruination.  I enjoyed Deneuve's daydream sequences, the most ironic of which appears at the end.  I also liked that it was a very sensual movie without blatant sex, nudity or even Mickey Roarke.  What I did not  like was that it was wrought with the emotional aloofness that French films are stereotypical known for.  If this is a point of contention, please contact me and provide examples as I'm always happy to be proven wrong.
<p>    In direct contrast to French erotic cinema is early German cinema.  On somewhat of a binge I watched <I>The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari, M</I>, and <I>Vampyr</I> back to back to back.
<p> My long suffering wife saw to it that <I>Sense and Sensibility</I> was rented soon after.
<p>      I was very eager  to see <I>Caligari </I>(1919) most because of all the hype heaped onto it over the years.  That Robert Weine's silent film was a pinnacle of Germany's expressionist period and that it was just plain creepy.  The film involves a man's encounter with a carnival sideshow man, Dr. Caligari, and his somnambulist, Cesare, who he suspects of mass murder.  Consequently, his pursuit of Caligari leads to the audience's realization of his own madness and detainment in an asylum.  I like the storyline as well as the hallucinogenic set design.  I can also see where<I> Batman</I> director Tim Burton is influenced by this period in cinema: Danny Devito's Penguin looked much more like Caligari than the comic book villain.
<p>      Creepier than<I> Caligari</I> was <I>Vampyr </I>(1931).  Carl Dreyer's film about protagonist, Allan Gray's excursion into an occult laden, nightmarish dreamscape is a bit difficult to follow with its, at best, sparse dialogue.  The film is all atmosphere and it is exactly that atmosphere which makes it worth watching.  Anyone who appreciates the faux-gothic scene going on now could take a history lesson form this bit of dark surrealism.  Though not as widely known as <i>The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari</i> and a flop upon its release in theaters, <i>Vampyr</i> is today considered a classic of early horror.
<p>      My favorite of the lot, so far, is Fritz Lang's <I>M</I> (1931).  Lang is probably best known to casual movie viewers as the maker of the silent sci-fi classic, Metropolis.  However, he made films all the way up to and including 1960.  M, Lang's first talkie, stars Peter Lorre as a child murderer stalking the streets of Dusseldorf, with both the police and members of the criminal underworld racing to capture him for vastly different reasons.  The impassioned debate at the film's climax over Lorre's fate is worth the price of rental.  Also striking is Lang's use of symbolism in describing the murders and the very effective portrayals by both Lorre and the almost gestapo-like mob boss, Schranker, played by Gustaf Grundgens.
<p>      What's most fascinating to me about early German cinema is that while America turned out costume epics, musicals and escapist fare, German film makers moved the camera away from spectacle and turned it inward toward the dark underbelly of the human psyche.
<p>      Switching gears again, in fact toward said American escapism, I have only one new film to talk about this time around.  Being 13 years old and male in 1981, it was hard to miss John Carpenter's <I>Escape from New York</I>.  To me, the lead character, Snake Plissken, was always much cooler than either <I>Indiana Jones</I> or<I> Rambo</I>.  When Escape came out, I was just getting tired of Star Wars toys.  Who would have thought that I'd have a wife, kid and a mortgage before Kurt Russell, who hasn't aged a bit, would finally put back on his eye patch and sneer for <I>Escape from L.A</I>.  While there are no real surprises in this film, I must admit that I kind of like it that way.  Basically, <I>L.A</I> is <I>New York </I>with earthquakes, surfing and a more comic book feel to it.  Hmm, sort of like  real life.  Anyway, I welcomed the return of a childhood hero and had a great time watching this film. However, it is easy to see that in light of director, John Carpenter's track record of late, he and producer, Debra Hill as well as Kurt Russell did not want to mess with the successful Escape formula.
<p>      I'm always open to other opinions and discussions on film, as well as suggestions on fare that I may not have yet stumbled upon.  Drop <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:JoeB@georgejr.com">me</A> a line. Talk to you next month.

</blockquote>
<p>
<HR><BR>
<a href="/october/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
</BODY>
