<head>
<title>george jr. / november 1996 / features / q & a / rafael belle yang</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/november/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<H2>q&a</H2> 
<h3>belle yang:  the odyssey of a Manchurian</h3>

<P>
<IMG SRC="/november/yang.jpg" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=148 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

Belle Yang's first book, <I>Baba: A Return to China Upon My Father's Shoulders,</I> received tremendous praise when it was first published in 1994.<I> The Los Angeles Times Book Review</I> called it "glorious...and captivating."  and <I>The San Jose Mercury News</I> said "this remarkable book...is a pure delight to relish through both eye and ear."
<P></P>  Picking up where<I> Baba</I> ("Father" in Chinese) left off, Belle Yang continues his story of survival in <I>The Odyssey of a Manchurian  </I>(Harcourt Brace, $35), starting with the flight from his native village during the civil war that engulfed China and ending with his arrival in Taiwan where he would hope to finally find peace. 
<P></P>   Like her first book,<I> The Odyssey of a Manchurian</I> is lavishly illustrated with 20 full-color paintings. As World War II comes to an end, a battle for power erupts between Mao Zedong's Communists and the Nationalist forces of Chiang Kai-Shek, 17-year-old Baba, trusting neither side, decides to leave both Manchuria and his family behind.
<P></P>   As he travels south from the ancient capital of Beijing, to the Yellow and Yangtze Rivers, to Shanghai  and eventually to Taiwan, he is consumed by the exodus from the Communist takeover: avoiding soldiers, battling hunger, and encountering hordes of ordinary people without political agendas who found themselves swept into the madness of revolution.
<P></P> Belle Yang was born in Taipei, Taiwan in 1960.  She lived in Japan from 1965 to 1967 and emigrated to the United States with her parents when she was seven.  She now lives in Carmel, California.


<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>

<blockquote>

<font size=5>q. </font> What first gave you the idea to tell Baba's story through both  words and pictures?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font> Chinese painters are poets and poets are painters.  Chinese written characters are pictographs.  Word and image are one.  Since childhood, I have watched my father paint and grace his work with poetry.
<p>

<font size=5>q. </font> Do you feel that there are some parts of Baba's story better  told through your paintings?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font> The writing can stand alone, but the images help to heighten the tension.  The background of<I> Baba</I> and<I> The Odyssey of a Manchurian </I> is the darkness of war.  The art is bright - even humorous and pretty. The contrast somehow darkens even the dark.
<p>

<font size=5>q. </font> How do you decide what parts of the story to express through  your painting?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font>  A tough question because there are a slew of answers.  In <I>The Odyssey of a Manchurian,</I> I chose, in most cases, to illustrate the flashbacks to the lyrical images of childhood. The images are not necessarily illustrations, but symbolic, representative of the mood or the central idea of that particular chapter.
<p>

<font size=5>q. </font> Which story that your father told most affected you?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font> Perhaps Chapter 4, the part I call "A Dream." It is the core philosophy of Chinese thinking: that life is but a dream, a bubble, lightning, morning dew, ephemeral, changeable.  The stories are equally wonderful and equally necessary in the telling of China of the 30's-50's; they flow into one another and is history.
<p>


<font size=5>q. </font> How do you go about preparing this book?  Do you listen to  your father's complete story and then go back and paint or do  you paint as work on each chapter?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font> In my first book, I listened, I painted then I wrote.  In this second book of my trilogy, I listened to each story, wrote the chapter then painted the accompanying image, alternating between writing and painting to keep both activities fresh.  In my third book, which I am currently working on, I've listened to my father's stories, set down all the material, and will paint as I complete the second draft of each chapter.
<p>

<font size=5>q. </font> What has changed in you and your father's relationship now  that you have completed the second part of his life story?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font> My father has "forgiven" me all the "mistakes" of my twenties.  he now sees my antics and the troubles of my earlier days as necessary to my artistic journey.  I've come to see the child in my father and no longer rage against his imperfections.  I now understand how the war had shaped him.  There is so much humor and laughter between father and daughter today.

<p>

<font size=5>q. </font>  How did returning to China for three years to study painting  influence your work?
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font>  The repression in China made me realize the freedom I had.  I came back certain that I did not want to remain silent.  Through my writing/painting I give one great big shout:  I'm alive!
   Chinese art helped me to see the world from multiple perspectives instead of from the classical Western one-point perspective.  I also move through the stories as one would view a horizontal scroll of a landscape, mountains unrolling into mountains and rivers winding into rivers.
<p>

<font size=5>q. </font> Elsewhere you have said that you found being both artist and writer liberating. 
<BR>

<font size=5>a. </font> Writing is tough. It drains me. When I tire of bleeding out words, I pick up the brush and, oh, how easy and comforting and "mindless."  When painting becomes too facile, I crave the hard-edged challenge of writing.

</blockquote>

<HR><BR>
