<head>
<title>george jr. / november 1996 / features / q & a / robert crais</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/november/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<H2>q&a</H2> 
<h3>robert crais: confronting the system </h3>

<P>
<IMG SRC="/november/craisqa.gif" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=220 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

   Louisiana-born Robert Crais is the award-winning author of the best-selling Elvis Cole novels, which include <i>The Monkey's Raincoat, Stalking the Angel, Lullaby Town, Free Fall</i> and <i>Voodoo River.</i> His latest is <i>Sunset Express </i>(Hyperion). 
   Crais has written TV scripts for <i>Hill Street Blues, Cagney & Lacey, Miami Vice</i> and <i>L.A. Law. </i> He won an Emmy for his work on <i>Hill Street Blues.</i><i>The Monkey's Raincoat </i>won both an Anthony Award and a Macavity Award.
   The interview:


<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>

<blockquote>
<font size=5>q. </font>In <I>Sunset Express</I> you paint a pretty dark picture of the legal system, especially the way that wealthy defendants have an unfair advantage.  Do you believe this inequality affects the whole country, or Los Angeles in particular?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> Well, we certainly have our share of headline cases here -- the Menendez brothers, O.J. -- but the plague of lawyers is not limited to L.A., and didn't just happen.  Lawyers control Washington.  Lawyers control business and the news media.  Lawyers are responsible for our huge insurance premiums and this hyper-litigious society we have.  Lawyers are also responsible for a so-called "justice system" where, for example, rich people hire lawyers whose specific goal isn't to seek truth or justice, but to confuse and befuddle emotionally weak jurors so that we can't even convict two guys who admitted murdering their parents.</B>
<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> A-ha. Is that why you chose to make the villain an attorney, and have Elvis Cole confront the legal system?  
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> Like most people, I'm frustrated by all of this.  On the one hand, I certainly want the rights of innocent people protected -- that's where defense attorneys serve a noble and worthwhile service -- but at the same time I'm enraged by a system that allows clearly guilty -- objectively guilty -- people to walk free.  I think the entire country feels powerless, and <I>Sunset Express </I> offers an outlet both for myself and my readers to deal with the feelings of grief and anger they experience.  Elvis does what the rest of us wish we could -- he digs into one of these high-profile criminal defense attorneys and reveals what we all suspect to be true but can't get close enough to prove: that many of these people are motivated by arrogance and greed, and that at their core they are amoral.
</B>
<P>

<font size=5>q. </font>It's been said that your novels have enormous appeal to women, who have become the largest segment of mystery readers.  What's your magic touch?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> A bookseller recently called to ask me to sign at her store, and told me that I'm the most popular male author among her female readers.  I asked her why she thought that was so, and she said, "It comes across in your work that you like women." Well, I do.  My life is filled with smart, bright, complex women after whom I model my characters.  I work very hard to make my female characters believable and true and complete, just the way the women in my life are believable and true and complete.  Besides, all these smart, bright women in my life are also very strong, and would beat the hell out of me if I didn't. </B>
<P>

<font size=5>q. </font> So often in fiction, art imitates life.  Your wife is a clinical psychotherapist who, I've heard, you consult for  insight into the motivations of your characters.
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> That's right.  She calls herself Motivations-R-Us.  Seriously, I love people's idiosyncrasies and I work very hard at creating characters who are interesting and authentic.  So, for me, having a practicing psychotherapist across the dinner table is like being a kid in a candy store -- we have these marvelous hours-long pinball conversations about why people do the things they do.  As for art imitating life, well, in <I>Sunset Express </I> Elvis seeks Lucy Chenier's expertise in the legal profession to help him understand lawyers.  Maybe the reason Elvis's and Lucy's relationship seems so natural is that it echoes the relationship in my own marriage.
</B>
<P>

<font size=5>q. </font> Why do you refuse to option your books to television and movies?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> All of the television networks and many of the film studios have tried to buy the rights to these things, but I couldn't do that to Elvis!  Look, Elvis Cole doesn't exist on the page -- he exists in the hearts and minds of my readers, and every one of my readers contributes to him. He doesn't come to life until he's read.  I used to think it would be neat to have Elvis on the screen, but if I committed Elvis to film I'd lose the reader from the equation and I simply will not do that.  Elvis wouldn't be Elvis any more -- he'd be an actor.</B>
<P>


<font size=5>q. </font>I've heard your hobbies include acrobatic flying.  Do you, like your boy Elvis Cole, seek out danger? 
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>  I don't see these things as dangerous.  Exciting, maybe, and definitely fun, but more importantly they are opportunities to learn about and develop one's self.  If there is an element of danger, then that's the price you pay for the fun of spinning and looping an airplane.  Elvis probably feels the same way: he likes to help people, and if he sometimes faces danger in order to help them, then that's the price of doing what he likes.
</B>
<P>

<font size=5>q. </font> Are you Elvis Cole? 
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> Elvis is the man I try to be.  I think that's a pretty good goal.</B>

</blockquote>

<HR><BR>
<a href="/november/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    
</BODY>
