<head>
<title>george jr. / november 1996 / features / q & a / james l. halperin</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/november/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<H2>q&a</H2> 
<h3>james l. halperin: truth or dare</h3>

<P>
<!--IMG SRC="/november/halperin2.gif" WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=188 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left-->

   James L. Halperin's speculative novel of the future<I> The Truth Machine </I>($24)  was initially published in cyberspace. Since then, Del Rey has reissued it in meat space - and too many of Halperin's edgy predictions look like they're coming to pass, and everyone knows who is telling the truth.
<p>
Can you imagine never having to worry whether someone is lying? Once perfected, "the truth machine" of the novel changes the face of civilization. Crime, violent behavior and court cases are eliminated overnight. And political candidates - well, suddenly there are fewer of them. The interview:

<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>

<blockquote>

<font size=5>q. </font>  What is <I>The Truth Machine</I> about?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> Basically, it's a futuristic story - I call it a speculative novel -  about a machine that can unfailingly assess whether a person is telling the  truth.  I wanted to get people thinking about issues that I think might  actually affect our survival as a species.  In my novel I envision a world  creeping ever more steadily toward self-destruction, which can be averted only  by people willingly giving up some of their liberties - a portion of their  right to privacy.  A truth machine that could detect lies with 100-percent accuracy would eliminate crime, violence, and civil litigation.  It  would affect everything we know, from politics to business to education.
<p>
<IMG SRC="/november/grinds.gif" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=269 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=right>

<font size=5>q. </font>  Where did you get the idea for this?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> Most of us wonder what tomorrow's innovations will be.  Will they improve  our lives, hasten our end?  What year will an AIDS vaccine be invented?  When  will cryogenic freezing become legal?  When will commercial supersonic airline  flights across the U.S. be introduced?  When will we colonize the moon?
<br>

And then I began to wonder what it would be like to live in a world in which no  one could lie.  And I realized that if someone could build a fool-proof lie  detector, it would be the most important invention in history.  A truth machine  would create some interesting controversies,  but, more importantly,  it could  actually solve many of the most intractable problems that now exist in  politics, science, justice and many other fields. 
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> <I>The Truth Machine </I>first was published, by yourself,  Mark Twain style, but in cyberspace.  What about the stuff that awaited browsers there?

<br>
<font size=5>a. </font> My book was on my Web site for anyone to read, but there was a slight  catch.  You had to answer some questions.  After filling in your name and  e-mail address, there's a series of questions.  "Suppose for one minute that  there's a technology  breakthrough.  This breakthrough results in a truth  machine.  This device is far more sophisticated than a lie detector.  Do you  think a truth machine would benefit mankind?  Do you wish there were a truth  machine?" And then you get the novel.  Actually, there are questionnaires along  the way, asking a variety of demographic questions.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font>  And what was the purpose of this information-gathering?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>It was for marketing purposes.  The information I gathered was to help  market the book.  When I start reading the responses, I'll know the professions  of the people who like the book, I'll know how old they are, I'll know whether  they would be interested in seeing a <I>Truth Machine</I>  movie or participating in a  chat group.  The Internet as a communications tool and marketing tool has  enormous potential.  All I've done is combine two simple techniques - writing  a book and posting it on the 'Net, and taking the opportunity to ask people to  fill out questionnaires along the way.  Whether the story's on screen or paper,  though, the best thing a writer can offer is still a good compelling read.
<p>
<font size=5>q. </font> James, James, James, James. Do you think a truth machine is technologically possible?
<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>  Well, the fax machine was actually invented during the 1800s, but it didn't  become financially viable until the last decade.  On the other hand, when the  space race against the Soviet Union made it politically popular to put men on  the moon, NASA did so in 1969 on less computing power than you probably have on  your desk today.  I researched the notion of a truth machine with scientists,  business colleagues and experts, and I believe it is indeed possible to build a  truth machine, but it would probably take 50 to 100 years to build.

</blockquote>

<HR><BR>
<a href="/november/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>    
