<head>
<title>george jr. / november 1996 / features / time line</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/november/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<!--img src="/graphics/gambit.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=15 ALT=""-->
<br>
<h2>everything's future</h2>

James Halperin has imagined a future that looks scarily possible. He discusses it in the interview in this issue of <B>george jr</B>. Halperin's speculative novel is <I>The Truth Machine </I>(Del Rey, $24). This is what his book portends:
<BR>


<H3>June 5, 1998 </H3>
President Clinton signs into law a bill that links the national average life 
expectancy (ALE) and which raises the age of eligibility for Social Security 
benefits to 85 percent of the ALE. Scientists announce the results of a new 
drug they predict will cure most forms of cancer within 10 to 12 years. The 
death toll in Ypsilanti, Michigan reaches 3,147 as the search continues for 
Elijah Abraham, leader of the religious cult suspected of poisoning the city 
water supply.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="/november/hotfor.gif" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=285 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=right>
<H3>December 24, 1998 </H3>
The President signs H.R. 1712, banning cigarette smoking in all public places 
throughout the United States and takes effect April 10,1999. Moslem terrorists 
take credit for the destruction of six government facilities in Algeria, 
killing at least 3,500 and injuring thousands more government workers; 
ironically most of them are Moslems.
<BR>

<H3>January 24, 2001 </H3>
The gp120 vaccine preventing HIV infection and developed by Genentech received 
full approval from the FDA.  Those infected still await a cure. Days after 
Albert Gore's inauguration as President of the United States, North Koreans 
invade South Korea.  Premier Kim threatens to use nuclear weaponry if other 
countries interfere with what he calls "an internal Korean matter."
<BR>

<H3>September 2, 2002 </H3>
Bosnian terrorists drop a 15-kiloton nuclear bomb on Belgrade that vaporized 
several dozen city blocks. President Gore endorses a bill requiring 5 hours a 
week of preventative health classes. Average life expectancy in the U.S. 
reaches 80 years of age. The unveiling of "Swift and Sure Anti-Crime Bill" 
calls for imprisonment of first time offenders and mandatory death penalty for 
any second violent crimes committed.
<BR>

<H3>January 28, 2003 </H3>
United States, Russia, and China sign a joint space exploration agreement. Iran 
admits to having several dozen atomic weapons.
<BR>
<H3>
January 29, 2003</H3>
Iraq ratifies the Arab-Israeli Free-Trade Pact. FDA bans hydrogenated oils in 
foods. President Gore announces he will not seek re-election to help the 
Democratic Party.
<BR><H3>

May 17, 2003 </H3>
Philip Morris is placed in Chapter 7 bankruptcy liquidation bringing an end to 
the legal Tobacco industry in the United States. Prime Minister Ibuka of Japan 
calls for worldwide measures to slow global warming and the melting of the 
polar ice caps which have caused tidal waves and floods.
<BR>

<H3>October 23, 2004 </H3>
Violent crime continues to be the number one political issue with 22 million 
cases reported. AT&T files for Chapter 7 bankruptcy due to the competition with 
other companies and free internet and audio-visual communications.
<BR>

<H3>February 28, 2006 </H3>
Truth Machine Bill is signed, calling on private industry to develop a device 
that could detect intentional deceit. Fidel Castro dies from Alzheimer's 
disease. United Airlines begins 115-minute supersonic passenger service from 
New York City to Los Angeles.
<BR>

<H3>May 6, 2006 </H3>
The FDA approves of a new drug Exovir, a cure for AIDS. An Irish Catholic 
terrorist group takes credit for blowing a hole in the Chunnel linking Britain 
and France, drowning at least 1,378 motorists. Scientist in Berkeley, 
California have technology to predict earthquakes anywhere in the world at 
least four hours before they occur.
<BR>

<H3>
July 15, 2006 </H3>
The U.S. Postal Service seeks a private buyer. China's gross national product 
becomes the world's largest, just over $19 trillion.
<BR>

<H3>November 14, 2006 </H3>
Iraq dictator Saddam Hussein and millions of others killed by a nuclear 
incineration of Baghdad. Surgeon General Abigail Swenson announces Alzheimer's 
disease as second leading cause of death in the United States.
<BR>

<H3>November 20, 2006 </H3>
French scientist revives a mouse frozen for two weeks. Eastman Kodak reveals a 
new 360-degree digital video camera weighing under half an ounce.
<BR>

<H3>December 6, 2007 </H3>
Swift and Sure Anti-Crime Program reduces violent crime rates by 55 percent. 
The U.S. opens trade with United Korea.
<BR>

<H3>November 8, 2008 </H3>
After the 6th anniversary of his death in state prison, Congress declares Dr. 
Jack Kevorkian's birthday a national holiday, and historians consider him one 
of the most influential Americans of the 20th century.

<BR>

<H3>August 15, 2009 </H3>
Cocaine is legalized in the U.S. as prescription-only treatment for Attention 
Deficit Disorder. Iran and Iraq sign a mutual nuclear defense treaty. Saudi 
Arabia announces plans to halt production of crude oil due to plummeting demand 
and electric powered automobiles capturing 96% of worldwide sales.
<BR>


<H3>September 2, 2011 </H3>
President Hall reorganizes monetary exchange; thumbprints will replace 
signatures on checks and credit card purchases, and coins and paper money are 
eliminated.  Ukrainian terrorists shoot down six supersonic passenger planes 
near Moscow.

<BR>

<H3>November 6, 2012 </H3>
Election of the first African-American U.S. President. Food prices plummet and 
worldwide malnutrition has been nearly expunged because of more efficient 
methods of transportation. The U.S., Israel, and Iraq join forces to rebuild 
Baghdad. New legislation requires all new parents to pass a basic test on child 
raising, general health, and nutrition, and to sign a contract agreeing to 
uphold their obligation as parents.
<BR>


<H3>March 17, 2013</H3> 
Police apprehend six Irish terrorists who tried to detonate a five-megaton 
nuclear device in the heart of London. The UN General Assembly passes a 
resolution outlawing violence as a means of resolving disputes. Cuba officially 
becomes the 53rd state. Texas Instruments breaks ground on its 190-story world 
headquarters in Dallas.
<BR>

<H3>June 15, 2015</H3>
 An American, Russian, and Chinese crew land on Mars. The Pope denounces the 
U.S. legalization of cryonic suspension (deep-freezing of bodies at death for 
possible revival in the future) for terminally ill humans as "matters that 
should be determined by God.".
<BR>
<H3>
January 28, 2017 </H3>
Israeli Prime Minister Aaron Ben-Gurion takes responsibility for the 
incineration of Baghdad claiming Saddam Hussein, having been diagnosed with 
terminal pancreatic cancer, planned to detonate four nuclear weapons in 
Jerusalem, Mecca, Paris, and Damascus in attempt to start W.W.III.
<BR>

<H3>August 15, 2021</H3> 
The U.S. and Canada plan to jointly build the world's largest underwater city. 
Basque separatists ignite a second neutron bomb in Madrid adding drawn-out, 
agonizing deaths to the one million lives claimed by Spain's civil war.
<BR>

<H3>November 7, 2022</H3>
$1.1 billion dollars were spent on political advertising for a referendum to 
divide Texas into five states. Japan, the United States, and the United Nations 
pass legislation to ban the programming of survival instinct, emotion, or free 
will into any machine.
<BR>
<H3>
March 26, 2023</H3> 
The FDA approves preventative genetic treatment for Alzheimer's disease, the 
last incurable disease not linked to lifestyle. Meteorite crashes through the 
dome of the oldest of six biospheres on Earth's moon.
<BR>

<H3>February 29, 2024</H3> 
Ex-football star and former murder suspect O.J. Simpson, age 76, dies in 
gyrocopter crash in Encino, California.
<BR>

<H3>August 2, 2024</H3> 
The Armstrong Cerebral Image Processor (a.k.a. The Truth Machine) received full 
and immediate governmental approval for use in judicial process. Jacques 
Peureux, the French software magnate, becomes the first human being to be 
successfully cloned. Former food-processing executive, Samuel Wesley Conwell is 
executed for murder of 12,626 person using genetically altered pineapple juice.
<BR>

<H3>August 6, 2024 </H3>
Mitsubishi releases an artificial gill that allows humans to breathe underwater 
for days at a time. Los Angeles suffers the worst earthquake in history 
measuring 9.6 on the Richter scale and destroying all highways and buildings 
constructed before 2005.
<BR>
<H3>
August 10, 2024 </H3>
Truth Machines are installed throughout the U.S. judicial system. Karachi 
sentences to death 14 U.S. executives for their role in an environmental 
disaster which killed 130,000 Pakistanis.
<BR>
<IMG SRC="/november/admire.gif" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=331 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>
<H3>
August 11, 2024 </H3>
The FDA shows that obesity drastically reduced in the United States.  Over 90 
percent of all Americans are now within 3 pounds of ideal weight as the result 
of computerized time-release appetite regulating system.  Nearly all Americans 
now use the system, at least occasionally.
<BR>
<H3>
August 25, 2024 </H3>
Microsoft founder and Chairman Emeritus William H. Gates delivers keynote 
address and the first annual Nanotechnology Conference, claiming nanomachines, 
built at the molecular level and already smaller than human cells, can be 
designed for diverse purposes.
<BR>

<H3>July 4, 2026 </H3>
The President lowers federal tax due to budget surplus after greater compliance 
and near elimination of tax fraud.
<BR>

<H3>November 7, 2028</H3> 
A new federal law goes into effect, allowing Truth Machine testing for 
employment, college and private school admission.
<BR>

<H3>May 16, 2031 </H3>
With the aid of the Truth Machine, it is learned that nearly everyone had 
committed a crime in their life. Amnesty Bill passed promising a less severe 
punishment for people who confess to crimes prior to January 1, 2032.  Over 56 
million individuals confess to crimes. Serial killer Carlos Francisco confessed 
during an employment interview with the Truth Machine to being responsible for 
over 75,000 nanomachine-induced deaths.
<BR>

<H3>November 4, 2032 </H3>
After legalized private use of the Truth Machine, the divorce rate falls, 
finding that honesty strengthens marriages.
<BR>

<H3>January 20, 2037</H3> 
Inauguration of the first woman President of the United States.
<BR>

<H3>February 16, 2041</H3>
The average life expectancy is now over 100 years in the United States.
<BR>
<H3>
June 15, 2045 </H3>
World Government is officially installed in Sydney, Australia. Sun 
Microsystems, Texas Instruments, and CyCare Systems release their own Truth 
Machine projects.
<BR>

<H3>August 5, 2046</H3> 
Opening ceremony of Aries One, the first permanent colony on Mars.  Motorola 
and the ATI Medical Division join efforts to develop therapies to extend human 
life beyond its natural 130-year span by repairing DNA with nanomachines.
<BR>
<H3>
December 5, 2047 </H3>
World President signs the International Weather Control Act to construct 
weather-proof domes over every city.
<BR>

<H3>August 13, 2049</H3> 
Albert Einstein and Nelson Mandela are slated as the first two subjects to 
undergo cloning from sample of their DNA.
<BR>
<H3>
September 8, 2049 
</H3>The World Health Department announces bionic restoration of all disabled people.

</blockquote>   
<P>
