<html>

<head>

<title>george jr. / november 1996 / arcadia / the uneasy chair</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0"
ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/november/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoa.gif" WIDTH=150
HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34
border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<img src="/graphics/uneasy.gif" width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15
VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

With the national presidential elections practically history, the 
leadership styles and abilities of candidates Bill Clinton and Bob Dole 
have been under close scrutiny from other politicians, the media and the 
American public.
In choosing a candidate, voters always are faced with many questions: 
What makes a great leader? Do either the Republican or Democratic 
candidates exhibit great leadership? What do we, the people, require of 
our leaders as we stand at the turn of the century? Does our political 
system allow for the kind of leadership we expect from public servants? 
Can we count on politicians, who want to be elected and re-elected, to 
lead in our best interests?
 <p>



James MacGregor Burns  is one of the nation's best-known and prolific 
scholars of American political history. The Pulitzer Prize-winning author 
of many books of political history including <I>The Power to Lead</I> 
(1984); <I>Roosevelt: The Soldier of Freedom</I>
(1970, for which he won the Prize); and<I> Government By the People,</I> 
a widely used American college text since 1951, Burns has spoken with 
most of the important politicians of our time.
 

<P>

Burns is generally considered to be one of the  foremost experts on 
political leadership. He is Woodrow Wilson Professor of Government, 
Emeritus, at Williams College; and Senior Scholar, Center for Political 
Leadership and  Participation at the University of Maryland at College 
Park.
<br clear=all>
<hr width=80%>

<blockquote>


<font size=5>q. </font> What makes a good leader?  Is there a formula for 
effective leadership style?

<br>


<font size=5>a. </font> Commitment, conviction, strong purpose; all 
grounded in a set of explicit values.
<p>
<font size=5>q.</font> How does a politician's personal values, or morality, fit 
into the scheme of leadership? Is "good character" necessary to being a 
good leader?<br>
<font size=5>a. </font>I think there are two levels of values.  One is 
what you might call "public values." These are the great American values 
like liberty, equality, justice, community that I think relate to all of 
us in the nation.  The other set is what you might call "ethical values," 
which are much more personal.  These present the ethical questions of how 
we deal with one another: Do we interact with honesty, with trust, with 
responsibility?
<P>
<font size=5>q. </font> Do public values and ethical values together make 
up what you have called "real and total character"?

<br>


<font size=5>a. </font> Again, there are two kinds of character.  One 
kind of leadership character is that of a leader who makes commitments, 
and, in terms of basic, accepted values, tries to live up to those 
commitments, fights for these values, and shows his or her character 
through that kind of commitment. The other level of character, is of 
those people who may not feel so strongly about the great values like 
liberty, equality and justice. They feel more strongly about personal 
ethics and personal behavior. Ideally, leaders ought to combine the two 
levels. They should be great believers in public values, but they should 
also be great believers in personal character and ethical behavior. I 
think you can say that George Washington combined belief in the great 
public values and in personal values, what might be called virtues.

<P>


The problem arises when the two levels clash, when a leader is pursuing 
great public values and feels that he or she must violate certain 
personal values.


<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> You've made the distinction between two different 
kinds of leaders, and you have said that President  Clinton's problem was 
that he hadn't  "decided what kind of leader he wants to be - a broker 
who wheels and deals or a visionary who takes a strong stand and sticks 
to it" (AARP Bulletin, November, 1994). Do you still feel this way about 
President Clinton?

<br>



<font size=5>a. </font> Well, I think this is a question about what kind 
of strategic leader you want to be. He does believe in certain great 
values but I think it comes down, for him, to more of a tactical 
situation: to what extent do you fight for your values, such as justice 
and fairness for the poor even though fighting for them may be 
politically unpopular. Clinton is a good example of someone who does have 
strong public values, but is not willing to risk defeat by pursuing these 
values as strongly as he might. The now-classic example is the welfare 
bill he signed.


<P>

And that raises another great political question: to what extent do you 
want to follow the people, follow the crowd, and always try for 
electability, or reelectibility? 

<P>

To what extent do you take the plunge and fight for something you believe 
in even though it's not very popular.  I don't think Clinton has resolved 
this issue. I think he wants to do the
right thing, but above all, he fears defeat.  In American politics, 
defeat is a very serious matter. The American public is not very kind to 
people who lose.


<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> Do you feel that President Clinton's leadership 
style has changed? What about his recent and continuing intervention in 
attempting to restore peace in the Middle East? Is there a difference 
between his domestic leadership and his international leadership?


<br>



<font size=5>a. </font>

 I do think that he's learned a lot from experience. I think the whole 
White House has become better organized, more deliberate, more effective 
in planning ahead. They've been better to sticking with their path in 
dealing with the Middle East and Haiti - you have a sense of continuous 
effort, but that is a separate thing from willingness to make a 
commitment, that is the right thing to do, but is politically unpopular.


<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> Political scientists have long discussed whether 
politicians should serve as agents for the will of the people, or if they 
should act as trustees, directed by their own personal interests. Do you 
think that leaders today are more like agents of a collective opinion, or 
more like individuals with good taste?

<br>


<font size=5>a. </font> The short answer is a question: do you do what 
the majority of the people want you to do, or do you do what you think is 
right? I think the people want the politicians to do what they think is 
right. They choose people who maybe even go against the peoples' 
interests because the people feel the politicians are doing something 
right. So it's not just a question of following the people. It's a 
question of leading the people.


<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> Can you compare the leadership styles of 
President Clinton and candidate Bob Dole, given this framework of 
leadership? Has Dole come to a better understanding of leadership? Has he 
better resolved this conflict between leading and following?

<br>


<font size=5>a. </font> The way that I differentiate between Dole and 
Clinton is through a concept we in political science call the difference 
between the "transforming" leader and the "transactional" leader. The 
transforming leader is the kind of person we've been talking about here, 
who wants to make basic changes, who's willing to risk unpopularity to 
try to make those changes. In contrast, there's the transactional leader, 
who is much more of a broker, much more of a conciliator, a mediator, a 
transactor. This kind of politician is typically not so much interested 
in fundamental change as
in simply being a broker among contending interests.  The transactional 
leader is constantly mediating between factions. This is a very important 
kind of leadership. 

<P>

It's really what keeps the system going because we're constantly trying 
to get agreement among different people. Since we have such a separated 
form of government, we desperately need these kinds of leaders.


<P>

I think Dole is the consummate transactional leader, in that he will know 
how to deal with both parties in the House and in the Senate. He'll know 
how to deal with the various interest groups, and he'll be very adroit on 
that score. But this raises basic leadership questions because the 
transactional leader is a very special kind of leader.  It's a very 
restricted, though very crucial role to play. You're really following 
other
people all the time, bringing people together; you're a compromiser -- 
you get people to compromise. That's a far cry from the transforming 
leader who has a vision of basic change.


<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> Would you characterize Clinton as a transforming 
leader? <br>
<font size=5>a. </font> I once talked to him about this. I think he wants 
to be a transforming leader but has discovered that the American 
political system makes it very difficult to do that. The system 
constantly calls for the broker.


<p>


<font size=5>q. </font>In your book <i>The Deadlock of Democracy: Four 
Party Politics in America,</i>  you discuss the problem of political 
gridlock. Do you think that leaders have perpetuated this gridlock or 
tried to overcome it? In other words, is gridlock a cause of failed 
leadership, or a result of failed leadership?

<br>


<font size=5>a </font>I think failures of leadership in this country 
are, to a great extent, the result of our gridlocked system. We have an 
anti-leadership system, an anti-transforming leadership system, but it's 
a system that is pro-transactional leadership. Leaders  can claim that 
the system makes it very difficult to bring about major, planned change. 
Have they done anything about the system? The answer is, no. Anytime you 
talk to
politicians about fundamental change,  like constitutional change, they 
say it's too hot too handle. They think it's sacred, or they think the 
people think it's sacred. They essentially accept an anti-leadership 
system even though it makes their own leadership so difficult.


<P>


<font size=5>q. </font> What about women in leadership? I know that one 
of your main focuses has been on women leaders. Where do you think women, 
as leaders, are positioned in our culture? Are they transactional or 
transforming leaders? Are they allowed to be leaders at all? You said 
that women are able to bring "nurturing and caring and compassion and 
communal qualities or emphases" to the political arena (<i>Dallas Morning 
News</i>, May 1993). Are women only allowed to participate in that sphere 
of leadership? Can leadership be gender neutral?

<br>


<font size=5>a. </font> I am particularly interested in leadership by 
women; it's part of my general interest in leadership. I think the 
American system is particularly hard on women because the American 
system, with its divided powers, builds so much petty conflict into the 
system that it's not something that women leaders, on the whole, 
naturally take to. Now there are women leaders who are much tougher than 
men, such as former Prime Minister of Britain Margaret Thatcher.

<P>


But I do think that women bring different qualities to politics than men, 
on the whole. And I think they find that this super-competitive system is 
incredibly hostile and mean-spirited. I think women, on the whole, find 
this exceedingly difficult. I think women in particular have a stake in 
fundamental change of the system.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

This interview, by<B> Meghan Searles</B>, originally appeared in the 
<I>Williams Record</I>,  a weekly newspaper written, edited, and 
published by Williams College students; and is published in <b>george 
jr.</b> with the permission of Williams College.




</blockquote>
