<head>

<title>george jr. / november 1996 / departments / national public rodeo (week 1)</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/november/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<B>It's a woman thing</B>


<P></P>

  <I> Woman Thing Music</I> CD is the first on the new Virginia Slims Woman Thing Music label. The CD is a collaboration between Emmy Award-winning daytime television actress  Martha Byrne and producer and musician Nile Rodgers.
  

<P> </P>

  The CD  will coincide with the ten-city tour in the spring of 1997.  Martha Byrne will be the headline performer in each of the tour markets including Dallas, New Orleans, Baltimore, Birmingham, New York, Atlanta, Detroit, Charlotte, Chicago and  St. Louis.
   

<P></P>

  The format of the program will afford local  bands with the opportunity to highlight their musical talent and create more visibility for themselves in their respective markets. Bands that are  led  by females or have female members, 21 years old or over, will perform at  popular clubs in their communities and will compete to become the opening act for Martha Byrne when she performs in that market.
   

<P></P>

  Rodgers' old band, Chic, sold more than 10 million units. Chic's recording of<I> Le Freak </I>still  holds  the record for the largest selling single in the history of Warner  Communications. Nile continues to produce new and exciting work. Career successes include Nile's work With Diana Ross, David Bowie and Jeff Beck.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<B>And speakin' of freaks</B>


     

<P></P>

Science writer Patrick Huyghe has created a guide to the extraterrestrials in the fully illustrated <I>The Field Guide to Extraterrestrials</I> (Avon, $12.50), which, yep, has pictures of your neighbors, the butcher and the policeman who always smiles at you when you drive by. 


<P></P>

A recent Roper Survey suggests that five million Americans may have been abducted by UFO  aliens. So much for Roper. The author presents four major types of alien classification: humanoid, animalian, robotic and exotic.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<B>Voyaging with Gould, Minsky
</B>



<P></P>

Two cool new CD-ROMS out from Voyager Co.: <I>First Person: Stephen Jay Gould-On Evolution</I> and<I> First Person: Marvin Minsky-The Society of Mind.</I>
  

<P></P>

  <I>First Person: Stephen Jay Gould </I>features the entire text of three books: Gould's <I>Bully for Brontosaurus,</I> Charles Darwin's <I>The Voyage of  the Beagle</I> and Darwin's <I>The Origin of Species;</I> an exclusive sixty-minute video lecture by Gould, hypertext links between the lecture and hundreds of additional historical documents; and over one hundred graphs and illustrations.  Gould teaches biology, geology, and the history of science at Harvard University and contributes a monthly column to<I> Natural History</I> magazine.


<P></P>

In 
<I>First Person: Marvin Minsky-The Society of Mind</I>, Minsky's theories come to life as the visionary thinker walks, talks, and jumps across the page, challenging conventional notions of what makes us tick. <I>First Person: Marvin Minsky</I> includes the full text of <I>The Society of Mind</I>, as well as a selection of Minsky's best articles, a video timeline, over 100 minutes of original and archival video, over 200 color graphics, over 1,100 pages of text, and an interactive tour of Minsky's living room.
Voyager titles are available from selected bookstores, software outlets, and directly from Voyager. Visit the Voyager Web site at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.voyagerco.com/">www.voyagerco.com</A> or call 800-446-2001.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<B>
Knipl the lovable goon
</B>


<P></P>

 Simon says, check out, Julius Knipl, Real Estate Photographer by Ben Katchor
(Little, Brown and Co.). In this long-awaited collection of strange and strangely absorbing urban adventures, Julius Knipl, Real Estate Photographer, takes to the streets to discover a lost metropolis and its residents, summoning up half-forgotten yesterdays and celebrating the surreal substrate of the quotidian. 

<P></P>

The ninety stories collection Ñ some a single strip, others many pages long and never published before Ñ include the tales of <I>The Evening Combinator</I>, a daily tabloid that chronicles the city's boisterous dreamlife. Join Knipl for the sights and reveries. The guy has his own <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.spacelab.net/~bkatchor/">web site</A>, too.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<B>Public Shelter wins big
</B>



<P></P>

EJL ProductionsÕ first  CD-ROM title, Jayne Loader's<I> Public Shelter</I> won two  NewMedia INVISION Awards at Comdex/Spring, where the  year's best new media applications were honored. 
 

<P></P>

<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.publicshelter.com/">Public Shelter</A>, inspired by Loader's classic film, <I>The Atomic Cafe</I>, expands the found footage concept to  the field of multimedia.  The disc contains 30 minutes  of video -much of it unseen since the 1950s -400 photographs,  18 original songs, 12 hours of audio and 1400 text files  (a total of 15 meg of fully searchable text) all pertaining to atomic weapons and energy, from the Trinity Test to  the present.  Atomic testing, nuclear waste, and human  radiation experiments are all prominently featured. 

<P></P>

Loader's books include <I>Wild America</I>, a collection of  short stories, and <I>Between Pictures</I>, a tawdry Hollywood 
novel, both published by Grove Press to great critical  acclaim.  The Website she created for the Public Shelter  project has received numerous awards for excellence.   Loader also writes a popular online column, <I>WWWench</I>.  

<P><hr width=75%><P>

<b>See you next Sunday.</b>
<HR><BR>

