<IMG SRC="/graphics/rodeo.gif" WIDTH=185 HEIGHT=132 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=30>
<br><br>

<B>Concerts on the half shell
   
</B>
<P></P>

   Progressive Networks, developers of RealAudio, and House of Blues Entertainment,  jammed their new Internet web site, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.liveconcerts.com/">LiveConcerts.com</A>, with a bunch o' concerts in October.  Shows are scheduled regularly every Wednesday and Sunday night at 7 pm PT (10 pm ET).  November shows  include  The  Cure  (Nov. 3), The Connells, Popa Chubby, and a special presentation of the Seattle End Fest. Full schedules are available on the Internet at<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.liveconcerts.com/"> http://www.liveconcerts.com.</A>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>





  
<B>Screen gems</B> 
   

<P> </P>

 The <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.voyagerco.com
/">Voyager </A>company celebrates the latest addition to the Voyager web site: <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.homevisioncinema.com/">Home Vision Cinema</A>. Home Vision Cinema opens the door to one of the most distinguished and critically acclaimed film libraries available on VHS.


<P></P>

Home Vision Cinema's rather cool film library makes accessible masterworks that span cinema's century-old history. The Home Vision catalog features the works of Kurosawa, Fellini, Truffaut, Bergman, Tati, Carne, Cocteau, Renoir, Reed, Welles, and many other landmark directors. This new site rounds out the Voyager effort to distribute classic films directly to customers over the internet, on VHS tape and laserdisc.


<P></P>


Home Vision takes painstaking care to present the most requested masterpieces and rare formative films on video in editions unprecedented in quality, using the same master materials as Voyager's standard-setting Criterion laserdisc collection. They have been restored to their original brilliance with up-to-date translations and enhanced subtitles. Many of these rare gems are available for the first time on video in the popular letterbox format with long-lost footage.



<P></P>

Home Vision Cinema Online features the complete Home Vision VHS catalog, including information about all of the films in the collection, essays by film scholars on the most important films ever made, and downloadable clips from the most popular films in the Home Vision library. Each week a different classic film will be discounted by 20 percent. (Ahoy, mates! This discount is only available over the Internet.) The site features a secure ordering system for online transactions.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<B>
 Animation Design Guide</B>

   

<P></P>

The face of the World Wide Web is changing, and Web page designers are constantly striving to surpass othersÕ efforts.<I> The Web Publisher s 3D & Animation Design Guide for Macintosh</I> features step-by-step instructions for using 3D graphics and animation to make your site the most talked about on the Web. Written by an expert Web designer and featuring the works of 30 top Web artists, it includes a bunch of things you need to master the creation of 3D rooms and objects, and teaches you the ins and outs of using VRML, 3D-processed sound, animation, and more.
   

<P></P>

YouÕll get detailed descriptions of the most popular rendering and animation software, and specific instructions for setting up real time chat rooms and palace servers, understanding rendering speeds, and adding sound to a 3D site. 
   

<P></P>

The companion CD-ROM includes the best 3D design and animation tools, artwork samples, multimedia files, and other resources that will help you create and design eye-popping Web pages. <I> Web Publisher s 3D & Animation Design Guide for Macintosh</I>, by  Mary Jo Fahey, costs $39.99 from Coriolis.
   

<P></P>

<I> Web Publisher 's 3D & Animation Design Guide for Windows</I>, which is pretty much the same deal, includes a chapter about Windows NT hardware that discusses rendering forms on a Windows NT network, MicrosoftÕs drag-and-drop interface, and   products for use with Windows NT. A real-life case study details the integration of a hybrid network. This baby, also by Fahey, retails for $39.99 from<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.coriolis.com  /"> Coriolis</A>.      
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>


 <B> Danger, Will Robinson</B>


    

<P></P>

 Now that NASA has discovered proof  of life on Mars, New Line Cinema is moving towards the launch of its own project about planetary exploration by announcing that Stephen Hopkins will direct  and produce the upcoming science fiction adventure film, <I>Lost In Space</I>.
    

<P></P>

 With a director on board and a February 1, 1997 start date, all systems are go for the studio to move ahead with the film adaptation of the classic 1960's television series.
   

<P> </P>

 New Line secured the remake rights to the material from Prelude Pictures, whose Chairman Mark Koch will produce the film. Veteran  filmmakers  Mace Neufeld and Robert Rehme will executive produce. Akiva Goldsman (<I>A  Time  To Kill, Batman and Robin</I>) wrote the screenplay and will also produce.  New Line is preliminarily slating the film for a late '97 or early '98 release  date.
   

<P></P>

 <I> Lost in Space,</I> which ran on CBS from 1965 to 1968, chronicled the adventures of the Robinson family, the crew of a sabotaged spaceship. 

<P><hr width=75%><P>

