<head>
<title>george jr. / november 1996 / departments / the joy of lex</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/november/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>


<H2>william kennedy: iron will & 'Ironwood'</H2> 
<h3><i>by nicholas a. basbanes</i></h3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

   Albany, N.Y., author William Kennedy spent several decades of his adult life as a journalist who "did it all,'' from covering politics, sports, spot news and crime to writing obituaries, columns, reviews, and editorials. 
<p>
   But somewhere along the way, he maintains, "something happened to my head and I turned into a novelist." The result of this creative metamorphosis has been the production of what Kennedy calls his Albany Cycle, a series of related books that do for New York's capital city what the Snopes, Sartoris, Benbow and Compson families did for the region in northern Mississippi that William Faulkner called Yoknapatawpha County.
<p>   Titles in Kennedy's oeuvre include <I>The Ink Truck Legs, Billy Phelan's Greatest Game, Ironweed, Quinn's Book</I> and<I> Very Old Bones</I>, to which now is added <I>The Flaming Corsage</I> (Viking, $23.95), a daring exploration of unbridled passion and the power of the imagination that turns on two events separated by three decades. 
   <p>At 209 pages, <I>The Flaming Corsage</I> is the most compactly written work in Kennedy's cycle, yet because of a clever structure that incorporates an actual disaster, slashing jumps in time, coinciding plots, a bona fide mystery and a fragmentary play-within-a-novel, it just may be his most ambitious. And his dialogue, as always, is crisp, evocative and unfailingly on target. 
<p>   "I started thinking about this right after I finished work on <I>Billy Phelan</I> in 1976, and my intention at that time was to write a whole play, and have a play and a novel in the same volume,'' Kennedy said in a recent interview. "The play would be a kind of coda, a parallel element, and they would work together."
<IMG SRC="/november/cranium.gif" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=174 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=left>

<p>    Once embarked on the project, though, Kennedy encountered problems. "I found at that time that to write a whole play would be ambitious beyond my capacity," he said, especially since the play in question was to be written by Edward Daugherty, a renowned playwright whose experiences are at the center of<I> The Flaming Corsage.</I>
<p>   "My primary purpose, I do believe, was an unconscious one, to make myself equal to Edward Daugherty, in order to invent him,'" Kennedy said with a wry smile. He also encountered a few other problems, not all of them structural.
<p>   "I just didn't know who all these people were at the time," he continued. "I had some ideas about them, but I didn't really know, to cite one instance, what happened in the love nest," by which he was referring to the opening scene of the book where an unidentified man bursts into a Manhattan hotel room, kills his wife, wounds another man - Edward Daugherty, it turns out - and then commits suicide; another woman in the room, an actress, escapes unharmed. 
<p>  "It was all a mystery to me, and the reason it was a mystery is because everybody was lying," Kennedy said. "They were lying to me as well as lying to one another, and it took me many, many thrusts and parries to arrive at the conclusion of who was in there, and what they were doing in there."
<p>   Putting <I>The Flaming Corsage</I> aside, Kennedy proceeded to write <I>Ironweed</I>, which focused on the redemptive homecoming of Francis Phelan, a former professional baseball player turned alcoholic vagabond, and the father of Billy the pool shark, the title character of <I>Billy Phelan's Greatest Game</I>. 
<p>   Easily one of the great American novels of the past 25 years, <I>Ironweed</I> was a best-seller that provided the basis for an exceptional film, won the Pulitzer Prize and National Book Award in 1983, and persuaded the MacArthur Foundation to give Kennedy a $250,000 "genius grant."
<p>   Coincidental to the recent publication of <I>The Flaming Corsage</I> in hardcover is release in trade paperback of <I>An Albany Trio </I>(Penguin, 606 pages, $17.95), which gathers in one volume Legs, <I>Billy Phelan's Greatest Game</I> and <I>Ironweed</I>.
<IMG SRC="/november/haunt.gif" WIDTH=220 HEIGHT=278 HSPACE=15 ALIGN=right>
<p>   Of particular interest is Kennedy's introduction to the collection called <I>Prelude in a Saloon</I>, a six-page piece that explains - in the form of a short story - how, in Kennedy's words, "the Albany Cycle came to be." It is a must read for any reader interested in the highways and byways of a consummate novelist's fictive road map, and provides a window into the workings of the creative process.
<p>   "I decided, for this little piece, to make Danny Quinn the  author of the Albany Cycle," Kennedy explained during our interview. "I chose Danny because he connects with everyone. He is Francis Phelan's grandson. He's George Quinn and Peg Phelan's son, just 10 years old in <I>Ironweed</I>. He grows up and goes into the Army, and he's a pal of Orson Purcell in <I>Very Old Bones</I>. They were in the Army together in Germany. He's also the grandson of Daniel Quinn of<I> Quinn's Book</I>."
<p>   As complicated as these relationships may sound, they are clear to appreciate readers of the Albany Cycle, especially since each book is propelled along by its own narrative force.
<p>   In the introductory piece to <I>An Albany Cycle</I>, Danny Quinn is interviewing Morty Besch, an old gangster who used to hang out with Legs Diamond. The meeting has been set up by Billy Phelan, who becomes prominent in the conversation, convincing Danny that Billy needed his own book, which in due course meant he had to
write the story of Billy's father Francis.
<p>   Thus was born a concept which Danny Quinn/William Kennedy describes as "an open-ended cycle of lives: the story of one man or woman begetting another, all of them counting time in the shared continuum of common ground, common history."
<p>And taken together, Quinn/Kennedy concludes, the corpus emerges as a sequence of "tragicomedies" that are distinctively different from one another, yet "kindred as blood: a mosaic of space, a collage of time."
<blockquote>
Nicholas A. Basbanes is a Massachusetts journalist and author. His book, <I>A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the Eternal Passion for Books</I>, was a finalist this year for the National Book Critics Circle Award in nonfiction.

</blockquote>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
