<title>george jr. / november 1996 / departments / weights & measures - sapphire</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/november/departments.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotod.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<H2>weights & measures</H2>
<h3>sapphire : when push comes to shove</h3>
<B>by nicholas a. basbanes</B>
<blockquote>
<img src=sapphire.jpg align=right width=176 height=220>
For 10 years of her adult life, a writer known as Sapphire lived in a tenement off Lenox Avenue in the heart of Harlem, a real-life setting she has used impressively in a controversial novel of misery and redemption called <I>Push</I> (Knopf, 179 pages, $20).
<p>  In the novel, Claireece Precious Jones, a 16-year-old girl known simply as Precious, relates the horrific details of a stolen childhood without hint of guile or false pathos. 
<p>  The degradations Precious has endured range from the obscene to the unspeakable. Yet, in an oddly affecting way, her story is one of measured triumph, not abject defeat, and the instrument of her bittersweet victory is the awakening gift of literacy.
<p>  Precious is a desperately impoverished African-American child of the 1980s who is profoundly abused by her dysfunctional parents and ignored by a largely indifferent society. Overweight and ridiculed by other children, her language is the language of the woefully uneducated - broken, minimally functional, and totally devoid of conventional verbal forms.
<p>  Virtually enslaved and frequently abused by a slothful mother, Precious tells of being repeatedly raped and degraded by her father for most of her life. As the novel opens, she is pregnant by him for a second time. 
<p>   Later, Precious will learn that she is HIV positive, a devastating disclosure that lets the reader know the fragility of her long-term prospects, and wonder what will become of her first child, a 4-year-old girl with Down's Syndrome, and Abdul, her 2- year-old son.
<p>  With so many daunting obstacles placed cleverly in the child's path, it is easy to describe<I> Push</I> as a work of anger, defiance and accusation, which is how some readers, including a number of African-Americans sensitive to the portrayal of the girl's socially parasitic parents, and men of all races who perceive themselves as the enemy, have already responded. 
<p>  But then there is the matter of the girl's participation in an alternative education program, and the attention she gets from an inspired teacher who introduces her to the rudiments of reading, encourages her to maintain a daily journal, and communicates with her through writing.
<p>   Toward the end of the novel, Precious tells how she enjoys sitting with her son in the dayroom of a halfway house, where she is living apart from her mother:
<p>   "The sun is coming through the window splashing down on him, on the pages of his book. It's called  The Black BC's I love to hold him on my lap, open up the world to him. When the sun shine on him like this, he is an angel child. Brown sunshine. And my heart fill."
<p>   The strikingly mixed reaction to <I>Push </I>-  which gets its title from the instructions Precious receives from nurses during childbirth - has not been lost on the author, a 45-year-old California native who moved to New York City in 1977 with hopes of getting an education and becoming a writer.
<p>   Sapphire, also known by her family name, Ramona Lofton, worked as a go-go dancer near Times Square to support herself while attending City College, where she graduated win 1983. For the next seven years, she taught reading to teenagers and adults in Harlem and the Bronx.
<p>   "The address is made up in the novel, but I lived in the building where Precious grows up for 10 years," Sapphire said during a recent interview.  
<p>   "I saw a generation of kids who were 6 and 7 when I got there have babies, go off to jail, get killed. I'm in the neighborhood seeing all that, and at the same time I'm teaching, and it's devastating to me."
<p>   The daughter of a career Army sergeant who grew up on military bases around the country, Sapphire said she changed her name while living in San Francisco during the 1970s. 
<p>  "Everybody took a gemstone name during the days of the New Age movement," she said with a light laugh. "And there was a time in African-American culture where 'Sapphire' had a negative connotation - so I took the name to make a statement."
<p>   After graduating from City College, Sapphire enrolled in a master of fine arts program at Brooklyn College, where she studied writing under the novelist Susan Fromberg Schaffer, who recommended she show a rough draft of<I> Push</I> to a literary agent.  Knopf offered her a two-book contract for $500,000, and issued a 75,000-copy first printing of Push. 
<p>  Sapphire said Precious is a composite of several children she knew, and is not modeled on any single individual. 
<p>  "The good news is that two-thirds of African-American children have made it out of poverty. This book is for the one-third who remain behind. For a victim of repeated failure like Precious to break out and come into language is as good as graduating from Harvard."
<p>   For those who think of Push as an "angry book" Sapphire replies by saying that anger was not her intent. "I didn't write it to make people feel bad or to make people feel guilty," she said. 
<p>  "I think of it as a window with the shade pulled down. You open the shade, and you can see. This was something that most people hadn't been able to see before. Now they can see it."
<blockquote>
Nicholas A. Basbanes is a Massachusetts journalist and author. His book, <I>A Gentle Madness: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the Eternal Passion for Books</I>, was a finalist this year for the National Book Critics Circle Award in nonfiction.
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<P>
