<title>george jr. / december 1996 / features / opening gambit</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/december/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<img src="/graphics/gambit.gif" hspace=10 width=150 height=100 ALIGN=left HSPACE=15 VSPACE=15 ALT="">
<br>
<B>Welcome to December's issue</B>
 <P></P> Don't let a little hoarfrost get you down.<P></P> 

<b>george jr.</b>
is here to bring you a cup of nog and a hodge of writing
                                                         talent, book 
talk, wishful thinking,  art
                                                         and literary 
links and, we hope, a measure of digitized comfort.

<P></P> 
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>   
   This month,<B> Wendell Berry </B>talks about technology and ecology. Gnostic bibliophile <B>Harold Bloom</B> eyes religion as the century grows a beard. The Canadian essayist <B>Margaret Visser</B>, an old favorite here, writes about, oh, we've just forgotten. In "The Joy of Lex," correspondent <b>Nicholas A. Basbanes</b> found out <B>Donald Hall,</B> who muses on what makes his much acclaimed poems tick. And <B>Kitty</B>, of course, tells or gives you what for.  Dublin painter <B>Michael Bowers</B> contributed this month's oil-on-linen cover painting, titled "Color Study - George Myers Jr.," posed in the manner of <b>James Whistler</b>'s "Portrait of Thomas Carlyle."  The subject's hands, you'll note, are froze in html agony.<P></P> 
   <b>Patrick Lennon</b>, the novelist and short-story writer who begins contributing a "Letter from Key West" with this issue, is enjoying, by the way, better weather than most of us. "The Southernmost town" doth have its charms.  	"A number of years ago," he writes, "the 'Conch Republic' was created when the Customs
Service blocked US 1 to search for drugs. The Conch Republic immediately
surrendered to the Federal Government and asked for foreign aid.  Each year we celebrate the rebellion by throwing loaves of stale Cuban bread at representatives of the Federal Government."<P></P>
   
    Up to his elbows in work, <B>george jr.</B> is happy if you are - and also that this mild-mannered effort has been awarded "Hot Site" status by <i>USA Today</i> ; a "Cool" from Yahoo, Netsurfer Digest and <i>WebSight</i> , four stars from Magellan and Internet Voyager; applause, applause from the PRN Radio Network. <i>The Net</i>  magazine says we're "a good mark by which to judge all the rest," which gives us way too much performance anxiety.<P></P> 
    Ever dream a dream that you don't mind sharing? Send it or them to <a href="mailto:dreams@georgejr.com">george jr.'s dream issue</a> for just that; and don't miss participating in the fiction contest (well, really it's a sing-along) next month.<P></P> 
    Enjoy, because tomorrow the employees could go on strike.<P></P> 

</blockquote>   

<P>

<HR><BR>

<a href="/december/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>





