<head>

<title>george jr. / december 1996 / features / harold bloom in endtime</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" ALINK="#c0c0c0">

<a href="/december/features.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotof.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 border=0 align=right></A>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<br>

<H2>heavenly days:</H2> 

<h1>harold bloom in endtime</h1>
<B>by nicholas a. basbanes</B>


<P>


<br clear=all>

<hr width=80%>



<blockquote>
It isn't often that literary critics write books that become best sellers, but then only one literary critic is named Harold Bloom.<p>
<IMG SRC="typewr2.gif" WIDTH="63" HEIGHT="60" BORDER=1 ALIGN="LEFT" BORDER="0" hspace=10 vspace =20>
   The man is a phenomenon, a reader in the purest sense who lives for the kind of nourishment that only the written word can provide. If the truth be known, Bloom's passion for knowledge has caused him to endure countless nights without sleep, and has contributed in the past to a severe case of bleeding ulcers and to a serious heart 
condition that required major surgery.<p>   Among the 22 books Bloom, 66, has written over the past 40 years, two of the most recent were surprisingly popular releases that prompted considerable controversy when they appeared.<p>
   In <I>The Book of J,</I> his 1990 book, Bloom boldly argued that a key text of the early Hebrew Bible was written by a woman, a hypothesis that occasioned brisk arguments in theology schools around the country.<p>
   Four years later, in <I>The Western Canon</I>, Bloom unequivocally articulated his position in a spirited debate that first surfaced a decade earlier, chiefly among feminist, Marxist, multicultural and Afrocentrist critics, and champions, like himself, of the traditional icons of Western literature. <P>
<P>
<H4>Dead White European Males</H4>

   At issue was the burning question of whether or not writers like Homer, Dante, Chaucer, Shakespeare, Cervantes, Rousseau, Goethe and Tolstoy, "Dead White European Males," as they are dismissively called in some academic circles, are "relevant"  to today's society, and whether they should continue to be taught in
American schools.<p>
<IMG SRC="deadwhite.gif" align=right WIDTH="230" HEIGHT="159" BORDER="0" hspace=10>
   In his latest effort, <I>Omens of Millennium</I> (Riverhead Books, 253 pages, $24.95), Bloom demonstrates a willingness to take on yet another brace of timely issues. The subtitle of this new book, "The Gnosis of Angels, Dreams, and 
Resurrection," clearly suggests a spiritual theme, but the genesis for the book goes far deeper than intellectual curiosity.  <p> "This is a very strange book, a weird book," Bloom readily offered during a recent interview at his home in New Haven, Conn., a short distance from Yale University where, as Sterling Professor of Humanities, he has the uncommon distinction of chairing a department of one.<p>
  "The problem with this book," he continued deliberately, "is that it's impossible to classify as a genre. It's not really a book about religion, even though the last chapter is a sermon. Maybe, in some sense, this entire book is a gnostic sermon. That's probably the answer - a gnostic sermon."<p>
   At that thought, Bloom laughed heartily. "A gnostic sermon is a joke, you see, since there can not be a gnostic sermon." He then explained what he meant by this. <p>
 "There can be a Protestant sermon, there can be a Judaic sermon, there can be a Muslim sermon, there can be a Catholic sermon, there can , I suppose, be a Buddhist sermon. But there can not be a gnostic sermon. That is because there is no one to
give it and no one to listen to it. And no place to hold it."<p>
   With that seeming paradox, Bloom laughed once again, and his good humor was contagious. Gnosticism, he pointed out, is a concept arguing that the knowledge of God resides in each  individual. <P>
<P>
<H4>The obsession with angels</H4>

   Indeed, the word  "gnosis" is generally defined to mean mystical or spiritual knowledge. Gnosticism has its roots in such ancient traditions as Jewish mysticism, Hellenistic mystery cults, Iranian religious dualism known as Zoroastrianism, and
Babylonian and Egyptian mythology. Widely influential in its time, much of early Christian doctrine was formulated in reaction to the Gnostic movement.
<br>

<IMG SRC="angels1.gif" WIDTH="294" HEIGHT="118" BORDER=0 ALIGN="LEFT">
<br clear=all>
<IMG SRC="angels2.gif" WIDTH="158" HEIGHT="222" BORDER=0 ALIGN="LEFT">

  More to the point of  <I>Omens of Millennium</I>, though, is the wide-ranging discussion Bloom offers on the current fascination in popular culture for angels, prophetic dreams, the near-death experience, and New Age philosophy.<p>
   "This book, in a sense, has been moving around in me for half-a-century, but the occasion for writing it was bemusement with this obsession that people, all of a sudden, have with angels, and this insane preoccupation with the near-death
experience, upon which I would say, well, all of life is a near-death experience."<p>



   Upon further contemplation, Bloom said he decided to write about a Western 
tradition of dream interpretation that goes back some 1,900 years before the writings of Sigmund Freud, and to include a deeply informed historical discussion of angels and
near-death experience through history.<p>
   "I thought I would write a gently humorous account trying to say, look, this New Age jazz is no good, and this popular debasement is no good either. There are all these people who buy these terrible New Age books, there are people who read all this
drivel about near-death experience, who read all this incredibly bad psychic dream stuff; so I wondered, do they have an authentic drive to understand what these matters really represent?"<p>
   On an elemental level, he added, the reason people are moved by such concerns, "is that this has always been the tradition of gnosis. This book took me two full years to write; it took as long to write this book as it did to write that huge book on the Western Canon."<p>
   The reason it took him two full years, he said after a meaningful pause, "was because I couldn't quite understand it myself at the start. I kept writing it and rewriting it. And finally, it wrote itself, more or less."<p>
   After another long pause, Bloom said, "I really have no idea what is going to happen to this book; I take it for granted that many reviewers will just be outraged by it."<p>
   <P>

<hr>
<blockquote>
<b>Nicholas A. Basbanes</b> is a Massachusetts journalist and author of <I> A Gentle: Bibliophiles, Bibliomanes, and the Eternal Passion for Books.</I>


</blockquote>
</blockquote>


