<br><br>


<h2>george jr.'s favorite christmas</h2>
<p>




This is a story about my favorite Christmas, LBJ's grandfather, the Pony 
Express and a placenta named Miles. It's why, in my mind, there never 
shall be a separation between church and the state of Texas.<P>
<br clear=all>
<blockquote>
   It stars my sister Melissa, who, at the time, was a Texan by choice; 
as well as a big dog named Amber; many stagehands and producers and three 
midwives.<P>

In the last year of Elvis and the Volkswagen Beetle, Melissa,  drove to 
the Austin airport, in labor, to meet my mother, a Victorian woman named 
Virginia who had borne three children without ever having witnessed one 
birth. She was about to become a saint.<P>
   My sister, her husband and daughter lived in a ramshackle one-story 
clapboard house in Buda, Texas (pop. a visible 12). This chalky house 
with green fence, white upright piano and wood-burning stove had been a 
Pony Express way station in the 1800s, and the home of LBJ's grandfather 
a bit after that. It was not grand.<P>
   My father, my grandfather and I were Pennsylvanians. We knew little 
about Texas birthings but, awaiting all of this back home, where we were 
willing as a packed suitcase. Off we went.<P>
 <IMG SRC="holly2.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="42" BORDER=0
ALIGN="LEFT"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" BORDER="0">
  Melissa and her husband, Roland, 
were to introduce us to lots of interesting friends in the Bigger 'n' 
Better State. Several were midwives. One was a woman named Joanne who 
liked to sit around her house naked while goats roamed in and out of her 
house - unless she was in the midst of her cycle, in which case she would 
fling the goats off the porch and grouch around with a fierce 
countenance.<P>
   At 4 a.m. Dec. 15, Melissa pushed one last time and Miles Ethan Stock 
landed in the arms of Roland, the midwives, two fire stokers, a baby 
catcher and a masseuse named Kathryn who, very soon, I was to covet.<P>
   Christmas was about to begin.<P><P>
   When the Pennsylvanians arrived Dec. 22, my mother, now a ghostly 
white, was well on her way.<P>
   By the time we had arrived, the little house was jigsawed in its 
deploy, and everyone looked slightly stunned - as though Halley's Comet 
had hit full force, carried off several of them and plunked them back 
into the Texas scrub.<P>
   A short, squat dog named Rosie scurried through the legs of the 
midwives and friends while, outside, the large yellow being named Amber 
loped up and down the trumk of a live oak. I swear, that dog climbed 
trees.<P>
   Nearby was a little mound where Roland and Melissa had buried their 
baby's placenta, for good luck, they said. Texans are unlike you and 
me.<P>
   A lot had happened that week that never had happened before.<P>
   My mother, who took great pains to volunteer herself to my birthing 
sister, wilted at the sight of us.<P>
   It had been a trying week. She had tried to cook what she thought was 
a road runner she found in the freezer. (It wasn't. It was an 
experimental chicken from Texas A&M's veterinary school that Roland's 
father had beheaded prior to our arrival.) This odd shaped fowl would 
neither cook, steam, boil, fry nor bake, as my mother tried them all.<P>
 <IMG SRC="blender.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="46" HSPACE=10 BORDER=0
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0">
 The kitchen was small and cramped, 
as a rubber hose lead from the the sink's faucet to a fig tree outside. 
Pasty hunks of oranges stuck to tables and chairs and walls, from 
frequent Juicerator accidents. Because the sink was given over to feeding 
the fig tree, Miles' diapers were washed in the toilet, which clogged and 
flushed back repeatedly onto adjacent kitchen floor.<P>
   My mother, who had blanched at a midwife's use of the word "pee" in 
front of her naked but grown-up daughter, and who had nearly fainted at 
the sight of Melissa's water breaking, and who had finally seen a birth 
from top to bottom, by now had a kerchief tied wildly around her head. 
The whites of her eyes were everywhere.<P>
   Within seconds of our arrival, I was smitten by a real Texan on the 
premises - the woman named Kathryn who lived with Roland and Melissa; and 
who, I was told, delivered impromptu massages. She had long brown hair 
and her skin was orange as a pumpkin's from Juicerating.<P>
   I bunked in the living room, pretending to read as she floated through 
the house, hair launching ships and battalions toward Troy; and my 
22-year-old brain percolated with heartfelt but indecent encounters. She 
ignored me utterly.<P>
   Mom, Dad and the Colonel, as I called my grandfather, bivouacked at a 
hotel some miles away. Each morning, they were slower and slower to 
return, even though Roland's family appeared at the house early and 
often.<P>
  <IMG SRC="john.gif" HSPACE=10 WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="42" BORDER=0
ALIGN="right"
BORDER="0" >

 Roland's parents were lovely but 
incessant talkers, which was tough on those of us who were trained from 
childhood to be incessant listeners. Once I found Roland hiding from them 
in his workshop, carving a clothespin.<P>
   In a day or two, a Christmas tree appaeared at the house, with 
Christmas balls. Caught up in the delirium, I dialed zero and sang "Merry 
Christmas" to the telephone operator, who sang it back.<P>
   The Colonel usually played a larger role in the family milestones, but 
he sat this one out, sipping Scotch on the front porch with my dad and 
wondering aloud why these "fine bullrushers  from Texas" never before 
heard of "Christmas balls." (But he and dad persevered: They managed to 
buy part of a store's Christmas display outright, driving it back to Buda 
and installing it at LBJ's grandfather's old place.<P>
Outside, in the air, blue birds and egrets sailed the currents of their 
migratory rivers; and Amber the Wonder Dog snatched fish from Big Onion 
Creek with powerful swipes of her paw to her mouth.<P>
   She could stand, storklike, moving nothing but her eyebrows, just 
waiting to strike.<P>
   Inside, lightening struck all week. Roland, who is more Lincolnesque 
than Lincoln, one day bumped his Texas-sized head against the house's 
stove pipe, knocking it from the stove and filling the house with soot 
and smoke.<P>
<IMG SRC="dog14.gif" WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="67" BORDER=0
HSPACE=10 ALIGN="LEFT"
BORDER="0">Having been caught up in the dramas 
of the house myself (and, of course, that unresolved lust), I developed a 
mild case of diarrhea and fled to the scrub - the bathroom toilet was 
kaput - to grip both hands around a live oak and pray. Quite 
unexpectedly, Amber nosed me from behind (just once) and I was cured.<P>
   Amber was what they called "a good ol' dog." She was trained to not 
chase the unusual breed of black deer or the cattle that grazed the 
rolling hills, but dogs do dig.<P>
   My mom, who was by now quaking and rattling from unproductively 
helping Melissa, was in the kitchen still volunteering and fairly mobile 
when Amber trotted in and coughed up something undesirable on her 
shoes.<P>
   It was the placenta, a yuletide gift that surpassed all others 
exchanged that day.<P>
   Saint Virginia is fine, now - never better, having since midwifed 
quite a few more people through various travails. Roland is still 
Lincolnesque, if not moreso. Miles is a strapping young man of 18. I love 
my sister Melissa.<P>
    Last I heard, Amber still roamed the plains of Texas.<P>
<P>

</blockquote>
<hr>

<br>
