<br>

<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Jerry Roscoe poems</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H3>three poems by jerry roscoe
</H3>
<P>
<blockquote>

<H2>visible man</H2>
<P>


They will remove more of my mother's insides today.<br>
Soon there will be nothing left where I come from,<br>
anywhere I face will be the future.<br>
I am traveling with my son,<br>
swimming at motel pools,<br>
meaning to talk to him today about his body.<br>
It was the Fifties.  My parents wanted me to be<br>
normal, which meant strangely without ego.<br>
And, you see, I have turned inward<br>
to this transparent life.<br>
They were right.  I will not miss<br>
any of the generic pleasures, the first of which<br>
is knowing where I stand: here, now,<br>
between the building up & the tearing down.<br>
<P>
<P>
<hr><P>
<P>

<H2>invisible fence</H2>

<p>

You think it's manners<br>
that keeps my dog in the yard,<br>
but it's fear & electronics.<br>
And habit the few times<br>
we let her out without first<br>
applying her spiked collar.<br>
But habits - good ones-<br>
will not stand for long<br>
without a threat of reprisal.<br>
When the battery runs low<br>
my dog is loose in the <br>
neighborhood, taunting others<br>
to charge at full speed, then stop<br>
as if before a glass wall.<br>
An animal requires discipline.<br>
What my dog likes is <br>
stalking the edge, setting <br>
her collar beeping & all<br>
the other dogs barking.<br>
If she were human,<br>
it'd be a ledge & they'd<br>
be screaming: "Jump!"<br><P>
<P>

<hr>

<H2>the fly</H2>
<P>


What prepared me for my career was not<br>
anything I read, no school I attended,<br>
no course I took, though I attended<br>
schools, took courses, read books.<br>
Moreover, it was certainly nothing<br>
I did in life, no job I held, no one experience,<br>
no love I had. It was, I believe, hanging out,<br>
sitting on the hood of a big car,<br>
leaning back against the windshield<br>
in some parking lot, looking for girls<br>
likely at the outset, or, secondarily, drink<br>
or drugs or action of any sort, but soon<br>
getting caught up in the process,<br>
dismissing these things the way a poem does<br>
its content, waving it away<br>
the way a gentle person does a fly.<br>
<P>
<blockquote><P>
<hr>
Poems by <b>Jerry Roscoe</b>, of Westerville, Ohio, have appeared in 
journals across the United States. He is poetry reviewer for <I>The 
Columbus Dispatch</I>. <P>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>



