<head>
<title>george jr. / december 1996 / arcadia /whorl's end</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#2F4F2F" VLINK="#c0c0c0" 
ALINK="#c0c0c0">
<a href="/december/arcadia.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/gotoa.gif" WIDTH=150 
HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 align=left></a>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/home.gif" WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=34 
border=0 align=right></A>
<br clear=all>
<hr>
<br>
<blockquote>
<img height=85 width=91 hspace=10 align=left src=somersault.gif>
<br><h2>whorl's end:</h2>
<h3>greco-roman wrestling</h3>
<BR clear=all>


<BR>

   Ancient Rome, where Julius Caesar agonized, "You too,  Brutus," and where Cicero declared, "While there's life, there's hope," is  about to be reborn in cyberspace.
 

<P></P>

Tufts University scholars, who already have created what is widely  considered the most comprehensive database on ancient Greece, are ready  to tackle first-century Rome.
 

<P></P>

As one of a handful of recipients of a new National Endowment for the  Humanities grant slated for projects that use technology to teach, a  Tufts classics professor and a colleague at the College of the Holy Cross  will be able to expand on a vision described by Cicero two thousand years  ago: "History ... illuminates reality, vitalizes memory, provides guidance  in daily life and brings us tidings of antiquity."
 

<P></P>

Through the newest database, which will be available to the public  through the Internet as well as on CD-ROM, Gregory Crane, associate  professor of classics at Tufts, expects to bring Roman history to life for  those interested in Latin, ancient history and art, including the 180,000  American high school students who study Latin. 
 

<P></P>

He also expects a wide variety of armchair historians to visit the web  site. The research team's existing <B>Perseus</B> site, which chronicles ancient  Greece, logs 30,000 hits a day. Named after the mythological hero who  explored the limits of the known world, Perseus lets people quickly and  easily explore ancient Greek literature, history, art and archeology. (You  can find Perseus at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/">www.perseus.tufts.edu</A>). The Roman Perseus will  continue a long-standing collaboration with archaeologist Neel Smith of 
the College of the Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass.
 A reference, research and teaching tool,<B> Perseus </B>also is available on  CD-ROM. It includes an overview of fifth-century B.C. history, archaic and  classical works in Greek and in translation, including the complete works  of Homer, Sophocles and others; interactive maps of Greece, still  photography and video of sites and scenes throughout Greece and a  catalog of hundreds of objects of Greek art, illustrated with color  images and drawings. Version 2.0 of the CD-ROM Perseus, as well as the 
Roman Perseus, runs on Macintosh.


<P></P>

 Perseus is widely accepted as the biggest and most complex database  on Greek civilization. The Roman Perseus is expected to do the same for  ancient Rome. 


<P></P>

 In Crane's view, databases such as these are the future of the  communications revolution, in which everyone will have equal access to  information."This is a big step forward in creating a real digital library  that will greatly expand the democratization begun by inexpensive print  distribution," he said.


<P></P>

 "Parents who are wondering what the Internet really holds for their  kids will see that web access through their schools or at home will  provide them with something of value."
 

<P></P>

Crane said that the team's immediate goal in this massive, long-term  project is to provide materials that will help students contextualize  first-century B.C. history and authors such as Cicero, Virgil, Horace and  Ovid in Latin as well as in English translation. The works of many of  these authors form the basis for 20th-century literature and  entertainment.
 

<P></P>

The first stage of the project is expected to take three years to  complete.


<P></P>

 The final version of Roman Perseus will include:
 <!-- List Tag --><UL>
<LI> Virtual, interactive guided tours and "fly-throughs" to introduce users  to the art, history, literature, architecture and daily life of the  first-century B.C.
<LI>  A wealth of images of Roman art and archeology, collected on a  digital camera from sources around the world.
<LI>  An atlas of the Roman world, including names of important places in  the Roman world, site plans and elevation models.
<LI>  Essays and course materials on Roman history and literature. Authors  will provide a general overview of subject matter that can be used by  younger students as well as detailed discussions for advanced students.
<LI>  A Latin lexicon.
</UL>
 The site also will include a worthy search engine allowing students, professors or general  users to explore the huge text database and perform research.




</blockquote>







