<IMG SRC="/graphics/kitty.jpg" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15>
<H2>ask kitty</H2>
<br>
  Cats are the most curious of sentient beings, who mostly care not a whit what we might think of them. Hence, they make the most excellent of advisors, even when answering our most dire of questions - as dear Kitty does this January.  Have a question? Ask <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:kitty@georgejr.com">Kitty</A>.



<br clear=all>

<hr width=80%>

  

<p>



<blockquote>

<font size=+3>q.</font>What's the best way to not get cramps?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> I have found that pregnancy is a sure-fire, although admittedly temporary, method of avoiding menstrual cramps. I still get some pretty nasty leg and foot cramps, but a massage and a little extra potassium usually helps take care of those. <br><br>

<font size=+3>q.</font> Should I bus Downtown on a stinky polluting bus that carries four people, or car pool with five people?<br>

<font size=+3>a.</font>
I don't like to pore over statistics that speak to the environmental impact of carpooling versus bus-riding, but a friend of mine who's into such things tells me the reduction in pollution <i>per passenger mile</i> that results from switching from car travel to motorbus travel is dramatic: 90 percent reduction in hydrocarbons, 75 percent reduction in carbon monoxide, and 10-15 percent reduction in nitrogen oxide. And I won't even get into the danger of automobile versus motorbus travel (.85 deaths/100 million passenger miles for cars; .01 deaths /100 million passenger miles for motorbusses). <br>I assume, however, that you would like me to let you know what I think is the better choice regarding your apparent commuting dilemma. Perhaps I can help clarify your thinking by treating the subject on two different levels: aesthetics and community.<br>
<p>
<center><b>1. Aesthetics.</b></center> 
<p>
Personally I would rather hop on a bus (empty or full), and be at leisure to read, think, stare out the window, people-watch, or vegetate, than be crammed into a car with four other people and forced to be social on my way to work. Maybe it's just me, but I appreciate a little transition time from home to work and back again. There's a certain beauty in letting a relative stranger chauffeur me to and from work, a person who asks nothing of me except that I pay my fare and not be a nuisance. The windows are nice and big, so I can actually see out and notice the seasons and the architectural details of buildings I would undoubtedly miss of I were stuck in a car.<br>
<p>
<center><b>2. Community.</b></center>
<p>	
<IMG SRC="pubtrans.gif" hspace=10 vspace=10 WIDTH="59" HEIGHT="135" BORDER=0 ALIGN="LEFT" BORDER="0">
O.K. So maybe you are one of the very rare people who might enjoy the "camaraderie" of four other people in a tight space before and after a stressful 
day. Maybe you like waiting for that one person who's continually late, and being able to personalize your rage. Based on my unscientific observations of cars on the road, you are rare indeed. Most cars boast only one occupant, the driver. I know it's hard, but you can't just think of yourself when considering issues such as this one. One bus, when full, replaces approximately forty cars. Forty cars. Or eight cars with five passengers each (dream on). So if not only you, but all your commuting friends would hop on the bus, very few busses would carry only four people during rush hour. And as demand for bus service increased, bus service would improve, road conditions would improve, fewer tax dollars would be needed to build and maintain roads, and maybe we could manage to get some decent schools for our kids. And if you live in a walkable community, you can lose the <i>stinky, polluting car</i> altogether and take a few trips to Europe every year on the money you save. <br><br>

<font size=+3>q.</font> Are you really a kid?<br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>According to my parents, yes. Maybe when I get a real job.... <br><br>

<font size=+3>q.</font> Does the election's outcome portend good or ill for the country?</b><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font> As Americans we tend to forget that the fact that we <i>have</i> elections portends good for the country. Call me a cock-eyed optimist, but I'm pretty glad to live in a place where I don't have to worry about the threat of a violent overthrow of the government every time someone has the urge to rule.  Admittedly, sometimes I feel pretty disgusted with the nature of how elections are conducted in this country, but generally I'm glad I don't have to carry a gun to make a point. <br><br>
<font size=+3>q.</font> My cats eat too fast and then puke. What can I do to change that??? They are both pretty fat even with the binge and purge, binge and purge....</b><br>
<font size=+3>a.</font>Maybe your home life is upsetting to your kitties. Cats are sensitive creatures with highly developed empathetic powers. Are you happy as an individual? Are you satisfied with your intra-human relationships? Is your job going O.K.? You owe it to your cats to shape up! Poor things are probably worried sick about you. Self actualize! Your cats will stop this gastrointestinal editorializing soon enough.


</blockquote>



<p>

<HR><BR>

