<head>
<title>Black and Decker Everyday Home Repairs Reviewed</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" 
bgcolor="#ddd9a2">
<font color="#0000b3"><h2><strong>Black and Decker Everyday Home Repairs Reviewed</font></strong></h2>
<font color="#ff0000"><h3>By Robert Penny</font></h3>

<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>I've never been good at doing repairs around the house. But, with the prices for hiring service
people becoming outrageously high, I have begun to learn to do many of  the minor repairs 
needed around my house, rather than call a repair person. Because of my new found interest in
fixing things around the house, I was very interested in a new CD-ROM from Parsons
Technology.  The new <em>Black &amp; Decker Everyday Home Repairs</em>-multimedia software is packed
with helpful secrets, tips and step-by-step instructions to handle more than 100 of the
most-common home repair headaches without hassle.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Everyday Home Repairs gives you everything you need, from the start of your tasks to their
completion, for repairing windows, doors, walls and ceilings; handling basic plumbing and
electrical chores; repairing and maintaining floors; and making exterior home repairs. By using the
program you will have the ability to learn how to fix over 100 common household repairs.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The program begins with a very brief audiovisual introduction that sets the tone of what the user
can expect to find while using the software. The program is laid out into six major areas:<em>
Plumbing, Electrical, Windows and Doors, Walls and Ceiling, Floor Repair, and Exterior</em>. Once
you've clicked on your area of choice, it begins with a brief audiovisual introduction on what will
be covered. Users then choose from a list of common repairs such as fixing a leaky faucet,
replacing an electrical outlet or repairing a damaged vinyl floor.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Once the repair problem is chosen from the list, the user is greeted by an easy to understand color
photographic slide show with audio instructions that take you step-by-step through the repair
process. For instance, you can learn to repair a damaged vinyl floor in just six simple steps. The
program also insures that your repairs are done correctly by including a complete list of safety
instructions that are specific to each task. Don't just skip over these safety steps, read them. They
can be very important and also save you down time during your repair.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>One great feature of the software is the ability to print out instructions with photos (in color on
color printers), so you can have them by your side at the repair site  (because it's obvious you
won't be sitting in front of the computer while fixing a toilet float right?). You can also print out a
list of tools and materials needed for the project. This will help a great deal when you're
wandering around aimlessly in one of those big home repair warehouses. You'll also be able to
obtain a time estimate on the project (depending on your level of expertise) and a cost estimate.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>There are two very nice glossaries, one for tools and the other on materials. Each is setup in
alphabetical order. By clicking on a given letter you get a list of tools or materials beginning with
that letter. Pick a tool or type of material and you'll be given a little summary on what the material
is or the tool does. The glossary will also help to explain any technical terms you don't
understand. In addition, there is  a list of tips for putting together the "perfect" collection of tools
for your toolbox.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While use of this program won't prepare you for staring in an episode of ABC Television's Home
Improvement along side Tim and Al, you will be able to learn a great deal about basic repairs for
around the home. At $29 for the disk, even if you use it once or twice to fix something minor,
you'll end up saving more than the cost of the program.

<p> 

<p><strong>SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS:</strong> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Everyday Home Repairs requires an IBM or compatible PC 486 or better system, 8MB of RAM,
a 2x CD-ROM drive, DOS 3.1 or higher, Microsoft Windows 3.1 or higher (yes, it works fine on
Windows 950),  a 256-color VGA monitor, 2MB hard drive space, a sound board and speakers,
and a mouse. 

<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><a href="toc.html">
