<html>
<head>
<title>Gift Ideas For The Gamer On Your List</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" 
bgcolor="ddd9a2">
<font color="#ff0000"></font><h2><strong><font color="#ff0000">Gift Ideas For The Gamer On Your List</font></strong></h2>
<h3><font color="#ff0000">By D.J. Haynes</font></h3>

<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Well here it is time to start thinking about the Holidays again. If the folks on your list are into
computer gaming then hopefully this collection of new games, and for the kids, some educational
programs as well, will help you choose the perfect gift. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>NEW GAMES:</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Our friends over at Activision have eleven great gift-giving games available for the holidays. Here
are reviews on the one's we liked best. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>The Elk Moon Murder:</em> This interactive CD-ROM draws you into a compelling murder mystery.
What's new about Elk Moon is that the tale takes place in the rich and diverse culture of the
American Southwest. The player races against time to solve a murder before the killer strikes
again. Written by Sam Egan, of Northern Exposure fame, the game features Amanda Donohoe of
L.A. Law. There is a lot of live action here and the production is very well done. Available for 
Mac, DOS, and Windows 95 CD, $29.95; ages 18 and up. A sequel, <em>Sacred Ground</em> is due out
soon. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Interstate 76: </em>I'm sure a great many of you have wished you had a rocket launcher mounted on
the hood of your car at one time or another while driving on the interstates. Well in this game you
do. Your job is to cruise the highways of the American Southwest as you face off against
terrorists intent on destroying the largest oil reserves in the U.S. The first-person 3-D action here
is really hot with a gripping soundtrack and great graphics. Available for Windows 95 and MS-Dos for about $49.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>MechWarrior 2: Mercenaries</em>: Last year Activision had one of the most successful computer
games of all-time with MechWarrior 2.  Following on the heels of that success, they've come out
with this "prequel". Players battle each other in huge Mechanized warrior robots in a quest for
money, power and fame. Gladiatorial style combat on a highly technological scale with tons of
destructive weapons that allow you to lay waste to your opponents without mercy. I thought it
was better that the original version because it's a no-holds barred slugfest with out rules or honor;
just fighting. Available for both Windows 95 and MS-Dos for $49.95. Also available for the Sony
Playstation for around $49.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Time Commando: </em>Activision is distributing this one but it's designed by a French company.
Seems that a computer virus has entered the tactical computers at a European military command
center. Your job as the time commando is to travel through various time periods defeating
computer created opponents (over 60 historical enemies in 9 time periods) until you are able to
finally defeat the last opponent and restore the core-memory of the main computer. The action
here is 3-D with nicely rendered backgrounds and flowing game play in a Mortal Kombat style. I
had a bit of trouble running it on a 486 but it does run well on a Pentium. I'm always a little leery
of games coming from France (maybe it's that complete crash of my system caused by Robinson's
Requiem a few years ago) but Time Commando was lots of fun to play as you master weapons
from each time period in an effort to defeat enemies and move to the next level. On CD-ROM for
Windows 95 and MS-Dos as well as Sony Playstation, for around $45.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Muppet Treasure Island:</em> What's more fun than a barrel of monkeys, why four CD-ROMs full of
Muppets, that's what! Join Kermet the Frog, Miss Piggy and actor Tim Curry in this fun-filled
adventure based on the recent Muppet movie. The interactive game play is enlivened with 20
different puzzles and activities coupled with great live-action video. Battle survey pirates and
search for fabulous treasure in the funniest adventure on CD-ROM. Available for Windows 95,
Windows 3.1 and Mac for about $39.95.
</em>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Also from Activision is <em>Blast Chamber: </em> an action-strategy game that allows up to 4 players to
challenge each other as they maneuver their character through a vast maze of obstacles ($44.95).
The race here is against time as your character has a time bomb strapped to their backs;<em> Shanghai
II:</em> a nice mah-jongg style tile game with great graphics ($19.95); <em>Hyperbalde:</em> A cross between
hockey, lacrosse and soccer, set in a future world. The game has very little rules - beat your
opponents into the ground and score goals ($49.95); <em>Zork Nemesis:</em> Travel to 5 different fantasy
worlds to unlock the secrets of the Forbidden Lands. Great graphics and sound effects make this a
nice gift for those interested in Science Fiction of Fantasy gaming ($49.95).

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>7th Level has a couple of nice games out or coming out for the Holidays.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Timon &amp; Pumbaa's Jungle Games: </em>In cooperation with Disney Interactive, two funny characters
from the Lion King are brought to the PC to host five fun jungle games. There's <em>Jungle Pinball
</em>with wild jungle animals acting as bumpers and a rolled up worm as your ball; <em>Slingshooter</em>,
where you sling berries at jungle creatures; <em>Hippo Hop</em> where you must cross a river of snakes
and crocodiles to get to the other side; <em>Bug Drop </em>- a tetris style game with stink bugs and <em>Burper</em>
- where Pumbaa burps bugs into oblivion. The fun part of the whole CD-ROM is the critiques,
insults and banter from Timon and Pumbaa. The cartoon graphics are excellent and the game is
fun for kids and adults. Available for around $39.95.<em></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>G-NOME</em> is an action combat game typical to the MechWarrior type games.  A G-NOME demo
is available to download from www.7thlevel.com.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>The Universe According to Virgil Reality: </em>This nifty little CD-ROM presents the wonders of
science in a fun environment through a combination of animation, audio and video. The wacked-out Professor Reality is your guide to this fun-filled look at science. Learn to make paper
airplanes and how they fly; view earthworm intestines and other equally gross things; view cool
space shots from NASA and lots more. ($39.99).

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Tracer</em>: You're a super hacker who can crack any code, defeat any strategy/action  rogue
program, and pry open any file. Now, you're up against a virus that's bent on destroying you.
That's the premise behind Tracer, an adrenaline-pumping, addictive action game that calls on
strategy and quick reflexes in equal measure. You play as one of four characters who must race
across a grid inside a vast computer network, using square "code pads"-divided into four triangles
of various colors-to reach the "exit." All the while, you're being chased by a virus that destroys
each pad almost as soon as you place it-and if the virus catches you, you're dead. Available for     
$29.950)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Ace Ventura-CD-ROM</em> offers adventures with that funny pet detective of movie fame. As Ace
you get to battle 4 twisted, animal hating villains, solve puzzles and visit 60 exotic locations for
only $39.95. This one has excellent animation and the game play is first rate.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>7th Level has a new web site they are working on, <em>Kids' World</em>. It's located at
http://www.kidsworld.com. While still under construction, by Christmas it's supposed to be an
exciting new interactive cartoon network.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>SimPark:</em> Kids build and manage their own nature park in this easy-to-play simulation. Kids begin
by designing the park and deciding what combination of plants and animals to include and what
things to allow humans to do. As park rangers, kids are responsible for maintaining the balance
between nature and humans and overseeing budgets, garbage, fires, and maintenance. From
Maxis, Windows and Windows 95 CD, $39.99. Ages 8 to 12.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Battle of the Ironclads: </em>You get the chance to change the course of history by taking the helm of
either classic Civil War ship, the USS Monitor or the CSS Virginia. The ships, weapons, tactics,
and technology of the era have been re-created to be historically accurate and are based on
blueprints and maps from the National Archives. The decisions you make, such as how fast to sail,
when to fire cannons, and when to anchor, are all part of the strategy in this game, which will
please historians as well as strategy gamers. Grolier Interactive, 800-285-4534 or 203-797-3530;
Windows CD, $49.99 street.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Titanic:</em> Adventure Out of Time: In this adventure game, you explore a historically accurate 3-D
replica of the Titanic while trying to accomplish a mission as a secret agent aboard the luxury
liner. You must defuse bombs, send and receive Morse code, regulate the Titanic's engines, and
interact with 25 passengers to gather clues before the ship sinks. Who knows, you may even be
able to prevent World War I if you make the right choices. CyberFlix, 800-483-8632 or
423-546-1157; Mac and Windows CD, $49.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Starcraft:</em> In this real-time strategy game, you journey into space to restore order to a galaxy on
the brink of interstellar warfare. As commander of one of three species vying for supremacy, you
undertake a series of strategic military missions while defending planets and constellations,
employing advanced technology, and controlling reserves of finite resources. Starcraft includes
multi player support for up to eight players and one-click free access to online opponents via the
company's battle.net server. Blizzard Entertainment, 800-953-7669 or 310-793-0600; Windows
95 CD, $50.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Also from Blizzard is <em>Warcraft</em>: Set in a mythical medieval world, Warcraft II features the
continuing battle for Azeroth over land, sea, and air. As in the original version, the two sides in
the conflict are the evil Orcs and the noble human race. You can play as either race in 28
campaign scenarios. The game also includes Map Builder, which lets you create your own
scenarios.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Warcraft II plays somewhat like SimCity or Civilization, in that you must construct buildings
(such as farms, barracks, town halls, and dragon lairs) based on the resources you collect,
including lumber, gold, and oil while battling your opponents. Among the troops and weaponry in
Warcraft are elves, orcs, troll berzerkers, ogres, goblins, dragons, giant sea turtles, griffins,
zeppelins, battleships, and spell-casting death knights. You can play against human opponents via
a network, modem, or serial connection. Mac, DOS, and Windows CD, $50.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>You Don't Know Jack Volume 2 and You Don't Know Jack Sports: </em>We reviewed the first Jack last
year and the sequel is pretty good too. The second volume of You Don't Know Jack retains the
irreverent humor of the original and has just as many questions -- 800. That's good. But you also
get celebrity guest appearances, high-score lists, and all new categories of questions. The sports
version covers everything from baseball to water polo, and its host makes Howard Cosell sound
tame. Both titles are stand-alone games and support up to three players on a keyboard. Berkeley
Systems, Mac and Windows CD, $29.99.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Comanche 3</em>: This helicopter flight simulation features an improved graphics engine that brings
3-D details to landscapes and targets and makes them look more realistic. Multi player options
give you a choice of playing two-player cooperative missions through a modem or playing with up
to eight players over a network. The features on your Comanche, such as the cockpit and landing
gear, are based on the actual Army aircraft. In addition, the approximately 30 missions are linked
through a narrative story line with live-action videos, such as mission briefings and footage of
Comanche test aircraft. If you enjoy serious flight sims and war-based strategy games, check it
out. From NovaLogic, DOS, Windows, and Windows 95 CD, $44.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>PowerChess:</em> PowerChess takes the ancient game of strategy and makes it accessible to novices
and experts alike while giving it a bit of personality. There are 25 animated characters to play
against, all incorporating different tactics. And you can play a match against an opponent over the
Internet. The PowerChess Queen offers tutorials and analysis immediately following matches. In
addition, there's narrated analysis of seven classic chess games, including the 1970 match where
Bobby Fischer defeated Wilhem Smyslov. In the Lab, you can create a training opponent so you
can practice specific points in your game.  From Sierra On-Line, Windows 95 CD, $39.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>X-Wing vs. Tie Fighter:</em> LucasArts' long-awaited space-combat simulation mixes all the elements
of the previous Star Wars games with the option for multi player action. Multi player modes allow
you to choose whether you want to fly for the Rebels or the Empire, and there is a choice of
about 12 different spacecraft. There are 15 challenging missions in which pilots communicate with
members of their squad to discuss tactics and objectives. In fact, the missions are designed to
promote cooperation among allies. Single-player mode is similar to the multi player scenarios,
though missions focus on a different set of conflicts between the Rebellion and the Empire. May
the force be with you, again. From LucasArts, Windows CD, $54.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Also from LucasArts, <em>Afterlife</em> lets the player run a sim-city type version of heaven and hell. Keep
your souls happy and things will go fine. If not, supernatural disasters will befall your worlds and
you'll lose souls by the bunch. One particularly harsh disaster includes a visit from the Four
Surfers of the Apocalypso. The 3-D graphics are excellent as is the game interface and playability.
I liked playing God or was it Satan. $39.95 on CD-ROM for Windows and Mac.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Space Jam:</em> Based on the soon to be released movie starring Michael Jordan and Bugs Bunny,
Space Jam takes you onto the court for an intergalactic three-on-three basketball game to decide
the fate of the Looney Tunes characters. You take on the evil alien "Monstars", who are armed
with the talents of top NBA superstars. The game features special dunks and defensive moves and
bonus power-ups. Acclaim Entertainment, Windows CD, $39.99.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Not to be outdone by anyone - the folks that make your operating system, help you surf the web,
run your word processor etc, Microsoft now has a first wave of holiday '96 PC games.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Deadly Tide</em> is an underwater action shooter in which players move from mysterious sunken ships
to alien mining operations to battles on the open sea as they attempt to save humanity from the
enemy that has invaded the Earth on a mission to drown the world. The wonderful 3-D graphics
in Deadly Tide were created by the same designers responsible for the effects on the "SeaQuest"
and "Star Trek: The Next Generation" television series and movies such as "RoboCop" and "Total
Recall." And yes, it's Windows 95 compatible. $54.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Hellbender</em> is an intense action shooter that offers players an integrated science-fiction story line
for challenging game-play experiences. Hellbender features secret worlds, hidden objects,
numerous weapons and a variety of enemies. The game is a technological powerhouse and
provides full support for Direct3D-based gaming, multi player competition via LAN, direct
modem and the Internet (via Microsoft Internet Gaming Zone at (HTTP://WWW.ZONE.COM/),
and full freedom of movement using the SideWinder 3D Pro joystick. Voice-over is provided by
"The X-Files" star Gillian Anderson ($44.95)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Monster Truck Madness</em>, the world's only PC monster truck racing simulation, features an
extraordinarily realistic racing experience that allows gamers to feel the uninhibited power and
outrageous fun of monster trucks. Play begins with highly detailed renderings of world-famous
monster trucks including BigFoot, Snake Bite and Gravedigger. Racing courses contain realistic
obstacles and terrain rendered in detailed, textured 3-D graphics. The gunning motors and cries of
twisted metal are the real things, too, recorded and digitized from actual monster truck races. And
narrating the drive to victory is the voice of Armey Armstrong, beloved by millions of monster
truck racing fans.  Gamers can also connect to the Microsoft Monster Truck Web Stop site on the
World Wide Web http://www.microsoft.com/games/monster/  to find the no-charge Monster
Truck Madness trial version, up-to-the-minute information on monster trucks, race results and
Monster Truck Madness. Somehow I never understood the attraction to monster trucks myself
($44.95).

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>NBA Full Court Press</em> is a great PC basketball game. Play head-to-head with up to four players
on one PC or across town over a modem or network. It has very true-to-life graphics, lifelike
player moves and intense, realistic five-on-five game play. NBA Full Court Press combines the
best of exciting arcade action with a sophisticated database of statistics of more than  250
motion-captured player moves - including jump shots, skyhooks, blocked shots and a variety of
creative dunks - real crowd noises, and all 29 NBA arenas captured and digitized in full detail. All
29 NBA teams are represented. $44.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>American Civil War:</em> This two-CD set teaches you about the tumultuous times surrounding the
Civil War. The strategy game CD includes various political and military victory scenarios, so you
face different strategic, economic, and political challenges each time you play. The multimedia CD
contains a 175,000-word narrative text, plus maps, photos, biographics, songbook, and video
clips. I ran it on a 486, 100mhz and play was slow but entertaining. I played the South and ended
up defeating the Union in under 1 year. Interactive Magic, Windows and Windows 95 CD, $36
street; ages 12 and up.
</em>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><em>HardBall 5</em> includes a pitching and batting practice area and home-run derby to practice your
skills. You can play exhibition games; all-star games; and complete, half, and short season games
drawing on a 40-man roster, 800 Major League players, and 40 stadiums. Sportscaster Al
Michaels calls the play-by-play. The Legends League features 12 old-time stadiums, plus player
photos and stats. The 1961 Yankees, the 1955 Brooklyn Dodgers, and even the 1916 Boston Red
Sox are represented. Accolade, Windows CD, $49.95; ages 6 and up.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>The Wild World of Madison Jaxx</em>: In this interactive geographical game, players are special agents
for the Global Special Services Corporation (GSS), headquartered in New York City. Headed by
Madison Jaxx, the GSS sends agents all over the world to catch dangerous criminals, stop deadly
viruses and locate lost treasures. This one is kind of like a cross between Carmen San Diego and
Indiana Jones. From Corel (sorry don't have a price on this one).

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Ashes to Ashes</em> - Devastated by decades of brutal warfare, earth's future is not pretty. The Order
was created to preserve the art of war while preventing  mass destruction. Under the Order's
control all disputes - personal, corporate, political - are settled by armed combat in sanctioned
arenas located around the world.  This process has maintained peace for over twenty years. But
now something has gone wrong and the soldiers have started to kill everyone in sight. The minds
of the soldiers have been twisted by fiendish brain implants. Players will be dropped into areas to
ferret out the brain controlled soldiers and destroy them. With 8 different worlds to explore, 6
different types of weapons, and 6 different types of hazards, Ashes to Ashes is a challenging game
that pits players against a powerful and crazed enemy. From Corel Corp - download a demo at
<a href="http://www.corel.com/">http://www.corel.com/</a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>NHL 97 </em>features 3-D polygonal players that incorporate the use of state-of-the-art motion capture
technology whereby real NHL players have been digitized into the game to provide authentic
animations and player graphics. It also includes multi player support via Local Area Network
(LAN) and modem.  NHL 97 features all of the NHL teams, logos and almost 900 players with
the latest trades, statistics and player ratings. The game play is incredibly fast and I am amazed at
how closely NHL 97 resembles the real game. From ElectronicArts Sports for $59.95 in Windows
or Dos.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Steel Panthers II:</em> Now offers players the option of fighting modern battles in Europe, Korea, and
the Middle East between the years 1950 and 1999. You get to command either a single squad or
an entire battalion. In addition to modern tanks,  players will preside over other intriguing unit
types, including helicopters, jet fighters, and missile silos. Finally,  armchair generals will be happy
to know Steel Panthers II features  super-VGA graphics and intense animation, not to mention
digitized photos of tanks and artillery and modern combat footage. From SSI for $39.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></em>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><em>Robert E. Lee: Civil War General</em> sets a new standard for graphical Civil War presentation, with
live-action video reenactments, animated battles, and a beautifully designed interface. The disc
captures the emotional toll of the conflict, and the melancholy of the famous general. This
captivating strategy game simulates six famous battles and one fictional skirmish involving Lee's

<p>Army of Virginia. Also included, but somewhat upstaged by the captivating game play, is a rich,
multimedia Civil War reference section.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>You lead either the Union Army of the Potomac or the Confederate Army of Virginia, battling a
computer or human opponent (via modem) through individual skirmishes or the entire campaign.
The game's stunning graphics will appeal to strategy fans, while Civil War buffs will love the
attention to detail. A beautifully rendered terrain map helps you keep your bearings; and unlike
with many military sims, an intuitive interface makes it easy to monitor troop strength, health,
morale, and firepower.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Sierra Online's Robert E. Lee: Civil War General balances the chesslike strategy of troop
deployment with the human side of war. Nightfall on the battlefield is not to be missed, as strife
and bloodshed are magically transformed into a peaceful, almost dreamlike scene, complete with
crackling campfires and rows of tents where columns of men once stood. Cost: $59.95 from
Sierra Online; http://www.sierra.com

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>FOR THE KIDS: </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Disney's Toy Story Animated StoryBook</em>: With the release of the movie on video this game may
prove to be a big seller for the holiday season. Basically Disney's Toy Story is a condensed
version of the movie, complete with the same phenomenal Pixar-produced animation, and familiar
character voices.  Built around ten static screen shots, the CD-ROM captures the story pretty
well. The program has five integrated activities that are inserted directly between sequences in the
story. The activities focus on early learning skills, like matching colors, hand eye coordination,
following oral directions, and navigating mazes. Help Woody and Buzz escape bad boy Sid, catch
the moving van, and become best buddies all on your computer. $39.95 from Disney Interactive.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Mortimer and the Riddles of the Medallion: </em>A magic medallion has been stolen and used to
replace all of the world's animals with statues. Now the medallion has exploded into seven pieces
and been scattered around the world. Enter Mortimer the giant flying snail and you. Your job is to
fly around the world and revitalize the animals, answer the riddles, face the evil Lodius, but you
only have one day to do it. This was a fun game to play. You view the screen from the inside of
Mortimer's shell, which is like a giant airplane cockpit. The graphics are very good and play is
fast. You need a Pentium to play - available for Windows 95 on CD-ROM for $39.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Green Eggs and Ham</em> This classic children's tale is brought to life with wacky games and
toe-tapping tunes. In the Silly Rhyming Sentence Machine, kids create their own Seussian
sentences using three rhyming words. Memory skills are enhanced with the Food Concentration
Game, where kids match cans in a Seussian kitchen. Living Books, Mac and Windows CD, $40;
ages 3 to 7.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Fractured Fairy Tales  </em>Follow the story's hero, Frog, as he attempts to find a witch able to turn
him back into a prince. Each screen allows children to play a game relating to the story and is
designed to challenge thinking and matching skills. Children can print out pictures of some of the
characters to color in. Media Station, Mac and Windows CD, $30, ages 4 and up.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Sesame Street: Elmo's Preschool:</em> Everyone's favorite little red guy, Elmo guides kids through
lessons on the alphabet, numbers, problem solving, and colors. Elmo also reminds kids about
important social concepts such as sharing, cooperation, and understanding. Creative Wonders, 
Windows CD, $34.95, ages 3 to 6.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Corel ChemLab:</em> This is a multimedia, interactive chemistry laboratory. Users can conduct canned
experiments or explore the lab in a free form manner, conducting their own experiments. In a
realistic - and safe - 3-D environment, students and chemistry buffs are able to explore and work
with the chemicals and equipment in the lab. Corel ChemLab includes an on-line textbook for
reference as well as extensive on-line help features, video clips of real experiments, and sound
effects. (Windows 3.1)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Eager To Learn:</em>  This two-CD-ROM reading and math program has plenty to play with for
preschool through first-grade kids, including games, puzzles, songs, an art studio, and a crazy
kitchen. Sierra On-Line, Mac, Windows, and Windows 95 CD, $40, ages 3 to 6.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Mighty Math Carnival Countdown</em>:  Five fun-filled activities teach addition and subtraction, 2-D
geometry, patterns, number symbols, logic, and early multiplication and division. Carnival
Countdown is the first title in Edmark's Mighty Math series, which will contain six titles spanning
three age groups (five to seven, eight to 10, and 11 to 14). Math concepts are presented in two
modes -- Question and Answer, and Explore -- and innovative teaching techniques will hold kids'
attention. Edmark, Mac and Windows CD, $39; ages 5 to 7.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Interactive Math Journey</em>: This complete learning program for early math skills follows the format
of The Learning Company's award-winning Interactive Reading Journey. Kids journey through 10
math lands and explore 25 sequenced activities designed to teach addition, subtraction, patterns
and shapes, fractions, measurement, and multiplication. Interactive Math Journey also

<p>includes five fun songs to keep the early learner's toes tapping. The Learning Company, Mac and
Windows CD, $99; ages 5 to 9.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Web Workshop: </em>This Web-page maker for kids makes it easy to create personal Web pages to
post on the Internet. It includes paint tools, background images, and clip art, and kids can paste
their own images and photographs in their pages, along with voices, sounds, and music. Vividus,
Mac and Windows disk, $29.95 (available through http://www.vividus.com); ages 8 and up.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Bill Nye the Science Guy:</em> Stop that Rock An asteroid is heading for Earth, and if kids can't
convince a computer to divert the asteroid's course by answering seven riddles, the human race
will go the way of the dinosaurs. This science adventure game hosted by everyone's favorite
science guy features lots of virtual experiments, scientific facts, and, of course, fun. Pacific
Interactive/Disney Interactive, Mac and Windows CD, $40 street; ages 9 and up.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Eyewitness Virtual Reality:</em> Dinosaur Hunter The latest installment of DK Multimedia's
Eyewitness Virtual Reality series takes children back 250  million years on a fact-filled, fascinating
journey to study dinosaurs. The disc includes lots of dinosaur facts, video, animation, a time line,
an interactive globe, and 3-D dinosaur models. Kids can dig for fossils at the dinosaur excavation
site, assemble what they find, and bring to life 3-D dinosaurs that walk around the virtual
museum. DK Multimedia, Mac and Windows CD, $29.95; ages 8 and up.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Also new from DK Multimedia are, <em>The Way Things Work 2.0</em> and <em>Castle Explorer</em>.  <em></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>The Way Things Work 2.0</em> is a wonderful CD-ROM that takes users on an entertaining
exploration of machines, inventors, science and technology. All done with excellent graphics and
animation. Users can also connect to Mammoth.net where they may interact with author David
Macaulay, other users and above all Mr. Macaulay's animated mascot the Great Wooly
Mammoth. For Windows and Mac at $39.95. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Castle Explorer</em> takes at look at what life was like in a medieval castle, plus there's a neat spy
adventure in which the player must adopt a disguise and complete a mission for the King. Also
included with the CD-ROM is a free-standing snap-together medieval castle puzzle. Nicely done
look at 13th century life with 4 hours of audio, 100,000 interactive objects, four 3-D rooms, 100
3-D objects, a glossary and index and lots more. For Windows and Mac, $29.95.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Microsoft Creative Writer 2</em>: The second version of Microsoft's writing program sports a slick
new interface and lots of new ready-made layouts for book reports, newsletters, journals, and
more. It also has tools to help kids design and save their own World Wide Web pages. Microsoft,
Windows 95 CD, $34.95; ages 8 and up.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Richard Scarry's Best Reading Program Ever:</em>  In Busytown, children develop reading-readiness
skills, including phonics and story writing, with help from Huckle Cat and Lowly Worm. Kids can
read or hear stories, and work with reading and phonics activities, including a clickable dictionary.
The program also includes a kid-friendly word processor so kids can create and print their own
stories.  Simon &amp; Schuster Interactive, Mac and Windows CD, $40 street; ages 3 to 6.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Lamb Chop Loves Reading:</em>  Shari Lewis and friends take kids on a learning journey with five
Aesop's fables, games, and an interactive storybook. On the journey, Lamb Chop learns that
sounding out words uncovers clues to help save Professor Spellwell's missing daughter. Shari is
getting a little dated, but kids can still learn from this one; and parents will have a familiar face
from their childhood as well. Philips Media, Mac and Windows CD, $29.99 (bundled with Lamb
Chop Loves Music); ages 3 to 6.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Snoopy's Campfire Stories:</em>  Featuring original TV animation and character voices, this program
lets kids sharpen reading and writing skills by interacting with the Peanuts gang. Snoopy's
Campfire Stories includes six stories and interactive letter-writing activities. Virgin Sound and
Vision, Mac and Windows CD, $29.95; ages 4 to 8.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Kid Phonics 2:</em>  Kids can dance and rhyme their way through phonics as they learn to sound out
words, connect sounds to clusters of letters, build words, and use those words in sentences. Kid
Phonics is designed to help young readers sound out more than 350 words, differentiate among
letter sounds, understand the uses of prefixes and suffixes, and identify silent letters and their
effects on words. Davidson &amp; Associates, Mac, Windows, and Windows 95 CD, $35; ages 6 to 9.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Hope this list helps you to find the perfect gift for the gamer on your list this year. In addition to
the games and education programs I've reviewed here, other gift ideas could include one of the
new high-tech joysticks or game pads, a new mouse, sound card, speakers, CD-ROM drives.. All
things needed to play most of the games reviewed here. A separate article on <a href="hardware.htm">hardware</a> for the
holidays can be found in this issue.

<p><hr>
