<head>
<title>Holiday Gift Ideas: Hardware </title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" 
bgcolor="#ddd9a2">
<font color="#0000ff"></font><font color="#000080"><h2><strong>Holiday Gift Ideas: Hardware </strong></font></h2>
<h3><font color="#000080">By T. Ardito</font></h3>

<p><font color="#000080"><hr>
</font>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p> The Holiday season is right around the corner so it's time to start thinking about what to give
that computer user on your list. With this article, I've put together a list of all sorts of hardware
ideas for your gift giving needs. Happy shopping.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Stocking Stuffers: </em>Boxes of floppy disks, mouse pads, CD-ROM jewel cases, zip-drive disks, CD-ROM cleaning kits, disk storage racks, special types of paper for a printer, how-to books, wrist
rests and back supports can all make great gifts at a cost of $25 or less

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>If you've got a spare couple of thousand sitting around <em><strong>A PC or Mac system</strong></em> is always a nice gift.
I couldn't hope to review all of the countless number of new systems hitting the market this
holiday season but here are a couple that caught my attention.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The <em>Micron's 200-MHZ Home MPC </em>is a multimedia powerhouse ready to respond to all of your
software needs now and in the future (well, at least until the next round of processors make all the
current ones obsolete).

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Home MPC's included  Diamond Stealth 3-D Video 2000 card delivers full-motion,
full-screen video thanks to its preloaded MPEG software and 3-D acceleration. Great sound
echos through a Creative Labs Sound Blaster 32 3-D Wavetable audio card and powerful 25-watt
speakers, while the included Microsoft SideWinder 3-D Pro joystick lets you have a blast with the
latest games.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Home MPC comes with an impressive collection of helpful software, including Microsoft
Office  Professional 95 (with Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Access and Schedule+), both Microsoft
Money 4.0 and Intuit's Quicken Deluxe 5.0 personal-finance programs, and a library of reference
titles, such as Bookshelf 95, Encarta 96 and Julia Child Home Cooking from Microsoft, plus
Quicken Family Lawyer. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The one snag to all of this is that you'll have to install the programs yourself. However, the
standard 1.2-gigabyte Quantum Fireball 1280 hard drive won't be cluttered with useless pre-installed software  you don't want or need.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Home MPC's 16 megabytes of EDO RAM and fast 200-MHZ Pentium processor is a solid
performer. Micron tops off  the package with a Microsoft mouse, a standard keyboard, and a
bright 17-inch monitor with a .26-mm dot pitch and 85-Hz refresh rate for clear, flicker-free video
display. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The cost for all this power is $3,099 with 16 MB of RAM ( I think for this price they should have
thrown in 24 or 32MB of RAM), 1.2- GB hard drive (might have been a bit larger for the price),
eight-speed CD-ROM drive and 17-inch monitor, from Micron Electronics, (800) 209-9686,
(208) 893-3434. <a href="http://www.mei.micron.com">http://www.mei.micron.com</a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>The IBM Aptiva S78 </em>is one fine looking machine. It's sleek black casing has a futuristic look like
something you might expect to see in an episode of Star Trek Voyager or the X-Files.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The most impressing aspect of the Aptiva S78 is its split components. Unlike other machines,
which sit either on the desk or under it, the Aptiva S78 does both. The minitower, which holds the
hard drive, CPU, RAM, and expansion slots, can be tucked under or even behind a desk. It
doesn't need to be within easy reach because a thin "media console" box slides under the monitor
stand and connects to the tower with a 6-foot-long cable. A pop-up bay in the console contains
the floppy and CD-ROM drives. The 15inch monitor, with wing-mounted speakers at each side,
sits high and dry on a cool two-legged stand.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>With a very functional cordless mouse, unattended receipt of phone messages and faxes (the
Aptiva S78 turns itself on when a call comes in), and notebook like Rapid Resume (which returns
the system to its pre-power-down condition, including open applications), this machine is useful
and a pleasure to use. Its audio is excellent, and the video accelerator whips through 3-D games in
a flash.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Aptiva S78's three-piece construction makes great sense: The components you need are
within easy reach; the ones you don't are out of sight. Add in the great software, handy power-up
and power-down features, and outstanding performance, and you've got one mean machine.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The system comes with a 200MHz Pentium processor,  32MB EDO RAM with 256K cache, 
2MB of VRAM, a 3.2GB Hard Disk, 8x CD-ROM drive, 16-bit IBM Mwave wave-table sound
card, a  33,600-bps fax modem, and a 15-inch IBM multimedia monitor with integrated speakers.
The Cost is $3,899; (800) 426-7235, ext. 4340, (919) 517-2430; <a href="www.pc.ibm.com/aptiva">www.pc.ibm.com/aptiva<em></a></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><strong>New CD-ROM Technology:</strong></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Olympus CD-Recorder Breaks the $500 Barrier:</em> Just a few years ago you couldn't touch a CD-ROM recorder for less than $2,000. Now with the CD-R2x4, making your own CD-ROMs is
within reach. The CD-R2x4 is a multi-session CD-Recorder, bundled with complete mastering
software for Macintosh and Windows. It's one of quickest dual speed CD-R drives with an
average seek time of less than 215 msec. Olympus is also one of the first companies to support
Sony's CD-RFS packet-writing software. CD-RFS allows users to drag files from their Windows
95 desktop directly to a CD, or save files right to a CD from any application. CD-RFS makes CD
recording as easy as writing to a floppy. A nice gift for the computer user who already thinks they
have everything.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Toshiba 12x CD-ROMs:</em> Seems like only yesterday the 4x CD-ROM was top of the line, now
Toshiba has a 12x on the market. Toshiba is the only manufacturer to offer 12-speed CD-ROM
drives in ATAPI and SCSI interfaces. The XM-5701B SCSI and the XM-5702B ATAPI
(enhanced IDE) drives provide increased performance with fast 115ms average random seek and
125ms average random access times.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Designed to provide the fastest possible access to data through enhanced performance, the new
XM-5701B and XM-5702B feature sustained data transfer rates of 1,800KB/sec. For easy set-up
in the SCSI environment, the XM-5701B drive comes complete with SCAM, or "SCSI
Configuration AutoMagically." When users connect the XM-5701B drive through a SCSI port to
a PC or Macintosh, SCAM configures all aspects of the CD-ROM drive with the computer
through the SCSI connection automatically. The SCSI XM-5701B also provides Plug-and-Play
compatibility. Suggested list prices for the drives are: $195 for the XM-5701B SCSI and $165 for
the XM-5702B ATAPI (I'm sure we can all remember only a few years ago when a 2x drive cost
more than that).

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><strong>Hot New Printers:</strong></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Macintosh Printers<strong>:</strong> </em>The Epson Stylus Color 500 is a great inexpensive printer for the Mac. It
produces beautiful color prints, has a CD loaded with Mac and Windows application software,
and includes both serial and parallel ports. The Hewlett-Packard DeskJet 870Cse is also a solid
option for Mac printing, with its mix of rapid output, fine print quality, and dependable
performance.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Apple's offers the <em>Color StyleWriter 2500</em> and <em>Color StyleWriter 1500</em>, both good products based
on Canon technology (though they are a generation behind Canon's current printers). The 2500
costs $389 with 720x360 dpi inch text and graphics, nice text printing, and easy to use operation.
The 1500 is a low-cost ($289) product with decent output, though definitely a cut below the
2500's. But neither of them can match the output quality, speed, and overall price/performance
ratio of the Epson printer.
</em>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><em>High Color- Low Price</em>: With breathtaking color output, sharp text pages, easy operation, and a
great price, the Epson Stylus Color 500 is a great all-around printer. Whatever the reasons your
considering a color ink-jet printer -- photo-like color pages, value, worthwhile software -- the
Epson is the best answer to be found.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Color ink-jets live and die by the quality of the output they produce, and here the Epson
outclasses many of it's competitors. Its 720-dot-per-inch technology produced documents that
were sharp in either black or color. On coated paper, the Epson came closer to matching the
quality of lab-processed color photographs than any other color ink-jet I've ever seen.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For this printer, Epson has come up with some new ink formulations that produce outstanding
output on both plain and glossy paper. The blacks were solid and balanced, and the color was the
most natural of the many ink-jet print-outs I have seen, although the reds in graphics tended just a
bit toward orange. Although the high-resolution 720-dpi mode works well with plain paper, you'll
get truly photo-quality results only on coated stock.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>To help you get the most from the 500, Epson ships an easy start-up package and a CD-ROM
with software for producing everything from newsletters to T-shirts and refrigerator magnets.
Among the applications included on the Color Pak CD-ROM are Adobe PhotoDeluxe, Sierra
Print Artist (for Windows systems), Adobe Home Publisher (for Macs), and lots of extra pictures
and fonts.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Adding to this printer's appeal was a very good warranty (two years of coverage and toll-free
support). Epson has a clear winner with the 500. The price is right, the output is easily the best,
and the entire package simply says, Buy me. Epson America, 800-289-3776 ext. 3000. $279
estimated street cost.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><strong>Storage Devices:</strong></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Last year the Iomega ZipDrive was the darling of disk back-up storage devices. Since then a
whole host of these types of drives have hit the market. Notable this year are some new products
from SyQuest.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>EZ135 Parallel Port External Drive: </em>From SyQuest is really something. You get the ability to
back up your files (up to 135 Megs of them) to a removable disk. Much like the Iomega ZipDrive
that it competes against, the EZ135 is a nice little unit to backup files with or to carry data from
one computer to another easily. Around $200. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>SyQuest also has the<em> EZFlyer 230</em>, at $299, it's a significantly superior product to Iomega's Zip
drive. This is hard drive technology, therefore the access time and performance is vastly superior
to any floppy drive technology. Uses a 230MB storage cartridge that costs about $30.Also just
shipping is the SyQuest <em>SyJet</em> removable cartridge drive. It's  a 1.3GB product that allows you to
back up a hardrive in minutes. Larger capacity than the touted Jaz, equal to or better
performance. Cost is about $500.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Hard Drives</em> come in all types of sizes. An average price for a decent 1.2-1.6GB drive is
somewhere between $200-300. Larger drives such as a 2GB are selling for $300-500. This isn't
bad when compared to the prices of last year which were practically double. If the person on your
list is complaining about lack of space - a new hard drive makes a great gift. Just make sure you
find out exactly what their system can handle so you buy the right one.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><strong>Mice, Joysticks, Game Pads:</strong></em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Looking Beyond The Mouse:</em> The keyboard and mouse are devices most commonly used to
control computers. In the days of DOS, with its text-oriented applications, we needed only
keyboards. With the advent of the Macintosh and Windows, though, a mouse was a must.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Today's multimedia software, with state-of-the-art graphics and sound, requires even more
precision. Anyone trying to operate the simplest flight simulator or play a game of Duke Nukem
3D knows what I mean. Games aside, graphical applications such as architectural programs and
other types of computer-assisted design cry out for something more. I've found a few new gizmos
that you should check out:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>SpaceOrb 360</em> ($99) is designed to be comfortably held in both hands. Its tightly arced crescent
shape sports four buttons positioned under your right thumb, along with two more on the
crescent's edge for your right index finger.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But the real genius behind SpaceOrb is the orb. It's made from a rubberized high-friction material
that makes it nearly impossible to slip. You can grip the sphere neatly in your left hand. It
provides a multi-axis 360-degree control in every direction. In addition to moving the orb like a
joystick for left-right-forward-back movement, you can press it down and lift it up. You can also
twist the orb at any point, but it does not rotate freely like a trackball. Release the orb and it
springs back to the neutral position. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>SpaceOrb includes a demo program that perfectly illustrates this multi-axis control by displaying a
simple jack-in-the-box. Pressing the orb in any direction bends the jack's long accordion neck;
pressing the orb up and down makes the neck stretch and collapse. Twisting the orb makes the
jack's head look around. All of these moves can be simultaneously combined for an instant
accuracy that would be almost impossible with conventional controllers. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Vivitar's WJ2000 </em>joystick ($129) is for those who want the accuracy of a joystick but crave the
freedom of wireless technology. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This is more than just a joystick that has shed its wires: It has no base, either. The unit looks like a
small ray gun that you hold in mid-air. Rotating your wrist counter-clockwise or clockwise moves
things left or right. Tilting it forward and angling backward gives you corresponding movements.
It's like gripping a virtual or an ``air'' joystick. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The receiving unit plugs into your PC's standard game port and doubles as a stand to hold the
WJ2000 when it's not in use. In addition to the freedom of movement, the WJ2000 offers two
triggers that are easily squeezed with the second and third fingers. If you want a more traditional
approach, flick a switch and you can use your other hand to press the four flush-mounted
directional buttons on top. Spacetec IMC (508) 970-0330 Vivitar (805) 498-7008

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Thrustmaster's new joystick, <em>TOP GUN, </em>with an estimated street price between $35.00 to $39.95
is a great buy this holiday season.  Modeled after the grip found in the F-4 Phantom fighter jet, the
TOP GUN joystick excels in all action, combat and flight simulator games.  No matter  what the
game scenario might be, TOP GUN gives the user an added advantage of speed, agility and
increased response time. For more information: call (503) 615-3237 or go to the ThrustMaster
Web site at http://www.thrustmaster.com.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Microsoft's new IntelliMouse</em> features a new combination wheel/button that lets you scroll up and
down Web pages (and wheel-compatible documents) in any direction onscreen. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Click the wheel once and documents continuously roll by like a TelePrompter message. In
Microsoft's upcoming Office '97 products, you'll be able to use the button in combination with the
Control key to reduce or enlarge documents. In Windows 95's Explorer, you'll strike the Shift key
and hold down the button to collapse and expand menu trees. Right now, Microsoft is the only
developer to offer compatible software, but third-party developers will soon announce their plans
to take this mouse for a spin. Microsoft; $84.95; (800) 426-9400; (206) 882-8080;
www.microsoft.com

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em><strong>Other Ideas</strong></em>:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Connectix has a new spin on last year's hot Quick Cam; the Color Quick Cam. This little tennis
size camera allows you to record color images to your PC/Mac. At $250 (around $200 with a
rebate that Connectix is offering) the price still seems a little high just to be able to record things
near my PC. I do see how some professionals might use the Quick Cam for creating sales or
marketing presentations. It is memory intensive, requiring 16MB when using Windows 95, 8MB
for Mac and Windows 3.11.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>RAM</em>- with RAM prices still relatively cheap, adding memory to a system is a great gift idea.
Again, make sure you check with the person you're buying the memory for as to what type they
need. Sure asking them will spoil the surprise, but not asking could make the surprise a
disappointment if you get the wrong kind of memory.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While not a hardware device,<em> screen savers</em> always make a nice gift. Today's monitors don't
really need screen savers as they no longer have the problems of burn-in. However, screen savers
are fun and add some life to your system. Berkeley Systems has a new version of it's award
winning <em>After Dark Screen Saver</em>. Version 4.0 includes over 20 new animated displays and 50
desktop wallpaper patterns to spruce up your screen's looks. It also includes a link to After Dark
Online; a web based new delivery screen saver service. You setup the schedule on when the news
is updated and After Dark dials into their web site and updated the info as requested. $40 from
Berkeley Systems. You can also get the After Dark Online screen saver as a download by going
to http://www.afterdark.com.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>With this short review, I've just scratched the surface of hardware available for the holidays.
There's a lot more hardware out there waiting to grab your dollars. One thing I would like to
emphasis when shopping for hardware is that you SHOP AROUND. Prices can vary from store to
store by wide margins. Also, don't rule out the mail order houses. Some catalog companies like
ComputAbility or Insight offer great deals, low prices, a nice selection of products and next day
shipping. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Above all, find out what the store's return policy is before you buy and SAVE your receipts when
you purchase an item. Good luck in finding the perfect gift. Shop early and beat the rush.

<p>  <strong></strong><em></em><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><a href="toc.html">
