<html>
<head>
<title>Disney's Animated StoryBook, Toy Story</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" 
bgcolor="#ddd9a2">
<font color="#ff0000"></font><font color="#ff0000"><h2><strong></strong><strong>Disney's Animated StoryBook, Toy Story</strong></font></h2>
<h3><font color="#ff0000">By A. Accetta</font></h3>

<p><font color="#ff0000"><hr>
</font>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Following close on the heels of the video release of this very popular Disney movie comes the
animated storybook on CD-ROM.  Disney's Toy Story is a condensed version of the movie,
complete with the same phenomenal Pixar Studios-produced animation, and the familiar character
voices of Tom Hanks and Tim Allen that delighted movie goers so much. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In case you've never seen the movie or the countless commercials and blatant promotions on TV,
the story goes like this: Woody, an old-fashioned pull-string cowboy, is the top toy in little Andy's
toy collection. He and the other toys take their job of being toys very seriously. Their biggest
fears are being replaced, getting broken, or becoming lost. They dread Christmas and Andy's
birthday, the two main days when Andy gets new toys.<p>
<center><img src="http://www.tccmweb.com/swcm/toys2.jpg"></center><p> 
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Toy Story begins with Andy's birthday, and at which he receives an awesome action figure called
Buzz Lightyear, who's got a laser beam, karate-chop action, pop-out wings, and glow-in-the-dark
paint! All the toys (except Woody) are impressed by the amazing Buzz, and soon he is everyone's  
favorite toy. Woody is upset by all this, especially since Buzz doesn't even know he's a toy--he
thinks he's a real Space Ranger!

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Woody tries to get rid of Buzz, but things backfire and he finds himself lost in the outside world
with Buzz. They land in the clutches of  the biggest villain of all: Sid, the toy destroyer. To top
things off, Andy and his family have moved. To survive and return to Andy, Woody and Buzz
must work together and they need your help..

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Toy Story Animated StoryBook is a CD-ROM adventure where you bring the story to life. With
the click of a mouse, you'll enter a wild 3-D world where wonderfully animated toys come to life.
As you read along (or have the narrator read for you), it's up to you to help toys Woody and Buzz
escape bad boy, toy-destroying Sid, catch the moving van, and become best buddies along the
way as they try to get back to Andy. There's also some new animation done especially for the CD-ROM.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Built around ten screen shots, the Toy Story CD captures the story line of the movie pretty well.
The program is basically a 15 page electronic book with activities. Your host is Hamm the
talkative Piggy Bank in the movie. John Ratzenberger, well known as Cliff Clavin on the TV
series Cheers,  reprises his role as the voice of Hamm.  The program is presented with the same
excellent Pixar Studios 3D animation that made the movie such a delight.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In addition to Ratzenberger's reading of a small piece of highlighted text on each screen, Toy
Story includes five integrated activities that include mazes, counting and sorting games, and the
creation of a chain reaction sequence. All of the characters from the movie are here, Po Peep,
Slinky Dog,  the Green Army Men, Mr. Potato Head, and even Sid's mutant toys. Unlike some
previous Disney StoryBooks, these activity screens are not optional side-roads to the story line;
here, they are inserted directly between sequences in the story. The activities focus on early
learning skills, like matching colors, hand eye coordination, following oral directions, addition and
subtraction, and navigating mazes. One activity I liked was a version of the old "you're getting
warmer" location game. These are good early learning tools for your child. Best of all, if your
child has problems during one of the activities, the on-screen characters offer hints and  positive
reinforcement. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Toy Story installed without difficulty. Beware, however, that this is a power-hungry, memory
intensive application. I had to reboot my system before I could run the program. The manual was
so-so, focusing mainly on the activities included and some trouble shooting. However, Disney
offers a 1-800 tech support line, six days/week, open to registered users.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>If your child is between five and nine, and saw the movie a couple of times, this is a program you
won't be able to pull them away from. Toy Story can also be enjoyed by children who haven't
seen the movie, but who enjoy animated book  programs with lots of
'click-and-something-happens' objects. Toy Story screens are filled with 14 or more clickable
objects per screen that say or do something when activated. I haven't seen so many clickable
objects on screen since 7th Level's TuneLand of a few years ago. The program has of course an
educational purpose as well. It teaches your children counting, sorting, spatial relations and
following directions all wrapped around some of the best animation I have ever seen. Lastly, the
program will make a nice holiday gift to go along with the video. From Disney Interactive,
800-688-1520 for around $35.<strong></strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>System Requirements:</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>PC:</em> Windows 3.1 or later, Win95; 486 or faster (I think you really need a Pentium for this) 

<p>10MB of free hard drive space; 8MB of RAM, 256 color graphics, 2x CD-ROM, and 8-bit sound
card and a mouse.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Macintosh:</em> System 7.1 or later; 68040 or faster; 8MB of RAM (16MB on a Power Mac);
640x480x256 color, 2x CD-ROM.
<a href="mailto:lcgeorge@aol.com"></a>
<p> <hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><a href="toc.html">
<p>Return to the Table of Contents</a>
<a href="http://www.tccmweb.com/swcm/nov96/toc.html">
<p>Return to the Main Page</a>

<p>Email us:<a href="mailto:sprynet.com"> swcm@sprynet.com</a>
