<html>
<head>
<title>3-D SPEX: not what I expected</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" 
bgcolor="#ddd9a2">
<h2><strong><font color="#ff0000">3-D SPEX: not what I expected</font></strong></h2>
<h3><font color="#000080">By Don Nelson</font></h3>

<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>When I was given the assignment of reviewing a pair of new 3-D gaming glasses my thoughts
were of  those stupid little paper glasses (with one red and one blue lens) I wore at the 3-D
movies as a kid. When I checked out NuVision Technologies' new 3-D SPEX and I realized this
wasn't the 3-D technology of my youth. Things had come a long way. But, after using the glasses
I think technology still has some way to go before actually giving the user a real 3-D experience
on the PC screen.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The product comes with the glasses (which look like a nice pair of sunglasses with green lenses),
a little plastic do-dad that connects to your PC's parallel port and two CD-ROMs that contain the
drivers for running the glasses and three very similar space-shoot-em up games. The games are
Descent (tm) II Destination Quartzon (OEM version, 8 levels) by Interplay (tm) Slipstream 5000
(tm) from Gremlin (full retail version) Whiplash (tm) (full retail version) by Interplay(tm)/Gremlin.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>My first try at loading the product up on a 486, 100mhz system with 8MB of RAM (the minimum
required) met with some problems. The software loaded fine and the glasses began to work (they
supposedly operate by shutters opening and closing each lens so fast that the picture looks smooth
and gives the illusion of 3-D viewing). The problem was that the game ran very slow and was for
the most part unplayable. I struggled to move the spacecraft out of the hanger but the system was
to sluggish. In addition, the lenses flickered to the point of giving me a headache. After about two
minutes I shut the whole thing down.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>I then tried a Pentium 100mhz and things got a bit better. I loaded the program and put on the
glasses and was engulfed in a three-dimensional game field that was, for this limited technology,
fairly realistic. Objects appeared to loom in the distance or float before my eyes, all in pretty fine
detail. The speed of the lenses improved and I was not able to sense the opening and closing of
the lens shutters as I had been under the 486.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>I do not think that these glasses are for everyone. They can, if left on for long periods of time,
produce eye-strain. And while the glasses are pretty comfortable to wear, the wire attached to
them is a bit annoying and you must also remember to stay a fair distance from the screen or
suffer the blurring of the 3-D effects. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>With only three games shipping with the glasses, and not much else yet available for play with 3-D
SPEX , your use of the product is somewhat limited. Especially since two of the games are sort of
lame, and Descent II isn't that much better. I also did not like the fact that the product is set to
run in MS DOS or the DOS only mode of Windows 95. I was hoping that there would be
Windows 95 games available. I feel that shoot-em up and flight games could really come into their
own if NuVision improves on this technology; and perhaps subsequent versions will offer a true 3-D experience. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For $99 the product is O.K. providing  you have the money to spend. If buying this product and
say some new RAM or another software is a choice, I suggest you buy the RAM or the other
software. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>System Requirements

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A 486 DX2/66 (you really need a Pentium Class Processor), 8M of RAM (though it will run
much better with 16M of RAM), an SVGA color monitor that supports 100 Hz refresh rate; a
video card that supports VESA1.2 BIOS in ROM or VBE emulator, a 4X or better CD-ROM,
30-80MB of free hard drive space, DOS 5.0 or later, including MS DOS only mode of Windows
95, and a Parallel port.

