<title>It's A Buyer's Market This Season</title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" 
bgcolor="#ddd9a2">
<h2><strong></strong><strong><font color="#008000">It's A Buyer's Market This Season</font></strong></h2>
<font color="#ff0000"><h3>By Trish Roberts</font></h3>

<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Last holiday season, we consumers were at the mercy of the computer industry. We wanted or
needed new systems and the PC makers knew it. This year, the ball is in our court. Industry
analysts are reporting that PC makers fear that we might not buy a new machine at all this year;
sales numbers are a-sliding downhill and with it prices.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Part of the reason for this is that such a large number of people bought or upgraded computers
during the frenzy of 1995's Internet and Windows 95 techno-hype. This year there is no huge
media push for a new machine, and there is no startling breakthrough product that every 
consumer can't do without. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Meanwhile, many customers have quickly adapted to the technological revolution, but the
majority of retail computer chains are still set up to pull in "newbies" -- specifically, first-time
buyers. Last week we saw price cuts from Apple; this week NEC has decreased prices on
corporate desktop models. Prices on the Entry Value, Value, Performance and Professional series
in the PowerMate line have been cut up to 18 percent. These are all high-end Pentium and
Pentium Pro machines. Why these cuts on professional systems now, during the consumer holiday
shopping push? Well, Apple, NEC, and Compaq all suffered sales drops this year, and they're
slashing prices to increase demand. Compaq price have fallen as I write this article, as have those
of Dell and Hewlett Packard.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As our culture becomes less intimidated by computers, more and more people are beginning to
make their second PC purchases from used PC brokers and direct sellers. Both Dell and Gateway
have been profiting from this situation. Dell, in fact, just further reduced prices on its corporate
OptiPlex PCS. The biggest reduction was on the OptiPlex GL166, now down 7.8 percent to
$2,189. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Home computers are being marketed in any way possible. The major buying audience is baby
boomers. That's you, right? Come on, don't try to tell me that you don't fit the very busy,
middle-class, gadget-envy stereotype. Based on this profile, you can expect marketers to appeal to
your need for a PC that can take care of time-intensive tasks as well as to your desire for the
latest gadgets, and to tempt you with bundling bargains and financing promotions. So watch for
PCs with voice mail, fast 33.6 modems, personal digital assistants, personal finance software,
ergonomic keyboards, bundled printers or monitors, and no-interest-for-X-months or
no-money-down deals this holiday season. I plan to buy that high-end Pentium I've had my eye on
- and I know that in just a couple more weeks and they'll be begging me to buy I at a price I
wouldn't have thought possible a few months ago.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><hr>

